var __index = {"config":{"lang":["en"],"separator":"[\\s\\-]+","pipeline":["stopWordFilter"],"fields":{"title":{"boost":1000.0},"text":{"boost":1.0},"tags":{"boost":1000000.0}}},"docs":[{"location":"index.html","title":"\ud83c\udf73 Home Culinary School \u2014 The 56-Week Culinary Project","text":"<p>A 56-Week Program for the Home Cook Who Already Cooks</p> <p>Your Schedule: Monday \u00b7 Tuesday \u00b7 Wednesday \u00b7 Friday cook | Saturday = Big Project | Thursday &amp; Sunday = Off</p> <p>Philosophy: Every session layers a professional skill into a meal you'd be cooking anyway. Skills compound. Confidence grows.</p>"},{"location":"index.html#how-to-use-this","title":"How to Use This","text":"<p>Each 2-week block has three files: - Full guide \u2014 daily skill focus, reading, recipes, and context for each session - Quick ref \u2014 one-page recipe + link table for when you're in a rush - Shopping list \u2014 organized grocery list for both weeks in the block</p> <p>New to the program? Read How to Get the Most Out of This Program first \u2014 it covers the mindset, the reading habit, and how to use Claude throughout. Then check the Kitchen Equipment Guide for every tool you'll need, when you'll first use it, and how to buy in phases.</p>"},{"location":"index.html#the-program","title":"The Program","text":""},{"location":"index.html#foundational-skills-weeks-18","title":"\ud83d\udd2a Foundational Skills (Weeks 1\u20138)","text":"Weeks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 1\u20132 Knife Skills &amp; Kitchen Setup \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 3\u20134 Heat &amp; Cooking Methods \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 5\u20136 The 5 Mother Sauces \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 7\u20138 Stocks &amp; Eggs \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"index.html#building-flavor-weeks-916","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Building Flavor (Weeks 9\u201316)","text":"Weeks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 9\u201310 Seasoning &amp; Flavor Building \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 11\u201312 Vegetables &amp; Plant-Forward Cooking \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 13\u201314 Pasta &amp; Grains from Scratch \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 15\u201316 Module 2 Capstone: Poultry &amp; Flavor Review \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"index.html#the-proteins-weeks-1728","title":"\ud83e\udd69 The Proteins (Weeks 17\u201328)","text":"Weeks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 17\u201318 Beef \u2014 Fundamentals \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 19\u201320 Beef \u2014 Advanced Cuts \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 21\u201322 Pork \u2014 All Cuts \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 23\u201324 Fish \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 25\u201326 Shellfish \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 27\u201328 Module 3 Capstone: Charcuterie &amp; Curing \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"index.html#the-worlds-kitchens-weeks-2944","title":"\ud83c\udf0d The World's Kitchens (Weeks 29\u201344)","text":"Weeks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 29\u201330 French \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 31\u201332 Italian \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 33\u201334 Japanese \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 35\u201336 Chinese \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 37\u201338 Mexican \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 39\u201340 Indian \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 41\u201342 Middle Eastern \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 43\u201344 Module 4 Capstone: Southeast Asian Cuisines \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"index.html#mastery-pastry-weeks-4556","title":"\ud83c\udf5e Mastery &amp; Pastry (Weeks 45\u201356)","text":"Weeks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 45\u201346 Bread \u2014 Fundamentals \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 47\u201348 Pastry \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 49\u201350 Desserts \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 51\u201352 Your Signature Dishes \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 53\u201354 Menus &amp; Timing \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 55\u201356 Module 5 Capstone: The Final Exam \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"index.html#weekly-rhythm","title":"Weekly Rhythm","text":"Element What it is The Skill One technique practiced with intention The Meal A complete dinner built around that skill \u2014 protein + veg + starch (or salad) The Read A short article that explains the why behind what you cooked Saturday Project A bigger cook that makes the week's skills visible Sunday Reflection 3 sentences in your notes app. The habit that separates cooks who plateau from cooks who keep growing. <p>Program design: Built for cooks who already cook 5 days a week and want to think like a chef \u2014 not just follow recipes. 56 weeks. Every skill. No fluff.</p>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html","title":"Kitchen Equipment Guide","text":"<p>For students starting out: This guide lists every piece of equipment used in the 52-week program, when you'll first need it, and how essential it is. Use this to plan your purchases in advance rather than scrambling week-of.</p> <p>Three tiers: - \ud83d\udd34 Essential \u2014 You cannot complete the skill without this. Buy before the week shown. - \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended \u2014 You'll use it repeatedly and improvisation is awkward. Worth buying. - \ud83d\udfe2 Optional \u2014 Nice to have. A workaround exists and is noted.</p>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#how-to-use-this-guide","title":"How to Use This Guide","text":"<ol> <li>Before you start: Buy everything in the Essential column for Weeks 1\u20138. That list is short and cheap.</li> <li>Before each module: Check the module's equipment table and buy any new Essential items at least a week ahead.</li> <li>Specialty items: Japanese knives, bannetons, tamagoyaki pans \u2014 buy when the week arrives, not sooner. No point cluttering the counter.</li> </ol>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#master-equipment-list","title":"Master Equipment List","text":""},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#knives-cutting","title":"\ud83d\udd2a Knives &amp; Cutting","text":"Item Priority First Used Module Chef's knife, 8\u201310 inch (German or Japanese) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 1 Foundational Skills Cutting board, large plastic or wood (at least 12\u00d718 in) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 1 Foundational Skills Honing steel \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 1 Foundational Skills Paring knife \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Week 1 Foundational Skills Kitchen shears \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 3 Foundational Skills Bench scraper (metal) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 41 Mastery &amp; Pastry Fish spatula (thin, flexible, slotted) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 21 The Proteins Whetstone (1000/3000 grit) \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Week 47 Mastery &amp; Pastry Mandoline slicer \ud83d\udfe2 Optional Week 51 Mastery &amp; Pastry"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#pans-cookware","title":"\ud83c\udf73 Pans &amp; Cookware","text":"Item Priority First Used Module Notes 10-inch stainless steel or carbon steel skillet \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 1 Foundational Skills For saut\u00e9ing, sauce-making 12-inch cast iron skillet \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 15 The Proteins Non-negotiable for beef sear Dutch oven, 5\u20137 qt (enameled cast iron) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 15 The Proteins Workhorse across modules 3\u20135 Saucepan, 2 qt \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 1 Foundational Skills Stocks, sauces Large stockpot, 8\u201312 qt \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 7 Foundational Skills Stock and pasta water Roasting pan (large, with rack) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 15 The Proteins Also used for bain-marie Half-sheet pan (18\u00d713 in) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 1 Foundational Skills Buy 2\u20133; used constantly Wire rack (fits half-sheet pan) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 15 The Proteins Resting meat, draining Wok, 14-inch carbon steel \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 31 World's Kitchens Round or flat-bottom for gas Comal or flat cast iron griddle \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 33 World's Kitchens Tortillas, flatbreads Tamagoyaki pan (rectangular) \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Week 31 World's Kitchens Workaround: small nonstick pan Steamer insert or tamale pot \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 33 World's Kitchens Dumplings, tamales, vegetables Springform pan, 9-inch \ud83d\udfe2 Optional Week 45 Mastery &amp; Pastry Workaround: regular cake pan with parchment Pullman loaf pan with lid \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Week 41 Mastery &amp; Pastry Sandwich bread; workaround: standard loaf pan 9-inch tart pan with removable bottom \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 43 Mastery &amp; Pastry 9-inch pie dish \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 43 Mastery &amp; Pastry 9-inch round cake pans (\u00d73) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 45 Mastery &amp; Pastry For layer cakes Ramekins, 4\u20136 oz (set of 6) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 45 Mastery &amp; Pastry Cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e, souffl\u00e9, bain-marie desserts Madeleine pan \ud83d\udfe2 Optional Week 43 Mastery &amp; Pastry"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#temperature-measurement","title":"\ud83c\udf21\ufe0f Temperature &amp; Measurement","text":"Item Priority First Used Module Notes Instant-read thermometer \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 1 Foundational Skills Most important tool in the kitchen after a knife Digital kitchen scale (0.1 g resolution) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 41 Mastery &amp; Pastry Required for bread; Recommended from Week 1 for baking Candy thermometer (or second instant-read) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 45 Mastery &amp; Pastry Sugar work, deep frying Multiple-channel timer \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Week 49 Mastery &amp; Pastry Managing multi-dish service; workaround: phone timers"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#tools-gadgets","title":"\ud83d\udd27 Tools &amp; Gadgets","text":"Item Priority First Used Module Notes Tongs (12-inch, locking) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 1 Foundational Skills Buy 2 Wooden spoons (\u00d72) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 1 Foundational Skills Silicone spatula \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 1 Foundational Skills Ladle \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 7 Foundational Skills Fine-mesh strainer \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 7 Foundational Skills Also used for stocks, custards, pasta water rescue Spider strainer / skimmer \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 23 The Proteins Shellfish, blanching, tempura Shellfish brush \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Week 23 The Proteins Cleaning mussels, clams Kitchen twine \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 17 The Proteins Trussing roasts and poultry Kitchen scissors \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 3 Foundational Skills Second pair stays in the kitchen Pastry brush \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 43 Mastery &amp; Pastry Egg wash, glazing, greasing Pastry bag + tips (set) \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Week 43 Mastery &amp; Pastry Workaround: ziplock bag with corner snipped Box grater \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Week 1 Foundational Skills Cheese, zesting, vegetables Microplane / rasp grater \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Week 5 Foundational Skills Citrus zest, garlic, nutmeg Bamboo skewers \ud83d\udfe2 Optional Week 31 World's Kitchens Yakitori, satay Pie weights (or dried beans) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 43 Mastery &amp; Pastry Blind-baking pastry shells"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#specialty-tools-by-cuisine","title":"\ud83e\udd59 Specialty Tools by Cuisine","text":"Item Priority First Used Module Notes Tortilla press (cast iron or aluminum) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 33 World's Kitchens Workaround: two heavy skillet bottoms + parchment paper Mortar and pestle \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 39 World's Kitchens Thai curry pastes; workaround: food processor (inferior result) Banneton / proofing basket \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Week 41 Mastery &amp; Pastry Workaround: bowl lined with floured cloth Bread lame (scoring blade) \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Week 41 Mastery &amp; Pastry Workaround: very sharp serrated knife or razor blade Rice cooker \ud83d\udfe2 Optional Week 31 World's Kitchens Workaround: stovetop absorption method Kitchen torch \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 45 Mastery &amp; Pastry Cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e, browning meringue"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#appliances","title":"\u26a1 Appliances","text":"Item Priority First Used Module Notes Stand mixer with dough hook, whisk, and paddle \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 41 Mastery &amp; Pastry Workaround for bread: by hand. For pastry: hand mixer for most tasks. High-powered blender \ud83d\udd34 Essential Week 33 World's Kitchens Mole, curry paste, smooth soups Food processor \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Week 5 Foundational Skills Pastry dough, chopping, pureeing Pasta machine (hand-cranked) \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Week 11 Building Flavor Workaround: rolling pin + patience Potato ricer \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Week 11 Building Flavor Gnocchi, smooth mash; workaround: hand masher (less smooth) Pressure cooker / Instant Pot \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Week 39 World's Kitchens Braising acceleration; workaround: Dutch oven + 3\u00d7 the time"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#buying-order-by-module","title":"Buying Order by Module","text":"<p>Use this as a phased shopping plan. Purchase each tier before the module begins.</p>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#before-week-1-foundational-essentials-200400","title":"Before Week 1 \u2014 Foundational Essentials (~$200\u2013400)","text":"<ul> <li>Chef's knife</li> <li>Cutting board (large)</li> <li>Honing steel</li> <li>Kitchen shears</li> <li>Tongs \u00d72</li> <li>Instant-read thermometer</li> <li>Half-sheet pans \u00d72</li> <li>10-inch skillet (stainless or carbon steel)</li> <li>2-qt saucepan</li> <li>8\u201312 qt stockpot</li> <li>Fine-mesh strainer</li> <li>Wooden spoons, silicone spatula, ladle, box grater</li> </ul>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#before-week-9-building-flavor-50150","title":"Before Week 9 (Building Flavor) \u2014 ~$50\u2013150","text":"<ul> <li>Potato ricer</li> <li>Pasta machine (or rolling pin upgrade)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#before-week-15-the-proteins-100200","title":"Before Week 15 (The Proteins) \u2014 ~$100\u2013200","text":"<ul> <li>12-inch cast iron skillet</li> <li>Dutch oven 5\u20137 qt</li> <li>Wire rack(s)</li> <li>Kitchen twine</li> <li>Roasting pan</li> </ul>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#before-week-21-fish-2040","title":"Before Week 21 (Fish) \u2014 ~$20\u201340","text":"<ul> <li>Fish spatula</li> </ul>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#before-week-23-shellfish-3050","title":"Before Week 23 (Shellfish) \u2014 ~$30\u201350","text":"<ul> <li>Spider strainer</li> <li>Shellfish brush</li> <li>Large second pot if needed</li> </ul>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#before-week-31-japanese-80150","title":"Before Week 31 (Japanese) \u2014 ~$80\u2013150","text":"<ul> <li>14-inch carbon steel wok</li> <li>Tamagoyaki pan (or nonstick workaround)</li> <li>Bamboo skewers</li> </ul>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#before-week-33-mexican-3070","title":"Before Week 33 (Mexican) \u2014 ~$30\u201370","text":"<ul> <li>Tortilla press</li> <li>Comal or flat cast iron</li> <li>High-powered blender (if not already owned)</li> <li>Tamale pot / steamer</li> </ul>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#before-week-39-southeast-asian-3060","title":"Before Week 39 (Southeast Asian) \u2014 ~$30\u201360","text":"<ul> <li>Mortar and pestle</li> <li>Pressure cooker / Instant Pot (optional)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#before-week-41-bread-150300","title":"Before Week 41 (Bread) \u2014 ~$150\u2013300","text":"<ul> <li>Kitchen scale (0.1g resolution)</li> <li>Stand mixer</li> <li>Bench scraper</li> <li>Banneton</li> <li>Pullman pan with lid</li> <li>Bread lame</li> </ul>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#before-week-43-pastry-60100","title":"Before Week 43 (Pastry) \u2014 ~$60\u2013100","text":"<ul> <li>9-inch tart pan with removable bottom</li> <li>Pie dish</li> <li>Pie weights</li> <li>Pastry brush</li> <li>Pastry bag + tips</li> </ul>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#before-week-45-desserts-80120","title":"Before Week 45 (Desserts) \u2014 ~$80\u2013120","text":"<ul> <li>Kitchen torch + butane canister</li> <li>Ramekins \u00d76</li> <li>Cake pans \u00d73</li> <li>Candy thermometer</li> </ul>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#notes-on-quality","title":"Notes on Quality","text":"<ul> <li>Knife: One great knife beats a block of mediocre ones. If you're buying new, the Victorinox Fibrox 8-inch gives professional results at home-cook prices. Japanese gyuto knives offer better edge retention but require more maintenance.</li> <li>Cast iron: Lodge skillet and Dutch oven are the standard; pre-seasoned and durable for decades.</li> <li>Thermometer: ThermoWorks Thermapen or ThermoPop are the reliable standards. Harbor Freight / cheap probes read slow and drift.</li> <li>Scale: OXO Good Grips, Escali, or My Weigh KD-8000 all hit the 0.1g sweet spot.</li> <li>Dutch oven: Le Creuset and Staub are lifetime purchases. Lodge enamel is the budget-friendly alternative.</li> </ul> <p>Back to: Master Index</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html","title":"How to Get the Most Out of This Program","text":"<p>The short version: Follow the recipes. Read the links. Write three sentences on Sunday. The reading is not optional.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#the-thing-most-people-skip-dont","title":"The Thing Most People Skip (Don't)","text":"<p>Every session has a Read \u2014 a linked article that explains the why behind what you just cooked. These are not supplemental. They are half the curriculum.</p> <p>When you cook a dish without understanding why it works, you learn one recipe. When you read the article alongside it, you learn a transferable principle that applies to a hundred dishes you haven't made yet.</p> <p>Kenji's article on wok hei isn't just about woks. It explains high-heat chemistry in a way that changes how you think about every sear, every saut\u00e9, every time you're tempted to crowd the pan. That's the difference between following a recipe and understanding cooking.</p> <p>The rule: Before you clean up, open the article. Read it while the meal is still in your memory.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#before-every-block-use-the-pre-start-file","title":"Before Every Block: Use the Pre-Start File","text":"<p>In your local <code>feedback/pre-start/</code> folder there's a checklist for every two-week block. Fill it out before you shop.</p> <p>It takes 15 minutes and catches problems that would otherwise surface mid-cook on a Wednesday night:</p> <ul> <li>Links that don't load</li> <li>Recipes that need overnight prep you didn't plan for</li> <li>Hard-to-source ingredients</li> <li>Sessions that won't fit your schedule as written</li> </ul> <p>Send the filled-out file to Claude before you start. Any issues \u2014 misaligned recipes, timing problems, broken links \u2014 get fixed before they become your problem.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#two-files-two-contexts","title":"Two Files, Two Contexts","text":"<p>Each block has a full guide (<code>index.md</code>) and a quick ref (<code>quick-ref.md</code>). Use them differently:</p> Full Guide Quick Ref When Before the session During the session What Read the skill explanation, context, and the linked article Glance at the recipe link and move on Why The narrative connects the skill to everything else You don't want to scroll mid-cook <p>The full guide is where you understand the session. The quick ref is where you execute it.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#the-saturday-project-is-not-optional","title":"The Saturday Project Is Not Optional","text":"<p>The Saturday cook is when the week's skill becomes real. Monday through Friday you practice technique in isolation \u2014 garlic mince, dice consistency, grip. Saturday is where you use all of it in one self-contained cook with a real result.</p> <p>Don't treat it as a harder weeknight. Treat it as a performance. Set the table. Plate carefully. Invite someone if you can.</p> <p>The feedback you get from cooking a full meal \u2014 timing pressure, heat management, plating decisions \u2014 is different from anything you get from a Tuesday session. It's irreplaceable.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#the-three-sentence-sunday-habit","title":"The Three-Sentence Sunday Habit","text":"<p>Every week ends with a Sunday reflection prompt. It asks for three sentences:</p> <ol> <li>What felt awkward this week?</li> <li>What clicked?</li> <li>What do you want to fix?</li> </ol> <p>This sounds trivial. It isn't. After 52 weeks you'll have a document that tracks your actual development as a cook \u2014 not a highlight reel, but a real log. It also forces you to pay attention during the week in a way that knowing you'll have to write about it creates.</p> <p>Your notes app is fine. A text file is fine. The format doesn't matter. The habit does.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#when-you-mess-something-up","title":"When You Mess Something Up","text":"<p>You will burn something. You will break an emulsion. You will undercook a braise and eat at 9pm. This is correct.</p> <p>The sessions that go wrong teach more than the ones that go right \u2014 but only if you stay curious about why. When something fails, before you move on, ask:</p> <ul> <li>Was the pan not hot enough?</li> <li>Did I skip a step?</li> <li>Was the timing unrealistic for a weeknight?</li> <li>Is the recipe wrong, or was I?</li> </ul> <p>Write it in the feedback log for that block (<code>feedback/</code> folder, local only). At the end of the block, send it to Claude. The curriculum adjusts.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#skills-compound-trust-the-sequence","title":"Skills Compound \u2014 Trust the Sequence","text":"<p>The program is deliberately sequenced. Week 1's knife skills feed into Week 3's mise en place, which feeds into Week 7's stock timing, which feeds into Week 15's butchery. You will notice callbacks and repetitions throughout \u2014 they're intentional.</p> <p>If you skip blocks or jump ahead, you'll cook the recipes but miss the compounding. The whole point is that by Week 40, you're not following a recipe for Thai curry \u2014 you understand what's happening in the pan and can adapt on the fly. That only happens if the foundations were built underneath it.</p> <p>Do the blocks in order. Skip a session if life happens \u2014 that's fine \u2014 but don't skip a block.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#using-claude-throughout","title":"Using Claude Throughout","text":"<p>Claude is a tool you can use at any point in the program, not just at the start:</p> When What to send What Claude does Before a block Your filled-out <code>pre-start/</code> file Fixes links, scheduling conflicts, alignment issues After a block Your filled-out <code>feedback/</code> file Updates the index, rebalances timing, improves recipes Mid-session A question (\"my beurre blanc broke \u2014 what happened?\") Explains the failure mode and how to prevent it Anytime A substitution question, a sourcing problem, a \"what does this recipe actually mean\" Answers in context of where you are in the program <p>The program is a living document. Your feedback makes it better. Use it.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#the-mindset-that-makes-this-work","title":"The Mindset That Makes This Work","text":"<p>You already cook. The goal isn't to teach you to follow recipes \u2014 it's to change how you think while you're cooking. That shift happens through:</p> <ul> <li>Reading the linked articles (not skimming them)</li> <li>Noticing what's happening in the pan, not just watching the timer</li> <li>Writing three sentences on Sunday even when it feels unnecessary</li> <li>Sending your feedback so the program adapts to you</li> </ul> <p>The recipes are the vehicle. The reading, the reflection, and the repetition are the program.</p> <p>Questions? Something not working? Something that could be better? Fill in the feedback file and send it. That's what it's for.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/index.html","title":"Module 1: Foundational Skills (Weeks 1\u20138)","text":"<p>The goal of this module: Build the physical and conceptual toolkit every cook needs before anything else \u2014 a confident knife hand, a fluent understanding of heat, the five mother sauces as a flavor map, and the ability to make great stock and eggs from memory.</p> <p>By the end of Week 8, you should be able to walk into any kitchen and produce restaurant-quality fundamentals without a recipe.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/index.html#weeks-in-this-module","title":"Weeks in This Module","text":"Weeks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 1\u20132 Knife Skills &amp; Kitchen Setup \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 3\u20134 Heat &amp; Cooking Methods \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 5\u20136 The 5 Mother Sauces \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 7\u20138 Stocks &amp; Eggs (includes Module 1 Checkpoint) \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/index.html#core-skills-covered","title":"Core Skills Covered","text":"<ul> <li>Knife work \u2014 grip, rocking motion, julienne, brunoise, chiffonade; blade maintenance and honing</li> <li>Heat control \u2014 saut\u00e9, sear, roast, braise, poach, steam; Maillard reaction and caramelization</li> <li>The mother sauces \u2014 b\u00e9chamel, velout\u00e9, espagnole, hollandaise, and tomato; their derivatives</li> <li>Stock fundamentals \u2014 white and brown stocks; roasting bones; the difference between stock and broth</li> <li>Eggs \u2014 every technique: scrambled, poached, basted, fried, soft-boiled; emulsification basics</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/index.html#equipment-youll-need","title":"Equipment You'll Need","text":"<p>See the Kitchen Equipment Guide for the full list. Essential items introduced in this module:</p> Item Introduced Chef's knife (8\u201310 inch) Week 1 Honing steel Week 1 Large cutting board Week 1 Instant-read thermometer Week 1 Kitchen shears Week 3 <p>Next module: Module 2 \u2014 Building Flavor (Weeks 9\u201316)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html","title":"\ud83d\udd2a Weeks 1\u20132: Knife Skills &amp; Kitchen Setup","text":"<p>\"Learn to hold a knife properly and half the battle is won.\"</p> <p>Quick Reference: \u2192 Week 1\u20132 Recipe Quick Ref</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#before-you-start-week-1","title":"Before You Start Week 1","text":"<p>Read these first \u2014 they'll make every session click:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Hold a Chef's Knife \u2014 the pinch grip vs. handle grip, with photos</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The 4 Knife Cuts Every Cook Should Know \u2014 the slice, chop, back-slice, and rock chop</li> </ul> <p>Rule for the week: Hone your knife before every session. Non-negotiable.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#week-1-your-knife-is-a-liar-and-your-hands-dont-know-it-yet","title":"Week 1 \u2014 Your Knife Is a Liar (And Your Hands Don't Know It Yet)","text":""},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#monday-the-pinch-grip","title":"Monday \u2014 The Pinch Grip","text":"<p>Skill: Switch to the blade pinch grip tonight and don't revert. Your thumb and forefinger rest directly on the blade just in front of the bolster \u2014 it's intimidating, but it gives you far better control. Hold it this way for the entire meal.</p> <p>Full Meal: Pasta with Butter and Parmesan</p> <p>The prep is simple \u2014 garlic and parsley \u2014 which lets you focus entirely on your grip without managing a complicated recipe. This is intentional.</p> Component Recipe Main Parmesan-crusted pasta Veg Wilted baby spinach, saut\u00e9ed in the pasta pan with olive oil, garlic, and lemon <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: POV Cacio e Pepe \u2014 Nearly the same dish. Watch how he builds the sauce with pasta water and keeps the heat low. Compare his approach to ours and see what you'd borrow.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#tuesday-the-claw","title":"Tuesday \u2014 The Claw","text":"<p>Skill: Before touching the stove, take one onion, one carrot, one celery stalk. Practice the claw grip \u2014 fingers curled, knuckles as the guide rail for the blade. Keep the tip of the blade in contact with the board, pull back slightly until the blade slices in, then press down and forward using the full length of the blade. Dice all three into rough \u00bd\" pieces. Time yourself. Don't worry about speed yet \u2014 worry about uniformity.</p> <p>Full Meal: The Best Chicken Noodle Soup</p> <p>A classic mirepoix \u2014 onion, carrot, celery \u2014 is the entire flavor base of this soup. Your Tuesday drill is the recipe's most important step. Everything else follows from it.</p> Component Recipe Protein Chicken, simmered and shredded into the broth Veg Mirepoix (your drill), plus parsley Starch Egg noodles, cooked directly in the soup <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Knife Skills: How to Slice and Dice an Onion \u00b7 How to Make Chicken Noodle Soup \u2014 Watch the knife video for the claw grip in real time at speed. The soup video shows a completely different approach to the same dish \u2014 both are worth thinking about.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#wednesday-rock-chop-vs-push-cut","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Rock Chop vs. Push Cut","text":"<p>Skill: Mince a full head of garlic and a large bunch of flat-leaf parsley before you start cooking. Use two strokes deliberately \u2014 the rock chop (blade tip stays on the board, heel rocks) and the push cut (blade lifts fully, pushes through cleanly). Notice the difference in speed and texture. The rock chop gives control; the push cut gives speed. Both have their place.</p> <p>Full Meal: Shrimp Scampi</p> <p>Shrimp scampi is built almost entirely on well-minced garlic and parsley. Your drill is the most important prep step in the dish.</p> Component Recipe Protein Shrimp, saut\u00e9ed in garlic butter and white wine Veg Burst Cherry Tomatoes with Garlic and Olive Oil \u2014 toss with a little pasta water and lemon Starch Crusty bread or linguine <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Knife Skills: How to Mince Shallots \u2014 Shallots, garlic, parsley \u2014 same motions, different ingredient. Watch how he uses the rock chop and push cut interchangeably depending on the task.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#thursday-off","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: How to Sharpen and Hone a Knife</p> <p>Is your knife actually sharp? A dull knife is the #1 reason home cook technique looks worse than it is. If you don't own a honing steel, order one tonight.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Also watch: How to Sharpen a Knife with a Whetstone \u2014 Kenji demonstrates the full whetstone process in his home kitchen. Pair with the reading above.</p> <p>Required reading \u2014 Food Safety Fundamentals</p> <p>This is not optional. A sharp knife reduces accidents. Clean food handling prevents you from poisoning yourself and the people you cook for. Most food poisoning events in home kitchens have a mundane cause \u2014 not a dramatic one.</p> <p>The four things to understand before you finish Week 1:</p> <ol> <li> <p>The danger zone is 40\u00b0F\u2013140\u00b0F (4\u00b0C\u201360\u00b0C). Bacteria multiply rapidly in this range. Cooked food left at room temperature should not spend more than 2 hours in the danger zone total \u2014 shorter in a warm kitchen. If you can't serve it within 2 hours, refrigerate it.</p> </li> <li> <p>Cross-contamination is the most common kitchen mistake. Raw poultry, beef, pork, and seafood carry bacteria. They should not touch anything that will be eaten raw \u2014 cutting boards, counters, hands, knife blades. Use separate boards for raw protein and produce, or wash and sanitize between tasks.</p> </li> <li> <p>Cool stocks and braises safely. A large pot of hot stock cools slowly through the danger zone. Don't put a hot pot directly in the fridge (it raises the fridge temperature). Instead: transfer to a wide, shallow container, ice bath it until it's below 70\u00b0F within 2 hours, then refrigerate. Improper cooling is the most common cause of home stock contamination.</p> </li> <li> <p>Internal temperatures are not optional suggestions. Poultry must reach 165\u00b0F. Pork at least 145\u00b0F. Ground beef 160\u00b0F. Whole muscle beef (steaks) can be cooked to lower temperatures because bacteria live on the surface and are killed by the sear. Knowing why these numbers differ is as useful as knowing the numbers themselves.</p> </li> </ol> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Safe Food Handling: What You Need to Know \u2014 covers danger zones, safe storage, and cross-contamination. 10 minutes of reading.</p> <p>The professional standard: CIA students spend their first week on food safety before they touch a knife in a hot kitchen. We're doing this here, at the end of Week 1, because now you understand what you're actually handling. A cook who knows safe temperatures is not being paranoid. They're being professional.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#friday-mise-en-place","title":"Friday \u2014 Mise en Place","text":"<p>Skill: The real chef's secret. Tonight, before you turn on a single burner, prep everything first. Every ingredient chopped, measured, and arranged in small bowls or on the cutting board. Then cook. Notice how the experience changes \u2014 you're not scrambling, you're assembling.</p> <p>Full Meal: Stir-Fried Beef and Broccoli</p> <p>Stir-fries punish you for skipping mise en place. The heat is too high and things move too fast. This recipe forces you to have everything ready before the wok gets hot.</p> Component Recipe Protein Thinly sliced flank steak, velveted in the wok Veg Broccoli florets, blanched then wok-tossed Starch Steamed jasmine rice, started before you begin the stir-fry <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Beef with Broccoli \u2014 This is the exact dish. Watch it before you cook. Notice how everything is prepped and staged before the wok gets hot \u2014 mise en place isn't a warm-up, it's the whole game in a stir-fry.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#saturday-project-meal-french-onion-soup","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: French Onion Soup","text":"<p>Skill: Slicing 4\u20135 lbs of onions into uniform thin half-moons. This takes 20+ minutes and teaches you more than any drill \u2014 because caramelization depends entirely on uniform thickness. Thin, even slices cook at the same rate. Uneven ones create pockets of raw and burned.</p> <p>Full Meal: French Onion Soup (Soupe \u00e0 l'Oignon)</p> <p>A self-contained stunning dinner \u2014 nothing else needed except a glass of red wine.</p> <p>Skill targets: Uniform half-moon slices. Pinch grip maintained throughout. Knife honed before you start.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The Mathematically Best Way to Cut an Onion \u2014 He breaks down the geometry of onion-cutting and why the angle of your cuts determines whether pieces stay together or fall apart. Perfect viewing before 4\u20135 lbs of half-moons.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#sunday-off","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>Write three sentences somewhere: What felt awkward this week? What clicked? What do you want to fix? Your notes app is fine. This three-sentence habit is worth more than any cooking class.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#week-2-cuts-have-names-learn-them","title":"Week 2 \u2014 Cuts Have Names. Learn Them.","text":"<p>The grip is feeling more natural. Now we add vocabulary and intentionality to the cuts themselves.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#monday-the-julienne","title":"Monday \u2014 The Julienne","text":"<p>Skill: Take two carrots and one zucchini. Square off each vegetable first (cut a flat face on one side so it doesn't roll). Slice into planks. Stack the planks and cut into matchsticks \u2014 roughly 2\u20133 inches long, \u215b inch thick. This is also the foundation of the brunoise (tiny dice). Go slow. Precision before speed.</p> <p>While you have your knife out: grab a small handful of fresh basil leaves. Stack them neatly, roll the stack into a tight cylinder, and slice straight across it into thin ribbons. That's chiffonade \u2014 the same logic as julienne, applied to soft leaves instead of hard vegetables. It takes 30 seconds and it's the right garnish for Pad Thai.</p> <p>Why it matters: Julienned vegetables cook faster and more evenly than rough cuts. Chiffonade keeps delicate herbs from bruising \u2014 a rough chop turns basil black at the edges almost immediately. Both cuts signal control.</p> <p>Full Meal: The Best Pad Thai</p> Component Recipe Protein Shrimp, chicken, or tofu Veg Your julienned carrots and scallions, plus bean sprouts; finish with fresh basil chiffonade Starch Rice noodles, soaked per the recipe <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Get More Out of Your Broccoli With This Knife Trick \u2014 Not broccoli today, but the principle is the same: thin, even cuts change how a vegetable cooks and eats. Watch the logic, apply it to your julienne.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#tuesday-the-dice-small-medium-large","title":"Tuesday \u2014 The Dice (Small, Medium, Large)","text":"<p>Skill: Dice three potatoes \u2014 one small (\u00bc\"), one medium (\u00bd\"), one large (\u00be\"). Notice the process: planks first, then batons, then cubes. Cook all three in the same hot pan at the same time. Watch what happens \u2014 the small ones finish first. The large ones are still raw when the small ones are done. That's the entire lesson.</p> <p>Why it matters: Uniform cuts = uniform cooking. This is the single biggest quality gap between home cooks and professionals.</p> <p>Full Meal: Home Fries + Pan-Seared Crispy Chicken Thighs</p> Component Recipe Protein Crispy pan-seared bone-in chicken thighs Veg/Salad Classic Green Salad with Vinaigrette Starch Home fries (your dice drill is the recipe) <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The Food Lab: How to Roast the Best Potatoes of Your Life \u2014 He explains why cut size and uniformity determine texture and doneness \u2014 the exact lesson from your three-potato drill, applied to the oven.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#wednesday-breaking-down-a-whole-chicken","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Breaking Down a Whole Chicken","text":"<p>Skill: Buy a whole chicken. Read How to Break Down a Chicken first, then do it. You'll get two bone-in breasts, two thighs, two drumsticks, two wings, and a carcass. Put the carcass in a zip-lock in the freezer \u2014 that's Week 7 stock material. Follow the joints, not the bones. Let the knife find the natural seams.</p> <p>Full Meal: Chicken Piccata (use the breasts) + Simple Arugula Salad</p> <p>The thighs and legs go in the fridge (use them Friday) or freeze for later. Nothing wasted.</p> Component Recipe Protein Chicken piccata using the breasts you broke down Veg/Salad Arugula with shaved parmesan and lemon vinaigrette Starch Buttered egg noodles or mashed potatoes <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: POV How to Break Down a Chicken \u00b7 28-Second Chicken Breakdown \u2014 Watch the full POV version before you start. The short shows what the motion looks like fully internalized. You'll get somewhere between the two.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#thursday-off_1","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: How to Sharpen a Knife</p> <p>The dishwasher, glass cutting boards, and storing knives loose in a drawer \u2014 these are the three biggest offenders. Check your own habits.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#friday-speed-benchmark","title":"Friday \u2014 Speed Benchmark","text":"<p>Skill: Time yourself dicing one onion. Write it down. This is your baseline. At the end of Week 4, you'll time yourself again. Speed is not the goal \u2014 having a reference point is.</p> <p>Full Meal: Shakshuka + Wednesday's leftover chicken thighs (warmed in a skillet)</p> <p>Shakshuka requires dicing onion, pepper, and garlic as its entire prep \u2014 your speed drill is built into the recipe.</p> Component Recipe Protein Eggs poached in the shakshuka sauce + Wednesday's leftover chicken thighs Veg Onion, bell pepper, tomatoes (the shakshuka base) Starch Crusty bread for dipping <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Shakshuka \u2014 The same dish. Notice that his onion and pepper dice is the entire prep step \u2014 the very thing you're timing today.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#saturday-project-meal-provencal-vegetable-tian","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Proven\u00e7al Vegetable Tian","text":"<p>Skill: Slice eggplant, zucchini, yellow squash, and tomatoes into rounds of identical thickness \u2014 ideally \u215b to \u00bc inch. The beauty of the finished dish is a direct function of your slicing precision. Uniform slices = a dish that looks like a restaurant made it.</p> <p>Full Meal: Proven\u00e7al Summer Vegetable Tian + crusty bread</p> Component Recipe Protein Optional \u2014 serve with good burrata or a soft-boiled egg on top Veg The tian (eggplant, zucchini, squash, tomato) Starch Crusty baguette <p>Skill targets: Consistent thickness on every slice. Go slow. This is about control, not speed.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Knife Skills: How to Dice Butternut Squash \u2014 Same family of vegetable, same slicing challenge. Watch the board control and how he maintains consistent pressure through each stroke.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#sunday-off_1","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>Compare this reflection to last week's. The grip should feel natural. You should know the difference between a julienne, a small dice, and a rock chop \u2014 not just in theory, but in your hands.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#buying-maintaining-your-knife","title":"Buying &amp; Maintaining Your Knife","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Best Chef's Knives \u2014 Serious Eats' tested roundup. The short answer for most people: a 8\" German-style knife (W\u00fcsthof or Victorinox) to start.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Wirecutter: The Best Chef's Knife \u2014 independent testing with a different methodology. Worth comparing both.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 German vs. Japanese Chef's Knives \u2014 What's the Difference? \u2014 harder steel, thinner bevel, more acute angle on Japanese; softer, more robust, easier to maintain on German. Useful context if you're buying soon.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Store Your Knives \u2014 magnetic strip vs. block vs. in-drawer protectors. The dishwasher is the enemy.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<p>Reading about knife technique only goes so far. These videos show you what the grip and motion actually look like at speed:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Jacques P\u00e9pin \u2014 Knife Skills \u2014 He's filmed these sessions multiple times across decades. Watching a 90-year-old chef break down an onion is humbling and clarifying.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Ethan Chlebowski \u2014 How to Actually Improve Your Knife Skills \u2014 More data-driven and modern. Good on speed benchmarks and how deliberate practice actually works in the kitchen.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#the-broader-concept-mise-en-place","title":"The Broader Concept: Mise en Place","text":"<p>The Friday session introduces mise en place but only as setup. The idea runs a lot deeper:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Set Up a Prep Station Like a Pro Cook \u2014 Sohla El-Waylly on the practical side of mise en place: how professional kitchens organize their workspace for vegetables, proteins, frying, and more. The Friday session introduces the habit; this shows you what it looks like fully applied.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Food Lab by J. Kenji L\u00f3pez-Alt \u2014 The first chapter covers knife skills and mise en place with the same scientific rigour as everything else in the book. If you're going to own one reference book for this program, this is it.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Weeks 1\u20132 Quick Reference \u2014 Knife Skills &amp; Kitchen Setup","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/quick-ref.html#week-1-recipes","title":"Week 1 Recipes","text":"Day Dish Skill Link Mon Pasta with Butter and Parmesan + Wilted Spinach Pinch grip Recipe Tue The Best Chicken Noodle Soup The claw / mirepoix Recipe Wed Shrimp Scampi + Burst Cherry Tomatoes Rock chop vs. push cut Scampi \u00b7 Tomatoes Thu OFF Read: knife sharpening Article Fri Stir-Fried Beef and Broccoli Mise en place Recipe Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: French Onion Soup Uniform half-moon slices Recipe"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/quick-ref.html#week-2-recipes","title":"Week 2 Recipes","text":"Day Dish Skill Link Mon The Best Pad Thai Julienne cut Recipe Tue Home Fries + Crispy Pan-Seared Chicken Thighs + Green Salad Small/medium/large dice Home Fries \u00b7 Chicken \u00b7 Salad Wed Chicken Piccata + Arugula Salad Break down whole chicken Piccata \u00b7 Breakdown \u00b7 Salad Thu OFF Read: knife sharpening Article Fri Shakshuka + Leftover Chicken Thighs Speed benchmark \u2014 time your onion dice Recipe Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Proven\u00e7al Vegetable Tian + Bread Uniform round slices Tian"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/quick-ref.html#shopping-notes","title":"Shopping Notes","text":"<p>Buy Wednesday of Week 1: A honing steel (if you don't own one)</p> <p>Buy for Week 2 Wednesday: One whole chicken \u2014 you'll break it down yourself. Breasts go in Piccata; thighs/legs go in the fridge for Friday's Shakshuka.</p> <p>Freeze: The chicken carcass from Week 2 Wednesday \u2192 this is your Week 7 stock.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 1\u20132: Knife Skills &amp; Kitchen Setup","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Do this in two produce trips \u2014 one before Week 1 starts, one before Week 2 starts. The list is already split that way. Produce bought in one go at the start of Week 1 will not survive to Week 2.</p> <p>Pantry and dry goods (pasta, sauces, oils, spices) can all be bought in one trip before Week 1 \u2014 they keep indefinitely.</p> <p>Proteins: Buy the Week 1 proteins (chicken breasts, shrimp, beef) before Week 1. Buy the Week 2 whole chicken the day before you plan to break it down \u2014 it must be fresh, not frozen, and fresh chicken has a short window.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/shopping-list.html#proteins","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Boneless, skinless chicken breasts \u2014 1 lb (Week 1 Tue, for soup)</li> <li>[ ] Large shrimp (16/20 count), peeled and deveined \u2014 1 lb (Week 1 Wed)</li> <li>[ ] Flank steak or beef sirloin \u2014 1 lb, thinly sliced (Week 1 Fri, stir-fry)</li> <li>[ ] Bone-in, skin-on chicken thighs \u2014 6 pieces (Week 2 Tue)</li> <li>[ ] Whole chicken \u2014 1 (Week 2 Wed): You will break this down yourself. This is the lesson. The breasts go into piccata; the thighs and legs are your Week 2 Friday leftovers. Save the carcass in the freezer \u2014 it becomes your Week 7 stock.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce","text":"<p>Week 1:</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Yellow onions \u2014 3 large (soup + French onion soup)</li> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 4 (soup + mirepoix)</li> <li>[ ] Celery \u2014 1 bunch (soup)</li> <li>[ ] Baby spinach \u2014 5 oz bag (Week 1 Mon pasta + salads)</li> <li>[ ] Arugula \u2014 2 bags (Week 1 Wed + Week 2 Wed salad)</li> <li>[ ] Broccoli \u2014 1 head (Week 1 Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads (multiple uses all week)</li> <li>[ ] Lemon \u2014 3 (Week 1 Wed + Wed pasta + salad dressings)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh thyme \u2014 1 bunch (French onion soup)</li> </ul> <p>Week 2:</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Russet or Yukon Gold potatoes \u2014 2 lbs (Week 2 Tue home fries)</li> <li>[ ] Red bell peppers \u2014 2 (Week 2 Tue home fries)</li> <li>[ ] Zucchini \u2014 2 medium (Week 2 Sat tian)</li> <li>[ ] Tomatoes \u2014 6 medium (Week 2 Sat tian + Week 2 Fri shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Yellow squash \u2014 2 medium (Week 2 Sat tian)</li> <li>[ ] Mixed greens / butter lettuce \u2014 2 bags (Week 2 salads)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 1 bunch (garnishes)</li> <li>[ ] Scallions \u2014 1 bunch (multiple uses)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh basil \u2014 1 bunch (Week 2 Mon Pad Thai garnish \u2014 chiffonade drill)</li> <li>[ ] Lemongrass (if available) \u2014 optional for Pad Thai garnish</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/shopping-list.html#dairy","title":"\ud83e\uddc0 Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Parmesan (Parmigiano-Reggiano block) \u2014 8 oz (pasta + Caesar + piccata)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 2 sticks</li> <li>[ ] Gruy\u00e8re \u2014 4 oz (Week 2 Sat tian topping)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (Week 2 Fri shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 1 small carton (optional for pasta)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry-goods","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Pantry &amp; Dry Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Pasta (linguine \u2014 Week 1 Wed) \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Egg noodles (Week 1 Tue soup) \u2014 8 oz</li> <li>[ ] Rice noodles, medium width (Week 2 Mon Pad Thai) \u2014 8 oz</li> <li>[ ] Chicken stock or broth \u2014 32 oz carton (soup)</li> <li>[ ] Canned whole peeled tomatoes \u2014 2 cans (Week 2 Fri shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Oyster sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Week 1 Fri stir-fry)</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce \u2014 1 bottle</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Pad Thai)</li> <li>[ ] Tamarind paste or concentrate \u2014 1 jar (Pad Thai) \u2014 find at Asian grocery or Amazon</li> <li>[ ] Cornstarch \u2014 1 box (stir-fry)</li> <li>[ ] Beef stock or broth \u2014 32 oz + 1 extra carton (Week 1 Sat French onion soup)</li> <li>[ ] Dry sherry or cognac \u2014 small bottle (French onion soup \u2014 can substitute extra beef stock)</li> <li>[ ] Unseasoned rice vinegar (Pad Thai)</li> <li>[ ] Roasted peanuts (Pad Thai garnish)</li> <li>[ ] Neutral oil (vegetable, grapeseed, or canola) \u2014 1 bottle if you don't have one</li> <li>[ ] Extra-virgin olive oil</li> <li>[ ] Capers \u2014 1 jar (Week 2 Wed piccata)</li> <li>[ ] Cumin, paprika, dried chili flakes, ground coriander (Week 2 Fri shakshuka)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/shopping-list.html#bread","title":"\ud83e\udd56 Bread","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Good baguette \u2014 1 (Week 1 Sat French onion soup croutons)</li> <li>[ ] Crusty bread for Week 2 Sat tian \u2014 1 loaf</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/shopping-list.html#equipment-if-you-dont-own-these-yet","title":"\ud83d\udd2a Equipment (if you don't own these yet)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Chef's knife \u2014 if you don't own a good one (8\" Victorinox Fibrox is the reliable budget pick)</li> <li>[ ] Honing steel \u2014 not optional. Buy one this week.</li> <li>[ ] Cutting board \u2014 large, wood or plastic (at least 12\" \u00d7 18\")</li> <li>[ ] Instant-read thermometer \u2014 useful now, essential from Week 3 on</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/shopping-list.html#notes","title":"\ud83d\udcdd Notes","text":"<p>French onion soup (Week 1 Sat) requires a LOT of onions. 4\u20135 large yellow onions is not too many. They cook down to almost nothing.</p> <p>Pad Thai (Week 2 Mon): Soak rice noodles in cold water for 30 minutes before cooking \u2014 don't boil them. They finish in the wok.</p> <p>Whole chicken (Week 2 Wed): Watch the Serious Eats chicken breakdown video before you start. Takes about 20 minutes the first time; 8 minutes by Week 6.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html","title":"\ud83d\udd25 Weeks 3\u20134: Heat &amp; Cooking Methods","text":"<p>\"Understanding heat is understanding cooking. Everything else is detail.\"</p> <p>Quick Reference: \u2192 Week 3\u20134 Recipe Quick Ref</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#before-you-start-week-3","title":"Before You Start Week 3","text":"<p>Read this first:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 An Introduction to the Maillard Reaction \u2014 the science of browning, flavor, and why a dry, hot pan matters more than any spice blend</li> </ul> <p>Core concept: Dry heat above 300\u00b0F triggers the Maillard reaction \u2014 the chemical cascade that creates crust, color, and hundreds of flavor compounds. Wet heat (steam, water) cannot get food above 212\u00b0F, which means it cannot trigger this reaction. This is why a boiled steak tastes nothing like a seared one.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#week-3-dry-heat-the-maillard-reaction-is-your-best-friend","title":"Week 3 \u2014 Dry Heat: The Maillard Reaction Is Your Best Friend","text":""},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#monday-saute-hot-pan-dont-crowd","title":"Monday \u2014 Saut\u00e9: Hot Pan, Don't Crowd","text":"<p>Skill: Saut\u00e9ing means high heat, small amount of fat, food in a single layer, moving frequently. The most common home cook mistake: cold pan, crowded pan, food that steams instead of browns. Tonight, heat your pan until a drop of water evaporates immediately before adding oil. Cook in batches if needed.</p> <p>Full Meal: Saut\u00e9ed Chicken Breasts with Quick Pan Sauce + Saut\u00e9ed Zucchini with Garlic and Herbs + Steamed Rice</p> Component Recipe Protein Saut\u00e9ed boneless chicken breast, finished with a quick pan sauce of shallot, white wine, and butter Veg Saut\u00e9ed zucchini \u2014 notice how a hot pan gives you color on the outside while keeping the inside tender Starch Steamed jasmine rice <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Pan-Seared Chicken Breasts with Pan Sauce and Spring Vegetables \u2014 Same cut, same pan sauce technique \u2014 notice how he builds flavor in the pan after pulling the chicken.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#tuesday-roasting-hot-oven-dry-surface","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Roasting: Hot Oven, Dry Surface","text":"<p>Skill: Roasting is dry oven heat that circulates around food, browning all exposed surfaces. The two secrets: (1) high heat (400\u00b0F+) and (2) a dry surface on the food. Pat everything dry. Never roast wet food \u2014 the moisture steams before it can brown.</p> <p>Full Meal: Sheet Pan Chicken Thighs with Roasted Vegetables + Simple Green Salad</p> <p>Use bone-in, skin-on thighs. Pat them completely dry. Compare the color and crispness tonight to Wednesday's braise \u2014 you'll eat the difference.</p> Component Recipe Protein Bone-in skin-on chicken thighs, roasted until crackling Veg Whatever is on the sheet pan \u2014 broccoli, potatoes, onions Salad Simple green salad alongside"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#wednesday-braising-low-slow-wet","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Braising: Low, Slow, Wet","text":"<p>Skill: Braising is a two-step method. First, sear the meat in a very hot pan (dry heat, Maillard reaction). Then add a small amount of liquid, cover, and cook at low heat for a long time. The collagen in tough cuts breaks down into gelatin, making the meat spoon-tender and the braising liquid silky. Never rush a braise.</p> <p>Full Meal: Braised Chicken Thighs with Tomatoes and Capers + Crusty bread or polenta</p> <p>Notice the difference in texture from Tuesday's roasted thighs \u2014 same cut of meat, entirely different result because of heat and moisture.</p> Component Recipe Protein Braised chicken thighs in a rich tomato-caper sauce Starch Crusty bread to mop the sauce, or polenta <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Crispy Braised Chicken with Tomatoes, Carrots, and Kale \u2014 Different vegetables, same braising logic \u2014 notice the deep sear he builds before any liquid goes in.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#thursday-off","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>Reflect: which of the three methods you used this week produced the best flavor on the same cut of chicken, and why? Write it down \u2014 one sentence.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#friday-steaming-and-poaching-gentle-wet-heat","title":"Friday \u2014 Steaming and Poaching: Gentle, Wet Heat","text":"<p>Skill: Wet heat keeps food moist and tender but produces no browning. It's ideal for delicate proteins and vegetables where you want to preserve texture and color. The trick: control your temperature. A hard boil beats up delicate proteins; a gentle simmer protects them.</p> <p>Full Meal: Perfect Poached Salmon + Steamed Bok Choy with Garlic Sauce + Steamed rice</p> Component Recipe Protein Gently poached salmon \u2014 silky, delicate, nothing like a seared fillet Veg Steamed bok choy, dressed simply with garlic and sesame Starch Steamed rice"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#saturday-project-meal-spatchcocked-roast-chicken","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Spatchcocked Roast Chicken","text":"<p>Skill: Spatchcocking (butterflying) a whole chicken removes the backbone, flattens the bird, and allows it to roast evenly in about half the time of a trussed bird. You'll use your knife skills from Weeks 1\u20132 and your roasting knowledge from this week. The result: the crispiest skin you've ever made at home.</p> <p>Full Meal: Spatchcocked Roast Chicken + Roasted Potatoes + Simple Green Salad with Vinaigrette</p> <p>Skill targets: Even butterflying, dry skin before roasting, proper resting time (10 minutes) before carving.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Cook a Perfect Roast Chicken (Spatchcock it!) \u00b7 Spatchcock Roast Chicken \u2014 The Fastest, Juiciest Method \u2014 He's done this twice; compare both approaches and borrow what you like.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#sunday-off","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF","text":""},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#week-4-dry-heat-mastery-the-benchmark-cook","title":"Week 4 \u2014 Dry Heat Mastery + The Benchmark Cook","text":"<p>This week you'll revisit dry-heat methods with beef and fish, and end with your first real benchmark: a complete multi-component dinner cooked with no recipes open in front of you.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#monday-searing-steak-the-art-of-doing-nothing","title":"Monday \u2014 Searing Steak: The Art of Doing Nothing","text":"<p>Skill: Put the steak in a screaming hot cast iron pan. Now don't touch it. The instinct to move, prod, and flip food constantly is the enemy of a good sear. Let the Maillard reaction happen. The steak will release from the pan when it's ready to flip. If you have to force it, it's not ready.</p> <p>Full Meal: Perfect Pan-Seared Steak with Butter Basting + Creamy Mashed Potatoes + Simple Saut\u00e9ed Green Beans</p> Component Recipe Protein Ribeye or NY strip, pan-seared in cast iron, basted in butter, thyme, and garlic Starch Ultra-creamy mashed potatoes (use more butter than you're comfortable with) Veg Green beans saut\u00e9ed in the steak pan drippings <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: POV How to Cook a Steak \u2014 Watch before you turn on the pan. Notice what \"don't touch it\" actually looks like in real time.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#tuesday-high-heat-fish-crispy-skin-without-fear","title":"Tuesday \u2014 High-Heat Fish: Crispy Skin Without Fear","text":"<p>Skill: Fish with crispy skin requires a hot, well-oiled pan and patience. Press the fish gently against the pan for the first 30 seconds to prevent curling. Then leave it alone. Cook 80% of the way on the skin side. Flip only once, finish for 60 seconds on the flesh side.</p> <p>Full Meal: Crispy Pan-Seared Salmon + Roasted Asparagus + Simple Arugula and Fennel Salad</p> Component Recipe Protein Crispy-skinned salmon fillet, finished with lemon and capers Veg Roasted asparagus (high-heat oven, single layer, very dry) Salad Arugula salad alongside"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#wednesday-broiling-overhead-heat","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Broiling: Overhead Heat","text":"<p>Skill: Broiling is essentially an upside-down grill \u2014 radiant heat comes from above. It's ideal for finishing dishes (melting cheese, charring a surface) or for cooking thin items quickly. Keep the rack close to the element and watch constantly. Broilers operate at max heat and burn food in seconds.</p> <p>Full Meal: Broiled Salmon with Miso Glaze + Saut\u00e9ed Bok Choy + Steamed rice</p> Component Recipe Protein Miso-glazed salmon under the broiler \u2014 8 minutes, no flipping needed Veg Saut\u00e9ed or steamed bok choy Starch Steamed rice <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Kenji's Cooking Show | Miso-Glazed Salmon \u2014 This is the exact dish \u2014 compare his glaze timing and broiler distance to yours.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#thursday-off_1","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\u23f1\ufe0f Speed benchmark: Dice one onion and time yourself. Compare to Week 2 Friday. Write both numbers down.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#friday-recap-cook-no-recipes","title":"Friday \u2014 Recap Cook: No Recipes","text":"<p>Skill challenge: Tonight you cook a full meal using only methods you've learned in Weeks 3\u20134, but with no recipe open. Pick a protein in your fridge. Choose a heat method. Season it. Make a simple sauce from the pan drippings. Cook a vegetable. Plate it.</p> <p>If you need to glance at times and temperatures, that's fine. But close the recipe tab.</p> <p>This is the week's most important session.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#saturday-project-meal-braised-short-ribs","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Braised Short Ribs","text":"<p>Skill: The full braise from start to finish. This is a long cook (3\u20134 hours) but almost entirely passive \u2014 you sear the ribs in batches, build the braising liquid, and let the oven do the rest. The hardest part is the patience.</p> <p>Full Meal: Braised Short Ribs + Creamy Polenta + Roasted Root Vegetables</p> Component Recipe Protein Bone-in beef short ribs braised in red wine and beef stock until they collapse Starch Creamy parmesan polenta (the perfect landing pad for the braising liquid) Veg Roasted root vegetables (carrots, parsnips, turnips) <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How Braises Get Tender \u00b7 Ask Kenji | How Can I Tell If My Braise Is Done? \u2014 Watch before you start; the short explains collagen breakdown in 60 seconds.</p> <p>Skill targets: A deep, dark sear on every side of the ribs before braising. Correct liquid level (one-third up the meat, not submerged). Internal temp of 200\u00b0F+ for collagen breakdown.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#the-science-of-the-sear","title":"The Science of the Sear","text":"<p>Understanding why a brown crust forms changes how you cook everything forever. The Maillard reaction is probably the single most important piece of food science a home cook can learn.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Right Way to Use a Meat Thermometer \u2014 Temperature is the only honest answer to \"is it done?\" This is the guide.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#braising-why-low-and-slow-works","title":"Braising: Why Low and Slow Works","text":"<p>You did a full braise this week. Here's the architecture behind it.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Food Lab on Resting Meat \u2014 Carries directly into braising logic: what happens to proteins and juice as meat cooks and rests.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Cooking With Olive Oil: Should You Fry and Sear in It? \u2014 The oil question every cook has. Answered properly.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#understanding-cooking-fats","title":"Understanding Cooking Fats","text":"<p>Oil isn't just oil. Fat choice affects flavor, smoke point, and technique \u2014 this week you used several.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 What's a Smoke Point and Why Does It Matter? \u2014 The concept behind why you use butter for finishing but not for searing.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda CookWise by Shirley Corriher \u2014 Corriher is a food scientist who explains not just how to cook, but why techniques work at a chemical level. The chapters on searing, browning, and fat behavior are the most practical food-science reading available for the exact techniques you did this week.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Weeks 3\u20134 Quick Reference \u2014 Heat &amp; Cooking Methods","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/quick-ref.html#week-3-recipes","title":"Week 3 Recipes","text":"Day Dish Method Link Mon Saut\u00e9ed Chicken Breasts with Pan Sauce + Saut\u00e9ed Zucchini + Steamed Rice Saut\u00e9 Chicken \u00b7 Zucchini Tue Sheet Pan Chicken Thighs + Roasted Veg + Green Salad Roast (dry) Chicken \u00b7 Salad Wed Braised Chicken Thighs with Tomatoes and Capers + Bread/Polenta Braise (wet) Recipe Thu OFF Read: cooking methods Article Fri Perfect Poached Salmon + Steamed Bok Choy + Rice Poach / Steam Salmon \u00b7 Bok Choy Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Spatchcocked Roast Chicken + Roasted Potatoes + Green Salad Roast Chicken \u00b7 Potatoes \u00b7 Salad"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/quick-ref.html#week-4-recipes","title":"Week 4 Recipes","text":"Day Dish Method Link Mon Pan-Seared Steak (Butter Basted) + Mashed Potatoes + Green Beans Sear (cast iron) Steak \u00b7 Mash \u00b7 Beans Tue Crispy Pan-Seared Salmon + Roasted Asparagus + Arugula Salad Sear (fish) Salmon \u00b7 Asparagus Wed Broiled Miso-Glazed Salmon + Bok Choy + Steamed Rice Broil Salmon \u00b7 Bok Choy Thu OFF \u23f1\ufe0f Onion dice speed benchmark Read Fri No-recipe recap cook \u2014 use what's in your fridge Your choice \u2014 Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Braised Short Ribs + Creamy Polenta + Roasted Root Veg Braise Ribs \u00b7 Polenta \u00b7 Veg"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/quick-ref.html#key-reminders","title":"Key Reminders","text":"<ul> <li>Before every session: Hone the knife. Pat proteins completely dry.</li> <li>Don't crowd the pan. One layer, high heat, batches if needed.</li> <li>Friday is a freeform cook \u2014 close the recipes, use the techniques.</li> <li>Saturday short ribs: 3\u20134 hours. Start early. Internal temp 200\u00b0F+ for full collagen breakdown.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 3\u20134: Heat &amp; Cooking Methods","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Buy week 3 proteins and produce at the start of Week 3, week 4 mid-week. The short ribs for Saturday of Week 4 should be bought Friday or early Saturday morning \u2014 they need 3\u20134 hours in the oven.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/shopping-list.html#proteins","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins","text":"<p>Week 3: - [ ] Boneless, skinless chicken breasts \u2014 4 pieces (Week 3 Mon) - [ ] Bone-in, skin-on chicken thighs \u2014 6 pieces (Week 3 Tue sheet pan + Wed braise) - [ ] Salmon fillets (skin-on) \u2014 2 pieces (Week 3 Fri poached) - [ ] Whole chicken \u2014 1 large (Week 3 Sat spatchcocked roast)</p> <p>Week 4: - [ ] Ribeye or NY strip steaks \u2014 2 (Week 4 Mon, 1\u20131.5\" thick \u2014 don't go thin) - [ ] Salmon fillets (skin-on) \u2014 4 pieces (Week 4 Tue seared + Wed broiled/miso) - [ ] Bone-in beef short ribs \u2014 3\u20134 lbs (Week 4 Sat PROJECT \u2014 buy early, they're expensive; ask the butcher)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce","text":"<p>Week 3: - [ ] Zucchini \u2014 3 medium (Week 3 Mon + leftover use) - [ ] Bell peppers (red and yellow) \u2014 4 (Week 3 Tue sheet pan + Wed braise) - [ ] Onions (yellow) \u2014 4 (braise base, mirepoix) - [ ] Bok choy \u2014 1 large head (Week 3 Fri) - [ ] Potatoes (Yukon Gold) \u2014 3 lbs total for Week 3 Sat and Week 4 Mon mash - [ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads - [ ] Lemons \u2014 3 - [ ] Fresh thyme and rosemary \u2014 1 bunch each - [ ] Mixed greens \u2014 2 bags (salads)</p> <p>Week 4: - [ ] Asparagus \u2014 1 bunch (Week 4 Tue) - [ ] Arugula \u2014 2 bags (Week 4 Tue salad) - [ ] Bok choy \u2014 1 head (Week 4 Wed) - [ ] Green beans \u2014 1 lb (Week 4 Mon) - [ ] Root vegetables (carrots, parsnips, turnips) \u2014 2 lbs total (Week 4 Sat)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/shopping-list.html#dairy","title":"\ud83e\uddc0 Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 3 sticks (basting, pan sauces, mash)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 1 cup (Week 4 Mon mashed potatoes)</li> <li>[ ] Parmesan \u2014 4 oz (arugula salad)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry-goods","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Pantry &amp; Dry Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] White wine (dry) \u2014 1 bottle (pan sauces, braise \u2014 use something drinkable)</li> <li>[ ] Red wine (dry) \u2014 1 bottle (Week 4 Sat short rib braise)</li> <li>[ ] Polenta (coarse-ground) \u2014 1 bag (Week 3 Wed + Week 4 Sat)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken stock \u2014 64 oz total (sauces, braise liquid)</li> <li>[ ] Beef stock \u2014 32 oz (Week 4 Sat short ribs)</li> <li>[ ] Canned whole peeled tomatoes \u2014 2 cans (Week 3 Wed braise)</li> <li>[ ] Capers \u2014 1 jar (Week 3 Wed braise)</li> <li>[ ] Black olives (pitted) \u2014 1 can or jar (Week 3 Wed optional)</li> <li>[ ] White miso paste \u2014 1 container (Week 4 Wed glazed salmon)</li> <li>[ ] Mirin \u2014 1 bottle (miso glaze)</li> <li>[ ] Sake or dry sherry \u2014 small bottle (miso glaze)</li> <li>[ ] Rice (long grain or jasmine) \u2014 2 cups (Week 3 Mon + Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Neutral oil \u2014 for high-heat searing</li> <li>[ ] Extra-virgin olive oil</li> <li>[ ] Shallots \u2014 1 bag (pan sauces)</li> <li>[ ] Dijon mustard \u2014 1 jar (vinaigrette + Week 4 Sat marinade)</li> <li>[ ] Canola or vegetable oil (Week 4 Sat long braise)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/shopping-list.html#notes","title":"\ud83d\udcdd Notes","text":"<p>Week 4 Saturday \u2014 Braised Short Ribs (the big one): This is a 3\u20134 hour cook. Buy the ribs fresh on Friday or Saturday morning. Pat them completely dry, salt generously, and sear in batches over very high heat until a deep brown crust forms on all sides. Don't rush this step. The fond from the sear is most of the sauce's flavor.</p> <p>Week 3 Spatchcock (Sat): Ask yourself the question before you buy: do I have kitchen shears? If not, buy a pair. A sharp chef's knife works too, but shears make spatchcocking dramatically easier.</p> <p>Miso glaze (Week 4 Wed): Mix equal parts white miso, mirin, and sake with a bit of sugar. Marinate salmon for 24 hours minimum for the full effect. Make it Tuesday night.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html","title":"\ud83e\udd63 Weeks 5\u20136: The 5 Mother Sauces","text":"<p>\"Master these five sauces and you can make virtually any sauce on earth.\"</p> <p>Quick Reference: \u2192 Week 5\u20136 Recipe Quick Ref</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#before-you-start-week-5","title":"Before You Start Week 5","text":"<p>Read this first:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The 5 French Mother Sauces, Explained</li> </ul> <p>The five mother sauces are: B\u00e9chamel (milk + roux), Velout\u00e9 (stock + roux), Espagnole (dark stock + roux + tomato), Hollandaise (emulsified egg yolk + butter), and Sauce Tomat (tomato-based).</p> <p>Four out of five start with a roux. Learn the roux and you learn four sauces at once.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#week-5-roux-based-sauces","title":"Week 5 \u2014 Roux-Based Sauces","text":""},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#monday-bechamel-the-white-sauce","title":"Monday \u2014 B\u00e9chamel: The White Sauce","text":"<p>Skill: A b\u00e9chamel is a white roux (equal parts butter and flour, cooked briefly until it smells nutty but hasn't browned) whisked with warm milk. The key is adding the milk gradually while whisking constantly, and cooking it long enough to lose the raw flour taste. Season with salt, white pepper, and a pinch of nutmeg.</p> <p>Full Meal: Baked Mac and Cheese (B\u00e9chamel-Based) + Simple Green Salad</p> <p>You'll make the b\u00e9chamel from scratch and transform it into a Mornay sauce (b\u00e9chamel + cheese). Then it becomes mac and cheese. This is the mother sauce \u2192 daughter sauce chain in action.</p> Component Recipe Main Baked mac and cheese (the whole dish) Starch Pasta (built-in) Salad Simple green salad to cut through the richness"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#tuesday-veloute-stock-instead-of-milk","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Velout\u00e9: Stock Instead of Milk","text":"<p>Skill: A velout\u00e9 starts with the same white roux as b\u00e9chamel but uses chicken (or fish, or veal) stock instead of milk. The result is lighter, more savory, and more versatile as a sauce base. It should coat a spoon lightly when done \u2014 if it's too thick, thin it with more warm stock.</p> <p>Full Meal: Chicken Pot Pie with Velout\u00e9 Base + Simple green salad</p> <p>The pot pie filling is a classic chicken velout\u00e9 extended with vegetables and cream. You're learning the mother sauce and a classic comfort food simultaneously.</p> Component Recipe Protein Chicken (cooked and pulled into the filling) Starch The pastry crust Veg Peas, carrots, and onion in the filling Salad Simple green salad alongside"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#wednesday-sauce-tomat-the-slow-tomato","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Sauce Tomat: The Slow Tomato","text":"<p>Skill: The mother tomato sauce is not marinara. It's a deeply flavored, long-cooked sauce built on a pork fat base, mirepoix, tomatoes, stock, and aromatics. The key is patience \u2014 low heat, long time, and tasting as the sauce develops. Learn to season in layers, not all at once.</p> <p>Full Meal: The Best Slow-Cooked Bolognese</p> <p>Bolognese takes 3\u20134 hours. Make it on a Wednesday when you can let it simmer while doing other things.</p> Component Recipe Protein Ground beef and pork, slow-cooked into the sauce Starch Fresh tagliatelle or good dried pasta Veg Mirepoix (in the sauce) + Classic Caesar Salad alongside <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Rag\u00f9 Bolognese is Easy, Actually \u2014 Compare how he builds the soffrito and when he adds each liquid \u2014 the patience is the technique.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#thursday-off","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: The Five Mother Sauces Every Cook Should Know</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#friday-espagnole-and-demi-glace-simplified","title":"Friday \u2014 Espagnole and Demi-Glace (Simplified)","text":"<p>Skill: Espagnole is a brown roux-based sauce made with dark beef stock and tomato. The demi-glace is espagnole reduced by half until it becomes intensely flavored and glossy. Tonight you make a simplified version \u2014 the same concept, without a days-long reduction.</p> <p>Full Meal: Steak with Red Wine Pan Sauce + Creamy Mashed Potatoes + Roasted Broccolini</p> <p>The pan sauce is your simplified Espagnole: browned bits from the steak, deglazed with wine, reduced with stock. It tastes like a restaurant made it because it is the technique restaurants use.</p> Component Recipe Protein Pan-seared steak with a red wine reduction pan sauce Starch Ultra-creamy mashed potatoes Veg Roasted broccolini <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The Best Way to Cook Steak: The Reverse Sear \u2014 A different approach to the same result \u2014 watch how he thinks about internal temperature versus crust formation.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#saturday-project-meal-greek-moussaka","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Greek Moussaka","text":"<p>Skill: A synthesis dish \u2014 you'll make a tomato-based lamb meat sauce and a b\u00e9chamel and roast eggplant, then layer them together and bake. Uses two of the five mother sauces in a single dish.</p> <p>Full Meal: Greek Moussaka + Greek Salad + Crusty bread</p> Component Recipe Protein Ground lamb or beef in the tomato layer Sauce B\u00e9chamel on top, baked to a golden crust Veg Roasted eggplant and potato layers Salad Greek salad alongside <p>Skill targets: Smooth, lump-free b\u00e9chamel. Uniform eggplant slices (Week 2 callback). Full mise en place before assembly.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#week-6-emulsified-sauces-vinaigrette","title":"Week 6 \u2014 Emulsified Sauces + Vinaigrette","text":""},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#monday-hollandaise-the-emulsion","title":"Monday \u2014 Hollandaise: The Emulsion","text":"<p>Skill: Hollandaise is the most technically demanding of the five mother sauces \u2014 an emulsion of egg yolks and clarified butter, stabilized by the lecithin in the yolks. The keys: gentle heat (too hot and the eggs scramble), constant whisking, adding the butter slowly. Use a double boiler and your thermometer tonight.</p> <p>Full Meal: Eggs Benedict with Hollandaise \u2014 yes, breakfast for dinner. It's legitimate when it teaches you hollandaise.</p> Component Recipe Protein Canadian bacon, poached eggs Sauce Hollandaise (your skill for tonight) Starch English muffins, toasted Veg/Salad Simple Watercress Salad alongside <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Eggs Benedict the Classic Way \u2014 Watch how he handles the hollandaise temperature \u2014 the moment it breaks and how to rescue it.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#tuesday-mayonnaise-emulsion-without-heat","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Mayonnaise: Emulsion Without Heat","text":"<p>Skill: Mayo is a cold emulsion \u2014 egg yolk, acid (lemon or vinegar), and oil, whisked until stable. Same principle as hollandaise (fat suspended in water-based liquid via lecithin) but much more forgiving. Start with a small amount of oil and add it very slowly at first to establish the emulsion before adding more quickly.</p> <p>Full Meal: Seafood Rolls with Homemade Mayo + Classic Coleslaw</p> <p>Make the mayo from scratch. Use it in the roll filling and the coleslaw.</p> Component Recipe Protein Shrimp, scallop, or lobster roll Veg Coleslaw made with your homemade mayo Starch Brioche or potato rolls <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Mayonnaise \u2014 Watch the oil addition speed \u2014 this is where the emulsion either forms or breaks.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#wednesday-the-vinaigrette-a-temporary-emulsion","title":"Wednesday \u2014 The Vinaigrette: A Temporary Emulsion","text":"<p>Skill: A vinaigrette is an unstable emulsion \u2014 oil and acid mixed together, which separate unless stabilized with an emulsifier like Dijon mustard or honey. The classic ratio is 3:1 oil to acid. Taste it on a piece of bread (not a spoon) to understand how it will actually taste on food.</p> <p>Full Meal: Pan-Seared Salmon Ni\u00e7oise Salad \u2014 a full composed dinner salad, not a side.</p> <p>Make the vinaigrette from scratch. Use it as the dressing and as a marinade for the salmon.</p> Component Recipe Protein Seared salmon or tuna Veg Green beans, olives, tomatoes, hard-boiled eggs Starch Boiled potatoes (dressed warm with the vinaigrette \u2014 they absorb it better) <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make a Ni\u00e7oise Salad \u2014 This is the exact dish \u2014 compare how he sequences the components and when the vinaigrette goes on.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#thursday-off_1","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: How to Make Any Salad Dressing Without a Recipe</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#friday-pan-sauce-the-working-sauce","title":"Friday \u2014 Pan Sauce: The Working Sauce","text":"<p>Skill: A pan sauce isn't one of the five mother sauces, but it's descended from all of them. After searing a protein, deglaze the pan (scraping the fond), reduce a liquid (wine, stock), and finish with butter. This is how restaurants make almost every sauce on their menu.</p> <p>Full Meal: Pork Chops with Apple-Cider Pan Sauce + Roasted Sweet Potatoes + Simple Green Salad</p> Component Recipe Protein Pan-seared pork chops with apple-cider pan sauce Starch Roasted sweet potatoes Salad Simple green salad with your from-scratch vinaigrette <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Pan-Seared Pork Chops with Apple Pan Sauce \u2014 This is the exact dish \u2014 compare when he deglazes and how he reduces the sauce to a glaze.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#saturday-project-meal-a-classic-french-bistro-dinner-3-courses","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Classic French Bistro Dinner (3 Courses)","text":"<p>Skill: Ties together everything from Weeks 5\u20136. Pan sauce, vinaigrette, and a three-course French bistro-style dinner at home \u2014 everything on the table at the same time.</p> Course Dish Link Starter French Onion Dip with Homemade Potato Chips Recipe Main Steak Frites with Pan Sauce Recipe Salad Classic Lyonnaise Salad (Fris\u00e9e aux Lardons) Recipe <p>Skill targets: Properly executed pan sauce. Vinaigrette made from memory. Everything on the table at the same time.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#the-architecture-of-french-sauce","title":"The Architecture of French Sauce","text":"<p>The five mother sauces aren't really recipes \u2014 they're frameworks. Understanding the progression (mother \u2192 daughter sauces) transforms how you read any European recipe.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Butter-Basting: The Technique Behind Restaurant Flavor \u2014 A pan sauce technique that applies directly to everything you built this week.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Make Brown Butter \u2014 Beurre noisette is one step past clarified butter and one of the most useful flavors in cooking.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#emulsification-why-sauces-break-and-how-to-fix-them","title":"Emulsification: Why Sauces Break (and How to Fix Them)","text":"<p>The reason hollandaise breaks and mayonnaise holds is the same \u2014 it's all about emulsification. Understanding the physics lets you rescue disasters and prevent them.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Guide to Cooking With Wine \u2014 Wine reductions are the backbone of dozens of French pan sauces. What wine does when it cooks is worth understanding.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Jacques P\u00e9pin's omelette \u2014 His 30-second French omelette is a direct counterpart to what you've been building: technique over time, speed as the result of understanding.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Gordon Ramsay's pan sauce \u2014 Overexplained in some ways but very clear on the mechanics of building flavor in a pan after a sear.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Jacques P\u00e9pin: New Complete Techniques \u2014 The definitive classical French reference from the man who best bridges professional technique and home cooking. Goes deep on every sauce category.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Weeks 5\u20136 Quick Reference \u2014 The 5 Mother Sauces","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/quick-ref.html#week-5-recipes","title":"Week 5 Recipes","text":"Day Dish Sauce Link Mon Baked Mac and Cheese + Green Salad B\u00e9chamel \u2192 Mornay Mac &amp; Cheese \u00b7 Salad Tue Chicken Pot Pie + Green Salad Velout\u00e9 Pot Pie Wed Slow-Cooked Bolognese + Fresh Pasta + Caesar Salad Sauce Tomat Bolognese \u00b7 Caesar Thu OFF Read: mother sauces Article Fri Steak with Red Wine Pan Sauce + Mashed Potatoes + Roasted Broccolini Espagnole (simplified) Steak/Sauce \u00b7 Mash \u00b7 Broccolini Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Greek Moussaka + Greek Salad + Bread B\u00e9chamel + Sauce Tomat Moussaka \u00b7 Salad"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/quick-ref.html#week-6-recipes","title":"Week 6 Recipes","text":"Day Dish Sauce Link Mon Eggs Benedict with Hollandaise + Watercress Salad Hollandaise Eggs Benedict \u00b7 Salad Tue Seafood Roll + Classic Coleslaw Homemade Mayo Seafood Roll \u00b7 Coleslaw Wed Pan-Seared Salmon Ni\u00e7oise Salad Vinaigrette Ni\u00e7oise Thu OFF Read: vinaigrette ratios Article Fri Pork Chops with Apple-Cider Pan Sauce + Roasted Sweet Potatoes + Salad Pan sauce Pork Chops \u00b7 Sweet Potato Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: 3-Course French Bistro Dinner Pan sauce + Vinaigrette French Onion Dip \u00b7 Steak Frites \u00b7 Lyonnaise Salad"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/quick-ref.html#the-5-mother-sauces-cheat-sheet","title":"The 5 Mother Sauces \u2014 Cheat Sheet","text":"Sauce Base This Week's Dish B\u00e9chamel Butter + flour roux + milk Mac &amp; cheese, Moussaka top Velout\u00e9 Butter + flour roux + stock Chicken pot pie Espagnole Dark roux + dark stock + tomato Steak pan sauce (simplified) Sauce Tomat Tomato + mirepoix + pork fat Bolognese, Moussaka bottom Hollandaise Egg yolk + clarified butter (emulsion) Eggs Benedict <p>Ratio to memorize: Vinaigrette = 3 parts oil : 1 part acid + Dijon to stabilize.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 5\u20136: The 5 Mother Sauces","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Weeks 5\u20136 are butter, flour, and eggs weeks. Buy your dairy in full at the start \u2014 you'll go through more butter and milk than you expect. The moussaka (Week 5 Sat) and eggs benedict (Week 6 Mon) both require prep the day before.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/shopping-list.html#proteins","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins","text":"<p>Week 5: - [ ] Ground beef \u2014 1 lb (Bolognese + moussaka) - [ ] Ground pork \u2014 \u00bd lb (Bolognese \u2014 adds richness; can sub with all beef) - [ ] Pancetta or guanciale \u2014 4 oz (Bolognese) - [ ] Bone-in chicken thighs \u2014 4 pieces (chicken pot pie filling) - [ ] Ribeye or NY strip steaks \u2014 2 (Week 5 Fri red wine pan sauce) - [ ] Ground lamb (or more beef) \u2014 1 lb (moussaka meat layer)</p> <p>Week 6: - [ ] Canadian bacon (back bacon) \u2014 8 slices (Week 6 Mon Eggs Benedict) - [ ] Lobster (pre-cooked) or large shrimp \u2014 1 lb meat (Week 6 Tue seafood roll) - [ ] Salmon fillets \u2014 2 pieces (Week 6 Wed Ni\u00e7oise) - [ ] Bone-in pork chops (thick-cut, 1.5\") \u2014 2 (Week 6 Fri) - [ ] Thick-cut bacon or lardons \u2014 6 oz (Week 6 Sat Lyonnaise salad) - [ ] Ribeye or hanger steaks \u2014 2 (Week 6 Sat steak frites)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce","text":"<p>Week 5: - [ ] Eggplant \u2014 2 large (moussaka \u2014 salt and drain before using) - [ ] Potatoes (Yukon Gold) \u2014 2 lbs (moussaka base layer) - [ ] Carrots \u2014 3 (Bolognese mirepoix + pot pie) - [ ] Celery \u2014 1 bunch (Bolognese + pot pie) - [ ] Onions (yellow) \u2014 4 (mirepoix, multiple uses) - [ ] Broccolini \u2014 2 bunches (Week 5 Fri) - [ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads - [ ] Roma tomatoes \u2014 4 (Greek salad) - [ ] English cucumbers \u2014 2 (Greek salad) - [ ] Red onion \u2014 2 (Greek salad + Bolognese) - [ ] Fresh flat-leaf parsley \u2014 1 bunch - [ ] Mixed greens \u2014 2 bags (salads) - [ ] Romaine lettuce \u2014 2 hearts (Caesar salad)</p> <p>Week 6: - [ ] Watercress \u2014 2 bunches (Week 6 Mon) - [ ] Green cabbage \u2014 \u00bd head (coleslaw) - [ ] Carrots \u2014 2 (coleslaw) - [ ] Baby potatoes or fingerlings \u2014 1 lb (Ni\u00e7oise) - [ ] Green beans \u2014 \u00bd lb (Ni\u00e7oise) - [ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 1 pint (Ni\u00e7oise) - [ ] Sweet potatoes \u2014 2 large (Week 6 Fri) - [ ] Fris\u00e9e or endive \u2014 2 heads (Week 6 Sat Lyonnaise salad) - [ ] Apples \u2014 2 (apple-cider pan sauce for pork chops) - [ ] Russet potatoes \u2014 3 lbs (Week 6 Sat frites) - [ ] Lemons \u2014 4 - [ ] Fresh tarragon \u2014 1 small bunch (hollandaise + optional)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/shopping-list.html#dairy-eggs","title":"\ud83e\uddc0 Dairy &amp; Eggs","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 2 dozen minimum (hollandaise uses 4 yolks; Ni\u00e7oise needs hard-boiled; omelette practice; cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e next block. Buy extra.)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 4 sticks (beurre blanc, hollandaise, roux for b\u00e9chamel/velout\u00e9, mashed sauces)</li> <li>[ ] Whole milk \u2014 \u00bd gallon (b\u00e9chamel, moussaka topping, pot pie sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 1 pint (moussaka topping, pot pie, pork chop sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Sharp cheddar \u2014 8 oz, block (mac &amp; cheese)</li> <li>[ ] Gruy\u00e8re \u2014 8 oz (moussaka b\u00e9chamel + mac topping)</li> <li>[ ] Parmesan (block) \u2014 8 oz (Caesar + Bolognese)</li> <li>[ ] Feta cheese \u2014 6 oz (Greek salad)</li> <li>[ ] Kalamata olives \u2014 1 jar (Greek salad + Ni\u00e7oise)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry-goods","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Pantry &amp; Dry Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] All-purpose flour \u2014 2 cups (roux for 3 mother sauces this week)</li> <li>[ ] Elbow macaroni \u2014 1 lb (baked mac)</li> <li>[ ] Dried pasta (rigatoni or tagliatelle) \u2014 1 lb (Bolognese)</li> <li>[ ] Dry breadcrumbs \u2014 1 cup (mac &amp; cheese topping)</li> <li>[ ] Puff pastry or pie dough \u2014 2 sheets (pot pie)</li> <li>[ ] Peas (frozen) \u2014 1 cup (pot pie)</li> <li>[ ] Canned whole peeled tomatoes \u2014 4 cans (Bolognese + shakshuka + moussaka)</li> <li>[ ] Tomato paste \u2014 1 small can</li> <li>[ ] Chicken stock \u2014 64 oz (pot pie velout\u00e9 + ramen)</li> <li>[ ] Beef stock \u2014 32 oz (pan sauces, moussaka)</li> <li>[ ] Red wine (full bottle, drinking quality) \u2014 1 (Bolognese + pan sauce)</li> <li>[ ] White wine (dry) \u2014 1 bottle (hollandaise, pan sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Apple cider or apple cider vinegar \u2014 1 bottle (Week 6 Fri pork chops)</li> <li>[ ] Dijon mustard \u2014 1 jar</li> <li>[ ] Capers \u2014 1 jar (Ni\u00e7oise salad)</li> <li>[ ] Tinned anchovies \u2014 1 can (Caesar salad)</li> <li>[ ] White wine vinegar \u2014 1 bottle (hollandaise poaching liquid)</li> <li>[ ] Cinnamon stick, allspice, bay leaves (moussaka \u2014 these make it taste right)</li> <li>[ ] Mayonnaise \u2014 1 jar (or make your own for coleslaw)</li> <li>[ ] Neutral oil \u2014 for frites (you'll need 1 quart of oil if deep-frying; shallow fry is easier)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/shopping-list.html#bread","title":"\ud83e\udd56 Bread","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Hot dog buns (top-split preferred) \u2014 4 (lobster/shrimp rolls, Week 6 Tue)</li> <li>[ ] English muffins \u2014 4 (Week 6 Mon Eggs Benedict)</li> <li>[ ] Crusty baguette (Week 5 Wed, for serving with Bolognese)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/shopping-list.html#notes","title":"\ud83d\udcdd Notes","text":"<p>Moussaka (Week 5 Sat) \u2014 the day-before prep: Slice eggplant, salt generously, and let drain on paper towels for 30 minutes. This removes bitterness and prevents a watery moussaka. B\u00e9chamel also benefits from being made fresh.</p> <p>Lobster rolls (Week 6 Tue): Pre-cooked whole lobster from a fishmonger is easiest. Or buy frozen lobster tails and steam them. Large shrimp are a fine substitute if lobster is cost-prohibitive.</p> <p>Steak frites (Week 6 Sat): Frites need a double-fry (once at 325\u00b0F to cook through, once at 375\u00b0F to crisp). Plan to start them 30 minutes before the steaks. Or make oven fries at 450\u00b0F \u2014 not quite the same but much less mess.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html","title":"\ud83e\udd5a Weeks 7\u20138: Stocks &amp; Eggs","text":"<p>\"Stocks are the foundation of professional cooking. Eggs are the chef's ultimate test.\"</p> <p>Quick Reference: \u2192 Week 7\u20138 Recipe Quick Ref</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#before-you-start-week-7","title":"Before You Start Week 7","text":"<p>Read these first:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Difference Between Stock and Broth</li> </ul> <p>The Week 7 Rule: Get your frozen chicken carcass from Week 2 out of the freezer Sunday night. You're going to use it.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#week-7-stocks-broths","title":"Week 7 \u2014 Stocks &amp; Broths","text":""},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#monday-chicken-stock-from-scratch","title":"Monday \u2014 Chicken Stock from Scratch","text":"<p>Skill: Cold water start, gentle simmer (never boil), skim the foam in the first 20 minutes, don't stir. A good stock simmers for 3\u20134 hours. It should be golden, clear (not murky), and taste of chicken without being aggressively salty. Cool it in an ice bath, then refrigerate. A proper stock should gel when cold \u2014 that's the gelatin from the bones.</p> <p>This takes time but is mostly passive. Start it when you get home, let it simmer while you do other things.</p> <p>Full Meal: Quick Weeknight Ramen Using Homemade Stock</p> Component Recipe Broth Your homemade chicken stock, seasoned with soy and mirin Protein Soft-boiled eggs, chashu pork or rotisserie chicken, scallions Starch Ramen noodles"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#tuesday-pan-sauces-from-real-stock","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Pan Sauces from Real Stock","text":"<p>Skill: Now that you have fresh stock, you understand why pan sauces taste so much better when made with real stock instead of water or canned broth. The gelatin creates body and silkiness that nothing else can replicate. Tonight's lesson: the difference is in your freezer.</p> <p>Full Meal: Chicken with Rich Pan Sauce (using your homemade stock) + Roasted Potatoes + Bitter Greens Salad</p> Component Recipe Protein Saut\u00e9ed chicken with a pan sauce made from your Week 7 stock Starch Crispy roasted potatoes Salad Bitter greens salad with a sharp vinaigrette"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#wednesday-fish-stock-fumet","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Fish Stock + Fumet","text":"<p>Skill: Fish stock (fumet) takes only 20\u201330 minutes \u2014 fish bones give up their gelatin quickly and become bitter if cooked too long. Ask your fishmonger for frames (carcasses) or use shrimp shells. Aromatics are lighter: white wine, leek, fennel, parsley stems, bay leaf.</p> <p>Full Meal: Bouillabaisse \u2014 the classic Proven\u00e7al fish stew, built on your fresh fish stock</p> Component Recipe Protein Mixed seafood \u2014 shrimp, clams, white fish Stock Your fresh fish fumet Starch Grilled bread rubbed with garlic (rouille on the side) Veg Fennel, leek, tomato in the stew"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#thursday-soups-a-taxonomy","title":"Thursday \u2014 Soups: A Taxonomy","text":"<p>Skill: Understanding soup as a category \u2014 not recipes, but architecture. Tonight you make one pur\u00e9e soup and learn how the same structure produces every pur\u00e9e soup in existence.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read first: How to Make Any Pur\u00e9e Soup \u2014 the technique scales to any vegetable.</p> <p>The five soup families \u2014 know these and you can improvise forever:</p> Family Technique Example Broth/consomm\u00e9 Clear liquid, flavored by solids Chicken noodle, pho, ramen broth Pur\u00e9e Cooked vegetables blended smooth; no cream needed Butternut squash, tomato, parsnip Cream soup Pur\u00e9e + cream or b\u00e9chamel for richness and texture Cream of mushroom, vichyssoise Bisque Shellfish shells simmered into the base; always cream-finished Lobster bisque, shrimp bisque Chowder Chunky; potato base; salt pork/bacon; cream-finished New England clam chowder, corn chowder <p>The universal pur\u00e9e method \u2014 memorize this, not any specific recipe: 1. Sweat aromatics (onion, leek, garlic, celery) in fat until soft \u2014 don't brown them 2. Add your main vegetable, cut uniformly so it cooks evenly 3. Add stock (just enough to cover); season lightly now, adjust at the end 4. Simmer until vegetables are completely tender \u2014 they should crush against the pot wall 5. Blend (immersion blender in the pot, or batches in a blender with the vent cracked) 6. Adjust consistency with stock; adjust seasoning. Finish with cream, butter, or acid.</p> <p>Full Meal: Roasted Butternut Squash Soup + crusty bread + simple salad</p> <p>The roasting step is optional but worth it: it caramelizes the squash and adds depth a boiled pur\u00e9e can't match.</p> <p>The professional difference between good and great pur\u00e9e soup: Seasoning at every stage (the aromatics, the stock, and the final adjust), and texture \u2014 it should be silky enough to coat a spoon without being so thick it's porridge. Strain it through a fine mesh sieve if it isn't smooth enough after blending.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Also read: How to Make Restaurant-Quality Stock at Home</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#friday-vegetable-stock-risotto","title":"Friday \u2014 Vegetable Stock + Risotto","text":"<p>Skill: Vegetable stock is the quickest and most approachable. Key: don't over-simmer \u2014 45\u201360 minutes max, or it turns bitter. Tonight you'll use it immediately for risotto, which also teaches you another core technique: the gradual addition of hot liquid while stirring to coax starch from Arborio rice.</p> <p>Full Meal: Parmesan Risotto + Roasted Mushrooms + Simple Arugula Salad</p> Component Recipe Protein Roasted mushrooms (the star) + parmesan as umami Starch Risotto (the main dish) Salad Arugula alongside to cut richness"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#saturday-project-meal-a-whole-soup-kitchen-day","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Whole Soup Kitchen Day","text":"<p>This Saturday you make three things \u2014 stock, soup, and a complete dinner \u2014 that set you up with leftovers and frozen stock for weeks.</p> Time Task Recipe Morning Big batch beef/veal stock (6\u20138 hrs, mostly passive) Homemade Beef Stock Dinner French Onion Soup using your fresh beef stock French Onion Soup Sides Simple Green Salad + good bread Salad <p>Freeze the remaining stock in 1-cup portions. You now have stock in your freezer at all times. This changes your cooking permanently.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#week-8-eggs","title":"Week 8 \u2014 Eggs","text":"<p>\"A chef is judged by their eggs.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#before-you-start-week-8","title":"Before You Start Week 8","text":""},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#monday-the-french-scramble","title":"Monday \u2014 The French Scramble","text":"<p>Skill: French scrambled eggs are not American scrambled eggs. They're cooked low and slow, constantly stirred with a spatula, off and on the heat, until they form soft, creamy, barely-set curds. The result tastes like what restaurants serve for brunch at $22 a plate.</p> <p>Full Meal: French Scrambled Eggs + Smoked Salmon with Cr\u00e8me Fra\u00eeche + Toasted Sourdough + Simple Green Salad</p> <p>A French scramble dinner is a legitimately elegant meal when served with smoked salmon and a sharp green salad.</p> Component Recipe Protein French scrambled eggs + smoked salmon Starch Toasted sourdough Salad Simple green salad <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Really Good Scrambled Eggs \u2014 Same goal, different execution \u2014 notice how often he's moving the pan and when he pulls it off the heat entirely.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#tuesday-the-perfect-poached-egg","title":"Tuesday \u2014 The Perfect Poached Egg","text":"<p>Skill: Fresh eggs, a wide shallow pan, simmering (not boiling) water with a splash of vinegar, a gentle swirl, and confidence. The white should be fully set and the yolk should run when broken. Most home cooks are afraid of poached eggs \u2014 by the end of tonight, you shouldn't be.</p> <p>Full Meal: Poached Eggs Over Saut\u00e9ed Greens with Crispy Bacon + Roasted Tomatoes + Toasted bread</p> Component Recipe Protein Poached eggs + crispy bacon Veg Wilted greens (kale or spinach), roasted cherry tomatoes Starch Good toast <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Truly Foolproof Poached Eggs \u2014 Watch the water temperature and the swirl \u2014 two details that determine whether you get a poached egg or a cloud of egg white.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#wednesday-the-omelette","title":"Wednesday \u2014 The Omelette","text":"<p>Skill: The French omelette is one of the hardest things in cooking to get right \u2014 pale, barely colored outside, softly set inside, folded into a cylinder in under 2 minutes. Practice the French version until you get it right. Make two omelettes \u2014 one for practice, one to eat.</p> <p>Full Meal: The French Omelette + Classic Green Salad + Crusty bread</p> <p>A properly made omelette with a glass of wine and a green salad is one of the most satisfying dinners in existence.</p> Component Recipe Protein Two omelettes (one per person or two attempts) Filling Gruy\u00e8re, herbs, or mushrooms Salad Classic green salad with vinaigrette Starch Crusty bread <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make a French Omelette \u00b7 Want Perfect French Omelettes? Start With Water \u2014 Watch the wrist and the pan angle. The fold happens faster than you think it should.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#thursday-off","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\ud83d\udcfa Watch: Jacques P\u00e9pin making a French omelette on YouTube. You'll either feel inspired or deeply humbled. Probably both.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#friday-custard-eggs-as-thickener","title":"Friday \u2014 Custard: Eggs as Thickener","text":"<p>Skill: When eggs are heated in liquid (cream, milk), the proteins set and thicken the mixture into a custard. Key: temperature control \u2014 too high and the eggs scramble, too low and it never sets. A proper custard coats the back of a spoon and holds a line when you drag your finger through it.</p> <p>Full Meal: Pasta Carbonara + Bitter Greens Salad with Anchovy Vinaigrette</p> <p>Carbonara is a savory egg custard sauce \u2014 eggs, pasta water, guanciale or pancetta, and pecorino. The pasta water (starchy, hot) tempers the eggs and keeps them from scrambling.</p> Component Recipe Protein Guanciale or pancetta (built into the sauce) Starch Spaghetti or rigatoni Salad Bitter greens with anchovy vinaigrette <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Classic Pasta Carbonara \u2014 Watch how he tempers the eggs using pasta water \u2014 this is the move that prevents scrambling.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#saturday-project-meal-a-complete-egg-dinner-party-3-courses","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Complete Egg Dinner Party (3 Courses)","text":"<p>The challenge: Cook a 3-course egg-forward dinner for at least two people, without recipes open in front of you during service.</p> Course Dish Link Starter Deviled Eggs (vehicle for your homemade mayo from Week 6) Recipe Main Shakshuka (scaled up, served family-style with salad and bread) Recipe Dessert Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e (classic baked egg custard, finished with a torch) Recipe <p>Skill targets: Proper custard texture in the cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e. Perfectly poached eggs in the shakshuka. Smooth, properly seasoned deviled egg filling from scratch.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#sunday-off-eight-week-reflection","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF + Eight-Week Reflection","text":"<p>You've been cooking for eight weeks with deliberate intention. Before Week 9 (Seasoning &amp; Flavor Building), write five sentences:</p> <ol> <li>What is the technique you're most proud of?</li> <li>What still feels unnatural?</li> <li>What recipe from the past 8 weeks did you want to make again?</li> <li>What did you learn that changed how you think about food?</li> <li>What do you want to tackle in the next 8 weeks?</li> </ol>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#module-1-checkpoint","title":"Module 1 Checkpoint","text":"<p>Before you move on to Module 2 (Building Flavor), take stock of where you are. The next module assumes everything here is solid.</p> <p>This is not graded. It is honest.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#knife-benchmark-repeat-from-week-2","title":"Knife Benchmark (repeat from Week 2)","text":"<p>Set a timer. Brunoise one medium onion. Stop the timer when you're done.</p> Week 2 time Today's time \u0394 _____ min _____ min _____ <p>If your time has improved by more than 20%, your knife skills are compounding. If not \u2014 that's useful information too, not a failure. Return to Week 2's onion exercise on a Saturday before Week 9.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#cook-from-memory-test","title":"Cook-From-Memory Test","text":"<p>Without opening any recipe, cook one of the following from scratch:</p> <ul> <li>A velout\u00e9 or b\u00e9chamel (one of the mother sauces from Weeks 5\u20136)</li> <li>A properly seasoned chicken stock (Weeks 7\u20138)</li> <li>A three-component dinner: seared protein + pan sauce + simply cooked vegetable</li> </ul> <p>The only rule: once anything goes on heat, no tabs open.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#skills-checklist","title":"Skills Checklist","text":"<p>Before Module 2, you should be able to answer yes to all of these:</p> <ul> <li>[ ] I can julienne, brunoise, and chiffonade without looking up how</li> <li>[ ] I understand the difference between saut\u00e9, sear, braise, poach, and steam \u2014 and when to use each</li> <li>[ ] I can make at least two of the five mother sauces from memory</li> <li>[ ] I can make a proper stock (bones, mirepoix, cold water, long simmer, strain)</li> <li>[ ] I can cook an egg five different ways and explain what I'm doing and why</li> <li>[ ] My knife is sharp and I know how to maintain it</li> </ul> <p>If you're checking all of these: you're ready for Module 2.</p> <p>If you have two or more unchecked: spend Week 9's first Monday revisiting the weak spots before committing to the new material. It's worth it.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#the-truth-about-stock","title":"The Truth About Stock","text":"<p>Stock is the most important prep you can do. The difference between a sauce made with real stock versus carton stock is the difference between a restaurant dish and a home-cooked dish.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Chicken Stock vs. Broth: What's the Difference? \u2014 This gets misunderstood constantly. Read this once and you'll never confuse them again.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#egg-science","title":"Egg Science","text":"<p>You cooked eggs five ways this week. Understanding the protein science \u2014 why they set at different temperatures, why salting before vs. after matters \u2014 unlocks every egg technique that exists.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Gordon Ramsay Was Wrong About Salting Scrambled Eggs \u2014 A properly controlled test on one of cooking's most debated questions. The answer will change how you make scrambled eggs.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Do 'Better' Eggs Really Taste Better? \u2014 Kenji runs the experiment so you don't have to. Includes what labels actually mean and when they matter.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Perfect Hard-Boiled Eggs \u2014 Everything you need to know about the hidden complexity in the simplest egg preparation.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda On Food and Cooking by Harold McGee \u2014 The original deep dive into food science. The egg chapter alone justifies the entire book. Not a cookbook \u2014 a reference work that explains why everything in the kitchen works.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Weeks 7\u20138 Quick Reference \u2014 Stocks &amp; Eggs","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/quick-ref.html#week-7-recipes","title":"Week 7 Recipes","text":"Day Dish Notes Link Mon Quick Weeknight Ramen (homemade chicken stock) Use the Week 2 carcass Ramen Tue Saut\u00e9ed Chicken with Pan Sauce (homemade stock) + Roasted Potatoes + Bitter Greens Salad Stock = silky pan sauce Chicken \u00b7 Potatoes \u00b7 Salad Wed Bouillabaisse (fish fumet) + Grilled Garlic Bread + Rouille 20\u201330 min fish stock only Bouillabaisse Thu OFF Read: restaurant-quality stock Article Fri Parmesan Risotto + Roasted Mushrooms + Arugula Salad Vegetable stock (make first) Risotto \u00b7 Mushrooms \u00b7 Salad Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Beef Stock (all day) \u2192 French Onion Soup (dinner) + Green Salad Freeze leftover stock in 1-cup portions Beef Stock \u00b7 French Onion Soup \u00b7 Salad"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/quick-ref.html#week-8-recipes","title":"Week 8 Recipes","text":"Day Dish Egg Technique Link Mon French Scrambled Eggs + Smoked Salmon + Toasted Sourdough + Greens Salad Low &amp; slow scramble Scramble \u00b7 Salmon Tue Poached Eggs over Saut\u00e9ed Greens + Crispy Bacon + Roasted Tomatoes + Toast Poach Poached Eggs \u00b7 Tomatoes Wed French Omelette + Green Salad + Crusty Bread Fold/omelette Omelette Thu OFF \ud83d\udcfa Watch: Jacques P\u00e9pin omelette on YouTube \u2014 Fri Pasta Carbonara + Bitter Greens Salad Egg custard (savory) Carbonara \u00b7 Salad Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: 3-Course Egg Dinner \u2014 Deviled Eggs \u00b7 Shakshuka \u00b7 Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e All of them Deviled Eggs \u00b7 Shakshuka \u00b7 Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/quick-ref.html#stock-cheat-sheet","title":"Stock Cheat Sheet","text":"Stock Time Gelatin Source Don't Chicken 3\u20134 hrs Bones + carcass Boil \u2014 gentle simmer only Fish (fumet) 20\u201330 min Fish frames/shrimp shells Go longer \u2014 turns bitter Vegetable 45\u201360 min None (no gelatin) Over-simmer \u2014 turns bitter Beef/veal 6\u20138 hrs Bones + knuckles Rush it <p>Freeze in 1-cup portions. This changes your cooking permanently.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 7\u20138: Stocks &amp; Eggs","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Week 7 is about using your stock. Get the Week 2 chicken carcass out of the freezer on Sunday night to thaw. Week 8 is egg week \u2014 buy 3 dozen eggs. You will use all of them.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#pre-week-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Pre-Week Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Week 2 chicken carcass from the freezer \u2014 this is your Week 7 Monday stock. If you didn't save it, buy a raw chicken carcass from your butcher or supermarket.</li> <li>[ ] Week 7 Saturday: Buy beef bones (knuckle bones and marrow bones) for beef stock \u2014 order ahead or request from your butcher. You need 3\u20134 lbs.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-7","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 7","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Chicken pieces (thighs + drumsticks) \u2014 4 pieces (Week 7 Tue pan sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Mixed seafood for bouillabaisse: shrimp (\u00bd lb), mussels (1 lb), clams (1 lb), cod or halibut chunks (1 lb), or 1 lb monkfish \u2014 (Week 7 Wed)</li> <li>[ ] Shrimp shells (or save from above) \u2014 freeze for quick shrimp stock or fumet base</li> <li>[ ] Beef knuckle and/or marrow bones \u2014 3\u20134 lbs (Week 7 Sat beef stock, all day project)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-8","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 8","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 3 dozen (every method this week: scrambles, poaches, omelettes, carbonara, deviled, shakshuka, cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e)</li> <li>[ ] Hot-smoked salmon or lox \u2014 4 oz (Week 8 Mon)</li> <li>[ ] Thick-cut bacon \u2014 6 oz (Week 8 Tue + Week 8 Sat deviled eggs garnish)</li> <li>[ ] Guanciale or pancetta (thick pieces) \u2014 4 oz (Week 8 Fri carbonara)</li> <li>[ ] Whole milk or heavy cream \u2014 1 pint (Week 8 Sat cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e \u2014 use full-fat cream)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#produce-week-7","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 7","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Yellow onions \u2014 6 large (Week 7 Sat French onion soup + stock mirepoix)</li> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 6 (stock vegetables + week meals)</li> <li>[ ] Celery \u2014 1 bunch (stock vegetables)</li> <li>[ ] Fennel \u2014 1 bulb (bouillabaisse + stock)</li> <li>[ ] Leeks \u2014 2 (vegetable stock, Week 7 Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Mushrooms (cremini or mixed) \u2014 1 lb (Week 7 Fri risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Arugula \u2014 2 bags (Week 7 Fri salad + Week 8 Mon salad)</li> <li>[ ] Bitter greens (radicchio, endive) \u2014 1 head each (Week 7 Tue salad)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Fresh thyme, parsley, bay leaves \u2014 1 bunch each (stocks)</li> <li>[ ] Tomatoes or canned tomatoes \u2014 2 cans (bouillabaisse)</li> <li>[ ] Saffron \u2014 1 small tin (bouillabaisse \u2014 expensive but essential)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#produce-week-8","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 8","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Baby spinach or Swiss chard \u2014 1 bag (Week 8 Tue poached eggs)</li> <li>[ ] Roma tomatoes \u2014 4 (Week 8 Tue oven roasted)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh chives \u2014 1 bunch (Week 8 Mon scrambled eggs + omelette)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh tarragon \u2014 1 small bunch (omelette filling, optional)</li> <li>[ ] Sourdough bread \u2014 1 loaf (Week 8 Mon toast + omelette bread)</li> <li>[ ] Baguette or crusty bread \u2014 1 (Week 8 Wed)</li> <li>[ ] Canned tomatoes \u2014 2 cans (Week 8 Sat shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Red bell pepper \u2014 2 (shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Yellow onion \u2014 2 (shakshuka + French onion soup Sat if making again)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#dairy","title":"\ud83e\uddc0 Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 4 sticks (Week 8 omelettes use a lot; Week 7 risotto finishing)</li> <li>[ ] Cr\u00e8me fra\u00eeche or sour cream \u2014 1 tub (Week 8 Mon with smoked salmon)</li> <li>[ ] Parmesan (block) \u2014 8 oz (Week 7 risotto + Week 8 carbonara)</li> <li>[ ] Pecorino Romano \u2014 4 oz (Week 8 Fri carbonara \u2014 use together with parmesan)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 1 pint (Week 8 Sat cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e needs 2 cups)</li> <li>[ ] Gruy\u00e8re \u2014 6 oz (Week 7 Sat French onion soup topping)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry-goods","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Pantry &amp; Dry Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Arborio or Carnaroli rice \u2014 1.5 cups (Week 7 Fri risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Ramen noodles \u2014 4 servings (Week 7 Mon)</li> <li>[ ] Spaghetti or rigatoni \u2014 1 lb (Week 8 Fri carbonara)</li> <li>[ ] Dry white wine \u2014 1 bottle (risotto + pan sauces)</li> <li>[ ] Red wine \u2014 1 bottle (Week 7 Sat French onion soup braising base)</li> <li>[ ] Beef stock \u2014 64 oz (Week 7 Tue pan sauce + Week 7 Sat French onion soup)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken stock \u2014 64 oz (risotto + ramen base)</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce \u2014 1 bottle (ramen seasoning)</li> <li>[ ] Mirin \u2014 1 bottle (ramen tare)</li> <li>[ ] Kombu \u2014 a few strips (ramen base \u2014 found at Asian grocery stores or Amazon)</li> <li>[ ] White wine vinegar (ramen seasoning, risotto touch)</li> <li>[ ] Granulated sugar \u2014 1 cup (Week 8 Sat cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e)</li> <li>[ ] Vanilla beans \u2014 2 (cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e \u2014 or 1 tsp pure vanilla extract)</li> <li>[ ] Mayo, Dijon, paprika, capers \u2014 small amounts (Week 8 Sat deviled eggs)</li> <li>[ ] Cumin, smoked paprika, chili flakes \u2014 (Week 8 Sat shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Rouille ingredients: jarred roasted red peppers, garlic, breadcrumbs (bouillabaisse)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#bread","title":"\ud83e\udd56 Bread","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Baguette \u2014 2 loaves (Week 7 Sat French onion soup + general use)</li> <li>[ ] Thick-sliced sourdough \u2014 1 loaf (Week 8 Mon + Wed)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#equipment-nice-to-have-for-this-block","title":"\ud83d\udd27 Equipment (Nice to Have for This Block)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Kitchen torch \u2014 for cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e (Week 8 Sat). Can substitute: broiler works, but you have less control. A cheap culinary torch costs less than $20.</li> <li>[ ] Fine mesh strainer (chinois) \u2014 essential for clarifying stocks. If you don't have one, a colander lined with cheesecloth works.</li> <li>[ ] Stockpot (8+ quart) \u2014 if you're making proper beef stock on Week 7 Saturday.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#notes","title":"\ud83d\udcdd Notes","text":"<p>Beef stock (Week 7 Sat) is an all-day project. Roast the bones at 450\u00b0F for 45 minutes first (this is what makes beef stock different from chicken stock). Then 6\u20138 hours of simmering. Start by 10 AM.</p> <p>Carbonara (Week 8 Fri) \u2014 no cream. Real carbonara is eggs, cheese, pasta water, and guanciale. The heat from the pasta cooks the eggs into a silky custard. Take the pan fully off the heat before adding the egg mixture. Temperature is everything.</p> <p>Cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e (Week 8 Sat) \u2014 make it the day before. They need 4\u20136 hours to set in the fridge after baking. Br\u00fbl\u00e9e the tops right before serving.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/index.html","title":"Module 2: Building Flavor (Weeks 9\u201316)","text":"<p>The goal of this module: Move beyond technique into taste. Learn how salt, acid, fat, and heat interact to build layered flavor \u2014 then apply that understanding to one of the most satisfying skill sets in the kitchen: fresh pasta, handmade grains, and confident poultry cookery.</p> <p>By the end of Week 14, your palate should be a tool as reliable as your knife.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/index.html#weeks-in-this-module","title":"Weeks in This Module","text":"Weeks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 9\u201310 Seasoning &amp; Flavor Building \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 11\u201312 Vegetables &amp; Plant-Forward Cooking \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 13\u201314 Pasta &amp; Grains from Scratch \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 15\u201316 Module 2 Capstone: Poultry &amp; Flavor Review \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/index.html#core-skills-covered","title":"Core Skills Covered","text":"<ul> <li>Seasoning \u2014 salting at the right moment, finishing acids, building depth with fat; tasting analytically</li> <li>Flavor layering \u2014 aromatics, fond, deglazing, reduction; how flavor compounds develop and stack</li> <li>Vegetables \u2014 blanching and shocking; high-heat roasting; charring; pur\u00e9e method; quick-pickling and lacto-fermentation</li> <li>Fresh pasta \u2014 dough by hand and machine, lamination, rolling to thickness, cutting tagliatelle and pappardelle</li> <li>Grains \u2014 pilaf method, risotto technique, polenta ratios; the difference between toasting and not</li> <li>Poultry \u2014 breaking down a whole chicken; roasting, pan-saucing, and braising; carryover cooking</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/index.html#equipment-youll-need","title":"Equipment You'll Need","text":"<p>See the Kitchen Equipment Guide. New items introduced in this module:</p> Item Introduced Mandoline slicer Week 11 Fine-mesh sieve Week 11 Potato ricer Week 13 Pasta machine (or rolling pin) Week 13 Large pasta pot (8+ qt) Week 13 <p>Previous module: Module 1 \u2014 Foundational Skills (Weeks 1\u20138) Next module: Module 3 \u2014 The Proteins (Weeks 17\u201328)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Weeks 9\u201310: Seasoning &amp; Flavor Building","text":"<p>\u2190 Quick Reference \u2192 | Shopping List \u2192</p> <p>Your Schedule: Monday \u00b7 Tuesday \u00b7 Wednesday \u00b7 Friday cook | Saturday = Big Project | Thursday &amp; Sunday = Off</p> <p>Where we are: Knife skills done. Heat methods done. Mother sauces done. Stocks and eggs done. Now we go deeper \u2014 into the invisible architecture of flavor itself.</p> <p>\"Salt makes food taste more like itself. Acid makes it taste more alive. Fat makes it taste more satisfying. Understanding all three changes everything.\"</p> <p>The core idea for these two weeks: Most home cooks season once, at the end, with a generic shake of salt and pepper. Professional cooks season in layers \u2014 each component seasoned individually, each layer building on the last. By the end of Week 10, you should never walk away from a dish thinking \"something's missing\" without knowing exactly what that something is.</p> <p>Before you start Week 9, read these two pieces back to back:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 The Food Lab: The Science of Salt \u2014 Why salt is more than a flavoring; how it restructures proteins, manages moisture, and builds flavor from the inside out</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 Why Every Recipe Should Have Acid \u2014 The most underused tool in the home cook's arsenal</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#week-9-salt-when-what-and-why","title":"Week 9 \u2014 Salt: When, What, and Why","text":"<p>The lesson: salt behaves differently at different stages of cooking, and learning to recognize what your food is missing \u2014 flat? dull? one-dimensional? \u2014 is more valuable than any single technique.</p> <p>The Week 9 experiment (do this before Monday): Take a carrot. Cut it in two. Salt one half with a pinch of kosher salt and wait two minutes. Taste both back to back. The salted carrot will taste more carrot-y \u2014 brighter, sweeter, more itself. That's the point. Salt doesn't make food taste salty. It makes food taste like food.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#monday-early-salt-brining","title":"Monday \u2014 Early Salt: Brining","text":"<p>Skill: Dry-brining (salting well in advance) allows salt to penetrate proteins deeply, seasoning from within rather than just the surface. The meat loses moisture initially, which is then reabsorbed as a concentrated, seasoned brine. The result: more flavorful, more evenly seasoned meat, and \u2014 as a bonus \u2014 drier skin that crisps better in the oven. Tonight you'll dry-brine chicken thighs in the morning and cook them at dinner.</p> <p>Before you leave for work or start your day: Pat 4\u20136 bone-in, skin-on chicken thighs dry, season generously with kosher salt (about \u00be tsp per pound), place on a rack over a sheet pan, and refrigerate uncovered. Come back to them at dinner.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Crispy-Skinned Chicken Thighs (use your dry-brined thighs) + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Broccoli with Garlic + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Arugula Salad with Lemon Vinaigrette</p> <p>Before you season the broccoli, taste a raw floret. Season it with salt and taste again. Notice the difference before it goes in the oven.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Dry-brined chicken thighs, seared until the skin is lacquer-crisp</li> <li>Veg: Roasted broccoli, each floret seasoned before roasting</li> <li>Salad: Arugula with shaved parmesan and a sharp lemon vinaigrette</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Dry Brining Is the Easiest Way to Improve Any Roast \u2014 A 60-second demonstration of the exact technique you're using tonight \u2014 notice that the salt goes on much earlier than most people think.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#tuesday-during-salt-layered-seasoning","title":"Tuesday \u2014 During Salt: Layered Seasoning","text":"<p>Skill: Tonight, season every single component of your dish at the moment it goes into the pan \u2014 not just at the beginning or the end. Salt the onions when they go in. Salt the garlic when you add it. Salt the tomatoes when they hit the pan. Taste after each addition. You're building flavor in layers, not slapping it on at the end.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Pasta all'Amatriciana + Serious Eats \u2014 Classic Caesar Salad</p> <p>Amatriciana is one of the great Roman pasta sauces \u2014 guanciale (or pancetta), white wine, tomato, pecorino. Each component is distinct and requires its own seasoning moment. It's a perfect layering teacher.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Guanciale or pancetta, crisped in the pan and layered through the sauce</li> <li>Starch: Bucatini or rigatoni \u2014 both are traditional</li> <li>Salad: Classic Caesar alongside \u2014 learn to taste and adjust the dressing before it goes on the leaves</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Food Lab Basics: POV Bucatini All'Amatriciana \u2014 Watch when he seasons at each stage \u2014 count how many separate times salt or salty ingredients go in before the dish is done.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#wednesday-late-salt-finishing","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Late Salt: Finishing","text":"<p>Skill: Some things should not be salted early. Delicate fish toughens if salted too far in advance. Soups and braises that reduce become dangerously salty if heavily salted at the start. Finishing salts \u2014 flaky Maldon, fleur de sel \u2014 exist to add texture and a burst of flavor right at the moment of eating. They should never dissolve. Tonight you'll deliberately hold salt until the final moment and let a finishing salt do the work.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Pan-Seared Halibut or Sea Bass with a squeeze of lemon and a pinch of Maldon flakes right at plating + Serious Eats \u2014 White Bean Salad with Olive Oil and Herbs + Serious Eats \u2014 Saut\u00e9ed Cherry Tomatoes</p> <p>The white bean salad benefits enormously from being dressed early (the beans absorb the seasoning) while the fish is seasoned only at the very end. Two different salt strategies on the same plate, by design.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Pan-seared white fish, seasoned only right before going in the pan and finished with Maldon flakes</li> <li>Veg: Saut\u00e9ed cherry tomatoes, blistered in olive oil</li> <li>Starch/Salad: White bean salad with olive oil, lemon, and fresh herbs \u2014 dressed 20 minutes ahead so the beans absorb the seasoning</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#thursday-off","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 The Complete Guide to Seasoning with Salt</p> <p>\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry audit: Do you have kosher salt, flaky Maldon or fleur de sel, and fine sea salt? These are three different tools and not interchangeable. If you're only working with one, fix that this week.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#friday-salt-as-texture-and-contrast","title":"Friday \u2014 Salt as Texture and Contrast","text":"<p>Skill: Tonight's focus is on salt as a textural and contrast element. A finishing salt on a rich braise doesn't just season \u2014 it provides crunch and a burst of concentrated flavor that cuts through the fat. A well-salted pasta water (it should taste \"pleasantly seasoned,\" like a light broth) actually seasons the pasta from within, not just its surface. Both are explored tonight.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Cacio e Pepe + Serious Eats \u2014 Bitter Greens Salad with Anchovy Vinaigrette + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Cauliflower with Crispy Capers</p> <p>Cacio e Pepe is three ingredients: pasta, pecorino, black pepper. There is nowhere to hide. The pasta water must be well-salted. The cheese is the only seasoning. This dish teaches you precision \u2014 and it's one of the best things you can make.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Pecorino and parmesan (the sauce is the protein component here)</li> <li>Starch: Tonnarelli or spaghetti</li> <li>Veg: Roasted cauliflower with crispy capers \u2014 the capers add a salty, briny pop that is the finishing-salt concept in action</li> <li>Salad: Bitter greens to cut through the richness</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Cacio e Pepe \u2014 Three ingredients. Watch how he uses pasta water to build a sauce, not just coat the noodles. That emulsification is the whole technique.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#saturday-project-meal-salt-crusted-whole-roasted-fish","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Salt-Crusted Whole Roasted Fish","text":"<p>Skill: Salt-crusting is an ancient technique where a whole fish (or chicken or beet) is encased in a thick crust of kosher salt before roasting. The salt absorbs moisture from the surface, seasons the interior gently, and creates a steaming environment inside the crust. The result is the most evenly cooked, delicately seasoned fish you will ever eat at home. Cracking the crust at the table is genuinely theatrical.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Salt-Crusted Whole Roasted Fish + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Fingerling Potatoes with Herbs + Serious Eats \u2014 Fennel and Orange Salad</p> <p>This is one of the most impressive things you can serve to guests and it requires almost no active cooking skill \u2014 just good salt technique and confidence.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Whole branzino or red snapper, salt-crusted and roasted</li> <li>Starch: Crispy roasted fingerling potatoes, dressed with herbs and flaky salt at the end</li> <li>Salad: Fennel and orange salad \u2014 light, acidic, a perfect counterpoint to the fish</li> </ul> <p>Skill targets: A properly sealed salt crust (no cracks before roasting). Even internal temperature of 130\u2013135\u00b0F at the thickest point. Confident tableside crack-and-reveal.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#week-10-acid-fat-and-the-fifth-taste","title":"Week 10 \u2014 Acid, Fat, and the Fifth Taste","text":"<p>The lesson: seasoning is not just salt. Acid brightens. Fat carries and extends. Umami deepens. Knowing which one is missing from a flat dish is the difference between following a recipe and actually cooking.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#monday-acid-the-brightness-lever","title":"Monday \u2014 Acid: The Brightness Lever","text":"<p>Skill: Acid \u2014 lemon juice, vinegar, wine, citrus zest \u2014 does something salt cannot: it lifts and brightens flavors, making food taste fresher and more vibrant. Most dishes benefit from a small hit of acid right at the end of cooking, before serving. Tonight you'll cook a dish twice in your mind: once without the final acid, once with. The difference is immediately obvious.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Chicken Marsala + Serious Eats \u2014 Creamy Mashed Potatoes + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Green Salad with Sharp Dijon Vinaigrette</p> <p>Before you finish the Marsala sauce, taste it. Now add a small squeeze of lemon and taste again. Notice how the whole sauce comes into focus. That is acid as a lever.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Chicken Marsala \u2014 mushrooms, Marsala wine, a final hit of lemon</li> <li>Starch: Mashed potatoes (their richness is exactly what needs the acid in the salad to balance the plate)</li> <li>Salad: Sharp Dijon vinaigrette salad \u2014 the acidic foil for the rich main</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#tuesday-different-acids-different-effects","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Different Acids, Different Effects","text":"<p>Skill: Not all acid is the same. Lemon juice is bright and immediate. Red wine vinegar is assertive and fruity. Sherry vinegar is mellow and nutty. White balsamic is sweet and gentle. Tamarind is deep and complex. Tonight you'll use two different acids in two different components of the same meal and taste the difference.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Glazed Pork Tenderloin with Balsamic Reduction + Serious Eats \u2014 Lentil Salad with Sherry Vinaigrette + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Carrots with Cumin</p> <p>Balsamic on the pork: sweet, deep, slightly caramelized. Sherry vinegar in the lentil salad: dry, nutty, assertive. Two acids, two entirely different effects.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Pork tenderloin with balsamic glaze</li> <li>Starch/Salad: Warm French lentil salad with sherry vinaigrette</li> <li>Veg: Roasted carrots with cumin</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#wednesday-fat-as-flavor","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Fat as Flavor","text":"<p>Skill: Fat is not just a cooking medium or a source of richness. Different fats carry fundamentally different flavors: brown butter is nutty and toasty; extra-virgin olive oil is grassy and peppery; duck fat is savory and deep; bacon fat is smoky and umami-forward. Tonight you cook the same vegetable three different ways \u2014 once in each of three fats \u2014 and taste the difference.</p> <p>The mini-experiment: Before dinner, saut\u00e9 three small batches of green beans \u2014 one in neutral canola oil, one in good extra-virgin olive oil, one in butter with a little brown at the end. Taste each with just a pinch of salt. The difference is the fat speaking.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Brown Butter Gnocchi with Crispy Sage + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Mushrooms with Thyme + Serious Eats \u2014 Bitter Greens Salad</p> <p>Brown butter is fat transformed \u2014 milk solids toasted to a deep hazelnut color, releasing a complex, nutty flavor that coats the gnocchi and makes the dish. Tonight fat is the whole story.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: The sage and parmesan carry the protein element</li> <li>Starch: Potato gnocchi, tossed in brown butter and crispy sage</li> <li>Veg: Roasted mushrooms alongside</li> <li>Salad: Bitter greens to cut through all that butter</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Spring Vegetable Gnocchi \u2014 Different filling, same brown butter sauce technique \u2014 watch how the butter goes from golden to hazelnut and how the gnocchi absorb the fat.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#thursday-off_1","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 What Is Umami and How Do You Cook With It?</p> <p>\ud83c\udf44 Pantry check for umami builders: Do you have soy sauce, fish sauce, miso paste, anchovy paste, parmesan rind, and dried mushrooms? If not, this week is a good time to start building that collection. These are the ingredients that make a dish taste deep even when the recipe is simple.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#friday-umami-the-depth-dial","title":"Friday \u2014 Umami: The Depth Dial","text":"<p>Skill: Umami is the fifth taste \u2014 the savory, lingering depth you get from glutamate-rich ingredients: aged parmesan, soy sauce, miso, fish sauce, anchovies, dried mushrooms, tomato paste. Tonight you'll learn to use umami ingredients as seasoning, not as central flavors \u2014 a tablespoon of fish sauce where you'd normally add salt, a smear of miso in a braise, a parmesan rind dropped into a soup pot. They should deepen the dish without announcing themselves.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Umami-Packed Mushroom Pasta + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan + Serious Eats \u2014 Arugula Salad with Shaved Parmesan</p> <p>This pasta uses anchovies (umami), mushrooms (umami), and tomato (umami) in combination. None of them taste like themselves in the finished dish \u2014 together they create a savory depth that makes you want to keep eating. The parmesan on the asparagus and the salad keeps the umami thread running through the whole meal.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Anchovies melted into the sauce (they disappear \u2014 trust the process)</li> <li>Starch: Spaghetti or rigatoni</li> <li>Veg: Asparagus with shaved parmesan \u2014 the parmesan is doing seasoning work here</li> <li>Salad: Arugula with more parmesan and lemon</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Pasta Puttanesca \u2014 Same principle: anchovies and olives as hidden umami, not as the headline flavors. Watch how they disappear into the sauce while deepening it.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#saturday-project-meal-a-composed-tasting-plate","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Composed Tasting Plate","text":"<p>The challenge: This Saturday isn't about following a single recipe. It's about applying everything from Weeks 9\u201310 in one deliberate meal. You'll cook a three-component plate and consciously think about salt timing, acid balance, fat choice, and umami depth for each component.</p> <p>Suggested composed plate:</p> <ol> <li>Protein: Serious Eats \u2014 Miso-Glazed Black Cod \u2014 umami from the miso marinade, fat from the fish, a hit of rice vinegar for acid in the glaze</li> <li>Grain: Serious Eats \u2014 Saffron Risotto alla Milanese \u2014 salt-seasoned at every stage, finished with butter (fat) and parmesan (umami), a squeeze of lemon at the end (acid)</li> <li>Salad: Serious Eats \u2014 Fennel and Citrus Salad \u2014 acid-forward, a deliberate foil to the rich risotto and fish</li> </ol> <p>Before you plate everything, taste each component and ask: Is it salty enough? Does it need acid? Is the fat coming through? Is there depth? Adjust one thing at a time.</p> <p>Skill targets: Each component consciously seasoned, not just salted. A finished dish where all four elements \u2014 salt, acid, fat, umami \u2014 are present and in balance.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#salt-when-to-add-it-and-why-it-matters","title":"Salt: When to Add It and Why It Matters","text":"<p>The single biggest improvement most home cooks can make is learning to salt earlier and more confidently. The science backs it up.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Dry-Brining Is the Best Way to Brine Meat, Poultry, and More \u2014 Salting in advance isn't just about flavor \u2014 it transforms texture. This is the technique that restaurants use.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How and When to Brine Vegetables \u2014 The same principle applied to produce. Salting a cucumber vs. a tomato vs. eggplant before cooking changes everything.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#acid-the-underused-seasoning","title":"Acid: The Underused Seasoning","text":"<p>Salt gets all the attention, but acid is what makes a dish taste complete. A squeeze of lemon or a splash of vinegar at the end is often all a dish needs.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 6 Chemistry-Based Cooking Tricks That Actually Make Food Better \u2014 A quick tour of how pH affects color, texture, and flavor in cooking. The sections on finishing with acid and on blanching vegetables are directly applicable to everything you cooked this week.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Samin Nosrat's Salt Fat Acid Heat \u2014 Four episodes, each focused on one of this week's themes. Her episode on salt is the best explanation of when and how to salt that exists on screen.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Salt Fat Acid Heat by Samin Nosrat \u2014 This week's curriculum in book form, written for exactly the stage you're at. Possibly the best cooking book of the last ten years for developing instinct rather than just technique.</li> </ul> <p>\u2190 Weeks 7\u20138 | Weeks 11\u201312: Vegetables &amp; Plant-Forward \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Weeks 9\u201310 Quick Reference \u2014 Seasoning &amp; Flavor Building","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/quick-ref.html#week-9-recipes-salt-when-what-and-why","title":"Week 9 Recipes \u2014 Salt: When, What, and Why","text":"Day Dish Skill Link Mon Crispy Chicken Thighs + Roasted Broccoli + Arugula Salad Dry-brine (early salt) Chicken \u00b7 Broccoli \u00b7 Salad Tue Pasta all'Amatriciana + Caesar Salad Layered seasoning (during salt) Amatriciana \u00b7 Caesar Wed Pan-Seared Halibut + White Bean Salad + Saut\u00e9ed Cherry Tomatoes Finishing salt (late salt) Halibut \u00b7 White Bean Salad \u00b7 Tomatoes Thu OFF Read: science of salt Article Fri Cacio e Pepe + Bitter Greens Salad + Roasted Cauliflower with Capers Salt as texture and contrast Cacio e Pepe \u00b7 Salad \u00b7 Cauliflower Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Salt-Crusted Whole Roasted Fish + Fingerling Potatoes + Fennel Orange Salad Salt crust technique Fish \u00b7 Potatoes \u00b7 Salad"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/quick-ref.html#week-10-recipes-acid-fat-and-umami","title":"Week 10 Recipes \u2014 Acid, Fat, and Umami","text":"Day Dish Skill Link Mon Chicken Marsala + Creamy Mashed Potatoes + Green Salad Acid as a brightness lever Marsala \u00b7 Mash \u00b7 Salad Tue Glazed Pork Tenderloin + French Lentil Salad + Roasted Carrots Two different acids in one meal Pork \u00b7 Lentils \u00b7 Carrots Wed Brown Butter Gnocchi + Roasted Mushrooms + Bitter Greens Salad Fat as flavor (brown butter) Gnocchi \u00b7 Mushrooms \u00b7 Salad Thu OFF Read: what is umami Article Fri Mushroom &amp; Anchovy Pasta + Roasted Asparagus + Arugula Salad Umami as background seasoning Pasta \u00b7 Asparagus \u00b7 Salad Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Miso-Glazed Cod + Saffron Risotto + Fennel Citrus Salad All four: salt \u00b7 acid \u00b7 fat \u00b7 umami in balance Cod \u00b7 Risotto \u00b7 Salad"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/quick-ref.html#shopping-notes","title":"Shopping Notes","text":"<p>Buy before Week 9: Kosher salt (Diamond Crystal or Morton), flaky Maldon sea salt or fleur de sel, fine sea salt. These are three distinct tools \u2014 don't skip the Maldon.</p> <p>Buy before Week 9 Wednesday: White fish (halibut or sea bass), canned white beans, cherry tomatoes.</p> <p>Buy before Week 9 Saturday: 1\u20132 whole branzino or red snapper (ask your fishmonger to gut and scale them for you). Fingerling potatoes.</p> <p>Pantry additions for Week 10: Anchovy paste or tinned anchovies, miso paste (white or red), soy sauce, fish sauce, balsamic vinegar, sherry vinegar.</p> <p>Week 10 Saturday: Miso marinade goes on the cod/salmon 24\u201348 hours ahead \u2014 start Sunday or Friday morning.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 9\u201310: Seasoning &amp; Flavor Building","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: These weeks are about salt, acid, and umami \u2014 meaning you'll be building your pantry more than stocking up on proteins. Buy the three types of salt before anything else. The miso-marinated cod/salmon (Week 10 Sat) needs 24\u201348 hours in the marinade \u2014 start it Thursday.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html#pre-week-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Pre-Week Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Three types of salt you must have: Kosher (Diamond Crystal or Morton), flaky Maldon or fleur de sel, fine sea salt. They are not interchangeable.</li> <li>[ ] Pantry umami builders (Week 10): Anchovies/anchovy paste, miso paste (white or red), soy sauce, fish sauce. You need all of these by Week 10 Monday.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-9","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 9","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Bone-in, skin-on chicken thighs \u2014 6 pieces (Week 9 Mon dry-brine)</li> <li>[ ] White fish fillets \u2014 halibut or sea bass, 2 pieces (Week 9 Wed pan-sear)</li> <li>[ ] Whole branzino or red snapper \u2014 1\u20132 fish (Week 9 Sat PROJECT \u2014 ask fishmonger to gut and scale). Alternatively: whole sea bass or trout works.</li> <li>[ ] Guanciale or pancetta \u2014 4 oz (Week 9 Tue amatriciana)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-10","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 10","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Chicken breasts or thighs \u2014 4 pieces (Week 10 Mon Marsala)</li> <li>[ ] Pork tenderloin \u2014 1 lb (Week 10 Tue)</li> <li>[ ] Black cod or salmon fillets \u2014 2 pieces (Week 10 Sat \u2014 start miso marinade Thursday)</li> <li>[ ] Tinned anchovies \u2014 2 cans (Week 10 Fri pasta + any remaining salads)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html#produce-week-9","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 9","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Broccoli \u2014 1 large head (Week 9 Mon)</li> <li>[ ] Arugula \u2014 3 bags (Week 9 Mon salad + Week 9 Fri salad + general use)</li> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 2 pints (Week 9 Wed saut\u00e9ed)</li> <li>[ ] Cauliflower \u2014 1 head (Week 9 Fri, with crispy capers)</li> <li>[ ] Radicchio or bitter greens \u2014 1 head (Week 9 Fri salad)</li> <li>[ ] Fennel \u2014 2 bulbs (Week 9 Sat salad)</li> <li>[ ] Navel oranges \u2014 3 (Week 9 Sat fennel orange salad)</li> <li>[ ] Fingerling potatoes \u2014 1.5 lbs (Week 9 Sat)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html#produce-week-10","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 10","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Mushrooms (cremini or mixed) \u2014 1 lb (Week 10 Mon Marsala sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 4 (acid finishes, multiple uses)</li> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 4 (Week 10 Tue roasted with cumin)</li> <li>[ ] Asparagus \u2014 1 bunch (Week 10 Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Arugula \u2014 2 bags (Week 10 Fri salad + Sat salad)</li> <li>[ ] Fennel \u2014 1 bulb (Week 10 Sat salad)</li> <li>[ ] Blood oranges or navel oranges \u2014 2 (Week 10 Sat salad)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html#dairy","title":"\ud83e\uddc0 Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Parmesan (block) \u2014 8 oz (cacio e pepe, pasta, salads)</li> <li>[ ] Pecorino Romano \u2014 4 oz (cacio e pepe \u2014 do not skip, it's different from parmesan)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 3 sticks</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream (optional) \u2014 \u00bd cup (Week 10 Mon Marsala finishing)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry-goods","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Pantry &amp; Dry Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] White miso paste \u2014 1 container (Week 10 Sat \u2014 also useful forever after)</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Week 10 Fri pasta + future use)</li> <li>[ ] Anchovy paste or whole tinned anchovies \u2014 2 cans (Week 10 Fri mushroom pasta)</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce \u2014 1 bottle (already have? check)</li> <li>[ ] Saffron \u2014 1 small tin (Week 10 Sat risotto \u2014 the good stuff, not the cheap powder)</li> <li>[ ] Marsala wine (dry) \u2014 1 small bottle (Week 10 Mon \u2014 use dry, not sweet)</li> <li>[ ] Balsamic vinegar \u2014 1 bottle (Week 10 Tue pork glaze)</li> <li>[ ] Sherry vinegar \u2014 1 bottle (Week 10 Tue lentil salad \u2014 different from balsamic)</li> <li>[ ] Mirin \u2014 1 bottle (Week 10 Sat miso marinade)</li> <li>[ ] Sake or dry sherry \u2014 small bottle (miso marinade)</li> <li>[ ] Cumin, ground \u2014 for Week 10 Tue roasted carrots</li> <li>[ ] Canned white beans \u2014 2 cans (Week 9 Wed white bean salad)</li> <li>[ ] Tonnarelli or spaghetti \u2014 1 lb (cacio e pepe)</li> <li>[ ] Bucatini or rigatoni \u2014 1 lb (Week 9 Tue amatriciana)</li> <li>[ ] Canned whole tomatoes \u2014 1 can (amatriciana)</li> <li>[ ] Arborio rice \u2014 1.5 cups (Week 10 Sat saffron risotto)</li> <li>[ ] French green lentils (Puy lentils) \u2014 1 cup (Week 10 Tue lentil salad)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken or vegetable stock \u2014 64 oz (risotto + Marsala deglazing)</li> <li>[ ] Capers \u2014 1 jar (Week 9 Fri cauliflower + general use)</li> <li>[ ] Extra-virgin olive oil (good quality \u2014 it will be tasted directly this week)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html#notes","title":"\ud83d\udcdd Notes","text":"<p>Week 9 Monday dry-brine: Do this in the morning. Salt the chicken thighs, place uncovered on a rack over a sheet pan, and refrigerate until dinner. This 6\u20138 hour window is the minimum; overnight is better.</p> <p>Week 9 Saturday salt-crusted fish: You'll need 3\u20134 cups of kosher salt for the crust. Mix it with egg whites (about 2 per cup of salt) to form a pliable paste that seals around the fish without falling off. The crust should not be eaten.</p> <p>Week 10 Sat miso-marinated cod: Mix 3 parts white miso, 2 parts mirin, 1 part sake, 1 part sugar. Coat the fish completely, cover, and refrigerate 24\u201348 hours. Wipe off excess before broiling or pan-searing \u2014 the sugar burns.</p> <p>The umami experiment (Week 10 Fri): Before you add the anchovies to the pasta, taste the plain saut\u00e9ed garlic and tomato. Then add 2\u20133 anchovies and stir until dissolved. Taste again \u2014 notice it doesn't taste like fish; it just tastes deeper. That's umami at work.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Weeks 13\u201314: Vegetables &amp; Plant-Forward Cooking","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 9\u201310: Seasoning &amp; Flavor | Weeks 15\u201316: Pasta &amp; Grains \u2192</p> <p>\"The professional kitchen tests you on your vegetables. Anyone can cook a steak. The chef who can make a carrot taste like the best thing on the plate \u2014 that person has actually learned something.\"</p> <p>Quick Reference: \u2192 Week 11\u201312 Recipe Quick Ref</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#before-you-start-week-11","title":"Before You Start Week 11","text":"<p>Vegetables are where most home cooks coast. The steak gets the technique; the vegetables get the afterthought. This block is a correction. Two weeks of treating vegetables like the main event teaches you more about heat, texture, timing, and flavor than another two weeks of protein cookery would.</p> <p>The CIA spends four full weeks on vegetable fabrication and cookery before touching protein. The principle: if you can't make a carrot interesting, you don't yet understand heat.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read first: Serious Eats \u2014 The Science of Browning Vegetables \u2014 the same Maillard logic from Week 3\u20134 applies here; the only difference is water content and sugar concentration.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#week-11-vegetable-mastery","title":"Week 11 \u2014 Vegetable Mastery","text":""},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#monday-blanching-shocking-and-color-science","title":"Monday \u2014 Blanching, Shocking, and Color Science","text":"<p>Skill: Blanching (brief boiling) plus shocking (ice bath) is the professional technique for preserving color, texture, and nutritional value in vegetables. It's also the mise en place move for any vegetable that needs to be partially cooked ahead of service.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 How and Why to Blanch Vegetables</p> <p>The color science \u2014 why it matters:</p> Pigment Vegetable examples Acid effect Alkali effect Chlorophyll (green) Broccoli, asparagus, spinach, peas Turns drab olive \u2014 add lemon after cooking Stays bright green \u2014 small pinch of baking soda in boiling water Anthocyanin (red/purple) Red cabbage, purple carrots, beets Stays vivid \u2014 add acid (vinegar) to braising liquid Turns blue-green; avoid alkali Carotenoid (orange/yellow) Carrots, squash, sweet potato Stable in acid Stable \u2014 heat-resistant, fat-soluble (cook in fat for best color) Betanin (deep red) Beets Stable but bleeds Stable <p>The blanching method: 1. Large pot, aggressively salted water (like pasta water), rolling boil 2. Add vegetable in small batches \u2014 too many drops the temperature 3. Cook until just tender but with a little resistance (al dente) 4. Shock immediately in salted ice water (the salt prevents leaching) 5. Drain and dry \u2014 wet vegetables steam instead of saut\u00e9</p> <p>Full Meal: Blanched and shocked asparagus + haricots verts + broccolini \u2014 dressed with brown butter and toasted almonds, served at room temperature</p> Component Recipe Vegetables Asparagus, haricots verts, broccolini \u2014 all blanched and shocked Dressing Brown butter + toasted almonds + lemon zest + fleur de sel Protein (optional) Soft-boiled eggs on top to make it a dinner <p>The test: Hold a blanched green bean next to an unblanched one. The color difference is stark. Blanching stops enzymatic activity (which turns vegetables drab) while the ice bath fixes the color at its brightest.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#tuesday-roasting-caramelization-and-concentration","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Roasting: Caramelization and Concentration","text":"<p>Skill: Roasting drives out moisture and concentrates flavor while caramelizing the natural sugars in vegetables. It's the technique that turns broccoli from something people tolerate into something people want seconds of.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 How to Roast Any Vegetable</p> <p>The roasting rules: - Hot oven: 425\u2013450\u00b0F. Lower temperatures steam instead of roast. - Dry vegetables: Water is the enemy of browning. Pat dry after washing. - Single layer: Crowded pans steam. One layer always. - Fat on every surface: Toss in oil until lightly coated \u2014 not swimming, not dry. - Don't move them: Let the cut face develop contact with the pan; resist stirring for the first 15 minutes.</p> <p>The flavor family you're learning: Any vegetable with natural sugar caramelizes with high dry heat. Carrots become candy. Cauliflower develops a nutty depth. Beets intensify. Brussels sprouts lose their bitterness and become tender-crisp.</p> <p>Full Meal: Sheet Pan Dinner \u2014 roasted carrots, cauliflower, and beets with whatever protein you prefer + a tahini dressing or romesco</p> Component Recipe Vegetables Carrots (halved), cauliflower (florets), golden beets (quartered) Dressing Tahini sauce or romesco Protein Chicken thighs on the same pan, or eat vegetarian <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The One-Pan Roasted Vegetable Technique (Internet Shaquille) \u2014 Why temperature and spacing are the only two variables that actually matter.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#wednesday-saute-braise-and-the-crucifer-redemption","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Saut\u00e9, Braise, and the Crucifer Redemption","text":"<p>Skill: Cruciferous vegetables (Brussels sprouts, cabbage, cauliflower, broccoli) are the most-hated and most-abused vegetable family. The problem is almost always method \u2014 boiled vegetables taste of sulfur; roasted or properly braised vegetables taste of caramelization and sweetness.</p> <p>Two techniques tonight:</p> <p>Pan-braising \u2014 a hybrid of saut\u00e9ing and steaming: sear in fat until color develops, add a small amount of liquid (stock, wine, vinegar), cover and finish until tender. The vegetables get both Maillard browning and tenderizing steam.</p> <p>Charred cabbage \u2014 the full-heat technique that turns cabbage from something tolerable into something remarkable.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Charred Miso Cabbage</p> <p>Full Meal: - Crispy Brussels Sprouts with Fish Sauce and Crispy Shallots \u2014 this dish converts Brussels sprout haters - Charred Cabbage with Miso-Sesame Sauce \u2014 a revelation; whole cabbage wedges charred in cast iron - Simple white rice or crusty bread</p> Component Notes Brussels sprouts Halved, pressed cut-side into very hot oil; don't move; then toss Cabbage Wedges, cast iron, very high heat; miso glaze brushed at the end <p>The insight: Both dishes rely on high heat applied to a flat surface of the vegetable. Steaming or boiling is never the answer for these vegetables at dinner.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#thursday-vegetable-purees-texture-as-a-skill","title":"Thursday \u2014 Vegetable Pur\u00e9es: Texture as a Skill","text":"<p>Skill: A vegetable pur\u00e9e is deceptively simple and technically demanding. The difference between a good pur\u00e9e and a great one is entirely in the texture \u2014 silky versus grainy, the right viscosity to coat a spoon, seasoned at every stage.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Silky Smooth Vegetable Purees \u2014 the principles apply beyond soup to plated pur\u00e9es.</p> <p>Tonight apply the universal pur\u00e9e method to two vegetables simultaneously \u2014 compare the results:</p> Pur\u00e9e Method notes Finish Celery root (celeriac) Sweat in butter, add stock, simmer until completely soft, blend very fine, strain Cream + butter; subtle and elegant Parsnip with roasted garlic Roast garlic until golden; simmer parsnips in stock; blend with roasted garlic and butter Rich, sweet, earthy <p>Both can be passed through a fine mesh sieve for professional-smooth results. This is worth doing at least once.</p> <p>Full Meal: Celery root and parsnip pur\u00e9es as the base + seared duck breast or seared scallops on top + a simple green salad</p> <p>Why texture matters this much: A great pur\u00e9e tastes better because it coats your palate more evenly \u2014 every bite carries more flavor. A grainy or waterlogged pur\u00e9e tastes less of itself because the structure interrupts contact with your taste receptors. Straining is not precious \u2014 it's functional.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#friday-grilling-and-charring-fire-as-flavor","title":"Friday \u2014 Grilling and Charring: Fire as Flavor","text":"<p>Skill: Direct heat on vegetables produces char \u2014 carbon compounds that add bitterness, smokiness, and complexity. This is the single most underused technique for home vegetable cookery.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 How to Grill Vegetables</p> <p>The char distinction: - Light char \u2014 grill marks + some softening; proper char without burning through - Full char \u2014 eggplant, peppers, onions burned until fully black on the outside \u2192 the outside is scraped off, leaving smoky flesh underneath. This is what makes baba ganoush and rajas with poblanos.</p> <p>Full Meal: A grilled and charred vegetable spread:</p> Vegetable Method Served as Eggplant Full char over gas flame or under broiler; peel and season Baba ganoush or dressed salad Zucchini Direct grill, slight char marks, finish with lemon + mint Side Scallions Whole on the grill until charred and collapsed Alongside everything Peppers Full char, steam in bag, peel and seed Roasted pepper salad with olive oil and capers <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The Art of Charring Vegetables (Joshua Weissman) \u2014 He goes deep on why char is a flavor, not a mistake.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#saturday-project-plant-forward-dinner-party","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Plant-Forward Dinner Party","text":"<p>Cook a complete dinner where vegetables are the headline, not the support act. No protein required (though a soft-boiled egg or some cheese is allowed).</p> <p>The challenge: Put at least three vegetable techniques from this week on one table.</p> Course Dish Techniques Starter Roasted beet salad with whipped feta and pistachios Roasting + acid dressing Main Seared mushroom \"steaks\" + celery root pur\u00e9e + pan sauce from mushroom fond Pur\u00e9e + sear + pan sauce Side Blanched and shocked green beans with brown butter Blanching + butter sauce Bread Good sourdough Bought is fine <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Mushroom \"steaks\": Serious Eats \u2014 Pan-Seared Mushrooms \u2014 portobello or king oyster, sliced thick, seared in cast iron, finished with thyme butter.</p> <p>Skill targets: Color retention on the green beans. True silkiness on the celery root pur\u00e9e. A fond-based pan sauce from the mushrooms. All three on the table at the same temperature.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#sunday-off","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>Write: what vegetable do you dislike? Cook it using a method from this week that you've never applied to it. Report back to yourself.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#week-12-plant-forward-advanced-vegetable-technique","title":"Week 12 \u2014 Plant-Forward &amp; Advanced Vegetable Technique","text":""},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#monday-the-composed-salad-dressing-is-a-technique","title":"Monday \u2014 The Composed Salad: Dressing Is a Technique","text":"<p>Skill: A well-composed salad is not a bowl of things with dressing poured over it. It's a dish with its own architecture: texture contrast, temperature contrast, acid-fat balance, and deliberate seasoning.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 The Food Lab's Guide to Better Salads</p> <p>Caesar dressing from scratch \u2014 the real lesson:</p> <p>Classic Caesar Salad teaches emulsification, acid balance, the role of anchovies as umami backbone, and why freshly grated Parmesan behaves differently than pre-grated.</p> Component Technique Dressing Raw egg yolk + anchovy + garlic + lemon + Worcestershire; emulsify with oil Croutons Day-old bread, torn not cut; tossed in olive oil; bake until very crispy Lettuce Romaine; the spine of the leaf stays crispy even under dressing <p>Full Meal: Caesar salad (full portion, not a side) + half a roast chicken or grilled fish on top + crusty bread</p> <p>The dressing principle that applies everywhere: Season the greens before dressing. Add dressing in thirds, tossing between each. The greens should be lightly coated, not swimming.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#tuesday-legumes-and-beans-the-forgotten-protein","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Legumes and Beans: The Forgotten Protein","text":"<p>Skill: Beans cooked from dried are meaningfully better than canned. They also teach you patience, seasoning over time, and how to build flavor in a humble ingredient.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 How to Cook Dried Beans</p> <p>The two legume techniques tonight:</p> <p>White beans \u2014 braised in olive oil, garlic, aromatics, and your homemade chicken stock. Where they end up should taste like they've been simmering in a French farmhouse for 6 hours.</p> <p>Braised White Beans with Roasted Garlic and Rosemary</p> <p>Chickpeas \u2014 pan-fried until crispy in olive oil, finished with smoked paprika and lemon. A completely different texture from boiled chickpeas.</p> <p>Full Meal: Braised white beans on toast + crispy chickpeas + wilted greens + poached egg on top</p> Component Recipe White beans Braised in stock with garlic, rosemary, anchovy Chickpeas Crispy-fried in cast iron, paprika + lemon Greens Wilted spinach or kale in the bean liquid Egg (optional) Poached on top to make it a substantial dinner"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#wednesday-mushrooms-umami-in-plant-form","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Mushrooms: Umami in Plant Form","text":"<p>Skill: Mushrooms deserve an entire session because they behave unlike any other vegetable \u2014 they're 80\u201390% water, which means crowding a pan turns them into steamed rubber. The technique that produces deep flavor is identical to a proper sear: high heat, no crowding, don't stir.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 The Food Lab: The Importance of Properly Browning Mushrooms</p> <p>The mushroom rules: - Dry pan, high heat, add mushrooms when pan is smoking \u2014 no fat yet (the mushrooms will immediately give up water if fat is added cold) - Once the water evaporates and the pan is dry again, add butter and aromatics - Never wash mushrooms in water \u2014 wipe clean with a dry cloth or brush - Salt after browning, not before (salt draws moisture)</p> <p>Full Meal: Mushroom Bourguignon \u2014 the vegetarian version of the French braise, using a mix of cremini, shiitake, and oyster mushrooms + a proper wine reduction</p> Component Recipe Mushrooms Mix of varieties; seared separately, then combined Sauce Red wine + stock + tomato paste + herbs and aromatics Base Creamy mashed potatoes, polenta, or buttered egg noodles <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Saut\u00e9 Mushrooms Properly (Ethan Chlebowski) \u2014 He tests the crowding variable specifically. Watch the difference in texture and color between the crowded and uncrowded batches.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#thursday-fermentation-and-pickling-vegetables-that-last","title":"Thursday \u2014 Fermentation and Pickling: Vegetables That Last","text":"<p>Skill: Understanding the difference between quick pickling (brine + acid), lacto-fermentation (brine + time + natural bacteria), and their role in a well-built kitchen.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Quick Pickling Guide</p> <p>Tonight make two things:</p> <p>Quick pickles (ready in 30 minutes): - Pickled Red Onions \u2014 red wine vinegar + salt + sugar + a few peppercorns - Pickled Jalape\u00f1os and Carrots \u2014 white wine vinegar + salt + cumin + garlic</p> <p>Lacto-fermented sauerkraut (takes 5\u20137 days \u2014 start it tonight, finish it next week): - Simple Sauerkraut \u2014 green cabbage + 2% salt by weight; massage until brine releases; pack into jar; weigh down; leave at room temp 5\u20137 days</p> <p>Full Meal: Use the pickles tonight on whatever you're eating \u2014 tacos, a grain bowl, grilled fish. Quick pickles don't need a dedicated meal. They improve everything they touch.</p> <p>Why this matters: Pickles and ferments are balance tools. When a dish is too rich, too fatty, or needs brightness, a quick pickle solves it in 30 seconds. Having pickled red onions in your fridge at all times is one of the highest-leverage kitchen habits you can build.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#friday-a-completely-vegetable-driven-main","title":"Friday \u2014 A Completely Vegetable-Driven Main","text":"<p>Skill: Executing a dinner where a vegetable is the structural main course \u2014 not a supplement to protein, not a side.</p> <p>Tonight's choice: stuffed whole roasted peppers.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Bon App\u00e9tit \u2014 Stuffed Peppers</p> <p>The stuffing is the lesson: aromatic base (onion, garlic) + grain (rice, farro, or barley) + acid (tomato) + fat (cheese or olive oil) + herbs. This formula produces a satisfying, cohesive dish where the vegetable wrapper is structural \u2014 not decorative.</p> <p>Full Meal: Stuffed roasted peppers (3 colors \u2014 red, yellow, orange) + simple tomato sauce beneath them + salad</p> Component Notes Peppers Halved, par-roasted before stuffing to soften walls Stuffing Saut\u00e9ed onion + garlic + cooked farro or rice + cherry tomatoes + parmesan Sauce beneath Simple tomato concass\u00e9 or straight from your Week 5 sauce skills"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#saturday-project-the-vegetable-tasting-menu","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: The Vegetable Tasting Menu","text":"<p>Cook 4\u20135 vegetable preparations using different techniques. Serve them as a tasting \u2014 small plates, one at a time, with bread.</p> Course Dish Technique 1 Celery root pur\u00e9e with roasted garlic oil Pur\u00e9e 2 Blanched asparagus with brown butter and fried capers Blanching + beurre noisette 3 Charred cabbage with miso-sesame Charring 4 Mushroom bourguignon on toast Sear + braise 5 Quick-pickled vegetables + bread Fermentation + pickling <p>This is practice for the multi-course timing you'll need for the dinner parties in Weeks 53\u201354.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#sunday-off_1","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>The sauerkraut you started Thursday needs checking. Push it down under the brine if any has floated above the liquid. It should smell pleasantly sour, not foul.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#module-2-checkpoint-continues","title":"Module 2 Checkpoint Continues","text":"<p>Vegetables are now in your repertoire, not just alongside your repertoire. Before moving to Weeks 15\u201316 (Pasta &amp; Grains), you should be able to answer yes to:</p> <ul> <li>[ ] I can blanch and shock a green vegetable and it stays bright green</li> <li>[ ] I can roast any vegetable without it steaming in its own moisture</li> <li>[ ] I can make a smooth, silky vegetable pur\u00e9e</li> <li>[ ] I understand why high heat is almost always the right answer for vegetables</li> <li>[ ] I have pickled onions in my fridge right now</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 The Food Lab: How to Get Maximum Browning on Your Vegetables \u2014 the science behind the single pan, high heat approach</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Samin Nosrat on Salt, Fat, Acid, Heat applied to vegetables \u2014 how acid changes everything</li> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Zuni Cafe Cookbook by Judy Rodgers \u2014 not primarily vegetarian, but contains the most thoughtful writing on vegetable cookery of any English-language cookbook</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html","title":"Weeks 13\u201314 Quick Reference \u2014 Vegetables &amp; Plant-Forward Cooking","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Week 11\u201312 Guide</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html#core-techniques-at-a-glance","title":"Core Techniques at a Glance","text":"Technique Best for Key rule Blanch &amp; shock Green vegetables, par-cooking Salted boiling water \u2192 salted ice water immediately Roasting Root veg, cruciferous, anything with sugar 425\u2013450\u00b0F, single layer, dry surface Panroasting Brussels sprouts, mushrooms, dense cuts Cast iron or stainless, very hot, don't move Pan-braising Cabbage, fennel, leeks Sear \u2192 small splash of liquid \u2192 cover \u2192 finish Charring Eggplant, peppers, scallions, cabbage Open flame or broiler; the burnt outside is removed or eaten Pur\u00e9e Any cooked vegetable Simmer until dead-soft, blend very fine, strain through sieve Grilling Zucchini, asparagus, corn, halved lemons Dry surface, oiled grate, high heat Quick pickle Onions, cucumbers, jalape\u00f1os, carrots Warm brine (water + vinegar + salt + sugar); ready in 20\u201330 min Lacto-ferment Cabbage (sauerkraut), brine-packed anything 2% salt by weight; room temp; 5\u20137 days"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html#the-puree-method-universal","title":"The Pur\u00e9e Method (Universal)","text":"<ol> <li>Sweat aromatics in butter or olive oil (don't brown)</li> <li>Add vegetable cut into uniform pieces</li> <li>Add stock or water \u2014 just enough to cover</li> <li>Simmer until completely, fully, collapse-on-a-fork soft</li> <li>Transfer to blender \u2014 blend 2\u20133 minutes until very smooth</li> <li>Pass through a fine mesh sieve, pressing with a ladle</li> <li>Adjust seasoning; add cream or butter to adjust richness and sheen</li> </ol> <p>Texture test: A spoonful held up should drop cleanly and coat the spoon evenly with no graininess.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html#color-science-reference","title":"Color Science Reference","text":"Color Pigment Acid Alkali Green Chlorophyll Turns olive/drab Brightens (pinch baking soda) Red/Purple Anthocyanin Stays vivid Turns blue-grey Orange Carotenoid Stable Stable Deep red Betanin (beets) Stable Stable <p>Rule of thumb: Season green vegetables with acid (lemon, vinegar) only after they come off the heat.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html#roasting-rules-summary","title":"Roasting Rules Summary","text":"<ul> <li>Oven: 425\u2013450\u00b0F</li> <li>Fat: enough to coat each piece \u2014 not swimming, not bare</li> <li>Pan: sheet pan with space \u2014 crowded = steamed</li> <li>Start: don't stir for the first 10\u201315 minutes \u2014 let the contact surface brown</li> <li>Test: a knife should slide in with no resistance</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html#mushroom-saute-protocol","title":"Mushroom Saut\u00e9 Protocol","text":"<ol> <li>Pan (cast iron or stainless) over high heat \u2014 no fat yet \u2014 until smoking</li> <li>Add mushrooms \u2014 they will sizzle and immediately weep water</li> <li>Resist stirring; let the water evaporate (~4\u20135 min)</li> <li>Once pan is dry and mushrooms are shrinking, add butter + aromatics</li> <li>Toss; cook 2 more minutes; season at the end</li> <li>Salt only after browning</li> </ol>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html#quick-pickle-formula","title":"Quick Pickle Formula","text":"Ingredient Ratio Vinegar (any) 1 cup Water 1 cup Salt 1 tsp Sugar 1 tsp (optional) Flavoring Peppercorns, garlic, chilli, herbs \u2014 whatever fits <ul> <li>Heat brine until salt and sugar dissolve</li> <li>Pour over sliced vegetables in a clean jar</li> <li>Cool; seal; refrigerate</li> <li>Ready in 20\u201330 minutes, best after 1\u20132 hours</li> <li>Lasts 2\u20134 weeks refrigerated</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html#lacto-fermentation-formula","title":"Lacto-Fermentation Formula","text":"Variable Target Salt by weight 2% of vegetable weight Temperature 65\u201375\u00b0F room temperature Time 5\u20137 days (taste daily after day 3) Container Clean glass jar with loose lid (release CO2) Key rule Keep vegetables submerged under the brine at all times"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html#week-1112-dishes-summary","title":"Week 11\u201312 Dishes Summary","text":"Week Day Dish Technique 11 Mon Brown butter asparagus + haricots verts Blanch + shock + beurre noisette 11 Tue Sheet pan carrots, cauliflower, beets Roasting 11 Wed Crispy Brussels + charred cabbage with miso Pan sear + char 11 Thu Celery root + parsnip pur\u00e9es Pur\u00e9e + strain 11 Fri Baba ganoush + grilled veg spread Charring + grilling 11 Sat Plant-forward dinner party Multi-technique 12 Mon Caesar salad from scratch Emulsification + dressing 12 Tue Braised white beans + crispy chickpeas Braising + pan-frying legumes 12 Wed Mushroom Bourguignon Sear + braise 12 Thu Quick pickles + start sauerkraut Pickling + fermentation 12 Fri Stuffed roasted peppers Roasting + grain stuffing 12 Sat 5-course vegetable tasting menu Multi-technique"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html","title":"Weeks 13\u201314 Shopping List \u2014 Vegetables &amp; Plant-Forward Cooking","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Week 11\u201312 Guide</p> <p>How to use this list: Shop once at the start of Week 11. The lacto-ferment (sauerkraut) starts on Week 12 Thursday with ingredients you'll already have. Items marked \ud83e\udd6c FRESH should be selected for peak quality \u2014 buy the best-looking specimens at the market.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#produce-week-11","title":"\ud83e\udd6c Produce (Week 11)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Asparagus \u2014 1 lb (thin to medium; not thick)</li> <li>[ ] Haricots verts (French green beans) \u2014 \u00bd lb, or use regular green beans</li> <li>[ ] Broccolini \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 6\u20138 medium (not baby cut)</li> <li>[ ] Cauliflower \u2014 1 large head</li> <li>[ ] Golden beets \u2014 1 bunch (about 4)</li> <li>[ ] Brussels sprouts \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Green or Savoy cabbage \u2014 1 large head (will also use for sauerkraut)</li> <li>[ ] Eggplant \u2014 2 medium globe or 4 Japanese</li> <li>[ ] Zucchini \u2014 2 medium</li> <li>[ ] Scallions \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Bell peppers (red, yellow, orange) \u2014 2 of each for Week 12 stuffed peppers</li> <li>[ ] Celery root (celeriac) \u2014 1 large (biggest one you can find)</li> <li>[ ] Parsnips \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 bulbs (roasting a whole head Thursday)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 5\u20136</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#produce-week-12","title":"\ud83e\udd6c Produce (Week 12)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Romaine lettuce \u2014 2 heads (for Caesar)</li> <li>[ ] Mixed mushrooms \u2014 2 lbs (cremini + shiitake + oyster or king oyster)</li> <li>[ ] Spinach or kale \u2014 2 large bunches</li> <li>[ ] Red onions \u2014 3\u20134 (pickling + regular use)</li> <li>[ ] Jalape\u00f1os \u2014 4 (pickling)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh rosemary \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Fresh thyme \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 1 large bunch</li> <li>[ ] Fresh mint \u2014 1 bunch</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc4 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Extra-virgin olive oil (good one \u2014 you'll taste it)</li> <li>[ ] Neutral oil (grapeseed or vegetable) \u2014 for high-heat roasting</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 2 sticks</li> <li>[ ] Diamond Crystal kosher salt</li> <li>[ ] Sliced almonds \u2014 \u00bc cup (toasted for asparagus)</li> <li>[ ] Tahini \u2014 \u00bd cup</li> <li>[ ] White miso paste \u2014 2\u20133 tbsp</li> <li>[ ] Toasted sesame oil \u2014 2 tbsp</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce \u2014 2 tbsp (for Brussels sprouts)</li> <li>[ ] Anchovy fillets \u2014 1 tin (Caesar dressing + bean braising)</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce \u2014 2 tbsp</li> <li>[ ] Worcestershire sauce \u2014 1 tsp (Caesar)</li> <li>[ ] Smoked paprika \u2014 1 tsp (crispy chickpeas)</li> <li>[ ] Red pepper flakes \u2014 1 tsp</li> <li>[ ] Capers \u2014 1 small jar</li> <li>[ ] Whole black peppercorns</li> <li>[ ] Bay leaves \u2014 4\u20135</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#canned-dried-goods","title":"\ud83e\uded9 Canned / Dried Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dried white beans (cannellini or Great Northern) \u2014 1 lb (soak night before Week 12 Tuesday)</li> <li>[ ] Dried or canned chickpeas \u2014 1 can (or 1 cup dried)</li> <li>[ ] Farro or barley \u2014 1 cup (stuffing for peppers)</li> <li>[ ] Canned whole peeled tomatoes \u2014 1 can (28 oz, for stuffed pepper sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Good chicken stock or vegetable stock \u2014 48 oz (beans, pur\u00e9es)</li> <li>[ ] Day-old bread or sourdough \u2014 half a loaf (croutons)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#dairy-eggs","title":"\ud83e\uddc0 Dairy / Eggs","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Parmesan \u2014 4 oz, block (grate your own; not pre-grated)</li> <li>[ ] Egg yolks \u2014 2 (Caesar dressing; raw, so use good eggs)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 \u00bd cup (pur\u00e9es, optional)</li> <li>[ ] Feta \u2014 4 oz (roasted beet salad, Week 11 Saturday)</li> <li>[ ] Ricotta or fresh goat cheese \u2014 4 oz (optional, stuffed peppers)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#protein-optional-all-proteins-in-this-block-are-supplementary","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Protein (Optional \u2014 all proteins in this block are supplementary)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Chicken thighs \u2014 4 (for sheet pan Tuesday; skip if cooking vegetarian)</li> <li>[ ] Duck breast or scallops \u2014 2 portions (for pur\u00e9e Thursday; skip if vegetarian)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (poached for bean toast, boiled for salads)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#acids-vinegars","title":"\ud83c\udf76 Acids / Vinegars","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Red wine vinegar \u2014 \u00bd cup (pickled red onions + dressing)</li> <li>[ ] White wine vinegar \u2014 \u00bd cup (pickled jalape\u00f1os and carrots)</li> <li>[ ] Apple cider vinegar \u2014 \u00bc cup (general use)</li> <li>[ ] Dijon mustard \u2014 1 small jar</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#fermentation-week-12-thursday","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Fermentation (Week 12 Thursday)","text":"<p>You'll already have green cabbage and salt from the list above. You only need a clean, wide-mouth glass jar (at least 1 quart) and patience.</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Wide-mouth glass jar \u2014 1-quart or half-gallon (mason jar with loose lid)</li> <li>[ ] Diamond Crystal kosher salt (already on list)</li> <li>[ ] Green or Savoy cabbage (already on list)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#equipment-notes-for-this-block","title":"\ud83e\uddca Equipment Notes for This Block","text":"<ul> <li>Sheet pan(s) with a rim \u2014 you want real space. If you only have one sheet pan, cook in shifts.</li> <li>Cast iron skillet \u2014 essential for charred cabbage and mushrooms</li> <li>Fine mesh strainer \u2014 needed for silky pur\u00e9es</li> <li>High-speed blender \u2014 a Vitamix-type produces better pur\u00e9es than a food processor; use what you have</li> <li>Ice bath bowl \u2014 large bowl + ice + water for shocking</li> <li>Knife + board \u2014 heavy fabrication this week (you already have this)</li> <li>Wide-mouth mason jar \u2014 for sauerkraut</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html","title":"\ud83c\udf5d Weeks 13\u201314: Pasta &amp; Grains from Scratch","text":"<p>\u2190 Quick Reference \u2192 | Shopping List \u2192</p> <p>\"Making pasta from scratch is not about showing off. It's about understanding gluten, hydration, and the relationship between flour and time \u2014 which teaches you more about cooking than any recipe.\"</p> <p>The Week 11\u201312 philosophy: These two weeks are about making things from scratch that most people buy. Not because scratch is always better \u2014 it isn't always \u2014 but because understanding the process makes you a better cook with even the store-bought version. When you've made your own pasta dough, you know what \"properly hydrated\" feels like and why overworked dough turns tough. That knowledge transfers everywhere.</p> <p>Before you start Week 11, read:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 Fresh Pasta vs. Dried Pasta: Which Should You Use?</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 The Science of Pasta Water</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#week-11-pasta-dough-the-foundation","title":"Week 11 \u2014 Pasta Dough: The Foundation","text":""},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#monday-the-dough-meeting-gluten","title":"Monday \u2014 The Dough: Meeting Gluten","text":"<p>Skill: Fresh pasta dough is flour, eggs, and time. The gluten network forms as you knead, the dough becomes elastic, and it needs to rest so the gluten relaxes and becomes rollable. Your job tonight: understand what the dough is telling you at each stage. Too dry \u2014 it cracks when folded. Too wet \u2014 it sticks and tears. Properly rested \u2014 smooth, supple, and cooperative.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Homemade Fresh Pasta (basic egg dough, cut into tagliatelle) + Serious Eats \u2014 Slow-Cooked Tomato Sauce (Sugo di Pomodoro) + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Green Salad with Vinaigrette</p> <p>Make a basic egg pasta dough. Rest it for 30 minutes. Roll it by hand or with a pasta machine. Cut tagliatelle. Cook for 90 seconds in aggressively salted water. Toss with a slow-cooked tomato sauce (or just brown butter and parmesan if you want to let the pasta speak).</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Parmesan carries the protein component; the pasta is the star</li> <li>Starch: Your own fresh tagliatelle</li> <li>Sauce: Slow-cooked tomato sugo (can be made on the weekend and reheated, or made earlier in the week in a big batch)</li> <li>Salad: Simple green salad</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Quick and Easy Pasta With Cherry Tomato Sauce \u2014 A fast tomato sauce versus your slow sugo \u2014 watch what the high heat does to the tomatoes in minutes and compare the result to your 3-hour cook.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#tuesday-ravioli-pasta-as-a-vessel","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Ravioli: Pasta as a Vessel","text":"<p>Skill: Stuffed pasta (ravioli, tortellini) requires you to roll the dough thinner than you think and seal the edges properly \u2014 no air pockets inside or they burst during cooking. The filling should be firm enough to hold its shape when piped or spooned but wet enough to be creamy when cooked. Tonight: ricotta and herb filling, classic.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Ricotta-Filled Ravioli with Brown Butter and Sage using the same base dough + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Cherry Tomatoes + Serious Eats \u2014 Radicchio Salad with Anchovy Vinaigrette</p> <p>Make the same dough from Monday (make it in the morning if you want to save time \u2014 it keeps in the fridge wrapped tightly overnight). Fill with ricotta, parmesan, lemon zest, and herbs. Toss the finished ravioli in brown butter and crispy sage.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Ricotta filling + parmesan</li> <li>Starch: Your own fresh ravioli</li> <li>Veg: Roasted cherry tomatoes alongside</li> <li>Salad: Radicchio with anchovy vinaigrette</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#wednesday-gnocchi-potato-and-restraint","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Gnocchi: Potato and Restraint","text":"<p>Skill: Potato gnocchi is one of the most unforgiving things in cooking. Too much flour and they're heavy and gluey. Too little and they fall apart in the water. The secret: bake your potatoes (don't boil \u2014 water makes them wet and you'll add too much flour), rice them while hot, and handle the dough as little as humanly possible. Overworking develops gluten and makes them tough.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Light and Tender Potato Gnocchi with Sage Butter + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Broccolini with Garlic and Chili + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Green Salad</p> <p>The gnocchi themselves are the project. The sage butter sauce takes 5 minutes. The broccolini goes in the oven while you shape the gnocchi. Everything comes together at the same time.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Parmesan and egg yolks in the gnocchi; the butter sauce finishes it</li> <li>Starch: Potato gnocchi \u2014 your own</li> <li>Veg: Roasted broccolini</li> <li>Salad: Simple green salad</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Ricotta Gnocchi \u2014 Different base ingredient (ricotta vs. potato), but the key instruction is the same: handle it as little as possible. Watch why overworking kills gnocchi.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#thursday-off","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 How to Cook Pasta Properly: The Complete Guide</p> <p>Pay particular attention to the section on pasta water and why it matters for emulsifying sauces. If you're not already saving a cup of pasta water before draining, start tonight.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#friday-pasta-water-the-secret-sauce-ingredient","title":"Friday \u2014 Pasta Water: The Secret Sauce Ingredient","text":"<p>Skill: Starchy pasta water is an emulsifier \u2014 it helps fat and water-based ingredients bind into a silky, coating sauce rather than separating. Aglio e olio and carbonara both depend on it. Tonight you'll make aglio e olio and notice how dramatically the pasta water changes the sauce.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Spaghetti Aglio e Olio + Serious Eats \u2014 Saut\u00e9ed Spinach with Garlic and Lemon + Serious Eats \u2014 Tomato and Cucumber Salad with Red Onion</p> <p>Aglio e olio is garlic, olive oil, pasta water, pasta, chili flakes, and parsley. Nothing else. It teaches emulsification, the function of pasta water, and proper sauce consistency \u2014 all in 15 minutes.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Anchovy in the aglio (optional but recommended \u2014 they dissolve completely)</li> <li>Starch: Spaghetti</li> <li>Veg: Saut\u00e9ed spinach with garlic and lemon</li> <li>Salad: Tomato and cucumber salad, bright and acidic alongside the rich pasta</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Spaghetti Aglio Olio e Fried Shallot \u2014 Same dish with one addition \u2014 watch the emulsification move: that moment when pasta water, oil, and garlic become a sauce instead of a greasy tangle.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#saturday-project-meal-a-full-italian-pasta-dinner","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Full Italian Pasta Dinner","text":"<p>The challenge: Three pasta shapes, three sauces, made in one evening. This is how an Italian family Sunday lunch actually works \u2014 generous, abundant, and a showcase of everything pasta can do.</p> <p>Full Meal (serves 4\u20136):</p> <ol> <li>Antipasto: Serious Eats \u2014 Bruschetta with Tomato and Basil \u2014 toasted bread, ripe tomatoes, garlic, good olive oil</li> <li>Pasta 1: Serious Eats \u2014 Classic Cacio e Pepe \u2014 a small portion per person as a first pasta</li> <li>Pasta 2: Your fresh tagliatelle from Monday's dough (make it ahead) with Serious Eats \u2014 Slow-Cooked Bolognese (make the sauce Saturday morning \u2014 it needs 3 hours)</li> <li>Salad: Serious Eats \u2014 Classic Italian Green Salad with a simple lemon and olive oil dressing</li> </ol> <p>Skill targets: Bolognese seasoned in layers throughout a 3-hour cook. Fresh pasta cut to even width. Cacio e Pepe silky and sauce-y, not dry and clumpy.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Rag\u00f9 Bolognese (Northern Italian Meat Sauce) \u2014 Watch the sequence of liquid additions \u2014 milk first, then wine, then stock \u2014 and why the order matters for the final texture.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#week-12-grains-rice-polenta-and-beyond","title":"Week 12 \u2014 Grains: Rice, Polenta, and Beyond","text":"<p>\"Every culture has a grain at its center. Learning to cook grains properly \u2014 not just until they're done, but until they're excellent \u2014 is a quiet superpower.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#monday-risotto-patience-as-technique","title":"Monday \u2014 Risotto: Patience as Technique","text":"<p>Skill (revisited with intention): You made risotto in Week 7 as a vehicle for vegetable stock. This week it's the subject. Risotto is a method \u2014 gradual liquid addition, constant encouragement, finishing with cold butter and parmesan off the heat. Tonight: no extra protein, no elaborate sauce. Just risotto made perfectly, to the point where the texture alone is enough.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Mushroom and Asparagus Risotto + Serious Eats \u2014 Bitter Greens Salad with Walnut and Gorgonzola</p> <p>The soy sauce called for in the Serious Eats mushroom risotto recipe is deliberate \u2014 it's a hit of umami (Week 10 callback) that deepens the mushroom flavor without tasting like soy sauce. Trust it.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Mushrooms and parmesan carry the savory weight; add a fried egg on top if you want more substance</li> <li>Starch: The risotto is the dish</li> <li>Salad: Bitter greens with gorgonzola and walnuts to cut through the richness</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Pause Risotto Halfway Through to Finish Later \u2014 A 60-second technique that changes how you host. Watch the starch behavior when he stops and restarts \u2014 that's what you're riding on every stir.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#tuesday-rice-the-worlds-most-important-grain","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Rice: The World's Most Important Grain","text":"<p>Skill: Most home cooks treat rice as an afterthought. Tonight it's the focus. You'll cook Persian-style rice with a tahdig crust \u2014 the goal is a golden, crispy bottom that releases from the pot in a crown. Too high heat and it burns; too low and it stays soft. This is heat control and patience in one dish.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Persian-Style Rice with Crispy Tahdig Crust + Serious Eats \u2014 Slow-Roasted Spiced Lamb Shoulder + Serious Eats \u2014 Cucumber and Yogurt Salad (Tzatziki-Style)</p> <p>Tahdig \u2014 the crispy rice crust at the bottom of the Persian rice pot \u2014 is one of the most coveted things in Iranian cuisine. Get it right and it releases from the pot in a golden crown.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Slow-roasted lamb shoulder (set it in the oven early, it takes 4 hours but is completely passive)</li> <li>Starch: Persian rice with tahdig \u2014 the project of the evening</li> <li>Salad: Cucumber and herb yogurt salad, cool and acidic alongside the rich lamb</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#wednesday-polenta-low-and-slow","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Polenta: Low and Slow","text":"<p>Skill: Traditional polenta is not the quick-cook kind. It takes 45\u201360 minutes of stirring over low heat, adding stock or water gradually as the cornmeal absorbs it. The result is fundamentally different from the 5-minute version \u2014 creamier, with a deeper corn flavor and a silky consistency that coats the back of a spoon.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Creamy Parmesan Polenta + Serious Eats \u2014 Braised Short Ribs or Beef Ragu (use leftover braising liquid from Tuesday's lamb, or start fresh with beef cheeks) + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Green Salad</p> <p>The polenta goes underneath. The braise goes on top. The salad cuts the richness. This is the entire meal and it's deeply satisfying.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Braised short ribs or lamb ragu (use Tuesday's lamb leftovers if you have them)</li> <li>Starch: Slow-cooked creamy polenta</li> <li>Salad: Simple green salad</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: POV Polenta Soup With Whatever You Want \u2014 A looser, brothier version of the same grain \u2014 watch how he adjusts the liquid ratio and seasoning as it cooks down. Same instincts, different texture target.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#thursday-off_1","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 An Introduction to Grains: How to Shop For, Store, and Cook Every Type</p> <p>Make a mental note of which grains you've never cooked before and add at least one to your Saturday shopping list.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#friday-farro-and-grains-that-think-for-themselves","title":"Friday \u2014 Farro and Grains That Think for Themselves","text":"<p>Skill: Unlike risotto, which needs constant attention, farro and other ancient grains (freekeh, barley, bulgur) are largely self-sufficient. The key is seasoning the cooking liquid well and knowing when to stop \u2014 farro should be tender but still have chew, never mushy.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Farro Salad with Roasted Beets and Goat Cheese + Serious Eats \u2014 Crispy Pan-Seared Salmon + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Arugula Salad</p> <p>The warm farro salad is a full grain side dish. The crispy salmon is the protein. The arugula salad provides the acid counterpoint.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Crispy-skinned salmon fillet</li> <li>Starch/Veg: Warm farro with roasted beets, goat cheese, and vinaigrette</li> <li>Salad: Arugula with lemon</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#saturday-project-meal-a-grain-forward-dinner-party","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Grain-Forward Dinner Party","text":"<p>The challenge: Grains as the hero \u2014 not the side. This Saturday's dinner could comfortably be served to guests who don't cook, and they would never suspect that every dish was a skills exercise in disguise.</p> <p>Full Meal:</p> <ol> <li>Starter: Serious Eats \u2014 Whipped Ricotta on Crostini with Honey and Walnuts \u2014 a quick, beautiful opener that requires no cooking</li> <li>Main: Serious Eats \u2014 Saffron Risotto alla Milanese with Serious Eats \u2014 Pan-Seared Scallops with Lemon-Brown Butter on top \u2014 the scallops rest on the risotto as the protein component</li> <li>Salad: Serious Eats \u2014 Fennel Salad with Blood Orange and Olives \u2014 serve alongside or between courses</li> </ol> <p>Skill targets: Risotto at perfect consistency (flows slowly like lava when plated, not stiff). Scallops with a deep, dry sear on each side. Everything on the table at the same time.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#fresh-pasta-the-physics","title":"Fresh Pasta: the Physics","text":"<p>Fresh pasta looks like pure craft but it's mostly chemistry. The ratio of egg yolks to flour, how the gluten develops as you knead, and why resting the dough matters are all understandable and learnable.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Best Slow-Cooked Tomato Sauce \u2014 The sauce you pair with your fresh pasta defines the dish as much as the pasta itself. This is the canonical red sauce recipe.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Fresh Egg Pasta \u2014 The full technical breakdown of fresh pasta from Kenji, including the science behind the dough.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#risotto-why-the-stir-matters","title":"Risotto: Why the Stir Matters","text":"<p>Risotto is not about patience. It's about starch gelatinization and gradual liquid absorption. Once you understand the mechanism, you can make it in 18 minutes.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Key Techniques for Perfect Risotto \u2014 The full technical breakdown: why the stock goes in gradually, what the starch is actually doing, and how to read the risotto's texture at each stage rather than relying on a timer.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Pasta Grannies \u2014 Documentary-style videos of Italian grandmothers making regional pasta. No voiceover required \u2014 just watching the hand technique is the education.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Mastering Pasta by Marc Vetri \u2014 The most comprehensive English-language book on pasta. Goes deep on shapes, doughs, sauces, and the regional logic behind pairing them.</li> </ul> <p>\u2190 Weeks 9\u201310 | Weeks 15\u201316 \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Weeks 13\u201314 Quick Reference \u2014 Pasta &amp; Grains from Scratch","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/quick-ref.html#week-11-recipes-pasta-dough-the-foundation","title":"Week 11 Recipes \u2014 Pasta Dough: The Foundation","text":"Day Dish Skill Link Mon Homemade Tagliatelle + Slow-Cooked Tomato Sugo + Green Salad Egg pasta dough, rest, roll, cut Pasta \u00b7 Sauce \u00b7 Salad Tue Ricotta Ravioli with Brown Butter and Sage + Roasted Cherry Tomatoes + Radicchio Salad Stuffed pasta \u2014 thin rolling and sealing Pasta \u00b7 Tomatoes \u00b7 Salad Wed Light Potato Gnocchi with Sage Butter + Roasted Broccolini + Green Salad Gnocchi: bake potatoes, rice hot, minimum flour Gnocchi \u00b7 Broccolini \u00b7 Salad Thu OFF Read: how to cook pasta properly Article Fri Spaghetti Aglio e Olio + Saut\u00e9ed Spinach + Tomato Cucumber Salad Pasta water as emulsifier Aglio e Olio \u00b7 Spinach \u00b7 Salad Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Full Italian Pasta Dinner \u2014 Bruschetta + Cacio e Pepe + Fresh Tagliatelle Bolognese + Green Salad Three pasta techniques in one service Bruschetta \u00b7 Cacio e Pepe \u00b7 Bolognese \u00b7 Salad"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/quick-ref.html#week-12-recipes-grains-rice-polenta-and-beyond","title":"Week 12 Recipes \u2014 Grains: Rice, Polenta, and Beyond","text":"Day Dish Skill Link Mon Mushroom and Asparagus Risotto + Bitter Greens Salad Risotto mastery \u2014 technique, not just recipe Risotto \u00b7 Salad Tue Persian Rice with Tahdig + Slow-Roasted Lamb Shoulder + Cucumber Yogurt Salad Tahdig \u2014 heat control and patience Rice \u00b7 Lamb \u00b7 Salad Wed Creamy Parmesan Polenta + Braised Short Ribs or Lamb Ragu + Green Salad Slow polenta \u2014 45\u201360 min of stirring Polenta \u00b7 Ribs \u00b7 Salad Thu OFF Read: intro to grains Article Fri Farro Salad with Beets &amp; Goat Cheese + Crispy Salmon + Arugula Salad Farro \u2014 dress while hot Farro \u00b7 Salmon \u00b7 Salad Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Grain-Forward Dinner Party \u2014 Whipped Ricotta Crostini + Saffron Risotto + Pan-Seared Scallops + Fennel Blood Orange Salad Grains as the star of a dinner party Crostini \u00b7 Risotto \u00b7 Scallops \u00b7 Salad"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/quick-ref.html#shopping-notes","title":"Shopping Notes","text":"<p>Week 11 pasta essentials: \"00\" flour or all-purpose flour, large eggs (farm eggs if available \u2014 the yolks make a difference), whole-milk ricotta, fresh sage.</p> <p>Week 11 Monday tip: Make a double batch of tomato sugo on Sunday \u2014 you'll use it Monday and the leftover becomes Pasta 2 on Saturday's dinner party if needed.</p> <p>Week 12 Tuesday: Lamb shoulder needs 4 hours in the oven. Start it mid-afternoon or set it early and hold warm. Leftover lamb becomes the ragu for Wednesday's polenta.</p> <p>Week 12 Saturday: Scallops must be completely dry before searing. Pat thoroughly on paper towels and let them sit uncovered on the rack in the fridge for 30 min before cooking. Wet scallops steam; dry scallops sear.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 13\u201314: Pasta &amp; Grains from Scratch","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Week 11 is flour and eggs. Week 12 is grains and patience. Buy the pasta flour and a potato ricer before Week 11 starts \u2014 they're the tools you absolutely need. The lamb shoulder (Week 12 Tue) needs 4 hours in the oven; start it by 3 PM.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Potato ricer \u2014 essential for gnocchi (Week 11 Wed). A box grater works as a backup but the ricer makes better gnocchi. Under $15.</li> <li>[ ] Pasta machine (optional) \u2014 hand-cranked pasta machine (~$35) makes rolling dramatically easier for Weeks 11 Mon/Tue. Rolling by hand works too.</li> <li>[ ] Large pot for pasta \u2014 you need volume and lots of salt. Pasta water should taste like a light broth.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-11","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 11","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Ricotta cheese (whole-milk) \u2014 1 lb (Week 11 Tue ravioli filling + Week 12 Sat crostini)</li> <li>[ ] Anchovies \u2014 1 can (Week 11 Fri aglio e olio, optional but recommended)</li> <li>[ ] Guanciale or pancetta \u2014 4 oz (Week 11 Sat Bolognese)</li> <li>[ ] Ground beef \u2014 1 lb (Week 11 Sat Bolognese)</li> <li>[ ] Ground pork \u2014 \u00bd lb (Week 11 Sat Bolognese \u2014 adds richness)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-12","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 12","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Mushrooms (mixed: cremini, shiitake, oyster) \u2014 2 lbs (Week 12 Mon risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Lamb shoulder \u2014 3\u20134 lbs, bone-in (Week 12 Tue PROJECT \u2014 buy fresh, ask butcher)</li> <li>[ ] Bone-in beef short ribs or beef cheeks \u2014 2 lbs (Week 12 Wed braised ragu, OR use Tuesday's leftover lamb)</li> <li>[ ] Salmon fillets (skin-on) \u2014 2 pieces (Week 12 Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Sea scallops \u2014 8\u201312 large, dry-packed (Week 12 Sat PROJECT \u2014 must be labeled \"dry-packed\" or \"day-boat\"; wet-packed scallops won't sear properly)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#produce-week-11","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 11","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 2 pints (Week 11 Tue roasted + Week 11 Sat bruschetta)</li> <li>[ ] Radicchio \u2014 1 head (Week 11 Tue salad)</li> <li>[ ] Broccolini \u2014 2 bunches (Week 11 Wed)</li> <li>[ ] Baby spinach \u2014 1 bag (Week 11 Fri saut\u00e9ed)</li> <li>[ ] Tomatoes (Roma or vine-ripe) \u2014 4 large (Week 11 Sat bruschetta)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 4</li> <li>[ ] Fresh sage \u2014 1 bunch (gnocchi butter sauce + ravioli butter sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Fresh basil \u2014 1 bunch (tomato sugo + bruschetta)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumber \u2014 2 (Week 11 Fri salad)</li> <li>[ ] Red onion \u2014 1 (Week 11 Fri salad)</li> <li>[ ] Mixed salad greens \u2014 2 bags</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#produce-week-12","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 12","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Asparagus \u2014 1 bunch (Week 12 Mon mushroom asparagus risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Basmati rice (not standard white) \u2014 2 cups (Week 12 Tue Persian rice / tahdig \u2014 long-grain Basmati is correct here)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumbers \u2014 2 (Week 12 Tue tzatziki)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh dill \u2014 1 bunch (tzatziki)</li> <li>[ ] Beets (raw) \u2014 4 medium (Week 12 Fri farro salad \u2014 roast them yourself)</li> <li>[ ] Arugula \u2014 2 bags (Week 12 Fri + Sat salads)</li> <li>[ ] Fennel \u2014 2 bulbs (Week 12 Sat salad)</li> <li>[ ] Blood oranges or navel oranges \u2014 3 (Week 12 Sat salad)</li> <li>[ ] Mixed bitter greens (radicchio, endive) \u2014 1 head (Week 12 Mon salad)</li> <li>[ ] Walnuts \u2014 \u00bd cup (Week 12 Mon salad)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 1 head</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#dairy","title":"\ud83e\uddc0 Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Parmesan (block) \u2014 12 oz (pasta, risotto, crostini, gnocchi)</li> <li>[ ] Pecorino Romano \u2014 4 oz (Week 11 Sat cacio e pepe)</li> <li>[ ] Gorgonzola \u2014 2 oz (Week 12 Mon salad)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 4 sticks (pasta sauces, risotto finishing, scallop searing)</li> <li>[ ] Whole-milk ricotta \u2014 as above (Week 11 Tue + Week 12 Sat crostini)</li> <li>[ ] Plain Greek yogurt (full-fat) \u2014 1 cup (Week 12 Tue tzatziki)</li> <li>[ ] Cr\u00e8me fra\u00eeche or heavy cream \u2014 \u00bd cup (Week 12 Wed polenta finishing)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry-goods","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Pantry &amp; Dry Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] \"00\" flour (Tipo 00) \u2014 2 lbs (fresh pasta \u2014 found at Italian delis or Amazon. All-purpose works but \"00\" makes silkier pasta)</li> <li>[ ] Semolina flour \u2014 \u00bd cup (dusting fresh pasta to prevent sticking)</li> <li>[ ] Russet potatoes \u2014 3 lbs (Week 11 Wed gnocchi \u2014 bake them, don't boil)</li> <li>[ ] Farro \u2014 2 cups (Week 12 Fri farro salad)</li> <li>[ ] Arborio or Carnaroli rice \u2014 2 cups (Week 12 Mon risotto + Sat saffron risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Saffron \u2014 1 tin (Week 12 Sat saffron risotto \u2014 if you used yours in Week 10, restock)</li> <li>[ ] Coarse-ground cornmeal (not instant polenta) \u2014 1 bag (Week 12 Wed)</li> <li>[ ] Canned whole tomatoes \u2014 3 cans (Week 11 Mon slow tomato sugo + Sat Bolognese)</li> <li>[ ] Tomato paste \u2014 1 small can</li> <li>[ ] Red wine \u2014 2 bottles (Week 12 Wed short rib braise + Week 11 Sat Bolognese)</li> <li>[ ] White wine (dry) \u2014 1 bottle (Week 12 Mon risotto + general)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken stock \u2014 64 oz (risotto, polenta, general)</li> <li>[ ] Beef stock \u2014 32 oz (Week 12 Wed braise)</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Week 12 Mon mushroom risotto \u2014 a small hit deepens the mushroom flavor; trust it)</li> <li>[ ] Goat cheese \u2014 4 oz (Week 12 Fri farro salad)</li> <li>[ ] Honey \u2014 1 jar (Week 12 Sat crostini)</li> <li>[ ] Walnuts \u2014 \u00bd cup (Week 12 Sat crostini)</li> <li>[ ] Capers \u2014 1 jar (Week 12 Sat scallop sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Extra-virgin olive oil (good quality \u2014 multiple uses)</li> <li>[ ] Kosher salt (large box \u2014 pasta water uses more than you think)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#notes","title":"\ud83d\udcdd Notes","text":"<p>Egg pasta dough (Week 11 Mon): The most common mistake is adding too much flour. Start with the minimum, add slowly. The dough should feel like Play-Doh \u2014 supple and smooth, not tacky or stiff. After kneading, wrap tightly and rest 30+ minutes.</p> <p>Gnocchi (Week 11 Wed) \u2014 the rules: 1. Bake the potatoes, don't boil 2. Rice them while they're hot (steam escapes and makes them lighter) 3. Add flour sparingly \u2014 start with less than the recipe says 4. Handle as little as possible. No kneading. Overworked = tough.</p> <p>Bolognese (Week 11 Sat) needs 3 hours. Start it by 11 AM. Add no more than \u00bd cup of liquid at a time and only when the previous addition has fully absorbed. The right consistency is thick and coating, barely any sauce.</p> <p>Scallops (Week 12 Sat) \u2014 critical prep: Pat dry on paper towels, then let them sit uncovered on a rack in the refrigerator for 30 minutes before cooking. They must be completely dry to sear, not steam. The pan must be screaming hot. Don't move them for 90 seconds.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html","title":"\ud83c\udfc1 Weeks 15\u201316: Module 2 Capstone \u2014 Poultry &amp; Flavor Review","text":"<p>\u2190 Quick Reference \u2192 | Shopping List \u2192</p> <p>\"You've been cooking with deliberate intention since Week 1. This week is your first real test: can you cook a full dinner for people you care about, with no recipes open in front of you during service? It also closes out Module 2 \u2014 Building Flavor. Before you enter the Proteins block, you should be able to season by instinct, not by instruction.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#week-13-the-module-2-capstone-cook","title":"Week 13 \u2014 The Module 2 Capstone Cook","text":"<p>The Week 13 rule: Recipes are allowed for preparation and mise en place. Once service begins \u2014 meaning once anything goes on the heat \u2014 close the tabs.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#monday-menu-planning","title":"Monday \u2014 Menu Planning","text":"<p>Skill: Professional kitchens don't decide what to cook while standing in front of the stove. They plan. Tonight's task: design a 3-course dinner menu for Saturday using only techniques you've learned in Weeks 1\u201312. Write the menu down. Plan the timing. Make your shopping list.</p> <p>Questions to ask yourself while planning:</p> <ul> <li>Does the menu have balance? (Rich and light? Warm and cool? Fat-forward and acid-bright?)</li> <li>Can I execute all three courses in the same kitchen, at the same time, without losing my mind?</li> <li>Is there anything on this menu I'm not confident about? (If yes, practice that thing this week, not Saturday.)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#tuesday-dry-run-the-most-difficult-component","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Dry Run: The Most Difficult Component","text":"<p>Whatever you identified as the hardest part of Saturday's menu \u2014 make it tonight as a dry run. No guests, no pressure. Just you and the technique.</p> <p>Full Meal: Your chosen dry-run dish + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Green Salad + whatever protein is simplest alongside</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#wednesday-knife-speed-benchmark","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Knife Speed Benchmark","text":"<p>Skill: Time yourself dicing one onion. This is the third benchmark in the program (Week 2 Friday and Week 4 Thursday were the others). Write the time down. You should be measurably faster than Week 2. More importantly: are your cuts more uniform? Speed is the secondary metric. Consistency is the primary one.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Thai-Style Larb (Ground Meat Salad) + Serious Eats \u2014 Jasmine Rice + Serious Eats \u2014 Quick-Pickled Cucumbers</p> <p>Larb requires a lot of fine knife work \u2014 fresh herbs, shallots, chili, lemongrass if using. It's also deeply delicious, uses acid (lime juice) and umami (fish sauce) in a way that is immediately instructive, and is unlike anything in the previous 12 weeks.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Ground pork or chicken, toasted with spices</li> <li>Starch: Jasmine rice</li> <li>Salad: Quick-pickled cucumbers alongside</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#thursday-off","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\ud83d\udcd6 Re-read your Week 1 Sunday reflection. Then your Week 8 reflection. Write one more paragraph \u2014 what has actually changed in how you cook and think about food since Week 1?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#friday-final-prep-day","title":"Friday \u2014 Final Prep Day","text":"<p>Mise en place everything for Saturday's dinner. Every sauce component prepped. Every vegetable cut. Every protein seasoned in advance (if appropriate). Every sauce component thought through. The goal: Saturday service should feel calm and controlled, not frantic and reactive.</p> <p>Dinner tonight: Something simple and low-effort \u2014 Serious Eats \u2014 The Best Grilled Cheese + Serious Eats \u2014 Tomato Soup \u2014 because you deserve a night off the skills grind.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#saturday-project-meal-the-week-13-dinner","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: The Week 13 Dinner","text":"<p>The cook: Execute your planned 3-course dinner for at least two guests. No recipes open during service. All techniques drawn from Weeks 1\u201312.</p> <p>Suggested framework if you can't decide:</p> <ol> <li>Starter: Serious Eats \u2014 Classic Shrimp Cocktail with Homemade Sauce \u2014 knife skills, salt timing</li> <li>Main: Serious Eats \u2014 Pan-Seared Duck Breast with Cherry Pan Sauce + Serious Eats \u2014 Creamy Polenta + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Root Vegetables \u2014 heat control, pan sauce, seasoning in layers</li> <li>Salad / Cheese: A composed cheese plate with good bread, honeycomb, and a handful of dressed greens \u2014 no recipe needed, just judgment</li> </ol> <p>Skill targets: Everything on the table at the same time. At least one course where you can identify all four flavor elements \u2014 salt, acid, fat, umami \u2014 working in balance. No recipe tabs open during service.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#sunday-off-13-week-reflection","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF: 13-Week Reflection","text":"<p>This is the most important reflection yet. Five questions, five sentences minimum each:</p> <ol> <li>What is the technique you've improved most since Week 1?</li> <li>What still feels unnatural or mechanical?</li> <li>Which recipe from the past 13 weeks do you want to master \u2014 cook repeatedly until it's genuinely yours?</li> <li>What ingredient have you cooked with for the first time that you now want to use regularly?</li> <li>You're 25% of the way through the program. Where do you want to be by the end?</li> </ol>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#week-14-poultry-in-depth","title":"Week 14 \u2014 Poultry in Depth","text":"<p>\"The chicken is the most cooked protein in the world and the most underestimated. Learning to roast, spatchcock, confit, and sauce a bird properly is the single most transferable skill in cooking.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#monday-high-heat-whole-bird-roast","title":"Monday \u2014 High-Heat Whole-Bird Roast","text":"<p>Skill: The classic high-heat roast \u2014 450\u00b0F, bird dry-brined overnight, no basting. This produces crackling skin and juicy meat if you understand why: the high heat cooks so fast it dries the surface before the interior overcooks. A chicken at high heat is not an accident. It's physics.</p> <ul> <li>Read (before you cook): Serious Eats \u2014 The Science of Perfect Roast Chicken</li> <li>Dry-brine the bird Sunday night: kosher salt inside and out, uncovered in the fridge</li> <li>Roast at 450\u00b0F on a rack. No tent. No basting. Let it go.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Roast chicken + Serious Eats \u2014 The Best Roast Potatoes Ever + simple green salad</p> <p>Skill note: Take the bird's temperature in three places \u2014 thigh near the joint, thickest part of the breast, and the cavity near the backbone. They'll never be the same reading. Understand the variance before you declare it \"done.\"</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Properly Roast a Chicken \u2014 Watch his setup before the bird goes in \u2014 dry skin, rack position, pan underneath. Every step is a reason.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#tuesday-spatchcock-why-it-changes-everything","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Spatchcock: Why It Changes Everything","text":"<p>Skill: Remove the backbone (kitchen shears, one firm cut down each side). Flatten the bird. Now roast it. Spatchcocking flattens the breast-to-thigh thickness differential \u2014 which is the single reason whole birds are so hard to cook to uniform doneness. When both parts hit the sheet pan at the same level, they cook much more evenly.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Spatchcock Roast Chicken \u2014 strip the flavor profile, study the method</li> <li>Save the backbone: put it in a bag in the freezer. It will go in your next stock.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Spatchcocked chicken (your own seasoning, not theirs) + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Cauliflower with Pine Nuts, Raisins &amp; Capers + tahdig or rice</p> <p>Side-by-side comparison optional: write down the cooking time and internal temp readings compared to Monday's whole bird. Did the spatchcock cook faster? More evenly? This is active learning.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: For the Best Roast Chicken, Slather Your Spatchcock in Mayo \u2014 A twist on the technique you're using \u2014 watch how the mayo acts as a fat and protein barrier that crisps differently than dry-brined skin.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#wednesday-braised-poultry-coq-au-vin","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Braised Poultry: Coq au Vin","text":"<p>Skill: Braising breaks the poultry rules deliberately. Low and slow in liquid. The collagen in the legs and thighs converts to gelatin, creating body in the sauce that doesn't exist after a quick sear. This is why drumsticks and thighs are better braised and breasts are better roasted \u2014 they're different muscles with different fat and collagen content.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Chicken Thigh Temperature &amp; Technique \u2014 explains why thighs handle heat differently than breasts</li> <li>Serious Eats \u2014 Coq au Vin \u2014 the classic</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Coq au Vin + crusty bread + simple green salad (the braise is the whole meal)</p> <p>Skill note: Taste the braising liquid at three stages \u2014 raw, after it reduces by half, after the chicken has spent 45 minutes in it. The flavor evolution is the lesson.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Coq au Vin (Jacques P\u00e9pin) \u2014 Watch how he handles the braising liquid at each stage and the moment he decides the sauce is done \u2014 compare it to what your pot smells like halfway through.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#thursday-off_1","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\ud83d\udcd6 Rest. Or read: what's the difference between a braise and a stew? What does gelatin actually do to a sauce's texture? (Think back to your stock week \u2014 how did chilled stock behave?) Let the coq au vin from Wednesday's leftovers teach you how a braise improves overnight.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#friday-pan-seared-chicken-breast-pan-sauce","title":"Friday \u2014 Pan-Seared Chicken Breast + Pan Sauce","text":"<p>Skill: The hardest everyday cook: a chicken breast at exactly the right temperature, seared in a pan, with a pan sauce built from the fond. Two proteins in two weeks \u2014 Monday's whole bird and tonight's breast \u2014 show you how different the same animal can be when you change the cut and the method.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Pan-Seared Chicken Breast with White Wine Pan Sauce</li> <li>The pan sauce is the skill. Deglaze the fond. Reduce. Mount with butter. Taste. Fix.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Pan-seared chicken breast + pan sauce + Serious Eats \u2014 Honey-Roasted Carrots + whatever grain you have</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The Secret Technique for the Juiciest Chicken Cutlets \u2014 Watch how he controls the sear to hit exactly 160\u00b0F without overcooking \u2014 the same logic applies to your breast tonight.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#saturday-project-duck-confit","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Duck Confit","text":"<p>Skill: Confit is patience-based cooking. Duck legs cured overnight in salt and aromatics, then slow-cooked in their own fat (or olive oil, which works fine) for 2\u20133 hours at 200\u00b0F. The result is impossibly tender, deeply flavorful meat that also crisp-skins beautifully when you finish it in a hot pan.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Classic Duck Confit</li> <li>Start the cure Friday night. Saturday is a long, low project cook. This is the kind of thing you can only learn by doing it.</li> </ul> <p>The Saturday menu: 1. Duck confit legs \u2014 crisped in a cast iron at high heat after the slow cook 2. Serious Eats \u2014 French Bistro Salad \u2014 fris\u00e9e or endive, lardons, mustard vinaigrette, a poached egg if you feel like it 3. Lentils or white beans cooked simply in the duck fat from the confit \u2014 this is called using the whole animal</p> <p>What you're proving to yourself: that patience and low heat create textures that no other method can.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Sunday Roasted Chicken, the Efficient Way (Ethan Chlebowski) \u2014 Before your confit, watch Ethan's reasoning about what heat does to poultry at each temperature \u2014 it gives direct context for why low-and-slow fat immersion produces such a different result.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#sunday-off-week-14-reflection","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF: Week 14 Reflection","text":"<p>You've now cooked poultry four different ways in one week: high-heat whole roast, spatchcock, red-wine braise, pan sear, and duck confit. Write one paragraph: of everything in the first 14 weeks, what technique do you now feel like you actually own? What still feels like you're following instructions rather than cooking?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#the-confit-technique","title":"The Confit Technique","text":"<p>Duck confit is the clearest example of a preserved food that gets better with time. The technique predates refrigeration \u2014 understanding the original purpose changes how you think about it.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 What the Heck Is Confit? | Ask The Food Lab \u2014 Kenji explains the term, the technique, and why it produces results that other low-and-slow methods don't.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#breaking-down-a-whole-chicken","title":"Breaking Down a Whole Chicken","text":"<p>The midpoint capstone includes whole-bird cookery. If you want to go deeper on butchery, this is the guide.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Break Down a Chicken \u2014 The step-by-step visual guide. Do this a few times and it becomes muscle memory.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Jacques P\u00e9pin breaks down a chicken \u2014 The most efficient human alive demonstrates what this skill looks like at speed. Watching once is worth three hours of reading.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Complete Robuchon by Jo\u00ebl Robuchon \u2014 The French culinary bible. Heavy reference for the classical techniques that anchor Module 2. Every major cooking method is here.</li> </ul> <p>\u2190 Weeks 13\u201314 | Weeks 17\u201318 \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Weeks 15\u201316 Quick Reference \u2014 Module 2 Capstone: Poultry &amp; Flavor Review","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/quick-ref.html#week-13-recipes-the-module-2-capstone-cook","title":"Week 13 Recipes \u2014 The Module 2 Capstone Cook","text":"Day Dish Skill Link Mon Menu planning Design a 3-course dinner for Saturday \u2014 Tue Dry-run of your hardest Saturday dish + Simple Green Salad Technique rehearsal, no pressure Salad Wed Thai-Style Larb + Jasmine Rice + Quick-Pickled Cucumbers Knife speed benchmark; acid + umami balance Larb \u00b7 Rice \u00b7 Pickles Thu OFF Read/reflect: Week 1 vs. now \u2014 Fri Grilled Cheese + Tomato Soup Rest \u2014 mise en place Saturday's dinner Grilled Cheese \u00b7 Tomato Soup Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: 3-Course Dinner for Guests \u2014 no recipes during service Full synthesis: Weeks 1\u201312 techniques Suggested: Shrimp Cocktail \u00b7 Duck Breast \u00b7 Polenta \u00b7 Root Veg"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/quick-ref.html#week-14-recipes-poultry-in-depth","title":"Week 14 Recipes \u2014 Poultry in Depth","text":"Day Dish Skill Link Mon High-Heat Roast Chicken + Roast Potatoes + Green Salad Dry brine; high-heat bird science Roast Chicken \u00b7 Roast Potatoes Tue Spatchcock Chicken + Roasted Cauliflower with Capers Spatchcocking; even doneness Spatchcock Method \u00b7 Cauliflower Wed Coq au Vin + Crusty Bread Braised poultry; collagen \u2192 gelatin Coq au Vin \u00b7 Thigh Technique Thu OFF Rest; eat coq au vin leftovers \u2014 observe how it improves \u2014 Fri Pan-Seared Chicken Breast + Pan Sauce + Honey-Roasted Carrots Pan sauce from fond; breast precision Pan-Seared Chicken + Sauce \u00b7 Carrots Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Duck Confit + French Bistro Salad + Duck-Fat Lentils Confit; patience-based fat cooking Duck Confit \u00b7 Bistro Salad"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/quick-ref.html#the-midpoint-benchmarks","title":"The Midpoint Benchmarks","text":"Benchmark Week 1 Target Week 13 Target Onion dice Sub 5 min Sub 2 min, uniform cuts Pan sauce Can make one Can make one from memory with any fond Seasoning Season at end Season in layers, know what's missing Mise en place Forget half of it Everything prepped before heat goes on Stock Just bought it Made it, stored it, used it"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/quick-ref.html#shopping-notes","title":"Shopping Notes","text":"<p>Week 13 Saturday dinner \u2014 shopping depends on your chosen menu. Plan it Monday, shop mid-week.</p> <p>If using the suggested Shrimp Cocktail + Duck Breast menu: - Shrimp: 1 lb large shrimp (16/20 count), cocktail sauce ingredients - Duck: 2\u20134 duck breasts, cherries or cherry preserves for sauce, good red wine - Polenta: coarse-ground cornmeal, good parmesan, butter, chicken stock - Root vegetables: carrots, parsnips, turnips, beets \u2014 your choice of combination</p> <p>Week 13 Wednesday (Larb): Ground pork or chicken, fresh mint, cilantro, shallots, fish sauce, lime juice, toasted rice powder (make your own: toast rice in a dry pan, grind in spice grinder).</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 15\u201316: Module 2 Capstone: Poultry &amp; Flavor Review","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Week 13 shopping depends on your menu choice for Saturday's dinner. The list below covers the suggested menu (shrimp cocktail + duck + polenta) plus Week 13's fixed weeknight meals. Week 14 content is coming soon.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-13-weeknights","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 13 Weeknights","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Ground pork or ground chicken \u2014 1 lb (Week 13 Wed Larb)</li> <li>[ ] Duck breasts \u2014 2\u20134 (Week 13 Sat suggested main) \u2014 found at specialty butchers and some grocery stores (Moulard or Pekin duck breasts both work)</li> <li>[ ] Large shrimp (shell-on, 16/20 count) \u2014 1 lb (Week 13 Sat suggested starter)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-13-saturday-dinner-choose-your-menu","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 13 Saturday Dinner (choose your menu)","text":"<p>If using the suggested framework: - [ ] 2\u20134 duck breasts, skin-on (main course) - [ ] 1 lb large shrimp, shell-on (cocktail starter \u2014 cook shell-on, then peel)</p> <p>If making your own menu (based on Weeks 1\u201312 techniques): \u2014 write your list here \u2014</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/shopping-list.html#produce-week-13","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 13","text":"<p>Wednesday Larb: - [ ] Fresh mint \u2014 1 large bunch - [ ] Fresh cilantro \u2014 1 bunch - [ ] Shallots \u2014 4 (thin-sliced) - [ ] Thai bird chilies or red Fresno chilies \u2014 3\u20134 - [ ] Limes \u2014 4 (fresh lime juice) - [ ] Jasmine rice \u2014 1 cup (also for toasted rice powder) - [ ] Cucumbers \u2014 2 (quick pickle) - [ ] Rice wine vinegar \u2014 1 cup (quick pickle) - [ ] Red onion \u2014 1 (quick pickle)</p> <p>Friday: - [ ] Good bread \u2014 1 loaf (grilled cheese) - [ ] Tomatoes (canned) \u2014 2 cans (tomato soup) - [ ] Yellow onion \u2014 1 (soup)</p> <p>Saturday dinner: - [ ] Root vegetables (carrots, parsnips, turnips) \u2014 2 lbs (suggested main side) - [ ] Cherries (fresh or preserved) or quality cherry preserves \u2014 \u00bd cup (duck pan sauce) - [ ] Fresh thyme \u2014 1 bunch - [ ] Shallots \u2014 4 additional (duck pan sauce)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/shopping-list.html#dairy","title":"\ud83e\uddc0 Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Good cheese for a cheese board (1\u20132 varieties) \u2014 Week 13 Sat optional third course</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 2 sticks (duck pan sauce, polenta finishing)</li> <li>[ ] Parmesan \u2014 4 oz (polenta)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 \u00bd cup (grilled cheese, optional; polenta finishing)</li> <li>[ ] Nice cheddar or Gruy\u00e8re \u2014 6 oz (grilled cheese)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry-goods","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Pantry &amp; Dry Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Coarse-ground cornmeal (not instant) \u2014 \u00bd bag (Week 13 Sat polenta)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken stock \u2014 32 oz (polenta + duck pan sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Good red wine \u2014 1 bottle (duck pan sauce + table)</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Week 13 Wed Larb \u2014 already in pantry from Week 10?)</li> <li>[ ] Shrimp cocktail sauce: horseradish, ketchup, Worcestershire, Tabasco, lemon</li> <li>[ ] Jasmine rice \u2014 1 cup + extra for toasting (toasted rice powder for larb)</li> <li>[ ] Honey \u2014 1 jar (Week 13 Sat cheese board)</li> <li>[ ] Good crackers or baguette (cheese board)</li> <li>[ ] Honeycomb (Week 13 Sat cheese board \u2014 optional but impressive)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/shopping-list.html#notes","title":"\ud83d\udcdd Notes","text":"<p>Larb (Week 13 Wed) \u2014 toasted rice powder: Toast 3 tbsp raw jasmine rice in a dry skillet over medium heat until golden, stirring constantly. Cool completely, then grind in a spice grinder or mortar and pestle to a coarse powder. This is a classic Thai technique and makes a significant difference in texture and flavor.</p> <p>Duck breast \u2014 the sear: Score the fat cap in a crosshatch pattern without cutting into the meat. Start in a cold pan (no oil) over low heat. Render the fat slowly for 8\u201310 minutes until most of it has melted and the skin is golden. Then flip once and finish in the oven at 400\u00b0F for 5\u20137 minutes. Rest 5 minutes. Duck is best medium-rare (130\u2013135\u00b0F internal).</p> <p>Week 13 Saturday rule: Everything is prepped and mis en placed before service starts. Once the first component goes on heat, no recipe tabs. You know what you're doing. Trust it.</p> <p>Week 14 (Poultry in Depth) \u2014 shopping list coming when content is finalized. You'll need: whole chickens, duck legs for confit, duck fat (or buy), and a selection of poultry for roasting experiments.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/index.html","title":"Module 3: The Proteins (Weeks 17\u201328)","text":"<p>The goal of this module: Master every major protein category \u2014 beef from cheap cuts to prime, pork in all its forms, finfish and shellfish, and finally the preserved meats of charcuterie. Each two-week block adds a new protein to your permanent repertoire.</p> <p>By the end of Week 26, you should be able to handle any cut of any animal with confidence and intention.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/index.html#weeks-in-this-module","title":"Weeks in This Module","text":"Weeks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 17\u201318 Beef \u2014 Fundamentals \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 19\u201320 Beef \u2014 Advanced Cuts \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 21\u201322 Pork \u2014 All Cuts \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 23\u201324 Seafood \u2014 Fish \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 25\u201326 Seafood \u2014 Shellfish \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 27\u201328 Module 3 Capstone: Charcuterie &amp; Curing \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/index.html#core-skills-covered","title":"Core Skills Covered","text":"<ul> <li>Beef fundamentals \u2014 internal temps, the steak triangle (sear/rest/slice), pan sauce; understanding grain and fat</li> <li>Advanced beef \u2014 braising tough cuts, compound butters, smoking and wrapping, reverse sear</li> <li>Pork \u2014 pork belly, shoulder, loin, and ribs; cure ratios, brining, fat rendering, crackling</li> <li>Fish \u2014 filleting round and flat fish; skin-on sear; en papillote; ceviche acid-cook; freshness indicators</li> <li>Shellfish \u2014 live and frozen; steaming, grilling, bisque; breaking down a lobster or Dungeness crab</li> <li>Charcuterie \u2014 dry-curing, equilibrium salt method, duck confit, p\u00e2t\u00e9, terrines; food safety in curing</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/index.html#equipment-youll-need","title":"Equipment You'll Need","text":"<p>See the Kitchen Equipment Guide. New items introduced in this module:</p> Item Introduced Cast iron skillet (12 inch) Week 17 Large Dutch oven (5\u20137 qt) Week 17 Wire rack + half-sheet pan Week 17 Outdoor grill or cast iron grill pan Week 19 Kitchen twine Week 19 Fish spatula Week 23 Shellfish brush Week 25 Spider strainer / skimmer Week 25 Kitchen scissors Week 25 <p>Previous module: Module 2 \u2014 Building Flavor (Weeks 9\u201316) Next module: Module 4 \u2014 The World's Kitchens (Weeks 29\u201344)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Weeks 17\u201318: Beef \u2014 Fundamentals","text":"<p>\u2190 Quick Reference \u2192 | Shopping List \u2192</p> <p>\"Beef is the protein that teaches you the most about heat. Every cut is a different conversation with the fire, and every mistake is immediately apparent on the plate.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#week-15-the-steak-education","title":"Week 15 \u2014 The Steak Education","text":"<p>The central question this week: Why does a ribeye require a different approach than a strip? Why does a two-inch-thick steak need different handling than a thin one? Beef cuts are not interchangeable \u2014 their fat content, fiber direction, and thickness all dictate the method.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#monday-the-dry-brine-reverse-sear-method","title":"Monday \u2014 The Dry Brine + Reverse Sear Method","text":"<p>Skill: Dry brining (salting and leaving uncovered in the fridge for at least 12 hours) is the single highest-leverage improvement most home cooks can make to their steak. Salt draws moisture to the surface, which then gets reabsorbed carrying salt deeper into the meat. The surface dries out \u2014 which means better, faster crust formation.</p> <p>The reverse sear \u2014 low oven first, then high-heat sear \u2014 gives you precise temperature control and faster, drier surface for searing.</p> <ul> <li>Read before cooking: Serious Eats \u2014 How to Dry Brine \u2014 the definitive explanation</li> <li>Dry brine your steak Sunday night. Reverse sear Monday.</li> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Reverse-Seared Steak</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Reverse-seared ribeye + Serious Eats \u2014 Rich and Creamy Mashed Potatoes + simple green salad</p> <p>Skill check: Take the steak's internal temperature in three places before searing. Write the readings down. This is how you learn to stop cutting into steak to check doneness.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The Reverse Sear is Still the Best Way to Cook Steak \u2014 Follow his oven temp and timer \u2014 then compare your internal temp curve to his. The reverse sear is consistent precisely because you can watch it happen.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#tuesday-pan-seared-strip-steak-compound-butter","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Pan-Seared Strip Steak + Compound Butter","text":"<p>Skill: A strip steak requires more finesse than a ribeye \u2014 it has less marbling to protect the meat from drying out. Tonight: cast iron, very high heat, minimal interference. Compound butter (softened butter + herbs + acid) is a classical French technique for finishing steaks \u2014 it's also a foundational formula you'll use in many other contexts.</p> <ul> <li>Read (for context): Serious Eats \u2014 Old Wives' Tales About Cooking Steak \u2014 debunks the myths you've definitely heard</li> <li>Compound butter formula: \u00bd stick softened butter + minced herbs (parsley, thyme, chive) + \u00bd tsp lemon zest + 1 tsp Dijon. Roll in plastic wrap. Refrigerate.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Pan-seared strip steak + compound butter + Serious Eats \u2014 Creamed Spinach + crusty bread</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#wednesday-burgers-understanding-ground-beef","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Burgers: Understanding Ground Beef","text":"<p>Skill: A great burger requires understanding fat ratios (80/20 is the standard \u2014 leaner grinds = drier burgers), handling (overworking = tough), and heat (screaming hot surface = crust without grey band). The smash burger technique works because maximum surface contact with maximum heat creates maximum Maillard reaction.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Classic Smash Burgers</li> <li>One rule: don't touch the beef. Season right before cooking, smash once, don't press again.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Smash burgers (double patty) + whatever you feel like alongside \u2014 this is your call</p> <p>Skill note: Make the patties with one hand. Loose, barely formed. No mix-ins. Salt only. Then smash.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to make a smash burger \u2014 Watch how hard he smashes and how fast the crust forms \u2014 that's the Maillard reaction happening in real time.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#thursday-beef-butchery-primal-cuts-fabrication","title":"Thursday \u2014 Beef Butchery: Primal Cuts &amp; Fabrication","text":"<p>Skill: Understanding the beef primal map \u2014 where every cut comes from and why it costs what it costs. Tonight is theory and light hands-on work: you'll trim and portion a short rib rack or fabricate a chuck roast into uniform braising pieces.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read first: Beef Cuts Explained: A Guide to the Different Cuts of Beef \u2014 understand why the same animal produces both a $6/lb chuck and a $30/lb tenderloin.</p> <p>The primal cut map \u2014 every beef cut descends from 8 primals:</p> Primal Characteristics Cuts it yields Chuck (shoulder) Well-worked muscle, lots of collagen Chuck roast, short ribs, flat iron Rib Less-worked, heavily marbled Ribeye, prime rib, ribeye cap Short loin Tender, central back T-bone, porterhouse, strip steak Sirloin Moderately worked Sirloin steak, tri-tip Round (rear leg) Lean, tough Round roast, top round, eye of round Brisket (chest) Very tough, collagen-heavy Whole brisket, flat, point Flank/plate Flat, thin, fibrous Skirt steak, flank steak, hanger Shank Very tough, maximum gelatin Osso buco (cross-cut shank) <p>The fabrication principle: Tough cuts (chuck, brisket, shank) need low heat and long time to convert collagen to gelatin. Tender cuts (rib, loin) need high heat and short time. The method should always match the muscle's work history.</p> <p>Hands-on tonight: Buy a rack of bone-in short ribs from your butcher as a slab (not pre-cut English style). Practice: 1. Identifying the grain direction of the meat 2. Trimming excess fat cap (leave \u00bc\" \u2014 flavor, not waste) 3. Portioning between bones for even braising pieces 4. Asking yourself: could I have bought these pre-portioned? Yes. But now you understand what you're paying for when you don't.</p> <p>Full Meal: The short ribs you trim tonight \u2014 braise them tomorrow or this weekend (see Week 16 for the full recipe). Tonight pair with whatever you have: bread and a salad is fine.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Also worth reading: Serious Eats \u2014 Should You Bring Steaks to Room Temperature Before Cooking? \u2014 the answer is more interesting than you expect.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#friday-skirt-steak-thin-cuts-marination","title":"Friday \u2014 Skirt Steak: Thin Cuts &amp; Marination","text":"<p>Skill: Thin cuts (skirt, flank, hanger) are the workhorse steaks of Latin American and Asian cuisines \u2014 they're cheap, extremely flavorful, and completely different from the thick-cut luxury steaks of earlier this week. Two rules: high heat, short time. And always cut against the grain \u2014 these muscles have very pronounced fiber direction, and cutting the wrong way makes them nearly inedible.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Grilled Skirt Steak Fajitas \u2014 the method applies even if you don't want fajitas</li> <li>Marinade is not optional here. Acid (lime/citrus), oil, aromatics \u2014 at least 30 minutes, preferably overnight.</li> <li>Finish with Serious Eats \u2014 Chimichurri</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Skirt steak + chimichurri + grilled or roasted peppers + rice or tortillas</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Grilled Skirt Steak with Herb Sauce \u2014 Compare his sear time and resting method to yours \u2014 skirt steak is thin enough that even 30 seconds matters.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#saturday-project-the-prime-rib","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: The Prime Rib","text":"<p>Skill: The prime rib (standing rib roast) is the most impressive home cook project in the beef repertoire. High-heat sear first (or last), then low-and-slow roasting to precise internal temperature. This is a $80+ cut of meat \u2014 you don't wing it. You plan it.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Perfect Prime Rib \u2014 read the whole thing, twice</li> <li>Serious Eats \u2014 High Heat vs. Low and Slow Prime Rib \u2014 understand both approaches before choosing one</li> </ul> <p>The Saturday spread: 1. Standing rib roast \u2014 2-bone minimum, reverse sear if it's your first time 2. Horseradish cream sauce (cr\u00e8me fra\u00eeche + prepared horseradish + lemon + black pepper) 3. Serious Eats \u2014 Creamed Spinach \u2014 the steakhouse classic 4. Roasted garlic mashed potatoes (use Monday's mashed potato technique)</p> <p>What you learn today: cooking to temperature on an expensive cut. If it's wrong, you know immediately. That's the best teacher.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The Food Lab's Reverse-Seared Prime Rib \u2014 Watch how the internal temperature climbs through the overnight rest \u2014 that carry-over on a roast this size is part of the method, not a mistake.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#sunday-off","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>Write down this week's learning: of the three fundamentally different cooked-beef textures (seared steak, smash burger, slow-roasted rib), which one are you most confident you understand? Which do you want to cook again before moving on?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#week-16-beef-braising-the-tougher-cuts","title":"Week 16 \u2014 Beef: Braising &amp; the Tougher Cuts","text":"<p>\"The most flavorful beef in the animal is in the cuts that require the most time. This is not a coincidence.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#monday-red-wine-braised-short-ribs","title":"Monday \u2014 Red Wine Braised Short Ribs","text":"<p>Skill: Short ribs take a 3-hour braise minimum in red wine and aromatics. The collagen-rich meat transforms from tough connective tissue into silk. This is the braise that impresses everyone \u2014 and it's also deeply forgiving. The only way to ruin it is rushing it.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Red Wine Braised Beef Short Ribs</li> <li>Brown the short ribs in batches \u2014 don't crowd the pan or they'll steam instead of sear</li> <li>Start by 2 PM if you're eating at 7</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Braised short ribs + egg noodles or creamy polenta + whatever vegetables are in season</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Forget Short Ribs, Try Red Wine-Braised Chuck Instead \u2014 A direct comparison of the same braise technique on a different cut \u2014 watch what the different fat and collagen content does to the final texture.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#tuesday-pot-roast-low-and-slow-chuck","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Pot Roast: Low and Slow Chuck","text":"<p>Skill: Chuck roast (blade roast) is the pot roast cut \u2014 it has connective tissue, fat pockets, and marbling in all the right places for a slow braise. Tonight is a weeknight version: the braise starts at 3 PM, everything goes in the Dutch oven, and dinner is ready at 7. The technique is identical to short ribs but the cut behaves differently.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Mississippi Pot Roast \u2014 don't make this one exactly, but understand the method completely</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Pot roast with braising liquid + the vegetables from the braise + whatever bread is around</p> <p>Skill note: Taste the braising liquid at the start, midway, and end. Watch what reduction does to salt concentration. You may not need to add salt at all \u2014 the liquid will already be intensifying.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#wednesday-brisket-patience-as-a-virtue","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Brisket: Patience as a Virtue","text":"<p>Skill: Brisket is a study in patience. At 6\u20138 hours (lower temp, longer time), the fat renders, the collagen converts, and the flat and point achieve very different textures. This is a Saturday cook being previewed midweek on a smaller scale.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Brisket Cooking Methods Tested \u2014 compare the approaches and understand why they produce different results</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Braised brisket slices + quick-pickled onions + coleslaw + rye bread</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#thursday-off","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\ud83d\udcd6 Think about the week: short ribs took 3 hours and fell off the bone. Pot roast took 4 hours and sliced cleanly. Brisket took 6+ hours and pulled apart. All three are \"braised beef.\" What made them different? The answer is in collagen content, fat distribution, and muscle structure. You don't need to read about this \u2014 you've cooked it. Trust what you observed.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#friday-steak-au-poivre","title":"Friday \u2014 Steak au Poivre","text":"<p>Skill: A French bistro classic that teaches two things at once: how to build a pan sauce from heavy cream and cognac, and how to handle intense, well-seasoned pan heat. This sauce is more aggressive than a simple butter sauce \u2014 it has body, alcohol, and the floral warmth of cracked black pepper.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Steak au Poivre \u2014 follow it precisely your first time</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Steak au Poivre + Serious Eats \u2014 Best Roast Potatoes Ever + grilled asparagus with olive oil and sea salt</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#saturday-project-the-beef-meal-for-four","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: The Beef Meal for Four","text":"<p>Skill: You've cooked beef five different ways this week. Tonight's project: cook a full meal for at least four people using one technique of your choice from this two-week block. Plan it, mise en place it, execute it without referring to recipes during service.</p> <p>Suggested menu if you want a framework: 1. Serious Eats \u2014 Shrimp Cocktail as a starter 2. Reverse-seared ribeye (your technique, not a recipe) + pan sauce from the fond + mashed potatoes 3. A salad dressed with a vinaigrette you make from memory</p> <p>The real test: can you cook a proper steak dinner for people without opening your phone once during service?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#sunday-off_1","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>Reflection: You've now completed 16 weeks. Write one sentence for each of the following \u2014 what skill you've gained most confidence in, what you need to keep practicing, and one cook from the past four weeks you want to repeat this month without any reference.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#understanding-beef-cuts","title":"Understanding Beef Cuts","text":"<p>Most home cooks buy whatever their supermarket stocks. Understanding the muscle map changes that.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Right Way to Use a Meat Thermometer \u2014 Temperature, not touch or time, is the only honest signal for steak doneness. Read this once and use it every time.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#steak-myths-worth-busting","title":"Steak Myths Worth Busting","text":"<p>Most steak advice is either wrong or oversimplified. The Food Lab has done more careful testing on steak than anyone else.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Old Wives' Tales About Cooking Steak, Debunked \u2014 Searing to \"seal in juices,\" letting it come to room temperature, pressing with a finger for doneness \u2014 all tested, most debunked.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Kenji's reverse sear at home \u2014 Watch the technique in real time. His narration explains the why behind each step better than any written recipe can.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Food Lab by J. Kenji L\u00f3pez-Alt \u2014 The beef chapter is the most thorough analysis of home steak cookery ever written. If you haven't read it yet, start there.</li> </ul> <p>\u2190 Weeks 15\u201316 | Weeks 19\u201320 \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Weeks 17\u201318 Quick Reference \u2014 Beef Fundamentals","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/quick-ref.html#week-15-recipes-the-steak-education","title":"Week 15 Recipes \u2014 The Steak Education","text":"Day Dish Skill Link Mon Reverse-Seared Ribeye + Creamy Mashed Potatoes + Salad Dry brine; reverse sear; temp precision Dry Brine \u00b7 Reverse Sear \u00b7 Mashed Potatoes Tue Pan-Seared Strip + Compound Butter + Creamed Spinach High-heat pan sear; classical butter finish Steak Myths \u00b7 Creamed Spinach Wed Smash Burgers Fat ratio; Maillard contact; ground beef handling Smash Burgers Thu OFF Optional read: room-temp steak myth Room Temp Steak? Fri Skirt Steak + Chimichurri + Rice Thin cuts; always against the grain; marination Skirt Steak Fajitas \u00b7 Chimichurri Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Standing Rib Roast + Creamed Spinach + Roast Garlic Mashed Expensive cut precision; reverse sear at scale Prime Rib \u00b7 High vs Low Heat \u00b7 Creamed Spinach"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/quick-ref.html#week-16-recipes-braising-tougher-cuts","title":"Week 16 Recipes \u2014 Braising &amp; Tougher Cuts","text":"Day Dish Skill Link Mon Red Wine Braised Short Ribs + Polenta or Egg Noodles Collagen \u2192 gelatin braise; patience Short Ribs Tue Chuck Pot Roast + Braising Vegetables Low-and-slow chuck; weeknight timing Pot Roast Method Wed Braised Brisket + Pickled Onions + Coleslaw + Rye Brisket; fat and collagen; long low cook Brisket Methods Thu OFF Reflect on what made each braise different \u2014 Fri Steak au Poivre + Roast Potatoes + Grilled Asparagus Cream-cognac pan sauce; pepper crust Steak au Poivre \u00b7 Roast Potatoes Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Beef Dinner for Four \u2014 technique of your choice Full synthesis: planning + execution for guests Beef Guides Reference"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/quick-ref.html#the-beef-fundamentals-key-rules","title":"The Beef Fundamentals: Key Rules","text":"Principle Why It Matters Dry brine 12\u201324 hrs ahead Salt penetrates, surface dries = better crust, more seasoning throughout High cuts need high heat + rest Ribeye, strip \u2014 fast and hot, then rest 5\u201310 min before cutting Tough cuts need low heat + time Short ribs, chuck, brisket \u2014 collagen converts to gelatin only above 3 hrs Always cut thin cuts against the grain Skirt, flank, hanger \u2014 fiber direction is visible; cutting with it makes it chewy Use a thermometer Not optional. 130\u00b0F = medium-rare. Every time."},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/quick-ref.html#shopping-notes","title":"Shopping Notes","text":"<p>Week 15: - Ribeye \u2014 1.5\u20132 inch thick, bone-in preferred; buy Thursday for Monday dry brine - Strip steak \u2014 2 pieces, 1 inch thick - Ground beef \u2014 80/20, NOT lean; 1.5 lbs for burgers for 2 - Skirt steak \u2014 1\u20131.5 lbs (inside skirt is often more tender than outside) - Standing rib roast \u2014 2-bone minimum; order from a butcher if not commonly stocked</p> <p>Week 16: - Beef short ribs \u2014 bone-in, flanken or English cut; 3 lbs minimum - Chuck roast \u2014 3 lbs, well-marbled - Brisket \u2014 flat or flat + point; 3\u20134 lbs (ask butcher for USDA Choice minimum)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 17\u201318: Beef Fundamentals","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Week 15 is all about precision and high heat. Week 16 is braises \u2014 patient and hands-off. Buy your Week 15 ribeye on Thursday so you can dry brine it Friday night for Monday. The standing rib roast (Saturday Week 15) needs to be ordered from a butcher if you're not in a good-stocked area. The brisket (Wednesday Week 16) needs to start by 11am if you're eating dinner.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Instant-read thermometer \u2014 non-negotiable this block. You are cooking to temperature, not to time. Under $30 for a Thermapen-style; Lavatools or ThermoPop work great.</li> <li>[ ] Cast iron skillet \u2014 essential for Mon/Tue/Fri steaks. The heavier the better.</li> <li>[ ] Large Dutch oven \u2014 needed for all three braises (Mon/Tue/Wed, Week 16). 5\u20137 quart.</li> <li>[ ] Wire rack \u2014 for the reverse sear setup (steak on rack in a sheet pan in the oven)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-15","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 15","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Ribeye steak \u2014 1.5\u20132 inch thick; bone-in or boneless (Mon dry brine/reverse sear). Buy Thursday, dry brine immediately.</li> <li>[ ] Strip steaks \u2014 2 pieces, 1 inch thick (Tuesday pan sear)</li> <li>[ ] Ground beef \u2014 80/20, NOT lean; 1.5 lbs (Wednesday smash burgers)</li> <li>[ ] Skirt steak \u2014 1\u20131.5 lbs; inside skirt preferred (Friday \u2014 marinate overnight)</li> <li>[ ] Standing rib roast (prime rib) \u2014 2-bone minimum; USDA Choice or Prime. Order ahead from a butcher.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-16","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 16","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Bone-in beef short ribs \u2014 English cut; 3 lbs (Monday braise)</li> <li>[ ] Chuck roast \u2014 3 lbs, bone-in preferred (Tuesday pot roast)</li> <li>[ ] Brisket \u2014 flat or point; 3\u20134 lbs, USDA Choice minimum (Wednesday; start early)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/shopping-list.html#produce-week-15","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 15","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Shallots \u2014 4 (compound butter + chimichurri)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh thyme \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 1 bunch (compound butter + chimichurri)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh chives \u2014 1 bunch (compound butter)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 4</li> <li>[ ] Baby spinach \u2014 1 large bag (Wednesday creamed spinach)</li> <li>[ ] Asparagus \u2014 1 bunch (Friday)</li> <li>[ ] Russet potatoes \u2014 3 lbs (mashed, Week 15 Mon + Sat)</li> <li>[ ] Mixed salad greens \u2014 1 bag</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/shopping-list.html#produce-week-16","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 16","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 4 large</li> <li>[ ] Celery \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Yellow onions \u2014 4</li> <li>[ ] Red onion \u2014 1 (quick-pickled for brisket)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Fresh thyme \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Fresh rosemary \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Cabbage \u2014 \u00bd head (coleslaw, brisket night)</li> <li>[ ] Potatoes (for roasting, Week 16 Fri) \u2014 1.5 lbs Yukon gold</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry-goods","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry &amp; Dry Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Kosher salt \u2014 buy a 3-lb box if you're running low; it goes fast this block</li> <li>[ ] Black pepper (whole, for cracking) \u2014 Week 16 Fri steak au poivre</li> <li>[ ] Red wine \u2014 1 bottle inexpensive (Week 16 Monday short ribs; anything drinkable is fine)</li> <li>[ ] Dry red wine \u2014 second bottle for Week 16 Wednesday brisket</li> <li>[ ] Dijon mustard</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 2 lbs</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 1 pint (Week 16 Fri pan sauce + Week 15 creamed spinach)</li> <li>[ ] Cognac or brandy \u2014 small bottle (Week 16 Fri; optional but correct)</li> <li>[ ] Red wine vinegar (chimichurri)</li> <li>[ ] Dried oregano (chimichurri)</li> <li>[ ] Crushed red pepper flakes</li> <li>[ ] Beef or chicken stock \u2014 1 quart (pot roast, brisket)</li> <li>[ ] Flour \u2014 1 cup (browning pot roast)</li> <li>[ ] Egg noodles or polenta \u2014 for Week 16 Monday</li> <li>[ ] Rye bread \u2014 for Week 16 Wednesday brisket</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/17-18-beef-fundamentals/shopping-list.html#timing-notes","title":"\ud83d\udd22 Timing Notes","text":"Day Key Timing Week 15 Thu Buy and immediately dry brine the ribeye (uncovered, in fridge) Week 15 Fri Marinate skirt steak overnight Week 16 Mon Short ribs: braise starts at 3 PM, eats at 7 PM Week 16 Tue Chuck: braise in by 3 PM Week 16 Wed Brisket: start by 10\u201311 AM; it needs 5\u20136 hours minimum"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Weeks 19\u201320: Beef \u2014 Advanced Cuts","text":"<p>\u2190 Quick Reference \u2192 | Shopping List \u2192</p> <p>\"The expensive cuts get all the press. But the cooks who really know beef are the ones who can do something extraordinary with a hanger steak or a flank \u2014 cuts that cost a third of the price and require twice the technique.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#week-17-grilling-the-grill-station","title":"Week 17 \u2014 Grilling &amp; the Grill Station","text":"<p>Theme this week: The outdoor fire. Grilling is a distinct cooking environment \u2014 intense radiant heat, smoke, flare-ups, and a cooler zone if you set it up correctly. A two-zone fire (direct heat on one side, no heat on the other) is the most important concept in grilling. Everything else follows from that.</p> <p>Setup note: If you don't have an outdoor grill, a cast iron grill pan on high heat indoors is an acceptable substitute. Open a window. The technique is almost identical.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#monday-t-bone-two-steaks-one-animal","title":"Monday \u2014 T-Bone: Two Steaks, One Animal","text":"<p>Skill: The T-bone is a porterhouse by another name \u2014 strip on one side of the bone, tenderloin on the other. The problem: strip requires higher heat for longer; tenderloin overcooks at lower temperature. Understanding how to grill a T-bone is the most concentrated lesson in thermal management for beef.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Perfect Grilled T-Bone Steak</li> <li>Set up a two-zone fire. Start with the strip side toward the hot coals. Finish reverse \u2014 move the tenderloin side closer at the end.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Grilled T-bone (or porterhouse) + Serious Eats \u2014 The Best Roast Potatoes Ever + simple green salad</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#tuesday-the-ribeye-cap-spinalis-and-how-to-think-about-premium-cuts","title":"Tuesday \u2014 The Ribeye Cap (Spinalis) \u2014 And How to Think About Premium Cuts","text":"<p>Skill: The outer cap muscle of the ribeye (the spinalis dorsi) is widely considered the single most flavorful piece of beef on the animal. It's accessible either by requesting it directly from a butcher or by buying a full bone-in ribeye and identifying the cap yourself. Tonight: simple preparation \u2014 let the beef do the work. Salt, pepper, high heat, butter baste.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Meet the Ribeye Cap: The Tastiest Cut on the Cow</li> <li>If you can't source the cap separately: buy a bone-in ribeye and marvel at the different textures in one steak</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Ribeye cap (or bone-in ribeye) + Serious Eats \u2014 Chimichurri + seasonal green vegetables simply cooked</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#wednesday-hanger-steak-the-butchers-secret","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Hanger Steak: The Butcher's Secret","text":"<p>Skill: Hanger steak (also called onglet, or butcher's cut) hangs between the tenderloin and rib. It's intensely beefy \u2014 some people find the flavor almost offal-adjacent (it is near the kidneys). It's cheap, has one notable seam of tough connective tissue through the center that should be removed, and cooks in 6 minutes total. A perfect weeknight steak if you know it.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Hanger Steak \u2014 how to trim, how to cook, how to serve</li> <li>Remove the silverskin seam before cooking if your butcher hasn't</li> <li>Always cut against the visible grain \u2014 very pronounced in this cut</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Hanger steak + Serious Eats \u2014 Chimichurri OR bagna cauda sauce + roasted potatoes or frites</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Hanger Steak, and One Good Way to Cook it \u2014 Watch how he handles the seam of sinew before cooking \u2014 removing it is the one step most people skip that actually changes the eating experience.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#thursday-off","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":""},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#friday-korean-style-galbi-grilled-short-ribs","title":"Friday \u2014 Korean-Style Galbi (Grilled Short Ribs)","text":"<p>Skill: Flanken-cut short ribs (cut thin across the bone) marinated in a sesame-soy-pear marinade and grilled fast over high heat. This is the opposite of the braised short rib \u2014 same cut, completely different result. The marinade reduces and caramelizes on the grill; the thin cut means 2\u20133 minutes per side. Korean BBQ is a master class in how marinade, heat, and timing interact.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Grilled Beef Galbi</li> <li>Marinate overnight; the grated pear or Asian pear is traditional and also tenderizes</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Galbi + steamed white rice + quick kimchi (store-bought is fine) + sesame cucumber salad</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#saturday-project-the-grill-dinner","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: The Grill Dinner","text":"<p>Skill: A full dinner cooked entirely on the grill. Grill management: maintaining two zones, cooking multiple items at different heats, bringing everything to the table at once. This is a timing and fire-management project as much as a cooking one.</p> <p>Suggested menu: 1. Serious Eats \u2014 Grilled Ribeye Steaks \u2014 for 2\u20134 people 2. Corn on the cob, grilled (no recipe needed \u2014 grill in husk, 15 min, turning) 3. Grilled asparagus with olive oil and sea salt finish 4. Bread with compound butter from Week 15</p> <p>Fire management test: can you keep the indirect zone at 250\u00b0F while the direct zone is screaming hot? Use the lid and vents.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#sunday-off","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>Write down: what's the actual difference between grilling and broiling? (They're related but not the same.) What did you learn about two-zone fire management that you'll now use every time you grill?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#week-18-beef-beyond-the-cut","title":"Week 18 \u2014 Beef: Beyond the Cut","text":"<p>Theme this week: Beef in other forms \u2014 ground, minced, international preparations, and the under-explored territory of beef offal-adjacent cuts. Also: the art of building a dish around beef as a flavoring agent rather than a centerpiece.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#monday-bolognese-beef-as-background","title":"Monday \u2014 Bolognese: Beef as Background","text":"<p>Skill: True Bolognese (rag\u00f9 alla Bolognese) uses beef as a supporting player in a rich, long-cooked sauce \u2014 not a thick, tomatoey meat sauce. The classic has very little tomato, lots of wine, and slow cooking that transforms cheap ground beef into something complex and silky. Three hours minimum.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 The Best Slow-Cooked Bolognese Sauce</li> <li>Start at 3 PM. Finish with a splash of whole milk at the end \u2014 this is traditional and rounds the flavor.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Bolognese with fresh or dried pappardelle + simple salad + bread</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Carbonnade Flamande \u2014 Belgian Beef and Beer Stew (Ethan Chlebowski) \u2014 A European tradition of beef braised in liquid from a completely different direction. Compare how each culture uses liquid to transform tough cuts \u2014 and what the beer does that wine doesn't.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#tuesday-steak-salad-beef-as-accent","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Steak Salad: Beef as Accent","text":"<p>Skill: A steak salad is fundamentally different from a beef entr\u00e9e \u2014 the steak is sliced thin, at most a supporting element in a composed dish with acid, crunch, and fresh contrast. Tonight: cook the steak to medium-rare, rest it, thin-slice it, and build around it.</p> <p>Full Meal: Sliced steak salad \u2014 arugula, shaved parmesan, roasted tomatoes, lemon vinaigrette + grilled bread</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: POV Thai-ish Steak Salad \u2014 A different flavor direction on the same idea \u2014 compare how the acid and herb balance changes completely depending on whether you go Italian (lemon, parmesan) or Southeast Asian (lime, fish sauce, herbs).</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#wednesday-tamarind-braised-short-ribs-southeast-asian-flavor-profile","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Tamarind-Braised Short Ribs: Southeast Asian Flavor Profile","text":"<p>Skill: The same fundamentals as Week 16's red wine braise \u2014 but with a completely different flavor vocabulary. Tamarind adds deep sourness. Fish sauce adds umami. This is about applying braising technique to a different cuisine's flavor palette.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Tamarind Braised Beef Short Ribs</li> <li>Start by 2:30 PM for a 7 PM dinner</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Tamarind short ribs + jasmine rice + stir-fried bok choy or greens</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Glazed Braised Short Ribs (Adam Ragusea) \u2014 Same cut, different flavor vocabulary. Watch how he reads the braise for doneness and what the reduction glaze does to the surface \u2014 compare that technique to the tamarind version you just made.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#thursday-off_1","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\ud83d\udcd6 Think about this two-week block. Beef has given you: 8 different cuts, 5 different cooking methods (sear, braise, grill, confit-adjacent, raw/tartare-adjacent), and at least 4 different cuisine contexts. Write one thing each technique taught you that will permanently change how you cook anything \u2014 not just beef.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#friday-flank-steak-marinated-and-stuffed","title":"Friday \u2014 Flank Steak: Marinated and Stuffed","text":"<p>Skill: Butterflied flank steak, marinated, stuffed with herbs and cheese, rolled and tied \u2014 then grilled or seared. This is a simple roast-and-slice technique that produces a beautiful cross-section and is excellent for a weeknight dinner that looks elaborate.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Grilled Stuffed Flank Steak</li> <li>Butterfly it yourself (cut parallel to the cutting board, stop before cutting through) or ask the butcher</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Stuffed flank steak + roasted tomatoes + crusty bread</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#saturday-project-module-3-skills-dinner","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Module 3 Skills Dinner","text":"<p>You're 18 weeks in \u2014 nearly halfway through the proteins block. Tonight's project is a dinner for guests built entirely from techniques you now own across proteins and sauces.</p> <p>Framework (or build your own): 1. Opener: Smash burgers as sliders \u2014 small, two-bite, served as a first course (use Week 15 technique) 2. Main: Galbi or hanger steak (this week's grilled cuts) + rice or potatoes 3. Dessert: Something from your freezer or a simple fruit dessert \u2014 the cooking is the point, not the pastry</p> <p>Skill target: every element on the table should be cooked from memory. Open the fridge, cook from what's in front of you, make decisions.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#sunday-off_1","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>18-week reflection \u2014 where do you think your cooking has improved most since Week 1? Be specific. Not \"I got better at seasoning\" but \"I now salt in layers and can tell by taste when a dish needs acid vs. more salt vs. more fat.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#grilling-more-than-charcoal","title":"Grilling: More Than Charcoal","text":"<p>Great grilling is about heat zoning, timing, and knowing when to leave the food alone. The science is the same whether you're using gas or charcoal.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Dry-Brining Is the Best Way to Brine Meat, Poultry, and More \u2014 Salting your steak 24 hours ahead (or even 45 minutes ahead) changes the texture. The guide explains why.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#cheaper-cuts-more-flavor-more-patience","title":"Cheaper Cuts: More Flavor, More Patience","text":"<p>Hanger, skirt, flank, and flat iron are the cuts that chefs reach for when they're cooking for themselves. They have more fat and connective tissue \u2014 which becomes flavor when handled right.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Best Inexpensive Steak for the Grill: Hanger Steak \u2014 Kenji's full breakdown of the hanger: where it comes from, how to trim the sinew down the middle, and why it needs a quick sear at high heat rather than slow cooking.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Five Budget Cuts You Should Know \u2014 The complete guide to the lesser-known cuts that punch above their weight: hanger, skirt, flat iron, chuck eye, and more, with technique notes for each.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Hanger steak preparation \u2014 Trimming the silver skin from a whole hanger is a technique that improves the texture significantly. Watch it once before you do it the first time.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Franklin Barbecue by Aaron Franklin \u2014 The grilling bible from the man who changed American barbecue. Even if you never own a smoker, his approach to heat management and patience applies to everything you do over fire.</li> </ul> <p>\u2190 Weeks 17\u201318 | Weeks 21\u201322 \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Weeks 19\u201320 Quick Reference \u2014 Beef Advanced Cuts","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/quick-ref.html#week-17-recipes-grilling-the-grill-station","title":"Week 17 Recipes \u2014 Grilling &amp; the Grill Station","text":"Day Dish Skill Link Mon Grilled T-Bone + Roast Potatoes + Salad Two-zone fire; dual-muscle management T-Bone Grilled \u00b7 Roast Potatoes Tue Ribeye Cap / Bone-In Ribeye + Chimichurri + Greens Premium cut restraint; butter basting Ribeye Cap \u00b7 Chimichurri Wed Hanger Steak + Chimichurri or Bagna Cauda + Potatoes Butcher's cut; seam removal; against the grain Hanger Steak Thu OFF Read: Beef Guides Hub Beef Guides Fri Korean Galbi + Rice + Kimchi + Sesame Cucumber Flanken cut; marinade caramelization; fast grill Galbi Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Full Grill Dinner \u2014 Ribeye + Corn + Asparagus + Compound Butter Bread Fire management; two-zone; timing multiple items Ribeye on Grill"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/quick-ref.html#week-18-recipes-beef-beyond-the-cut","title":"Week 18 Recipes \u2014 Beef Beyond the Cut","text":"Day Dish Skill Link Mon Bolognese + Pappardelle + Salad Beef as background; long braise; wine + milk finish Bolognese Tue Steak Salad \u2014 arugula, shaved parm, roasted tomatoes, lemon vinaigrette Beef as accent; thin slice; acid balance \u2014 Wed Tamarind Braised Short Ribs + Jasmine Rice + Stir-Fried Greens SE Asian flavor profile on a braise Tamarind Short Ribs Thu OFF Reflect: what technique insight carries beyond beef? \u2014 Fri Stuffed Flank Steak (pesto, mozzarella, prosciutto) + Roasted Tomatoes + Bread Butterflying; rolling; grill or sear Stuffed Flank Steak Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Module 3 Skills Dinner \u2014 your choice of technique Full synthesis from Weeks 17\u201320 Smash Burgers (as starter option)"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/quick-ref.html#shopping-notes","title":"Shopping Notes","text":"<p>Week 17: - T-bone or porterhouse \u2014 1.5\u20132 inches thick; 1 per 1\u20132 people - Ribeye cap or bone-in ribeye \u2014 ask your butcher specifically for the spinalis cap if available - Hanger steak \u2014 1\u20131.5 lbs; ask butcher to trim the tough center seam if possible - Flanken-cut short ribs (galbi) \u2014 \u00bd inch thick, cross-cut; 2 lbs; Asian grocery stores often have these pre-cut</p> <p>Week 18: - Ground beef \u2014 80/20, 1.5 lbs (Bolognese) \u2014 buy the cheapest 80/20 you can find - Beef short ribs (English cut) \u2014 3 lbs (Wednesday braise) - Flank steak \u2014 1.5\u20132 lbs (Friday) - Tamarind concentrate or paste \u2014 small jar; Asian grocery stores; not tamarind candy</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 19\u201320: Beef Advanced Cuts","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Week 17 is grilling week \u2014 set up your outdoor setup before Monday. Week 18 has a long braise on Wednesday (start by 2:30 PM). The galbi (Week 17 Fri) needs overnight marinade \u2014 buy and prep on Thursday. The stuffed flank steak (Week 18 Fri) benefits from butterflying ahead of time.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Outdoor grill or grill pan \u2014 gas or charcoal; need two-zone setup capability</li> <li>[ ] Charcoal chimney \u2014 if using charcoal; skip lighter fluid</li> <li>[ ] Instant-read thermometer \u2014 still essential</li> <li>[ ] Kitchen twine \u2014 for tying the stuffed flank steak (Week 18 Fri)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-17","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 17","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] T-bone or porterhouse \u2014 1.5\u20132 inch thick; 1 per person (Monday)</li> <li>[ ] Ribeye cap (spinalis) OR bone-in ribeye \u2014 call your butcher ahead (Tuesday)</li> <li>[ ] Hanger steak \u2014 1\u20131.5 lbs; ask butcher to trim center seam if possible (Wednesday)</li> <li>[ ] Flanken-cut short ribs (galbi) \u2014 \u00bd inch cross-cut; 2 lbs. Asian grocery stores often stock these; standard grocery stores may not (Friday \u2014 marinate Thursday night)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-18","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 18","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Ground beef \u2014 80/20; 1.5 lbs (Monday Bolognese)</li> <li>[ ] Strip steak or hanger \u2014 for Tuesday steak salad; leftovers from Week 17 also work</li> <li>[ ] Beef short ribs \u2014 English cut; 3 lbs (Wednesday tamarind braise)</li> <li>[ ] Flank steak \u2014 1.5\u20132 lbs (Friday stuffed flank; ask butcher to butterfly if you prefer)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/shopping-list.html#produce-week-17","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 17","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Yukon gold potatoes \u2014 1.5 lbs (Monday roast)</li> <li>[ ] Asparagus \u2014 1 bunch (Saturday grill dinner)</li> <li>[ ] Corn \u2014 4 ears (Saturday grill dinner)</li> <li>[ ] Shallots \u2014 4</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Parsley \u2014 1 bunch (chimichurri)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh oregano \u2014 1 bunch (chimichurri)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 4</li> <li>[ ] Cucumber \u2014 2 (galbi sesame salad, Friday)</li> <li>[ ] Mixed greens \u2014 1 bag</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/shopping-list.html#produce-week-18","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 18","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Yellow onion \u2014 2 large (Bolognese mirepoix)</li> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 3 (Bolognese mirepoix)</li> <li>[ ] Celery \u2014 4 stalks (Bolognese mirepoix)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Tomatoes \u2014 6\u20138 plum/Roma (Bolognese; also for Thursday steak salad)</li> <li>[ ] Arugula \u2014 1 bag (Tuesday steak salad)</li> <li>[ ] Bok choy \u2014 2 heads (Wednesday with tamarind ribs)</li> <li>[ ] Jalape\u00f1o or chili \u2014 2 (tamarind braise)</li> <li>[ ] Basil \u2014 1 bunch (Friday flank)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-advanced/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry-goods","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry &amp; Dry Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Tamarind concentrate or paste \u2014 small jar (Wednesday; NOT tamarind candy)</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce \u2014 small bottle (Wednesday tamarind braise)</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce \u2014 for galbi marinade (Thursday/Friday)</li> <li>[ ] Sesame oil \u2014 for galbi and cucumber salad</li> <li>[ ] Asian pear or regular pear \u2014 1 (galbi marinade, grated)</li> <li>[ ] Korean chili flakes (gochugaru) \u2014 optional but authentic for galbi</li> <li>[ ] Dry white wine \u2014 \u00bd bottle (Bolognese)</li> <li>[ ] Whole milk \u2014 1 cup (Bolognese finish)</li> <li>[ ] Tomato paste \u2014 1 can</li> <li>[ ] San Marzano whole tomatoes \u2014 1 can (28 oz)</li> <li>[ ] Pappardelle or wide pasta \u2014 1 lb (Bolognese)</li> <li>[ ] Jasmine rice \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Pesto \u2014 small jar (stuffed flank; or make from scratch)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh mozzarella \u2014 8 oz (stuffed flank)</li> <li>[ ] Prosciutto \u2014 3 oz (stuffed flank)</li> <li>[ ] Parmesan \u2014 wedge (steak salad + Bolognese)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html","title":"\ud83d\udc37 Weeks 21\u201322: Pork \u2014 All Cuts","text":"<p>\u2190 Quick Reference \u2192 | Shopping List \u2192</p> <p>\"Pork is the most versatile protein in the world kitchen. It scales from a 2-minute chop to a 12-hour shoulder. It responds beautifully to fat, acid, smoke, sweetness, and spice. Learning pork is learning half the world's food traditions.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#week-19-the-pork-fundamentals","title":"Week 19 \u2014 The Pork Fundamentals","text":"<p>The key principle of pork this week: Pork \u2260 tough. The modern farmed pig is different from 30 years ago \u2014 leaner, safer at lower internal temperatures. The new standard is 145\u00b0F (USDA updated this in 2011), which means medium pork \u2014 still slightly pink \u2014 is correct. Cooking pork to 165\u00b0F the way you might have learned produces dry, grey, flavorless meat.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#monday-perfect-pork-chop","title":"Monday \u2014 Perfect Pork Chop","text":"<p>Skill: The hardest weeknight cook well-done: a bone-in pork chop, properly seared, properly finished, properly rested. Most home cooks overcook pork chops because they're afraid of undercooked pork. Tonight: understand the actual target (145\u00b0F), achieve it, taste the difference.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Perfect Pan-Seared Pork Chop \u2014 the technique and temperature explanation is the lesson</li> <li>Dry brine the night before. 145\u00b0F. Rest 5 minutes. Cut and taste.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Bone-in pork chop + pan sauce (apple cider or white wine, shallot, thyme) + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Cauliflower with Pine Nuts and Capers + simple salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Pork Chops with Madeira Mustard Pan Sauce (Helen Rennie) \u2014 Watch her pan sauce construction after the sear \u2014 the deglazing sequence and butter mount are the same technique you're using, just with different liquid.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#tuesday-chashu-pork-belly-low-and-slow-japanese-style","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Chashu Pork Belly: Low and Slow Japanese-Style","text":"<p>Skill: Chashu is braised and rolled pork belly \u2014 the origin is Japanese but the technique (braise in soy, mirin, sake, sugar) is a master class in balancing the four flavor elements in one preparation. The rendered belly collagen gives the braising liquid richness; the soy gives umami; the mirin and sugar give the glaze sweetness and lacquer.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Chashu Pork Belly for Ramen</li> <li>This is a 3\u20134 hour project cook on a Tuesday \u2014 start by 3 PM</li> <li>The leftover chashu will be used Thursday and works for ramen all week</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Chashu pork belly + steamed rice + quick pickled cucumbers + soft-boiled egg</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Why Lu Rou Fan is One of Taiwan's Favorite Comfort Foods (Ethan Chlebowski) \u2014 Different Asian tradition for braised pork belly. Compare how the five-spice and soy base contrasts with your chashu's mirin-sake approach \u2014 same ingredient, entirely different result.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#wednesday-pork-tenderloin-speed-and-precision","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Pork Tenderloin: Speed and Precision","text":"<p>Skill: Pork tenderloin is the leanest cut from the pig \u2014 cooked wrong it becomes the driest. The solution: high-heat sear, quick oven finish, immediate rest. There's almost no room for error in temperature here. Practice tonight.</p> <ul> <li>Dry brine 2 hours minimum. Sear in cast iron 2 minutes per side. Into 400\u00b0F oven. Thermometer in. Pull at 140\u00b0F (it'll carry over to 145\u00b0F while resting).</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Seared pork tenderloin + herb pan sauce (deglaze with white wine, add thyme, mount with butter) + Serious Eats \u2014 Honey-Roasted Carrots + rice</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#thursday-off","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\ud83d\udcd6 Rest. Or use the leftover chashu from Tuesday: slice it thin, make a simple bowl with rice, soft-boiled egg, nori, and whatever sauces you have on hand. This teaches you how a long-cook project pays off in multiple meals.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#friday-vietnamese-grilled-pork-chop-thit-heo-nuong","title":"Friday \u2014 Vietnamese Grilled Pork Chop (Thit Heo Nuong)","text":"<p>Skill: Marinated, grilled until caramelized and slightly charred. This is one of the traditional Vietnamese broken rice (c\u01a1m t\u1ea5m) preparations \u2014 the marinade is lemongrass, garlic, fish sauce, and a little sugar. The key technique: high heat, fast cook, maximum caramelization.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Vietnamese Grilled Pork Chop</li> <li>Marinate overnight for best results</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Grilled pork chops + steamed jasmine rice + nuoc cham dipping sauce + cucumber slices and herbs</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#saturday-project-ultra-crispy-slow-roasted-pork-shoulder","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Ultra-Crispy Slow-Roasted Pork Shoulder","text":"<p>Skill: One of the most satisfying large-format cooks in the pork repertoire. The shoulder (Boston butt or picnic) goes into a 300\u00b0F oven for 5\u20136 hours, then gets blasted at 500\u00b0F for 20\u201330 minutes to develop explosive crackling. The result feeds a crowd and requires almost no active cooking \u2014 mostly patience.</p> <ul> <li>Read (and mostly follow): Serious Eats \u2014 Ultra-Crispy Slow-Roasted Pork Shoulder</li> <li>Start by 11 AM. Score the fat cap deeply. Dry brine overnight.</li> </ul> <p>The Saturday spread: Pulled/sliced pork shoulder + whatever sides feel right \u2014 slaw, pickled jalape\u00f1os, fresh tortillas, or a simple potato salad. This is a meal for the table.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Easy Oven-Pulled Pork (Plus Four Ways to Use the Leftovers) \u2014 Compare his oven temperature and internal temp target to yours \u2014 two different paths to the same falling-apart shoulder, and the differences are instructive.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#sunday-off","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>Write: what was the biggest surprise about pork this week? Did the chashu (Tuesday) change how you think about braises? Did the crispy shoulder crackling make sense physically once you did it?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#week-20-pork-belly-ribs-and-curing","title":"Week 20 \u2014 Pork: Belly, Ribs, and Curing","text":""},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#monday-belly-pan-crispy-no-5-hour-braise","title":"Monday \u2014 Belly: Pan-Crispy, No 5-Hour Braise","text":"<p>Skill: Pork belly doesn't always require hours of cooking. Sliced pork belly (about \u00bd inch thick from your butcher) pan-seared in its own fat until crispy and rendered \u2014 this is the basis for guanciale, pancetta, and bacon-adjacent flavor without the cure. A learning cook this week.</p> <ul> <li>Cut into lardons (1cm x 4cm batons). Render slowly in a dry pan (no oil). Let the fat render out. Finish high heat for the crust.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Crispy pork belly lardons over white beans and wilted greens + crusty bread</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#tuesday-pork-ribs-understanding-the-two-methods","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Pork Ribs: Understanding the Two Methods","text":"<p>Skill: Spare ribs (more fat, more flavor) vs. baby back ribs (more tender, faster). Tonight: a hybrid method \u2014 2 hours low in the oven, then a finish on the grill or under the broiler. This solves the classic rib problem: you need collagen conversion (time + moderate heat) AND caramelized exterior (high heat).</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Sous Vide Pork Ribs \u2014 even if you're not sous viding, the texture targets and timing are instructive</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Ribs (your choice of spare or baby back) + coleslaw + cornbread or baked beans</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#wednesday-porchetta-italian-pork-at-its-peak","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Porchetta: Italian Pork at Its Peak","text":"<p>Skill: Porchetta is pork belly wrapped around a seasoned loin (or all-belly), rolled, tied, and slow-roasted. Fennel seed, rosemary, garlic, black pepper, and lemon zest are traditional. The skin crackles. The interior stays impossibly juicy. This is the most complex pork project of the block.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 All-Belly Porchetta</li> <li>Prep and roll Thursday or Friday and refrigerate uncovered \u2014 the drying is critical for the skin.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Porchetta slices + braised white beans + simple arugula salad with lemon</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#thursday-off_1","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\ud83d\udcd6 Look up: what is the difference between guanciale, pancetta, and prosciutto? All three are Italian cured pork products. Why does guanciale give cacio e pepe its specific flavor (which pancetta doesn't replicate perfectly)? You've cooked with all three \u2014 now understand the distinctions.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#friday-pork-meatballs-ground-pork-technique","title":"Friday \u2014 Pork Meatballs: Ground Pork Technique","text":"<p>Skill: Ground pork makes the most flavorful meatballs \u2014 more than beef, because the fat content is higher. Tonight: traditional Italian-style meatball technique (bread soaked in milk, gently mixed, seared rather than baked).</p> <p>Full Meal: Pork meatballs + simple tomato sugo + fresh pasta or spaghetti</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The Key to Tender Balls: How to Make Excellent Meatballs \u2014 Watch how he handles the mix \u2014 the less you work the meat, the more tender the result, and that principle applies to your pork meatballs too.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#saturday-project-carnitas-and-the-whole-shoulder-taco-dinner","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Carnitas and the Whole Shoulder Taco Dinner","text":"<p>Skill: Carnitas \u2014 Mexican lard-braised pork shoulder \u2014 is one of the finest applications of cheap pork in any cuisine. The shoulder goes into a Dutch oven with lard (or a combination of water + lard), orange, lime, bay, and cumin. The water evaporates and the pork fries in its own fat at the end, creating both tender interior and hard-crisped exterior simultaneously.</p> <ul> <li>Read (and mostly follow): Serious Eats \u2014 No-Waste Tacos de Carnitas</li> <li>Serve with: Serious Eats \u2014 Charred Tomatillo Salsa Verde + guacamole + pickled jalape\u00f1os + fresh white onion and cilantro + warm corn tortillas</li> </ul> <p>The real skill: the warm tortilla is important. Wrap them in a cloth. Keep them warm. The taco is only as good as the tortilla.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Carnitas are Easy, Inexpensive, and Delicious \u2014 Watch the final fat-frying step closely \u2014 that's the moment the pork goes from braised to both tender AND crispy simultaneously.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#sunday-off_1","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>One paragraph: What do you now understand about pork fat that you didn't before? (Hint: it's not just \"flavor.\" It's about rendering temperature, smoke point, and the way fat transfers heat to the meat it surrounds.)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#the-pork-map","title":"The Pork Map","text":"<p>Pork is the most versatile animal in the kitchen. Understanding the cuts \u2014 shoulder vs. loin vs. belly vs. leg \u2014 explains why carnitas works but a pork loin doesn't shred.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Pork Shoulder Demystified: Boston Butt vs. Picnic \u2014 The same cut, sold under different names \u2014 here's what the difference actually means for your cooking.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#cured-and-preserved-pork","title":"Cured and Preserved Pork","text":"<p>This week is a natural gateway to charcuterie. Bacon, pancetta, and guanciale are the same muscle treated differently \u2014 and understanding that difference changes how you cook with them.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Bacon, Pancetta, and More: Cured Pork Products Explained \u2014 A clear guide to all the cured pork products you'll encounter in Italian and French recipes and why they're not interchangeable.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Case for Pink Pork \u2014 The USDA updated its pork temperature guidelines. Most people still overcook it. This explains what medium-rare pork actually means for food safety.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Kenji's carnitas \u2014 The confit-braised-then-crisped method explained in real time. The key moment is the fat rendering at the end.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Charcuterie: The Craft of Salting, Smoking, and Curing by Michael Ruhlman &amp; Brian Polcyn \u2014 The gateway book into everything you'll explore in Weeks 27\u201328. Covers the principles and science of every cured and preserved pork product.</li> </ul> <p>\u2190 Weeks 19\u201320 | Weeks 23\u201324 \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Weeks 21\u201322 Quick Reference \u2014 Pork All Cuts","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/quick-ref.html#week-19-recipes-pork-fundamentals","title":"Week 19 Recipes \u2014 Pork Fundamentals","text":"Day Dish Skill Link Mon Bone-In Pork Chop + Pan Sauce + Roasted Cauliflower 145\u00b0F target; dry brine; pan sauce Pork Chop Technique \u00b7 Cauliflower Tue Chashu Pork Belly + Rice + Pickled Cucumbers + Soft Egg Braise in soy-mirin; fat rendering; umami layering Chashu Pork Wed Pork Tenderloin + Herb Pan Sauce + Roasted Carrots + Rice Lean cut precision; carry-over temp; butter-mounted sauce Honey-Roasted Carrots Thu OFF / Leftover Chashu Bowl Use Tuesday's project \u2014 observe multi-day yield \u2014 Fri Vietnamese Grilled Pork Chop + Jasmine Rice + Nuoc Cham + Herbs Marinade caramelization; lemongrass; fish sauce balance Vietnamese Pork Chop Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Ultra-Crispy Slow-Roasted Pork Shoulder + Slaw + Pickled Jalape\u00f1os Long low roast; blast finish; crackling Slow-Roasted Shoulder"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/quick-ref.html#week-20-recipes-belly-ribs-curing","title":"Week 20 Recipes \u2014 Belly, Ribs &amp; Curing","text":"Day Dish Skill Link Mon Crispy Pork Belly Lardons + White Beans + Wilted Greens Fat rendering; lardon technique; no brine needed \u2014 Tue Oven-and-Grill Ribs + Coleslaw + Cornbread Collagen + caramelization hybrid method Pork Ribs Method Wed Porchetta + Braised White Beans + Arugula Salad Roll + tie; fennel-rosemary-garlic; crispy skin All-Belly Porchetta Thu OFF Read: difference between guanciale, pancetta, and prosciutto \u2014 Fri Pork Meatballs + Tomato Sugo + Pasta Ground pork; milk-bread ratio; sear not bake \u2014 Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Carnitas Taco Dinner + Salsa Verde + Guacamole + Pickled Jalape\u00f1os Fat-braise; water-fry finish; taco assembly Carnitas \u00b7 Salsa Verde"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/quick-ref.html#key-pork-temperature-rules","title":"Key Pork Temperature Rules","text":"Cut Target Internal Temp Notes Pork chop 145\u00b0F Rest 5 min; slight pink is correct and safe Pork tenderloin 140\u00b0F (pull early) Carryover to 145\u00b0F Pork shoulder (slow) 195\u2013205\u00b0F For pulling; collagen fully converted Pork belly Internal temp matters less Cook to visual \u2014 rendered fat and tender Pork ribs 195\u2013203\u00b0F Probe should slide in with no resistance"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/quick-ref.html#shopping-notes","title":"Shopping Notes","text":"<p>Week 19: - Bone-in pork chops \u2014 1 inch thick; rib chop preferred; 1 per person. Dry brine Sun night. - Pork belly \u2014 2 lbs, skin-on; ask butcher if not at standard grocer (Chashu, Tuesday) - Pork tenderloin \u2014 1 lb; usually comes in a vacuum pack of 2 - Thin pork chops for grilling \u2014 \u00bd inch bone-in (Vietnamese, Friday) \u2014 marinate overnight - Bone-in pork shoulder \u2014 4\u20135 lbs, fat cap on (Saturday; buy by Fri for dry brine overnight)</p> <p>Week 20: - Pork belly slabs \u2014 1.5 lbs (Monday lardon cook), skin off; ask butcher to skin - Spare ribs or baby back \u2014 1 rack (Tuesday) - Pork belly, skin-on \u2014 2 lbs for porchetta (Wednesday); buy early to dry in fridge - Ground pork \u2014 1 lb, 80/20 (Friday meatballs) - Pork shoulder \u2014 4 lbs (Saturday carnitas); can use the same cut as Week 19 Saturday</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 21\u201322: Pork All Cuts","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Two major project cooks this block \u2014 the slow-roasted pork shoulder (Week 19 Sat, start by 11 AM) and carnitas (Week 20 Sat, start by noon). Carnitas ingredients are simple; don't overthink the shopping. The porchetta (Week 20 Wed) should be assembled and dried uncovered in the fridge at least overnight \u2014 prep it Monday or Tuesday.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dutch oven (5\u20137 quart) \u2014 essential for chashu, carnitas, meatballs</li> <li>[ ] Kitchen twine \u2014 for rolling and tying porchetta</li> <li>[ ] Wire rack + sheet pan setup \u2014 pork shoulder needs to sit on a rack in a shallow pan</li> <li>[ ] Instant-read thermometer \u2014 non-negotiable for pork (145\u00b0F target)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-19","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 19","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Bone-in rib chops \u2014 1 inch thick; 1 per person (Mon; dry brine Sun night)</li> <li>[ ] Pork belly (skin-on, slab) \u2014 2 lbs (Tue chashu; buy early for prep)</li> <li>[ ] Pork tenderloin \u2014 1\u20131.5 lbs (Wed; often sold in 2-pack)</li> <li>[ ] Bone-in pork chops, thin \u2014 \u00bd inch; 2\u20133 pieces (Fri Vietnamese grill; marinate Thu night)</li> <li>[ ] Bone-in pork shoulder \u2014 4\u20135 lbs with fat cap (Sat; buy Fri to dry brine overnight)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-20","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 20","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Pork belly (skin removed) \u2014 1.5 lbs (Mon lardon cook)</li> <li>[ ] Pork spare ribs or baby back \u2014 1 full rack (Tue)</li> <li>[ ] Pork belly (skin-on) \u2014 2 lbs (Wed porchetta; buy Mon and prep immediately)</li> <li>[ ] Ground pork \u2014 1 lb (Fri meatballs)</li> <li>[ ] Pork shoulder \u2014 4 lbs boneless (Sat carnitas)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/shopping-list.html#produce-week-19","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 19","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 3 heads</li> <li>[ ] Ginger \u2014 1 knob</li> <li>[ ] Shallots \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Lemongrass \u2014 4 stalks (Friday marinade)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Limes \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Oranges \u2014 2 (Saturday pork shoulder brine + Sunday carnitas)</li> <li>[ ] Jalape\u00f1os \u2014 6 (for pickling; Saturday)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumbers \u2014 3 (pickled for chashu bowl + Vietnamese meal)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh mint, cilantro, Thai basil \u2014 for Friday meal and Saturday sides</li> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 4 (honey-roasted Wednesday)</li> <li>[ ] Cauliflower \u2014 1 head (Monday side)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/shopping-list.html#produce-week-20","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 20","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Fennel seed \u2014 (also pantry; Week 20 Wed porchetta)</li> <li>[ ] Tomatillos \u2014 1 lb (Week 20 Sat salsa verde)</li> <li>[ ] Poblano pepper \u2014 1 (salsa verde optional addition)</li> <li>[ ] Avocados \u2014 4 (guacamole, Week 20 Saturday)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh white onion \u2014 1 (carnitas toppings)</li> <li>[ ] Cilantro \u2014 2 bunches (Week 20 Sat)</li> <li>[ ] Arugula \u2014 1 bag (Week 20 Wed porchetta salad)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/shopping-list.html#pantry-week-19","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry \u2014 Week 19","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Soy sauce \u2014 \u00bd cup (chashu marinade)</li> <li>[ ] Mirin \u2014 \u00bc cup (chashu)</li> <li>[ ] Sake or dry vermouth \u2014 \u00bc cup (chashu)</li> <li>[ ] Sugar \u2014 white (chashu)</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce (nuoc cham Friday)</li> <li>[ ] Rice vinegar (nuoc cham + quick pickles)</li> <li>[ ] Kosher salt \u2014 plenty; dry brining all week</li> <li>[ ] White wine + chicken stock (tenderloin pan sauce)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/21-22-pork/shopping-list.html#pantry-week-20","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry \u2014 Week 20","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Lard or neutral oil \u2014 2 cups (carnitas)</li> <li>[ ] Bay leaves \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Cumin \u2014 ground and seeds</li> <li>[ ] Fennel seed \u2014 for porchetta</li> <li>[ ] Fresh rosemary \u2014 2 bunches (porchetta)</li> <li>[ ] Corn tortillas \u2014 2 packs (Saturday carnitas)</li> <li>[ ] White beans \u2014 2 cans (Wednesday with porchetta + Monday with belly)</li> <li>[ ] San Marzano tomatoes \u2014 1 can (Friday meatball sugo)</li> <li>[ ] Dry pasta (spaghetti or rigatoni) \u2014 1 lb (Friday)</li> <li>[ ] Day-old bread \u2014 \u00be cup (for meatball panade)</li> <li>[ ] Whole milk \u2014 \u00bd cup (meatball panade)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html","title":"\ud83d\udc1f Weeks 23\u201324: Seafood \u2014 Fish","text":"<p>\u2190 Quick Reference \u2192 | Shopping List \u2192</p> <p>\"Fish is the most immediate teacher in the kitchen. You overcooked it? You know in 30 seconds. The window for perfection is narrow \u2014 narrow enough that it forces your full attention every time.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#week-21-the-fundamentals-of-fish-cookery","title":"Week 21 \u2014 The Fundamentals of Fish Cookery","text":"<p>The central principle this week: Fish cooks faster than you think, at lower temperatures than you're used to, and the margin between perfect and overdone is about 30 seconds. Salmon at 125\u00b0F (slightly translucent at the center) is perfect. At 145\u00b0F it becomes dry and flaky in the wrong way. Everything this week is about developing the instinct to pull fish early.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#monday-crispy-skin-pan-seared-salmon","title":"Monday \u2014 Crispy-Skin Pan-Seared Salmon","text":"<p>Skill: Perfectly crisped fish skin in a pan is one of the most technically satisfying results in everyday cooking. The two secrets are: dry the skin completely before cooking (paper towels, uncovered in fridge if possible), and resist the urge to move it. The skin needs sustained contact with the hot pan to release its moisture and crisp. If it sticks, it's not ready.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Crispy Pan-Seared Salmon Fillets \u2014 the technique section is essential reading</li> <li>Cold pan start is debated; we recommend room-temp pan, medium-high heat, oil just to shimmer</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Crispy skin salmon + herb oil or lemon butter + Serious Eats \u2014 Stir-Fried Garlic Spinach + steamed rice</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Grill Salmon (Helen Rennie) \u2014 Different heat source, same goal as your pan sear; notice how she reads doneness and what she says about the margin for error.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#tuesday-sole-meuniere-the-french-lesson","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Sole Meuni\u00e8re: The French Lesson","text":"<p>Skill: Sole meuni\u00e8re is one of the first dishes classically taught to French culinary students. It's also one of the most instructive: dredge in flour, cook in butter, make the brown butter sauce in the same pan in 60 seconds, finish with lemon. Brown butter (beurre noisette) is a flavor you'll reach for constantly once you know it.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Sole Meuni\u00e8re</li> <li>The brown butter sauce: butter continues to cook in the hot pan after you remove the fish. Watch it turn amber. Smell it \u2014 it should smell nutty, like hazelnuts. Off the heat. Lemon juice. Pour immediately.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Sole meuni\u00e8re + steamed haricots verts or asparagus + crusty bread to catch the sauce</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Sole Meuni\u00e8re (Jacques P\u00e9pin) \u2014 Watch the brown butter timing and how little it takes to cross from noisette to burned. This is the master class version of what you're cooking tonight.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#wednesday-the-universal-crispy-fish-technique","title":"Wednesday \u2014 The Universal Crispy Fish Technique","text":"<p>Skill: Serious Eats \u2014 The Easiest Crispy Pan-Seared Fish \u2014 works on almost any white fish fillet. Tonight: cod, halibut, sea bass, or snapper \u2014 whatever is freshest and least expensive at your market. This is the workhorse technique you'll use for the rest of your life.</p> <ul> <li>The key insight: a stainless steel or cast iron pan, properly preheated, with enough oil, prevents sticking better than nonstick does because it creates a proper sear</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Crispy white fish + whatever vegetable you feel like + rice or potatoes</p> <p>Skill note: If the fish sticks, it's telling you something. It means the pan wasn't hot enough or there isn't enough fat. This is useful information \u2014 not failure.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#thursday-fish-butchery-filleting-a-whole-fish","title":"Thursday \u2014 Fish Butchery: Filleting a Whole Fish","text":"<p>Skill: Breaking down a whole round fish into two clean fillets. This is the single most useful fish skill you can own \u2014 when you can fillet, you buy whole fish (cheaper, fresher, more honest), and you understand why a halibut fillet costs what it does.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read and watch before starting: Serious Eats \u2014 How to Fillet a Fish \u2014 the Kenji walkthrough is the clearest English-language video on this.</p> <p>The technique for a round fish (salmon, sea bass, snapper, branzino): 1. Find the backbone \u2014 place the fish belly-down; feel the spine through the flesh 2. First cut \u2014 score behind the head diagonally to the backbone; don't cut through 3. Run the knife along the spine \u2014 blade angled slightly toward the bone, long smooth strokes, let the backbone guide you; use the rib cage as a fence 4. Fillet off the ribcage \u2014 once past the spine, angle the knife to follow the rib curve; you should hear the blade scraping bone (that's correct \u2014 you're not wasting meat that way) 5. Pin bones \u2014 run your finger down the centerline of the fillet; tiny bones perpendicular to the flesh. Pull with needle-nose pliers or fish tweezers, always pulling in the direction the bone points 6. Repeat for the second fillet</p> <p>Freshness signals \u2014 know these before you go to the fishmonger: - Eyes: clear and slightly bulging. Cloudy or sunken = not fresh - Gills: bright red when fresh; brown or grey = older fish - Smell: clean, oceanic, or neutral. \"Fishy\" smell is TMA (trimethylamine) \u2014 bacterial decomposition. Fresh fish smells like the sea, not like fish - Flesh: springs back when pressed; doesn't hold the indentation - \"Sushi-grade\" has no legal definition \u2014 it means the seller is comfortable selling it raw. Ask your fishmonger directly</p> <p>Full Meal: Fillet and cook the fish in whatever style you prefer tonight \u2014 the miso glaze is already prepped for Friday, or use the Wednesday technique (crispy skin pan sear). You've broken it down yourself. That changes how it tastes.</p> <p>Why this matters beyond skills: A whole 2 lb branzino costs $12\u201314 at a good fishmonger. The same fish sold as fillets costs $18\u201322. You just learned where $6\u20138 of the price comes from \u2014 and you can have fresher fish for less money.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#friday-miso-glazed-salmon-japanese-technique","title":"Friday \u2014 Miso-Glazed Salmon: Japanese Technique","text":"<p>Skill: The miso glaze (white miso, mirin, sake, sugar) is applied to salmon and left to cure for several hours or overnight. The sugars in the miso caramelize under the broiler in 3\u20134 minutes. This is one of the most famous fish preparations in Japanese home cooking \u2014 Nobu Matsuhisa's black cod version made it internationally famous, but salmon is the accessible entry point.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Miso-Glazed Salmon \u2014 toaster oven technique; standard oven broiler works identically</li> <li>Glaze and refrigerate Thursday night. Friday is 8 minutes total.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Miso-glazed salmon + steamed rice + quick pickled cucumbers + wilted bok choy</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#saturday-project-whole-roasted-fish","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Whole Roasted Fish","text":"<p>Skill: A whole fish \u2014 scored, stuffed with aromatics, and roasted at high heat \u2014 is one of the most impressive and least technically demanding cooks in this program. The bones protect the fish from overcooking significantly more than fillets do. The crispy skin pulls away from the bone with a wonderful texture.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Salt-Baked Whole Fish with Fresh Herbs \u2014 a more dramatic version of the whole-fish concept; alternatively roast the fish simply with just olive oil, lemon, and herbs in a 425\u00b0F oven for 25\u201330 minutes per kilo</li> <li>Any whole fish works: snapper, branzino, sea bass, striped bass, or whatever is freshest</li> </ul> <p>The Saturday meal: Whole roasted or salt-baked fish + olive oil, lemon, and capers dressed over the top + roasted potatoes or simple rice + salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Grill and Eat a Whole Fish (Branzino) (Helen Rennie) \u2014 Same fish, different heat source; pay attention to how she talks about the bones changing the cook time calculus compared to fillets.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#sunday-off","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>Write: what was the biggest mental adjustment about fish cookery compared to beef and pork? Most people cook fish longer than necessary \u2014 did you resist this tonight?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#week-22-fish-deeper-techniques-global-preparations","title":"Week 22 \u2014 Fish: Deeper Techniques &amp; Global Preparations","text":""},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#monday-seared-fish-mushroom-asian-style","title":"Monday \u2014 Seared Fish + Mushroom, Asian Style","text":"<p>Skill: Pan-searing fish over a bed of shiitake mushrooms and aromatics \u2014 a technique from Chinese and East Asian cooking where the mushrooms both flavor the fish and prevent it from sticking dramatically. The result is fish with deeply savory umami below it, almost stock-like in the pan.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Pan-Seared Fish with Shiitake Mushrooms</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Seared fish with mushrooms + rice + wilted greens</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#tuesday-fish-tacos-west-coast-done-right","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Fish Tacos: West Coast Done Right","text":"<p>Skill: Baja fish tacos \u2014 battered, fried white fish, shredded cabbage, crema, and salsa. The batter is rice-flour-light; the oil temperature matters (350\u00b0F); the fish cooks in 90 seconds. Building a perfect taco is a lesson in acid, fat, heat, and crunch in one bite.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Baja Fish Tacos</li> <li>Set up a simple deep-fry station: Dutch oven, 3 inches of neutral oil, thermometer. Don't skip the thermometer.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Baja fish tacos + pickled jalape\u00f1os + guacamole or avocado crema + cold beer (optional)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#wednesday-salmon-teriyaki-the-weeknight-standard","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Salmon Teriyaki: The Weeknight Standard","text":"<p>Skill: True teriyaki is a Japanese glaze (soy, mirin, sake, sugar) applied and cooked in the pan \u2014 not the thick bottled sauce you pour over cooked meat. The technique: sear the salmon, flip, add the teriyaki glaze to the pan, baste continuously as it reduces and lacquers the fish. This takes about 4 minutes total.</p> <ul> <li>Read and follow closely: Serious Eats \u2014 Easy Teriyaki Glazed Salmon</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Teriyaki salmon rice bowl + cucumber + avocado + sesame seeds + pickled ginger</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#thursday-off","title":"Thursday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>\ud83d\udcd6 Think about this week's fish sources. Where did you buy them? Can you learn to identify freshness yourself \u2014 clear eyes on whole fish, smell (ocean mild, not \"fishy\"), gills that are bright red, flesh that springs back? Challenge: go to the fish counter and choose the freshest fillet without asking.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#friday-whole-grilled-branzino","title":"Friday \u2014 Whole Grilled Branzino","text":"<p>Skill: Small whole fish on the grill \u2014 scored, rubbed with olive oil, placed over direct heat, flipped once. The bones protect the flesh from drying, the skin chars beautifully, and the result is cleaner-tasting than almost any fillet preparation. Two minutes per side is usually enough for a 500g fish.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Whole Grilled Fish</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Whole grilled branzino (or snapper) + salsa verde or gremolata + roasted potatoes + salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Go Fish (Jacques P\u00e9pin) \u2014 Watch how he reads the cooked fish and separates the fillet from the bone at the table; that's the finishing move that makes whole fish feel confident rather than awkward.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#saturday-project-bouillabaisse-the-grand-fish-stew","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Bouillabaisse (The Grand Fish Stew)","text":"<p>Skill: Bouillabaisse is the most technically demanding fish recipe in this block \u2014 and the most rewarding. It requires: a flavorful, deeply reduced broth made from fish bones and shells; aromatics cooked in stages; multiple fish and shellfish added in sequence by how long they need. The rouille (saffron-garlic aioli spread on croutons) is the soul of the dish.</p> <p>This is a half-day project. Buy the bones/shells the same day (ask your fishmonger to save fish bones when you buy the fillets).</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Bouillabaisse Marseillaise \u2014 the definitive home-cook version</li> </ul> <p>The Saturday spread: Bouillabaisse + rouille croutons + crusty bread + simple green salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Bouillabaisse and How to Make Fish Stock (Helen Rennie) \u2014 The stock-building section is the real lesson; watch how she extracts flavor from bones and shells before anything else goes in the pot.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#sunday-off_1","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>Write: what is the universal fish truth you take away from these two weeks? (Suggested reflection direction: fish communicates readiness \u2014 it turns from translucent to opaque, from raw pink to cooked white, from raw flesh that sticks to the pan to cooked flesh that releases. All you have to do is watch.)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#buying-fish","title":"Buying Fish","text":"<p>The most important fish skill happens before you cook. Knowing what fresh fish looks and smells like \u2014 and what to ask a fishmonger \u2014 matters more than technique.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Fillet a Whole Fish \u2014 The knife skill most home cooks never develop. Understanding the angle, pressure, and feel for running a blade along the spine changes how you approach any finned fish \u2014 whether you buy it whole or not.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#the-bouillabaisse-deep-dive","title":"The Bouillabaisse Deep Dive","text":"<p>Bouillabaisse is a lesson in building shellfish stock, saffron, and rouille \u2014 three techniques that extend into a dozen other recipes.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Real Bouillabaisse (Bouillabaisse Marseillaise) \u2014 The full recipe and process: building the saffron-shellfish broth, making the rouille, and understanding why the dish is served in two stages. The technique is transferable to any rich shellfish stew.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Jacques P\u00e9pin fillets a fish \u2014 Watch the knife angle and the way he reads the bones. This is the hand skill that separates cooks who buy fillets from cooks who buy whole fish.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Sole meuni\u00e8re in real time \u2014 Brown butter moves fast. Watching the color progression before attempting it is worth doing.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Whole Fish Cookbook by Josh Niland \u2014 Argues for cooking the entire fish, reduces waste, and teaches you to see fish the way butchers see meat. Transformative for serious fish cooks.</li> </ul> <p>\u2190 Weeks 21\u201322 | Weeks 25\u201326 \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Weeks 23\u201324 Quick Reference \u2014 Seafood: Fish","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/quick-ref.html#week-21-recipes-fish-fundamentals","title":"Week 21 Recipes \u2014 Fish Fundamentals","text":"Day Dish Skill Link Mon Crispy-Skin Pan-Seared Salmon + Garlic Spinach + Rice Dry skin; resist moving; read the stick Crispy Salmon \u00b7 Garlic Spinach Tue Sole Meuni\u00e8re + Haricots Verts + Crusty Bread Brown butter sauce; speed; classical French Sole Meuni\u00e8re Wed Crispy Pan-Seared White Fish (your choice) + Veg + Rice Universal technique; high-heat; stainless principle Easiest Crispy Fish Thu OFF Think about freshness; visit a fishmonger if possible \u2014 Fri Miso-Glazed Salmon + Rice + Quick-Pickled Cucumbers + Bok Choy Miso cure; broiler caramelization (glaze Thu night) Miso-Glazed Salmon Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Salt-Baked or Whole Roasted Fish + Roast Potatoes + Salad Whole fish; bone protection; salt crust drama Salt-Baked Whole Fish"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/quick-ref.html#week-22-recipes-fish-deeper-techniques","title":"Week 22 Recipes \u2014 Fish: Deeper Techniques","text":"Day Dish Skill Link Mon Seared Fish + Shiitake Mushrooms + Rice + Greens Asian layering; mushroom umami base Pan-Seared Fish + Mushrooms Tue Baja Fish Tacos + Picked Jalape\u00f1os + Guacamole Light batter; 350\u00b0F fry; taco acid-fat-crunch Baja Fish Tacos Wed Teriyaki Salmon Rice Bowl + Cucumber + Avocado In-pan glaze; real teriyaki technique Teriyaki Salmon Bowl Thu OFF Practice freshness identification at the fish counter \u2014 Fri Whole Grilled Branzino + Salsa Verde + Roast Potatoes + Salad Whole fish on grill; score and flip once Whole Grilled Fish Sat \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Bouillabaisse + Rouille Croutons + Crusty Bread Grand fish stew; bone broth + sequenced fish Bouillabaisse"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/quick-ref.html#fish-doneness-quick-reference","title":"Fish Doneness Quick Reference","text":"Fish Pull from Heat at Texture at Target Salmon 120\u2013125\u00b0F Slightly translucent at center; moist and silky White fish (cod, halibut) 130\u00b0F Just opaque throughout; flakes when pressed Sole/flounder 125\u00b0F Cooks very fast \u2014 2\u20133 min each side Whole fish Flesh pulls cleanly from bone Usually 25\u201330 min per kg at 220\u00b0C / 425\u00b0F Tuna (seared) 90\u2013100\u00b0F Raw-cold center; seared crust \u2014 60 sec per side"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/quick-ref.html#shopping-notes","title":"Shopping Notes","text":"<p>Week 21 \u2014 Buy fresh day-of or at most 1 day ahead: - Salmon fillets, skin-on \u2014 2 pieces (Monday + Friday miso) - Dover sole or flounder \u2014 2\u20134 fillets (Tuesday) - Any fresh white fish fillet \u2014 cod, halibut, sea bass (Wednesday; buy what's freshest/cheapest) - 1 whole fish \u2014 snapper, branzino, or sea bass; 1\u20131.5 kg (Saturday) - Coarse sea salt \u2014 3 lbs (if salt-baking)</p> <p>Week 22 \u2014 Again, freshness is the priority: - Firm white fish \u2014 cod or halibut (Monday)  - White fish for frying \u2014 cod, mahi-mahi, or tilapia (Tuesday tacos) - Salmon fillets \u2014 2 pieces (Wednesday teriyaki) - Branzino or snapper, whole \u2014 2 small fish (Friday grill) - Assorted fish + shellfish for bouillabaisse \u2014 2\u20133 types of firm white fish, plus clams or mussels; ask your fishmonger to save fish bones for the broth</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 23\u201324: Seafood Fish","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>The golden rule of fish shopping: Buy it day-of or the day before. Not earlier. Fish quality degrades faster than any other protein. If your usual grocery store doesn't have great seafood, find a fishmonger. Tell them you're cooking fish five nights a week for two weeks \u2014 they will help you figure out timing.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dutch oven \u2014 for Tuesday's fish tacos (frying)</li> <li>[ ] Thermometer \u2014 essential; also useful for checking oil temp for frying (350\u00b0F target)</li> <li>[ ] Fish spatula \u2014 wide, thin, flexible; the tool that makes flipping fish easy</li> <li>[ ] Wire rack + sheet pan \u2014 for draining fried fish tacos (Week 22 Tue)</li> <li>[ ] Coarse sea salt \u2014 3\u20134 lbs if doing the salt-bake version of Saturday's whole fish</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-21-buy-as-close-to-cook-day-as-possible","title":"\ud83d\udc1f Proteins \u2014 Week 21 (buy as close to cook day as possible)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Salmon fillets, skin-on \u2014 2 thick pieces (Mon); 2 more pieces (Fri miso glaze)</li> <li>[ ] Dover sole or flounder fillets \u2014 2\u20134 (Tue meuni\u00e8re)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh white fish fillet \u2014 cod, halibut, or sea bass; 2 pieces (Wed technique practice)</li> <li>[ ] Whole fish \u2014 1\u20132 branzino, snapper, or sea bass, 500g\u20131kg each (Sat)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-22-buy-as-close-to-cook-day-as-possible","title":"\ud83d\udc1f Proteins \u2014 Week 22 (buy as close to cook day as possible)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Firm white fish \u2014 cod or halibut, 2 pieces (Mon mushroom cook)</li> <li>[ ] White fish for frying \u2014 cod, mahi-mahi, or tilapia; 1 lb (Tue tacos)</li> <li>[ ] Salmon fillets \u2014 2 pieces (Wed teriyaki)</li> <li>[ ] Branzino or snapper, whole \u2014 2 small (Fri grill)</li> <li>[ ] Bouillabaisse assortment \u2014 2\u20133 types: e.g., cod (1 lb), monkfish (1 lb) + 1 lb clams or mussels (Sat); ask fishmonger to save bones/heads for the broth</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/shopping-list.html#produce-week-21","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 21","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Baby spinach \u2014 2 bags (Mon + other sides)</li> <li>[ ] Haricots verts or green beans \u2014 1 lb (Tue)</li> <li>[ ] Bok choy \u2014 2 heads (Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumbers \u2014 3 (quick pickled; Fri and Week 22)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Fresh dill \u2014 1 bunch (whole fish garnish)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Fresh thyme \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Yukon gold potatoes \u2014 1.5 lbs (Saturday)</li> <li>[ ] Mixed greens \u2014 1 bag</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/shopping-list.html#produce-week-22","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 22","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Shiitake mushrooms \u2014 8 oz (Mon fish + mushroom)</li> <li>[ ] Avocados \u2014 3 (Tue tacos + Wed bowl)</li> <li>[ ] Cabbage \u2014 \u00bd head, shredded (Tue fish tacos slaw)</li> <li>[ ] Jalape\u00f1os \u2014 4 (quick pickled for tacos)</li> <li>[ ] Limes \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Green onions \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Cucumber \u2014 2 (Wed teriyaki bowl)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh herbs for bouillabaisse \u2014 parsley, fennel fronds, thyme, bay (Sat)</li> <li>[ ] Fennel bulb \u2014 2 (bouillabaisse aromatics)</li> <li>[ ] Tomatoes \u2014 4 (bouillabaisse)</li> <li>[ ] Leeks \u2014 2 (bouillabaisse)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] White miso paste \u2014 small tub (Week 21 Fri glaze)</li> <li>[ ] Mirin and sake \u2014 small bottles (Week 21 Fri glaze + Week 22 Wed teriyaki)</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce</li> <li>[ ] Rice flour \u2014 for fish taco batter (Week 22 Tue; all-purpose also works)</li> <li>[ ] Neutral oil \u2014 1 quart (frying Week 22 Tue)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 1 lb (meuni\u00e8re + pan sauces)</li> <li>[ ] Sesame oil (Week 22 Wed bowl)</li> <li>[ ] Sesame seeds</li> <li>[ ] Saffron \u2014 small pinch (bouillabaisse rouille; expensive but worth it)</li> <li>[ ] Fennel seeds \u2014 1 tsp (bouillabaisse)</li> <li>[ ] Baguette \u2014 for rouille croutons (Sat bouillabaisse)</li> <li>[ ] Corn tortillas \u2014 2 packs (Tue fish tacos)</li> <li>[ ] Rice \u2014 jasmine and/or white (multiple days)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html","title":"Weeks 25\u201326: Shellfish","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 23\u201324: Fish | Weeks 27\u201328: Charcuterie &amp; Curing \u2192</p> <p>\"Shellfish are the ocean's most generous gift \u2014 clams that open in minutes, scallops that take eight minutes total, shrimp that go from raw to overcooked in the span of a distracted text message. Shellfish teach the hardest lesson: restraint.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#week-23-bivalves-crustaceans-the-pure-flavor-approach","title":"Week 23 \u2014 Bivalves &amp; Crustaceans: The Pure Flavor Approach","text":"<p>You've cooked through poultry, beef, pork, and finfish. Now comes shellfish week \u2014 the category where the main job is not screwing it up. Clams and mussels are seasoning themselves with their own liquor. Scallops want nothing more than a hot pan and a hard sear. Your restraint and heat management are the only variables that matter.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#monday-spaghetti-alle-vongole-clams-white-wine","title":"Monday \u2014 Spaghetti alle Vongole (Clams + White Wine)","text":"<p>Skill: Clam selection, purging sand, building a brothy pasta sauce from shellfish liquor Read first: Spaghetti alle Vongole</p> <p>What you're learning: How to coax a restaurant-quality pasta sauce from two dozen little clams, a splash of wine, olive oil, and garlic \u2014 and why the pasta goes into the pan before it's fully cooked.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Spaghetti alle Vongole - Crusty bread for the broth at the bottom of the bowl</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Pasta alle Vongole \u2014 Watch when he adds the pasta to the clam pan \u2014 the starchy pasta water is the sauce, not an afterthought.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#tuesday-moules-mariniere-mussels-french-style","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Moules Marini\u00e8re (Mussels, French Style)","text":"<p>Skill: Sourcing and cleaning mussels; building \"broth in a pot\" cooking technique Read first: The Best Moules Marini\u00e8re</p> <p>What you're learning: Mussels give up their liquid as they open \u2014 that liquid is your sauce. The hard part is building aromatics beforehand and not overcooking once the mussels hit the heat. Open mussels = done.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Moules Marini\u00e8re - Frites (or good store-bought fries; this is mussels-and-fries night)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#wednesday-roasted-oysters-with-bacon-and-parmesan","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Roasted Oysters with Bacon and Parmesan","text":"<p>Skill: Buying and handling live oysters; dry heat cooking for bivalves Read first: Roasted Oysters with Bacon and Parmesan</p> <p>What you're learning: Raw oysters are a skill-and-taste vertical unto themselves. But roasted oysters are accessible, warm, and show you how heat changes shellfish character. No shucking experience required for this preparation \u2014 heat opens them.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Roasted Oysters (appetizer quantity \u2014 6\u201312) - Caesar salad or simple green salad for a full dinner</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Grill Oysters \u2014 The heat-opening approach is the same whether grilling or roasting \u2014 compare when he calls them done and why the timing matters for bivalves.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#thursday-rest-day","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":"<p>Reflect: You've now worked through clams, mussels, and oysters. What was the brininess difference? What happened to the mussels' texture if you left them a minute too long? Note it.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#friday-shrimp-scampi","title":"Friday \u2014 Shrimp Scampi","text":"<p>Skill: Quick-cooking crustaceans, building a pan sauce in under 5 minutes Read first: Shrimp Scampi</p> <p>What you're learning: Shrimp cook in 2 minutes total and keep cooking off the heat. The window between raw and rubbery is narrow. Scampi is a study in speed: garlic in oil, shrimp in, flip, wine in, butter swirled, done.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Shrimp Scampi over linguine - Simple green salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Gambas al Ajillo (Spanish Garlic Shrimp) (Helen Rennie) \u2014 Spanish garlic shrimp vs. Italian scampi: same speed, same garlic-and-fat logic, completely different flavor. Watch the oil temperature and how briefly the shrimp touch the heat.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#saturday-project-lobster-night","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Lobster Night","text":"<p>Skill: Cooking whole live lobster humanely and confidently; making a pan sauce or bisque from shells Read first: Stop Overcooking Lobster | Lobster Bisque</p> <p>Plan: Buy 2 lobsters (1.25\u20131.5 lb each). Cook one for immediate eating (broiled, steamed, or grilled). Save shells + any unused parts for a quick bisque or at minimum a shell oil/butter you can freeze.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Lobster, cooked your chosen method - Lobster bisque from shells (or shell butter to freeze) - Sides of your choice (drawn butter, lemon, herbs)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Prepare and Cook a Lobster (Jacques P\u00e9pin) \u2014 Watch how he dispatches and breaks it down with total confidence. The technique is as much about handling a live animal as it is about cooking \u2014 there's no video that teaches that instinct better.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#week-24-the-next-level-seared-scallops-already-happened-what-comes-after","title":"Week 24 \u2014 The Next Level: Seared Scallops Already Happened. What Comes After?","text":"<p>(Weeks 13\u201314 covered dry-packed seared scallops. This week extends into more complex shellfish territory \u2014 built dishes, larger preparations, and pairing shellfish with other proteins.)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#monday-chili-crab-singaporean","title":"Monday \u2014 Chili Crab (Singaporean)","text":"<p>Skill: Cooking blue crab or Dungeness crab; sweet-savory-spicy sauce building Read first: Singapore Chili Crab</p> <p>What you're learning: Chili crab is one of the great dishes of Singapore. The sauce (a slightly sweet, slightly spicy, egg-thickened tomato base) clings to the crab and eats like a main course. Messy and worth it.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Singaporean Chili Crab - Steamed white rice - Fried mantou buns or crusty bread for sauce dipping</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#tuesday-shrimp-bisque-shrimp-in-compound-butter","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Shrimp Bisque / Shrimp in Compound Butter","text":"<p>Skill: Transforming shrimp shells into flavorful stock; reading shrimp doneness Read first: Shrimp Scampi \u2014 Butter-Garlic Version</p> <p>What you're learning: Even shell-on shrimp carry flavor that transfers to fat. This session, peel the shrimp yourself (saving shells), then make a quick compound butter or simple shrimp stock that elevates any seafood dish later in the week.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Shrimp in compound butter over grits or polenta - Roasted cherry tomatoes</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#wednesday-clam-chowder-or-clam-corn-pasta","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Clam Chowder or Clam + Corn Pasta","text":"<p>Skill: Using canned clams confidently; chowder-building ratios Read first: New England Clam Chowder</p> <p>What you're learning: Canned clams are a legitimate pantry staple (SE says so). Build a clam chowder from scratch or pivot to a clam + corn + butter pasta that uses the same technique as vongole but heads in a different direction.</p> <p>Full Meal: - New England\u2013style clam chowder or clam-corn linguine - Oyster crackers or crusty bread</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Thicc Clam Chowder \u2014 Watch how he builds the potato-and-cream base before the clams go in \u2014 timing the clams last prevents the rubbery texture that ruins most chowder.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#thursday-rest-day_1","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":"<p>Reflect: Look back at your shellfish notes from both weeks. Which protein had the narrowest doneness window? Where did you mess up? What would you do differently with lobster next time?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#friday-mussels-in-tomato-saffron-broth","title":"Friday \u2014 Mussels in Tomato-Saffron Broth","text":"<p>Skill: Building a second mussel preparation with Mediterranean flavors vs. French Read first: Moules Marini\u00e8res (Sailor-Style Mussels) for the base technique \u2014 today you\u2019re swapping white wine and cream for saffron, tomato, and fennel. Same bivalve, different broth logic.</p> <p>What you're learning: Same bivalve, different flavor frame. Saffron + tomato + fennel gives mussels a completely different character than cream and white wine. This is your first \"what changes when I swap the broth?\" lesson applied to shellfish.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Mussels in Tomato-Saffron Broth - Grilled bread rubbed with garlic</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#saturday-project-multi-shellfish-plateau-cold-hot","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Multi-Shellfish Plateau (Cold &amp; Hot)","text":"<p>Skill: Sourcing, timing, and presenting multiple shellfish together Goal: Buy three types of shellfish. Serve some raw (or cured), some broiled, some in a sauce. This is a dinner-party-ready shellfish spread.</p> <p>Plan:  - Raw oysters or ceviche-style clams (cold) - Roasted oysters or mussels (hot) - Scallops or shrimp (quick-seared at the end) - Lemon, mignonette, aioli on the side</p> <p>Full Meal: - Three-shellfish plateau with accompaniments - Crusty baguette, green salad, white wine</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#sourcing-and-handling-shellfish","title":"Sourcing and Handling Shellfish","text":"<p>Live shellfish is the most time-sensitive ingredient in the kitchen. Knowing how to select, store, and clean it before you cook it is the bulk of the skill.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Clean and Debeard Mussels \u2014 The step-by-step process for mussels: pulling the beard, testing for live ones, and storing properly before cooking. The same inspection logic applies to clams and oysters.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 A Comprehensive Guide to Buying Better Shrimp \u2014 What the labels actually mean, when fresh versus frozen matters, and how to read shrimp quality at the counter. The sourcing principles carry across all shellfish.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#the-scallop-sear","title":"The Scallop Sear","text":"<p>A properly seared scallop has a deep, dry crust on each flat side and remains translucent at the center. Getting there requires a very specific sequence.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Right Way to Use a Meat Thermometer \u2014 Scallops at 115\u2013125\u00b0F interior are perfect. Above 130\u00b0F they become rubbery. Temperature matters more for scallops than almost any other protein.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Scallop sear technique \u2014 The dry-pat, hot pan, single flip, no-fuss method explained step by step.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Oyster shucking \u2014 Watch before you try. The knife angle and the location of the hinge are the whole skill.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Joy of Cooking by Irma Rombauer \u2014 The shellfish chapter remains one of the most comprehensive references for home cooks. Every preparation covered, without unnecessary complexity.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Weeks 23\u201324: Fish | Weeks 27\u201328: Charcuterie &amp; Curing \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Weeks 25\u201326: Shellfish","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/quick-ref.html#week-23-bivalves-crustaceans","title":"Week 23 \u2014 Bivalves &amp; Crustaceans","text":"Day Dish Technique Key Temp / Timing Mon Spaghetti alle Vongole Steam-open in wine Open = done; ~5 min Tue Moules Marini\u00e8re Steam open in aromatics Open = done; 4\u20136 min Wed Roasted Oysters w/ Bacon Dry heat oven roast 450\u00b0F until open; 8\u201310 min Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Shrimp Scampi Fast saut\u00e9 + butter pan sauce Shrimp: 1\u20132 min/side; pull early Sat PROJECT: Lobster Night Broil / steam + shell bisque Internal 140\u00b0F; rest before serving"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/quick-ref.html#week-24-complex-shellfish","title":"Week 24 \u2014 Complex Shellfish","text":"Day Dish Technique Notes Mon Singaporean Chili Crab Stir-fry crab in sauce Pre-crack shell before cooking Tue Shrimp in Compound Butter Quick saut\u00e9, shell stock Make compound butter for freezer Wed Clam Chowder or Clam-Corn Pasta Simmer / pasta Canned clams fine for chowder Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Mussels in Tomato-Saffron Steam open in broth Same technique as Week 23 Tue Sat PROJECT: Shellfish Plateau Multi-prep, raw + roasted + seared Time: cold first, hot served last"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/quick-ref.html#key-shellfish-doneness-notes","title":"Key Shellfish Doneness Notes","text":"Shellfish When It's Done Danger Sign Clams Shell opens Still closed after 8 min \u2192 discard Mussels Shell opens Still closed after 6 min \u2192 discard Oysters (roasted) Shell opens, meat barely firms Curled/shrunken = overcooked Shrimp Pink and curled into loose C shape Tight O shape = overcooked Scallops 120\u2013125\u00b0F internal Rubbery = overcooked Lobster 140\u00b0F tail meat Dry/stringy = overcooked"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/quick-ref.html#key-shellfish-sourcing-notes","title":"Key Shellfish Sourcing Notes","text":"<ul> <li>Bivalves: Buy live, shells tightly closed; tap any open ones \u2014 they should close</li> <li>Shrimp: \"Fresh\" shrimp at grocery stores is usually frozen-thawed; frozen wild-caught is fine</li> <li>Lobster: Buy day of cook from a store with a live tank; avoid if tank smells off</li> <li>Crab: Ask fishmonger for live or freshly cooked; frozen legs are a valid option for chili crab</li> <li>Scallops: Dry-packed only (see Weeks 13\u201314 for full technique)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 25\u201326: Shellfish","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Shellfish mantra: Buy it alive, cook it the day you buy it, and don't overthink anything.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Large Dutch oven or pot \u2014 for mussels, clams, and bisque</li> <li>[ ] Tongs + spider strainer \u2014 for pulling shellfish out of liquid</li> <li>[ ] Instant-read thermometer \u2014 lobster tail target: 140\u00b0F</li> <li>[ ] Sharp kitchen scissors \u2014 for lobster shell if broiling</li> <li>[ ] Shellfish brush \u2014 for scrubbing mussels/clams</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-23","title":"\ud83e\udd9e Proteins \u2014 Week 23","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Manila or littleneck clams \u2014 2\u20133 dozen (Mon vongole)</li> <li>[ ] Mussels \u2014 2 lbs (Tue moules marini\u00e8re)</li> <li>[ ] Live oysters \u2014 12 (Wed roasted)</li> <li>[ ] Shrimp \u2014 1 lb, 16\u201320 count, peeled or shell-on (Fri scampi)</li> <li>[ ] Live lobsters \u2014 2 \u00d7 1.25\u20131.5 lb (Sat project)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-24","title":"\ud83e\udd9e Proteins \u2014 Week 24","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Blue crab or Dungeness crab \u2014 2 lbs (Mon chili crab); or frozen crab legs</li> <li>[ ] Shrimp \u2014 1 lb, shell-on (Tue compound butter; save shells for stock)</li> <li>[ ] Canned clams \u2014 3 \u00d7 6.5-oz cans (Wed chowder or clam pasta)</li> <li>[ ] Mussels \u2014 2 lbs (Fri tomato-saffron)</li> <li>[ ] Shellfish for plateau \u2014 oysters (6), scallops (4 dry-packed), shrimp (\u00bd lb) (Sat)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 3 heads (used every day)</li> <li>[ ] Shallots \u2014 4</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 8</li> <li>[ ] Fennel \u2014 2 bulbs (Fri tomato-saffron broth + bisque aromatics)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 1 pint (Tue Week 24)</li> <li>[ ] Canned San Marzano tomatoes \u2014 1 can (Fri Week 24)</li> <li>[ ] Potatoes \u2014 1 lb (chowder Week 24 Wed)</li> <li>[ ] Celery \u2014 4 stalks (chowder aromatics)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 1 cup (Wed chowder)</li> <li>[ ] Corn \u2014 2 ears or 1 cup frozen (if doing clam-corn pasta instead)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dry white wine \u2014 1 bottle (used Mon, Tue, and for bisque)</li> <li>[ ] Vermouth \u2014 can substitute for white wine in bisque</li> <li>[ ] Olive oil \u2014 extra-virgin</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 \u00bd lb</li> <li>[ ] Spaghetti or linguine \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Saffron \u2014 pinch (Fri Week 24)</li> <li>[ ] Crushed red pepper flakes</li> <li>[ ] Oyster crackers or crusty baguette (Wed Week 24 chowder)</li> <li>[ ] Baguette \u2014 for both weeks (bread with broth is mandatory)</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce or Worcestershire \u2014 small amount for bisque depth</li> <li>[ ] Sriracha and ketchup \u2014 for chili crab sauce (Mon Week 24)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 2 (chili crab sauce is egg-thickened)</li> <li>[ ] Jasmine rice \u2014 for Mon Week 24 (chili crab)</li> <li>[ ] Cornichons, shallot vinegar \u2014 for oyster mignonette (Sat Week 24)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html","title":"Weeks 27\u201328: Charcuterie &amp; Curing","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 25\u201326: Shellfish | Weeks 29\u201330: French Classics \u2192</p> <p>\"Charcuterie is patience made edible. A piece of pork belly cured for five days, rinsed, dried, and sliced \u2014 that's the result of standing in a kitchen for twenty minutes spread across a week. The time is doing all the work. Your job is to not rush it.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#week-25-curing-salt-time-and-transformation","title":"Week 25 \u2014 Curing: Salt, Time, and Transformation","text":"<p>Salt curing is the oldest form of preservation in human civilization, and it's also one of the most revelatory cooking methods you'll encounter. This week you'll cure fish, grind your first sausage (or learn to), and understand how salt changes protein texture in ways heat cannot.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#monday-gravlax-cured-salmon","title":"Monday \u2014 Gravlax (Cured Salmon)","text":"<p>Skill: Dry cure ratios, curing time, slicing technique Read first: Gravlax \u2014 Cured Salmon</p> <p>What you're learning: Gravlax is cured salmon \u2014 no heat involved. A 2:1 salt-to-sugar ratio by weight, plus dill, applied to fresh salmon for 48\u201372 hours. The salt draws out moisture, firms the texture, and intensifies flavor. The result eats like the best smoked salmon you've ever had, made at home for a fraction of the cost.</p> <p>Note: Start the cure tonight (Monday). It will be ready to slice and eat by Wednesday or Thursday.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Begin gravlax cure \u2014 no dinner from this tonight - Quick seared salmon for Monday dinner (side benefit: perfect salmon to compare against cured version later)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#tuesday-sausage-making-fundamentals","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Sausage Making Fundamentals","text":"<p>Skill: Sausage stuffing, emulsification, seasoning, casing handling Read first: Homemade Merguez Sausage</p> <p>What you're learning: Sausage is ground and seasoned meat, packed into casings. The fat content matters (25\u201330% for juicy links). Temperature control during grinding matters (keep everything cold \u2014 fat smearing is the enemy). Spice blooming matters. This is your first step into charcuterie production.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pan-fried merguez with roasted peppers and couscous - Yogurt sauce and harissa on the side</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: 8 Rules for Sausages \u2014 The fat temperature and emulsification rules apply to merguez even if the spice profile is different \u2014 pay attention to rule #1 and #3.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#wednesday-taste-the-gravlax-cured-charcuterie-board","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Taste the Gravlax / Cured Charcuterie Board","text":"<p>Skill: Slicing cured fish, building a charcuterie spread Read first: Best Charcuterie Boards</p> <p>What you're learning: Today you slice your gravlax (if it went in Monday) and taste the result alongside store-bought cured products \u2014 prosciutto, salami, coppa. The comparison trains your palate on what curing does to flavor and texture.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Charcuterie board: your gravlax + store-bought cured meats, mustard, cornichons, bread - Small green salad</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#thursday-rest-day","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":"<p>Reflect: What surprised you about the gravlax? How does chemically \"cooked\" salmon differ from heat-cooked salmon? Write a note about next time \u2014 would you adjust the salt, sugar, or time?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#friday-quick-pickles-lacto-fermented-vegetables","title":"Friday \u2014 Quick Pickles &amp; Lacto-Fermented Vegetables","text":"<p>Skill: Quick-pickle acid ratios; understanding fermentation vs. pickling Read first: Quick-Pickled Onions</p> <p>What you're learning: Quick pickles aren't fermentation \u2014 they're acid baths (vinegar-based). But the result is similar: preserved, tangy, crunchy vegetables that transform simple dishes. This session make pickled red onions + one other vegetable (cucumbers, jalape\u00f1os, or carrots). These become your charcuterie board companions all weekend.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Sausage and pickled pepper sandwiches (use leftover merguez or store-bought sausage) - Quick pickles from today's session on the side</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Kosher Dill Pickles \u2014 His brine ratio and timing explain the chemistry behind quick pickles vs. fermentation \u2014 the acid vs. salt distinction changes everything about how long they keep.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#saturday-project-full-charcuterie-spread-potted-rillettes","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Full Charcuterie Spread + Potted Rillettes","text":"<p>Skill: Making rillettes (pork potted in its own fat); assembling a composed spread Goal: Cook a rillette-style spread using pork shoulder or duck (slow cook in fat, shred, pot in fat with seasoning). This is beginner charcuterie production. Plus, compose a full charcuterie spread featuring the week's cured products.</p> <p>Reference: Pork Rillettes \u2014 season generously, cook low and slow in fat (300\u00b0F / 3\u20134 hours), shred while warm, mix with rendered fat, pot and chill.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pork rillettes on toasted baguette - Full charcuterie spread: rillettes, gravlax, merguez, pickles, board accompaniments - Wine and bread \u2014 this is a meal celebration</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#week-26-applying-curing-techniques-program-midpoint-check-in","title":"Week 26 \u2014 Applying Curing Techniques + Program Midpoint Check-In","text":"<p>(This is the program's six-month mark. Half the year done. Use this week both to cook and to reflect.)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#monday-pancetta-style-cured-belly-start-the-project","title":"Monday \u2014 Pancetta-Style Cured Belly (Start the Project)","text":"<p>Skill: Multi-day salt cure on pork belly; understanding cure penetration and timing Read first: Reference duck confit and gravlax techniques already covered</p> <p>What you're learning: Pork belly rubbed with salt, black pepper, and aromatics and left to cure in the fridge for 5\u20137 days becomes a homemade pancetta (unsmoked). You won't be able to eat it until next week, but this is how you start to think in longer cooking time scales.</p> <p>Tonight: Apply cure to pork belly. Label with date. Refrigerate uncovered or wrapped loosely.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pasta carbonara using store-bought pancetta while yours cures (perfect comparison for next week)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Sous Chef Erik's Pancetta Class, Part One \u2014 Watch the cure application and the fridge setup \u2014 uncovered and elevated is not optional, it's how the surface dries for proper curing.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#tuesday-duck-or-chicken-rillettes","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Duck or Chicken Rillettes","text":"<p>Skill: Confiting poultry; rillettes texture and fat ratio Read first: Reference classic duck confit technique from Week 14</p> <p>What you're learning: Chicken thighs confited in duck fat (or vegetable oil), then shredded and packed in their own fat, become rillettes. Lighter than pork rillettes, equally rich. This builds on the poultry confiting technique from Week 14.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Chicken rillettes on toast - Simple pickled vegetable salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Chicken Jardini\u00e8re (Jacques P\u00e9pin) \u2014 P\u00e9pin shows poultry cooked low-and-slow in fat and aromatics \u2014 the same principle your rillette is built on. Watch how he reads texture rather than temperature.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#wednesday-module-3-capstone-six-month-inventory","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Module 3 Capstone: Six-Month Inventory","text":"<p>Note: This is a reflective cook day \u2014 pick one dish from weeks 1\u201325 that you want to redo.</p> <p>Choose ONE technique that didn't go as planned in the past six months. Cook it again. Measure how different the result is now versus the first time. This is the most important practical exercise in the program.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#thursday-rest-day_1","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":"<p>Write down: What are the three best things you cooked in the first 25 weeks? What's still unresolved? Set three specific goals for the second half of the year.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#friday-bacon-cured-salmon-breakfast-board","title":"Friday \u2014 Bacon-Cured Salmon Breakfast Board","text":"<p>Skill: Applying cure variations; building breakfast charcuterie Read first: Reference gravlax technique from Week 25</p> <p>What you're learning: Make a light variant of gravlax using a bit of brown sugar and cracked pepper instead of white sugar and dill. The result is a \"candied salmon\" cure. Serve on bagels or rye toast with cream cheese, cucumber, capers, and red onion.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Cured salmon breakfast board (brunch-style dinner \u2014 allowable) - Sliced tomatoes, cream cheese, everything bagel spice, capers, pickled onion</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#saturday-project-complete-cured-meat-tasting-pancetta-check-in","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Complete Cured Meat Tasting + Pancetta Check-In","text":"<p>Skill: Evaluating sourced cured meats; understanding regional charcuterie differences Goal: Visit a deli or specialty market and buy 5 different cured meats: one prosciutto, one salami, one coppa or speck, one regional specialty, one p\u00e2t\u00e9 or rillette. Taste critically \u2014 fat content, salt, spice blends, texture. Your pancetta is curing in the fridge \u2192 not done yet, but check it.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Curated cured meat tasting board with accompaniments - Crusty bread, mustards, cornichons, honey, fresh and dried fruits - The pancetta is now 5\u20136 days in \u2014 slice off one thin strip and taste (it's edible, just not fully penetrated yet)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Pasta alla Carbonara: 3 Ricette (Italia Squisita) \u2014 Three Michelin-starred chefs debate guanciale vs. pancetta vs. nothing else \u2014 the cured pork you've been making is the ingredient they fight over. Listen to the arguments.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#the-chemistry-of-curing","title":"The Chemistry of Curing","text":"<p>Salt draws out moisture, creates an inhospitable environment for bacteria, and transforms texture over days or weeks. Understanding the mechanism takes the mystery out of recipes that ask you to wait.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Italian Cured Meats: Salumi Guide \u2014 The full vocabulary of Italian charcuterie: prosciutto, salami, guanciale, mortadella, and everything in between.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Prosciutto di Parma: The Long Road \u2014 A longform piece on what actually goes into making the world's most famous ham. Puts your pancetta project in context.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#gravlax-salt-sugar-and-time","title":"Gravlax: Salt, Sugar, and Time","text":"<p>Gravlax is the cleanest introduction to curing \u2014 no smoking, no casings, no specialized equipment. Salt, sugar, dill, and a weight. The endpoint speaks for itself.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Bacon, Pancetta, and More: Cured Pork Products Explained \u2014 The overlapping chemistry between fish curing and pork curing, laid out clearly.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa How sausage is made \u2014 The mechanical steps of grinding, emulsifying fat, and stuffing casings are easiest to understand visually.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Charcuterie: The Craft of Salting, Smoking, and Curing by Michael Ruhlman &amp; Brian Polcyn \u2014 The foundational English-language charcuterie text. Covers every technique you did this week (and the next ten years of possible projects).</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Weeks 25\u201326: Shellfish | Weeks 29\u201330: French Classics \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Weeks 27\u201328: Charcuterie &amp; Curing","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/quick-ref.html#week-25-curing-fundamentals","title":"Week 25 \u2014 Curing Fundamentals","text":"Day Project Method Timing Mon Gravlax cure (start) Dry cure (salt + sugar + dill) Cure 48\u201372 hrs; taste Wed\u2013Thu Tue Merguez sausage Grind + season + stuff Cook same day Wed Taste gravlax + charcuterie board Slice cured fish; compose spread Slice thin, on bias Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Quick pickles Vinegar brine Ready in 1\u20132 hours; keeps 2 weeks Sat PROJECT: Pork rillettes + spread Slow confit + shred + pot in fat 3\u20134 hrs active; chill 2+ hrs before serving"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/quick-ref.html#week-26-applied-curing-six-month-review","title":"Week 26 \u2014 Applied Curing + Six-Month Review","text":"Day Project Method Timing Mon Pancetta cure (start) Dry cure on pork belly Cure 5\u20137 days (back in Week 27) Tue Duck/Chicken rillettes Confit + shred 2 hrs total Wed Midpoint Redo Pick one dish; cook it again Reflective cook Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Brown-sugar cured salmon (candied) Variant gravlax cure Cure 24\u201336 hrs; start Thu night Sat PROJECT: Cured meat tasting + pancetta check Sourced + produced comparison Buy 5+ types; taste critically"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/quick-ref.html#key-curing-ratios","title":"Key Curing Ratios","text":"Cure Type Salt Sugar Time Notes Gravlax (standard) 2 parts 1 part 48\u201372 hrs Dill, white pepper Candied salmon 1 part 1 part 24\u201336 hrs Brown sugar, black pepper Pancetta / dry cure ~2.5% of meat weight Small amount 5\u20137 days Black pepper, aromatics Quick pickle brine 1:1 water/vinegar 1 tbsp per cup 1\u20132 hrs Salt, spice to taste"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/quick-ref.html#key-sausage-notes","title":"Key Sausage Notes","text":"<ul> <li>Fat content: 25\u201330% for juicy sausage; less \u2192 dry</li> <li>Keep everything cold: meat, grinder parts, bowl</li> <li>Test cook a small patty before stuffing \u2014 adjust seasoning before casings</li> <li>Sheep casings (for merguez) available at good butchers or online</li> <li>No casings? Form as patties or loose ground</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 27\u201328: Charcuterie &amp; Curing","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Plan ahead: Monday of Week 25, you start a 48\u201372 hour gravlax cure. Monday of Week 26, you start a 5\u20137 day pancetta cure. There's always something in the fridge transforming.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Meat grinder or food processor \u2014 for sausage; KitchenAid grinder attachment is fine</li> <li>[ ] Sausage stuffer or piping bag \u2014 for stuffing casings; skip casings for patties</li> <li>[ ] Sheet pan + wire rack \u2014 for curing and airing</li> <li>[ ] Scale \u2014 cure ratios must be by weight, not volume</li> <li>[ ] Czech or glass container with lid \u2014 for gravlax cure</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-25","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 25","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Salmon fillet, skin-on, center-cut \u2014 1\u20131.5 lbs (Mon gravlax cure)</li> <li>[ ] Ground lamb or lamb shoulder \u2014 1 lb (Tue merguez; grind your own if possible)</li> <li>[ ] Pork shoulder \u2014 2 lbs (Sat rillettes \u2014 slow confit)</li> <li>[ ] Duck fat \u2014 1 lb jar (Sat rillettes; lard works too)</li> </ul> <p>For charcuterie board (Wed): - [ ] Prosciutto, salami, coppa \u2014 varied deli assortment - [ ] P\u00e2t\u00e9 or store-bought rillette</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-26","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 26","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Pork belly \u2014 1.5 lbs (Mon pancetta cure \u2014 won't eat until Week 27)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken thighs \u2014 4 bone-in or duck legs \u00d7 2 (Tue rillettes)</li> <li>[ ] Store-bought pancetta \u2014 for Mon pasta carbonara comparison</li> </ul> <p>For cured meat tasting (Sat): - [ ] 5 different cured meats from deli/specialty market \u2014 prosciutto, salami, coppa or speck, regional specialty, p\u00e2t\u00e9</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/shopping-list.html#spices-cure-ingredients","title":"\ud83c\udf3f Spices &amp; Cure Ingredients","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Diamond Crystal Kosher salt \u2014 large box (all curing uses by weight)</li> <li>[ ] Granulated sugar (gravlax) and brown sugar (candied salmon)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh dill \u2014 1 large bunch (Mon gravlax)</li> <li>[ ] Whole black peppercorns (cure + merguez)</li> <li>[ ] Cumin, coriander, smoked paprika, cayenne \u2014 for merguez</li> <li>[ ] Harissa \u2014 small jar (Tue merguez meal)</li> <li>[ ] Bay leaves \u2014 dried (pancetta cure)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh thyme \u2014 1 bunch (pancetta cure + rillettes)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Red onions \u2014 4 (quick pickles Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumbers \u2014 3 (pickles)</li> <li>[ ] Jalape\u00f1os \u2014 4 (optional pickles)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 4</li> <li>[ ] Shallots \u2014 4</li> </ul> <p>Board accompaniments (Wed + Sat): - [ ] Cornichons \u2014 1 jar - [ ] Whole-grain mustard - [ ] Honey \u2014 small jar - [ ] Grapes or dried cherries - [ ] Marcona almonds</p>"},{"location":"weeks/03-the-proteins/27-28-charcuterie-review/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] White wine vinegar (quick pickles + brine)</li> <li>[ ] Apple cider vinegar</li> <li>[ ] Baguette \u2014 multiple (boards; buy fresh each time)</li> <li>[ ] Rye bread or pumpernickel (Fri cured salmon board)</li> <li>[ ] Cream cheese (Fri cured salmon)</li> <li>[ ] Capers (Fri and boards)</li> <li>[ ] Couscous (Tue merguez dinner)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 6 (Mon Week 26 carbonara; various)</li> <li>[ ] Pecorino Romano + Parmesan (carbonara Mon Week 26)</li> <li>[ ] Spaghetti \u2014 1 lb (Mon Week 26 carbonara)</li> <li>[ ] Sheep casings \u2014 optional; order online (Tue sausage)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/index.html","title":"Module 4: The World's Kitchens (Weeks 29\u201344)","text":"<p>The goal of this module: Take every technique you've built and apply it through seven distinct culinary traditions. Each two-week immersion goes beyond recipes \u2014 you'll study the flavor logic, pantry structure, and cultural context that makes each cuisine a coherent system.</p> <p>By the end of Week 40, you should be able to cook with the grammar of seven world cuisines, not just their recipes.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/index.html#weeks-in-this-module","title":"Weeks in This Module","text":"Weeks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 29\u201330 French Classics \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 31\u201332 Italian \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 33\u201334 Japanese \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 35\u201336 Chinese Cuisine \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 37\u201338 Mexican \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 39\u201340 Indian \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 41\u201342 Middle Eastern \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 43\u201344 Module 4 Capstone: Southeast Asian Cuisines \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/index.html#core-skills-covered","title":"Core Skills Covered","text":"<ul> <li>French \u2014 classical brigade technique; beurre blanc, roux-based soups, coq au vin, tarte Tatin, proper knife work in a French context</li> <li>Italian \u2014 handmade pasta shapes beyond tagliatelle; risotto and polenta deep-dives; soffritto; regional sauce logic</li> <li>Japanese \u2014 dashi and umami layering; tamagoyaki; ramen broth; tempura batter; the philosophy of restraint; knife care (Japanese knives)</li> <li>Chinese \u2014 wok hei and high-heat stir-fry; velveting proteins; red-braising (hong shao); Cantonese steaming; Sichuan flavor logic; congee</li> <li>Mexican \u2014 dried chili taxonomy and toasting; masa and tortilla press; mole foundations; tamales; acid balance with lime</li> <li>Indian \u2014 whole spice blooming; wet and dry masalas; dal technique; tandoor-style high-heat cooking; yogurt-based marinades</li> <li>Middle Eastern \u2014 mezze construction; labneh and dairy ferments; sumac and pomegranate molasses as finishing acids; slow-roasted lamb</li> <li>Southeast Asian \u2014 wok technique (high heat, short time); curry paste from scratch; fish sauce as seasoning backbone; larb and acid-balance</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/index.html#equipment-youll-need","title":"Equipment You'll Need","text":"<p>See the Kitchen Equipment Guide. New items introduced in this module:</p> Item Introduced Tamagoyaki pan Week 33 Wok (14 inch carbon steel) Week 33 Bamboo skewers Week 33 Fine-mesh strainer Week 33 Rice cooker (optional) Week 35 Steamer / bamboo steamer Week 35 Tortilla press Week 37 Comal or flat cast iron griddle Week 37 High-powered blender Week 37 Steamer / tamale pot Week 37 Mortar and pestle Week 43 Pressure cooker / Instant Pot Week 43 <p>Previous module: Module 3 \u2014 The Proteins (Weeks 17\u201328) Next module: Module 5 \u2014 Mastery &amp; Pastry (Weeks 45\u201356)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html","title":"Weeks 29\u201330: French Classics","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 27\u201328: Charcuterie &amp; Curing | Weeks 31\u201332: Italian \u2192</p> <p>\"French cuisine is not a style or a national preference \u2014 it's a grammar. Learn it and you understand the logic underneath every b\u00e9arnaise, every braise, every reduction. Every other cuisine becomes more readable once you can parse the French sentence.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#week-27-the-sauces-hollandaise-bearnaise-and-the-french-mother-sauces","title":"Week 27 \u2014 The Sauces: Hollandaise, B\u00e9arnaise, and the French Mother Sauces","text":"<p>French cooking week means sauce week. No other cuisine has built such a systematic framework around sauce-making \u2014 not just for tradition's sake, but because the system works. This week you'll tackle the two emulsified egg yolk sauces (hollandaise and b\u00e9arnaise), build a proper French onion soup, and finish with a cassoulet that will take most of Saturday.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#monday-french-onion-soup","title":"Monday \u2014 French Onion Soup","text":"<p>Skill: Low-and-slow caramelized onion technique; proper gratin\u00e9e finish Read first: French Onion Soup</p> <p>What you're learning: Real caramelized onions take 45\u201360 minutes. Not 10, not 20. Any recipe that says \"caramelize in 10 minutes\" is lying. Today is a patience lesson: low-medium heat, stirring every 5 minutes, watching sugar develop \u2014 and then building the soup around that deep onion sweetness.</p> <p>Full Meal: - French Onion Soup, properly gratin\u00e9ed with Gruy\u00e8re and a crouton - Simple green salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: This Video Will Change How You Think About Onions (Ethan Chlebowski) \u2014 The 45-minute caramelization time is the whole argument. Watch him document the color and smell at each interval \u2014 that's the evidence your patience is justified.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#tuesday-hollandaise-and-eggs-benedict","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Hollandaise and Eggs Benedict","text":"<p>Skill: Emulsified egg-yolk sauce; gentle double-boiler heat control Read first: Foolproof 2-Minute Hollandaise</p> <p>What you're learning: Hollandaise is an emulsion of egg yolks, clarified butter, and lemon juice. It breaks when it gets too hot (scrambled eggs) or too cold (butter solidifies). SE's blender hollandaise method removes most of the anxiety. Then: poached eggs, Canadian bacon, toasted English muffin. The full build.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Eggs Benedict with blender hollandaise - Simple roasted potatoes or hash browns</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Eggs Benedict for a Crowd \u2014 Watch how he poaches eggs in batches and holds them in water \u2014 the hollandaise staying warm while eggs wait is the real challenge of the dish.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#wednesday-bearnaise-sauce-with-steak","title":"Wednesday \u2014 B\u00e9arnaise Sauce with Steak","text":"<p>Skill: B\u00e9arnaise (hollandaise with tarragon vinegar reduction); pan-seared steak application Read first: Foolproof B\u00e9arnaise</p> <p>What you're learning: B\u00e9arnaise = hollandaise with a tarragon-and-shallot reduction swapped for plain lemon. The technique is the same; the flavor completely different. Serve over a reverse-seared or pan-seared steak (you now know how to do this from Weeks 17\u201318). The sauce elevates a simple steak into a restaurant dish.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pan seared strip or sirloin steak with B\u00e9arnaise sauce - Oven fries or saut\u00e9ed haricots verts</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#thursday-rest-day","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":"<p>Reflect: Compare Monday's soup (sugar extraction) vs. Tuesday's sauce (emulsification) vs. Wednesday's sauce (emulsification + acid reduction). Three different French techniques used in three days. Write a note on which felt most precarious.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#friday-steak-frites","title":"Friday \u2014 Steak Frites","text":"<p>Skill: The restaurant standard: perfect fries + properly cooked steak in parallel Read first: Steak Frites</p> <p>What you're learning: Steak frites is deceptively hard to execute at home at restaurant quality because it requires parallel timing: the fries can't sit, the steak needs rest time, and a pan sauce is nice but adds another layer of complexity. This is a timing and plate management exercise as much as a cooking one.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Steak frites: steak of your choice + twice-fried or oven fries - Simple Dijon vinaigrette salad alongside</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#saturday-project-cassoulet","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Cassoulet","text":"<p>Skill: Bean preparation; regional French braising (multi-component slow dish) Read first: Traditional French Cassoulet</p> <p>What you're learning: Cassoulet is the great peasant dish of southwestern France: confit duck, pork sausage, white beans, and a crust that forms and gets pushed down repeatedly. It's a multi-component dish requiring 4\u20136 hours on Saturday. The payoff is extraordinary. Start by noon.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Cassoulet (serves 4\u20136; freeze the rest) - Good country bread - Green salad dressed with walnut vinaigrette</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#week-28-duck-beurre-blanc-and-the-composed-plate","title":"Week 28 \u2014 Duck, Beurre Blanc, and the Composed Plate","text":""},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#monday-beurre-blanc-white-butter-sauce","title":"Monday \u2014 Beurre Blanc (White Butter Sauce)","text":"<p>Skill: Pure butter emulsion sauce; wine-and-shallot reduction base Read first: Beurre Blanc</p> <p>What you're learning: Beurre blanc is butter whisked into a reduced shallot-and-white-wine base, creating a light but rich sauce that coats fish and vegetables beautifully. Unlike hollandaise, no eggs involved \u2014 the emulsion is butter protein in an acidic liquid. It will break if overheated.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Beurre blanc over pan-seared halibut or salmon - Steamed asparagus as the vehicle for extra sauce</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#tuesday-duck-a-lorange","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Duck \u00e0 l'Orange","text":"<p>Skill: Roasting duck; building a bittersweet gastrique Read first: Duck \u00e0 l'Orange</p> <p>What you're learning: Duck \u00e0 l'orange is a French classic and a useful study in gastrique (sugar caramelized to amber + acid to stop it = sweet-sour syrup base). The duck must render properly \u2014 its fat layer needs time and heat \u2014 and the sauce has to balance sweet, sour, and savory without tipping too far in any direction.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Duck \u00e0 l'Orange with rendered skin - Braised red cabbage and potato gratin as sides</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#wednesday-souffle-cheese-or-chocolate","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Souffl\u00e9 (Cheese or Chocolate)","text":"<p>Skill: Whipped egg white foam structure; baking to serve immediately Read first: Savory Cheese Souffl\u00e9</p> <p>What you're learning: Souffl\u00e9s are not as hard as their reputation. What fails them is undermixed whites, overfolding, or an underprepared dish (unbuttered, no sugar/Parmesan coating). Make a cheese souffl\u00e9 tonight: it's impressive and straightforward with proper preparation.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Cheese souffl\u00e9 (Gruy\u00e8re + Parmesan) as main - Simple green salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Fast Cheese Souffl\u00e9 (Jacques P\u00e9pin) \u2014 His efficiency is the point: he makes this look like a weeknight dish. Understand which steps he collapses vs. which ones he refuses to rush.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#thursday-rest-day_1","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":"<p>Reflect: French week has covered: soup-based technique, two emulsified sauces, a gastrique, a butter sauce, slow bean braise, and egg foam structure. You've touched most of French technique's pillars. What surprised you?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#friday-french-bistro-dinner","title":"Friday \u2014 French Bistro Dinner","text":"<p>Skill: Multi-component French bistro execution; proper service timing Goal: Cook a complete three-course French bistro meal:</p> <ol> <li>Starter: Salad Lyonnaise (fris\u00e9e, lardons, poached egg, Dijon vinaigrette)</li> <li>Main: Pan-seared duck breast with cherry or red wine reduction</li> <li>Dessert: Chocolate mousse (made ahead \u2014 Chocolate Mousse)</li> </ol> <p>Full Meal: - Salad Lyonnaise \u2192 Duck Breast \u2192 Chocolate Mousse - French baguette throughout</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Jacques P\u00e9pin Makes His Famous Cr\u00eapes \u2014 Add cr\u00eapes Suzette or plain cr\u00eapes as an alternative dessert; watch the wrist movement and how little batter goes in the pan \u2014 bistro cooking done with zero fuss.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#saturday-project-le-grand-aioli-provence-style","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Le Grand Aioli (Provence-Style)","text":"<p>Skill: Making aioli from scratch (emulsified garlic mayo); Proven\u00e7al composed platter Goal: Grand aioli is one of Provence's great communal dishes: a massive creamy garlic sauce served alongside a platter of vegetables (blanched and raw), salt cod, and hard-boiled eggs. Everything on the table, aioli in the center.</p> <p>Reference: Aioli technique = mayonnaise technique (from Weeks 9\u201310) with garlic and olive oil. The principle you already know \u2014 the application is new.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Le Grand Aioli: scratch-made garlic aioli + blanched vegetables + hard-boiled eggs + bread + whatever protein you choose - White wine from Provence if possible</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Old-Fashioned Handmade Aioli is Perfect for Spring Asparagus \u2014 Watch the mortar and pestle technique and compare it to your blender version \u2014 the texture and flavor absorption are genuinely different.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#classical-french-sauce-logic","title":"Classical French Sauce Logic","text":"<p>French cuisine is a system. Understanding where hollandaise sits in the sauce family \u2014 warm emulsion, egg-yolk-stabilized, related to b\u00e9arnaise by a flavor swap \u2014 shows how the system works.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Foolproof 2-Minute Hollandaise \u2014 The technique breakdown from SE, explaining why the blender method is actually more stable than the double-boiler version.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Guide to Cooking With Wine \u2014 Reduction sauces are at the heart of French bistro cooking. This is the wine guide that covers the how and why.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#aioli-and-emulsion-science","title":"Aioli and Emulsion Science","text":"<p>Aioli made with patience and good olive oil is nothing like the commercial version. It's also a direct relative of hollandaise \u2014 same emulsion principle, different fat.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Two-Minute Aioli \u2014 Kenji's immersion blender method makes the emulsification nearly foolproof. Understanding why it works \u2014 and what causes it to break \u2014 is the more important lesson than the recipe itself.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Cassoulet technique \u2014 The build order of cassoulet \u2014 confit, sausage, beans, breadcrumb crust \u2014 is visual. Look before you cook.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Jacques P\u00e9pin: New Complete Techniques \u2014 The definitive classical French kitchen reference. Every sauce, every cut, every technique. If you're going deep into French cooking, this is the shelf book.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Weeks 27\u201328: Charcuterie &amp; Curing | Weeks 31\u201332: Italian \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Weeks 29\u201330: French Classics","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/quick-ref.html#week-27-sauces-braises","title":"Week 27 \u2014 Sauces &amp; Braises","text":"Day Dish Technique Key Point Mon French Onion Soup Low-slow caramelized onions 45\u201360 mins for real caramelization Tue Eggs Benedict + Hollandaise Blender emulsified egg-yolk sauce 160\u00b0F danger zone \u2014 keep warm, not hot Wed B\u00e9arnaise + Steak Tarragon reduction + egg yolk emulsion Make reduction cold, whisk in butter warm Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Steak Frites Parallel timing: steak rest + fries Twice-fry for crispy frites Sat PROJECT: Cassoulet Multi-component bean braise, 4\u20136 hrs Break crust and push down 3\u20134 times"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/quick-ref.html#week-28-duck-butter-sauces-composed-plates","title":"Week 28 \u2014 Duck, Butter Sauces &amp; Composed Plates","text":"Day Dish Technique Key Point Mon Beurre Blanc + Seared Fish Cold-butter emulsion into acid reduction Don't boil the beurre blanc \u2014 it will break Tue Duck \u00e0 l'Orange Gastrique + roasted duck Render fat slowly; sauce balance: not too sweet Wed Cheese Souffl\u00e9 B\u00e9chamel base + folded egg whites Stiff peaks; fold gently; serve immediately Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri French Bistro Dinner (3 courses) Multi-course timing + composition Do mousse ahead; mise en place everything Sat PROJECT: Le Grand Aioli Scratch aioli + composed vegetable platter Use room-temp eggs; add oil drop by drop first"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/quick-ref.html#key-french-sauce-reference","title":"Key French Sauce Reference","text":"Sauce Base Emulsifier Served With Hollandaise Clarified butter Egg yolks + lemon Eggs, asparagus, fish B\u00e9arnaise Clarified butter Egg yolks + tarragon reduction Steak, lamb Beurre Blanc Whole butter Shallot + white wine reduction Fish, scallops, vegetables Aioli Olive oil Egg yolk + garlic Vegetables, fish, bread Gastrique Sugar + acid n/a \u2014 syrup, not emulsion Duck, game, rich meats"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/quick-ref.html#cassoulet-component-timing-saturday","title":"Cassoulet Component Timing (Saturday)","text":"Component Cook Time Notes Soak white beans Overnight or quick-soak Cannellini or Great Northern Duck confit If not already made: 2 hrs Can use store-bought duck confit Toulouse sausage or garlic sausage 20 min Prick first Salt pork or pork belly 1 hr simmer Blanch first to remove excess salt Full cassoulet assembly 3\u20134 hrs oven Break crust 3\u20134\u00d7 during cooking"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 29\u201330: French Classics","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Plan ahead: Cassoulet (Saturday Week 27) requires dried whites beans soaked overnight. Duck confit (Tue Week 28) is better if started a day ahead. Plan accordingly.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Large Dutch oven / cocotte \u2014 essential for cassoulet</li> <li>[ ] Blender \u2014 for foolproof hollandaise (Tue Week 27)</li> <li>[ ] Souffl\u00e9 dish (6-cup) \u2014 for cheese souffl\u00e9 (Wed Week 28)</li> <li>[ ] Fine-mesh strainer \u2014 for sauces</li> <li>[ ] Heat-proof bowl \u2014 beurre blanc and b\u00e9arnaise work</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-27","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 27","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Duck confit \u2014 store-bought legs \u00d7 4 (Sat cassoulet; or make your own from Week 14 technique)</li> <li>[ ] Toulouse sausage or garlic sausage \u2014 1 lb (Sat cassoulet)</li> <li>[ ] Salt pork or pork belly \u2014 8 oz (Sat cassoulet)</li> <li>[ ] Steak \u2014 strip or sirloin \u00d7 2 (Wed b\u00e9arnaise + Fri frites)</li> <li>[ ] Canadian bacon \u2014 4 slices (Tue eggs benedict)</li> <li>[ ] Bacon lardons \u2014 4 oz (Fri bistro salad Week 28)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-28","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 28","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Halibut or salmon \u2014 2 fillets (Mon beurre blanc)</li> <li>[ ] Whole duck, 4\u20135 lb OR 2 duck breasts (Tue \u00e0 l'orange)</li> <li>[ ] Salt cod, if available \u2014 8 oz for grand aioli (Sat Week 28; optional \u2014 other protein works)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 2 dozen (hollandaise, poached eggs, souffl\u00e9, aioli, salad Lyonnaise)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/shopping-list.html#produce-week-27","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 27","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Onions \u2014 5 lbs (Mon French onion soup \u2014 ~3 lbs per pot)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 3 heads</li> <li>[ ] Shallots \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Fresh thyme \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Bay leaves</li> <li>[ ] Gruy\u00e8re cheese \u2014 6 oz (Mon gratin\u00e9e + Wed souffl\u00e9)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Dried cannellini or Great Northern beans \u2014 1 lb (Sat cassoulet \u2014 soak Fri night)</li> <li>[ ] Canned tomatoes \u2014 1 can (cassoulet)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/shopping-list.html#produce-week-28","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 28","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Oranges \u2014 4 (Tue duck \u00e0 l'orange: juice + zest)</li> <li>[ ] Asparagus \u2014 1 bunch (Mon beurre blanc)</li> <li>[ ] Fris\u00e9e lettuce \u2014 2 heads (Fri salad Lyonnaise)</li> <li>[ ] Assorted vegetables for grand aioli (Sat): carrots, green beans, radishes, cauliflower, beets, potatoes</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 1 additional head (aioli)</li> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 1 pint (Sat aioli platter)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh tarragon \u2014 1 bunch (b\u00e9arnaise + various)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/29-30-french/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Beef or chicken stock \u2014 2 quarts (onion soup)</li> <li>[ ] Cognac or brandy \u2014 small bottle (cassoulet + various)</li> <li>[ ] Dry white wine \u2014 2 bottles (beurre blanc, mussels, souffl\u00e9)</li> <li>[ ] Dry red wine \u2014 1 bottle (cassoulet)</li> <li>[ ] White wine vinegar (b\u00e9arnaise reduction)</li> <li>[ ] Dijon mustard \u2014 large jar (vinaigrettes + various)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 2 lbs (beurre blanc eats butter; hollandaise, souffl\u00e9)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 1 pint (souffl\u00e9 b\u00e9chamel + various)</li> <li>[ ] Parmesan \u2014 4 oz (souffl\u00e9)</li> <li>[ ] Baguette \u2014 multiple (souffl\u00e9 croutons, onion soup croutons, aioli platter)</li> <li>[ ] Olive oil \u2014 extra-virgin (aioli + dressings)</li> <li>[ ] Duck fat \u2014 small jar if making duck confit vs. buying</li> <li>[ ] Orange marmalade \u2014 small jar (\u00e0 l'orange backup if juice not enough) | Whole black peppercorns \u2014 for gastrique</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html","title":"Weeks 31\u201332: Italian","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 29\u201330: French Classics | Weeks 33\u201334: Japanese \u2192</p> <p>\"Italian cooking is the most forgiving cuisine that still demands respect. No one cares if your risotto isn't perfect \u2014 but they care deeply if you added cream. Italian cooking's rules are not about technique. They're about ingredients. Get the right ones, and the technique almost takes care of itself.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#week-29-risotto-osso-buco-and-the-art-of-italian-patience","title":"Week 29 \u2014 Risotto, Osso Buco, and the Art of Italian Patience","text":"<p>Italian classics this week: risotto (patience + stirring + understanding when it's done), osso buco (braised veal shanks that take the afternoon and reward you royally), and a proper cold-weather ribollita. These are not quick Italian dishes. These are the ones that define why Italian cuisine is foundational.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#monday-mushroom-risotto","title":"Monday \u2014 Mushroom Risotto","text":"<p>Skill: Ladle-by-ladle stock addition; risotto consistency (mantecatura); choosing the right rice Read first: Pressure Cooker Mushroom Risotto</p> <p>What you're learning: The SE version uses a pressure cooker for efficiency, but the lesson is the same: risotto requires Arborio or Carnaroli rice (short-grain, high starch), warm stock added in stages, and the final \"mantecatura\" \u2014 stirring in cold butter off heat until silky and slightly loose. Serve immediately; risotto kills itself waiting.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Mushroom Risotto (porcini + cremini, ideally) - Simple arugula salad with lemon and Parmesan</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Risotto \u2014 Two Chefs One Recipe (Italia Squisita) \u2014 Watch how two different chefs make the same dish diverge in texture and philosophy. The starch discussion alone changes how you hold your spoon at the mantecatura step.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#tuesday-minestrone-the-full-version","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Minestrone (The Full Version)","text":"<p>Skill: Building vegetable-forward Italian broth; proper pasta-in-soup timing Read first: The Best Minestrone Soup</p> <p>What you're learning: Minestrone is not a simple ingredient dump \u2014 the vegetables go in stages based on cook time. Parmesan rind in the pot adds depth. The pasta/beans/bread component depends on region. This version respects the soup's architecture.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Minestrone with Parmesan rind broth - Crusty bread, additional Parmesan on top</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Minestrone Soup \u2014 Watch how he stages the vegetables by cook time \u2014 the architecture of the soup is the lesson, not the ingredient list.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#wednesday-osso-buco-alla-milanese","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Osso Buco alla Milanese","text":"<p>Skill: Cross-cut veal shank braising; gremolata (the raw herb-lemon finish) Read first: Osso Buco \u2014 Italian Braised Veal Shanks</p> <p>What you're learning: Osso buco = \"bone with a hole.\" The marrow inside is the reward for patience. Brown the shanks aggressively (all sides), braise 2\u20133 hours until the bone loosens, finish with gremolata (parsley + lemon zest + garlic) added right before serving. The raw freshness of gremolata against the deep braise is the whole point.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Osso Buco alla Milanese - Saffron risotto alla Milanese (a simpler weeknight risotto)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Ossobuco alla Milanese (Italia Squisita) \u2014 The gremolata moment at the end is what separates this from any other braise \u2014 watch when exactly he adds it and why freshness on top of richness is the whole idea.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#thursday-rest-day","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":"<p>Reflect: Three big Italian dishes, three different timelines. Risotto: real-time attention. Minestrone: low supervision. Osso buco: long and unattended. Which style suits your schedule best? How do you plan a week's cooking to include all three types?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#friday-ribollita-tuscan-bean-bread-soup","title":"Friday \u2014 Ribollita (Tuscan Bean Bread Soup)","text":"<p>Skill: Tuscan \"re-boiled\" soup; building body with day-old bread Read first: Pressure Cooker Ribollita</p> <p>What you're learning: Ribollita (\"re-boiled\") is meant to be made, cooled, then reheated (the name is the instruction). Thick with cavolo nero, cannellini beans, and day-old bread that dissolves into the soup. If it isn't thick enough to hold a spoon upright, it needs more bread or more time.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Ribollita, ideally made a day ahead and reheated with good olive oil poured on top at the table - Nothing else needed</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#saturday-project-pan-roasted-whole-branzino-tiramisu","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Pan-Roasted Whole Branzino + Tiramisu","text":"<p>Skill: Herbed whole fish for the table; tiramisu assembly and setting time Read first: Pan-Roasted Whole Branzino | Best Tiramisu</p> <p>Make the tiramisu in the morning \u2014 it needs at least 4 hours refrigeration before serving.</p> <p>What you're learning: Branzino is a mild Mediterranean sea bass ideal for the pan-roast technique (high heat, fat side/skin side down, briefly into oven). The tiramisu lesson is about layering, coffee saturation of ladyfingers (brief dip, not soak), and allowing the mascarpone cream to set \u2014 no gelatin, just structure from time and egg.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pan-Roasted Whole Branzino with herbs and lemon - Simple Italian green salad - Tiramisu for dessert</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#week-30-gnocchi-bistecca-and-the-italian-feast","title":"Week 30 \u2014 Gnocchi, Bistecca, and the Italian Feast","text":""},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#monday-gnocchi-from-scratch","title":"Monday \u2014 Gnocchi from Scratch","text":"<p>Skill: Potato gnocchi dough; reading texture by feel; avoiding gummy results Read first: Light and Tender Potato Gnocchi</p> <p>What you're learning: Great gnocchi are light (barely there) because they contain barely enough flour to hold together. Too much flour \u2192 rubbery. The test: drop one in boiling water; if it rises and floats within 30 seconds and tastes right, roll the rest.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Gnocchi with brown butter and sage (simplest and best) - Roasted cherry tomatoes on the side</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Gnocchi di Patate: Veloce vs. Gourmet (Italia Squisita) \u2014 A quick weeknight version and a chef's version side by side \u2014 find where your dough lands on that spectrum and which version you'd choose again.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#tuesday-pasta-fresca-fresh-egg-pasta","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Pasta Fresca (Fresh Egg Pasta)","text":"<p>Skill: Making egg pasta dough by hand; rolling and cutting; various shapes Read first: Reference pasta-making from Weeks 13\u201314 (pasta fresca was introduced there) \u2014 this session goes deeper into filled pasta</p> <p>What you're learning: Now that you know the dough, try a filled shape: either tortelloni (large), ravioli, or a simple pappardelle if fresh dough's not been practiced recently. The filling: ricotta + spinach + Parmesan + nutmeg.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Fresh ricotta and spinach ravioli with brown butter or sage cream sauce - Parmesan, black pepper</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Fresh Pasta from Scratch with a New York Chef (Italia Squisita) \u2014 Watch how he reads the dough by touch and feel, not by timing \u2014 the pasta you're making is the same recipe at the source.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#wednesday-spaghetti-alle-vongole-revisited-from-italian-perspective","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Spaghetti alle Vongole (Revisited from Italian Perspective)","text":"<p>Skill: Building a white brothy sauce; pasta finishing technique; the two vongole versions (in bianco vs. in rosso) Read first: Spaghetti alle Vongole (used in Week 23 for shellfish technique \u2014 now revisit as Italian pasta lesson)</p> <p>What you're learning: The same dish from week 23, but now you're thinking about it differently: pasta al dente, reserved pasta water as sauce thickener, the ratio of clam liquor to olive oil. Make the white version (in bianco) if you made red baked mussels before; make red if not.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Spaghetti alle Vongole (the other version from Week 23) - Crusty bread</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#thursday-rest-day_1","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":""},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#friday-saltimbocca-alla-romana","title":"Friday \u2014 Saltimbocca alla Romana","text":"<p>Skill: Pan-searing thin veal or chicken cutlets; prosciutto application; sage crisp Read first: Veal Saltimbocca \u2014 or Chicken Saltimbocca if substituting</p> <p>What you're learning: Saltimbocca = \"jump in the mouth.\" Thin protein + salty prosciutto + sage + butter + white wine reduction. It's a 15-minute dish that requires absolute timing: in the pan, prosciutto-side down briefly, then flip, deglaze, done.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Saltimbocca alla Romana - Saut\u00e9ed spinach with garlic - Simple roasted potatoes</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#saturday-project-italian-sunday-dinner","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Italian Sunday Dinner","text":"<p>Skill: Multi-course Italian meal; timing, preparation, and service Goal: Build a complete Italian Sunday dinner for 4 or more:</p> <ol> <li>Antipasto: Cured meats, olives, fresh mozzarella, bruschetta</li> <li>Primo: Risotto or fresh pasta</li> <li>Secondo: Bistecca alla Fiorentina (thick T-bone, wood-fire or cast iron) \u2014 or osso buco if not done on Wed Week 29</li> <li>Contorni: Roasted vegetables or simple salad</li> <li>Dolce: Tiramisu or panna cotta (make ahead)</li> </ol> <p>Full Meal: - Complete 4-course Italian Sunday dinner - Italian wine appropriate to each course</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#the-italian-pantry","title":"The Italian Pantry","text":"<p>Italian cooking is defined by its pantry as much as its technique. Knowing what makes a San Marzano tomato different, why the olive oil matters for finishing, and what \"00\" flour does changes how you shop.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Best Slow-Cooked Tomato Sauce \u2014 The canonical red sauce breakdown, with the reasoning behind each ingredient choice.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#braising-italian-style","title":"Braising Italian-Style","text":"<p>Osso buco is a braise but it's also a study in gremolata \u2014 the lemon zest, garlic, and parsley condiment added at the end that lifts the entire dish. Italian braising is different from French braising in that finishing acid and fresh herbs are always part of the architecture.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Osso Buco (Italian Braised Veal Shanks) \u2014 The full technique for the dish: the sear, the soffritto, the wine reduction, the stock, and \u2014 critically \u2014 when to add the gremolata at the end. The structure is the template for every Italian braise.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Pasta Grannies \u2014 The most authentic window into Italian regional home cooking available on the internet.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Essentials of Classic Italian Cooking by Marcella Hazan \u2014 The foundational Italian cookbook in English. Everything you cooked this week, at greater depth, in one volume.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Weeks 29\u201330: French Classics | Weeks 33\u201334: Japanese \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Weeks 31\u201332: Italian","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/quick-ref.html#week-29-italian-patience-dishes","title":"Week 29 \u2014 Italian Patience Dishes","text":"Day Dish Technique Key Point Mon Mushroom Risotto Ladle-by-ladle stock; mantecatura Serve immediately; never cream Tue Minestrone Stage-order veg, Parmesan rind broth Pasta/beans go in last 15 min Wed Osso Buco + Saffron Risotto Brown all sides; 2\u20133 hr braise Gremolata added raw at serving Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Ribollita Day-old bread in soup; reheat Better day 2; olive oil on top Sat PROJECT: Whole Branzino + Tiramisu Pan-roast fish; tiramisu sets 4+ hrs Make tiramisu in the morning"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/quick-ref.html#week-30-fresh-pasta-bistecca-and-the-sunday-feast","title":"Week 30 \u2014 Fresh Pasta, Bistecca, and the Sunday Feast","text":"Day Dish Technique Key Point Mon Gnocchi Baked potato + minimal flour Test one before rolling all Tue Fresh Ricotta Ravioli Egg pasta dough + filled shape Don't over-flour the filling Wed Spaghetti alle Vongole White or red brothy pasta Reserve pasta water; finish in pan Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Saltimbocca alla Romana Fast saut\u00e9; prosciutto-down first 15-minute dish; prep everything first Sat PROJECT: Italian Sunday Dinner 4-course meal; parallel timing Antipasto \u2192 Primo \u2192 Secondo \u2192 Dolce"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/quick-ref.html#risotto-troubleshooting","title":"Risotto Troubleshooting","text":"Problem Cause Fix Gluey, sticky Overcooked; too high heat Cook on medium; don't rush Soupy, watery Undercooked or too much stock More time; stop adding stock earlier Dry, clumpy Undercooked; mantecatura skipped Add splash of warm stock; stir in cold butter off heat No creaminess Wrong rice or no mantecatura Use Arborio/Carnaroli; cold butter off heat is mandatory"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/quick-ref.html#gnocchi-troubleshooting","title":"Gnocchi Troubleshooting","text":"Problem Cause Fix Dense / gummy Too much flour; boiled potatoes Bake potatoes; add flour gradually Falls apart Not enough flour Add 1 tbsp at a time; test one Chewy Overworked dough Mix just until cohesive"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 31\u201332: Italian","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Make-ahead note: Tiramisu (Saturday Week 29) needs 4+ hours to set \u2014 make it in the morning. Ribollita (Friday Week 29) is best made the day before and reheated. Plan accordingly.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dutch oven \u2014 for osso buco and ribollita</li> <li>[ ] Pressure cooker or Instant Pot \u2014 optional but SE's risotto and ribollita are tested with one</li> <li>[ ] Pasta machine or rolling pin \u2014 for Tuesday Week 30 fresh pasta</li> <li>[ ] Large heavy pot \u2014 for blanching gnocchi</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-29","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 29","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Veal shanks \u2014 2\u20134 cross-cut osso buco pieces, 1\u20131.5\" thick (Wed)</li> <li>[ ] Whole branzino or snapper \u2014 1\u20132, 500g\u20131kg each (Sat)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-30","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 30","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Veal scaloppine or chicken breast \u2014 4 thin pieces for saltimbocca (Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Prosciutto di Parma \u2014 4 thin slices (Fri saltimbocca)</li> <li>[ ] Bistecca protein \u2014 T-bone or Porterhouse, 1.5\u20132\" thick (Sat Sunday dinner)</li> <li>[ ] Cured meats for antipasto \u2014 prosciutto, salami, sopressata assortment (Sat)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/shopping-list.html#produce-week-29","title":"\ud83c\udf44 Produce \u2014 Week 29","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Porcini mushrooms \u2014 1 oz dried (Mon risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Cremini or button mushrooms \u2014 8 oz (Mon risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Arborio or Carnaroli rice \u2014 1\u00bd cups (Mon risotto + Wed osso buco risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Saffron \u2014 small pinch (Wed Milanese risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Cavolo nero (Lacinato kale) \u2014 1 bunch (Fri ribollita)</li> <li>[ ] Canned cannellini beans \u2014 2 \u00d7 15-oz cans (Fri ribollita)</li> <li>[ ] Day-old Tuscan bread or ciabatta \u2014 4\u20136 slices torn (Fri ribollita)</li> <li>[ ] Zucchini, carrots, celery, onion \u2014 (Tue minestrone + Fri ribollita)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Fresh sage \u2014 1 bunch (gnocchi Mon Week 30 + saltimbocca Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 6 (gremolata + various)</li> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 1 pint (Week 30 sides)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/shopping-list.html#dairy-eggs","title":"\ud83e\udd5b Dairy &amp; Eggs","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Parmesan Reggiano \u2014 8 oz block (risotto, ribollita, minestrone, pasta)</li> <li>[ ] Parmesan rind \u2014 save from block (minestrone stock)</li> <li>[ ] Mascarpone \u2014 8 oz (Sat Week 29 tiramisu)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh ricotta \u2014 1 lb (Tue Week 30 ravioli filling)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh mozzarella \u2014 1 ball (Week 30 antipasto)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 \u00bd pint</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (gnocchi, pasta dough, tiramisu)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-italian/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Beef or veal stock \u2014 2 quarts (osso buco + Milanese risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken or vegetable stock \u2014 2 quarts (risotto, minestrone, ribollita)</li> <li>[ ] Dry white wine \u2014 1 bottle (osso buco, saltimbocca, various)</li> <li>[ ] Canned whole San Marzano tomatoes \u2014 2 cans (minestrone + vongole rosso option)</li> <li>[ ] Dry pasta \u2014 spaghetti 1 lb + pappardelle or tagliatelle 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] All-purpose flour (pasta dough + gnocchi)</li> <li>[ ] Semolina flour \u2014 optional (pasta dusting)</li> <li>[ ] Espresso or strong brewed coffee \u2014 for tiramisu (Sat Week 29)</li> <li>[ ] Kahl\u00faa or rum \u2014 small amount (tiramisu)</li> <li>[ ] Ladyfinger biscuits (savoiardi) \u2014 1 pack (tiramisu)</li> <li>[ ] Unsweetened cocoa powder \u2014 (tiramisu topping)</li> <li>[ ] Manila clams \u2014 2 lbs (Wed Week 30 vongole \u2014 buy day of)</li> <li>[ ] Olive oil \u2014 extra-virgin, good quality</li> <li>[ ] Dried oregano, red pepper flakes, bay leaves</li> <li>[ ] Nutmeg \u2014 whole (ravioli filling)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html","title":"Weeks 33\u201334: Japanese","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 31\u201332: Italian | Weeks 35\u201336: Chinese \u2192</p> <p>\"Japanese cooking is the art of restraint applied to extraordinary ingredients. The recipe is the last thing a Japanese chef learns. First: knife skills, stock-making, fire control, and respect for the season. The recipe is a formality \u2014 the judgment underneath is everything.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#week-31-foundations-dashi-katsu-tamagoyaki-tempura","title":"Week 31 \u2014 Foundations: Dashi, Katsu, Tamagoyaki, Tempura","text":"<p>Japanese cooking builds on a different set of foundational principles than French or Italian cooking, but the logic is the same: master the foundational techniques first, then apply them broadly. Dashi is the Japanese stock \u2014 it underpins miso soup, ramen, braises, and sauces. Learn dashi and you understand Japanese flavor.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#monday-dashi-kombu-and-katsuobushi-stock","title":"Monday \u2014 Dashi (Kombu and Katsuobushi Stock)","text":"<p>Skill: Cold-infusion technique for kombu; adding bonito; filtering clearly Read first: Basic Japanese Dashi</p> <p>What you're learning: Dashi is made in under 30 minutes from two ingredients \u2014 kombu (dried kelp) and katsuobushi (dried bonito flakes). Cold-soak the kombu, bring slowly to 140\u00b0F, remove kombu, add bonito, steep, strain. The result is subtle, deeply savory (umami-forward), and nothing like Western stock in color or flavor.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Miso soup from your dashi (the simplest application) - Simple Japanese rice with furikake - Practice making the dashi twice to compare extraction timing</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Cheap, Quick and Easy Shoyu Ramen (Way of Ramen) \u2014 Watch the broth layering: the tare goes in after the stock, not during. That's the same logic as dashi \u2014 build a clean base, then season at service.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#tuesday-tonkatsu-japanese-breaded-pork-cutlet","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Tonkatsu (Japanese Breaded Pork Cutlet)","text":"<p>Skill: Japanese breading technique (flour \u2192 egg \u2192 panko); deep-fry temperature management Read first: Tonkatsu \u2014 Japanese Breaded Cutlets</p> <p>What you're learning: Panko breadcrumbs create a uniquely airy, shattering crust because the flakes are flatter and lighter than Western breadcrumbs. The frying oil at 350\u00b0F (180\u00b0C) is the critical variable. Tonkatsu sauce (Worcestershire + ketchup + soy) goes on everything.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Tonkatsu with shredded cabbage slaw and tonkatsu sauce - White rice and pickled ginger</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Tonkatsu \u2014 Pay attention to his breading station setup and why the panko matters more than you'd expect.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#wednesday-tamagoyaki-japanese-rolled-omelette","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Tamagoyaki (Japanese Rolled Omelette)","text":"<p>Skill: Dashi-seasoned egg rolling technique; control of thin layer cooking Read first: Home-Style Tamagoyaki</p> <p>What you're learning: Tamagoyaki is a multi-layer rolled omelette made in a rectangular pan with sweetened, dashi-flavored egg. The technique: pour a thin layer, allow to set partially, roll toward you, push aside, pour another layer underneath, roll again. Each layer bonds to the last. Patience creates the beautiful cross-section.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Tamagoyaki with white rice and miso soup (a full Japanese breakfast-style dinner) - Quick cucumber sunomono (rice vinegar, sesame, cucumber)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#thursday-deep-frying-as-a-systematic-skill","title":"Thursday \u2014 Deep Frying as a Systematic Skill","text":"<p>Skill: Understanding deep frying as a discipline \u2014 not just \"put food in hot oil.\" Tonight: karaage (Japanese fried chicken), which teaches double-frying, the most important technique in deep-fry cooking because it separates moisture removal from crust formation.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read first: Just One Cookbook \u2014 Karaage \u2014 the double-fry logic is explained clearly here.</p> <p>The principles that govern every deep-fry \u2014 Japanese or otherwise:</p> Variable What it controls Target for most frying Oil temperature Crust formation speed; steam generation 325\u2013375\u00b0F depending on item Oil volume Temperature recovery after adding food At least 3\" deep; more is better Batch size Temperature drop Never more than 30% of surface area at once Moisture in food Steam (which escapes) vs. oil absorption Drier surface = less oil absorbed Batter/coating type Crust texture and thickness See below <p>The batter taxonomy: - Dry coat (flour/cornstarch) \u2014 karaage, Korean fried chicken; creates a thin, very crispy shell - Wet batter (flour + liquid) \u2014 tempura, fish and chips; creates a puffed, lighter crust - Bread crumb (panko/breadcrumbs) \u2014 tonkatsu, schnitzel; creates the thickest, crunchiest crust - Double coat (flour \u2192 egg \u2192 breadcrumb) \u2014 standard Western breading; creates maximum thickness</p> <p>The double-fry technique (karaage and Korean fried chicken): 1. First fry at 325\u00b0F \u2014 low temperature drives out moisture from the inside; the crust forms but doesn't fully color; 3\u20134 minutes; remove and rest on a rack 2. Rest 5 minutes \u2014 steam continues to escape; the interior finishes cooking from residual heat 3. Second fry at 375\u00b0F \u2014 high heat rapidly crisps the exterior without overcooking the interior; 1\u20132 minutes until deep golden</p> <p>Oil management (what most home cooks don't do): - Strain the oil after frying through a fine mesh sieve; store in a sealed container - Cool oil can be reused 3\u20135 times if filtered; discard when it smokes at lower temperatures than normal, smells rancid, or turns very dark - Never mix oils from different frying sessions - Never add water to hot oil (steam explosion risk)</p> <p>Full Meal: Japanese Karaage + steamed rice + kewpie mayo + lemon + quick cucumber salad</p> <p>Why the double-fry matters: A single fry at medium heat can't simultaneously cook the interior and crisp the exterior. The moisture escaping from inside prevents the crust from setting. Two fries at two temperatures solve this completely. This logic applies to French fries, fried chicken everywhere, and any thick-cut fried item.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#friday-tempura","title":"Friday \u2014 Tempura","text":"<p>Skill: Ice-cold batter technique; frying at high temperature; tempura dipping sauce from dashi Read first: Deep-Fried Green Bean and Shiitake Tempura</p> <p>What you're learning: Tempura batter is barely mixed (lumpy is correct), ice cold (prevents gluten development), and fried hot (350\u2013370\u00b0F). The result is a translucent, almost ghostly crust \u2014 not thick bread coating. Mix the batter immediately before frying, not ahead of time.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Vegetable and/or shrimp tempura with tentsuyu dipping sauce (dashi + mirin + soy) - White rice or soba noodles underneath</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#saturday-project-oyakodon-full-japanese-dinner","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Oyakodon + Full Japanese Dinner","text":"<p>Skill: Donburi-style (rice bowl) cooking; egg barely set at the finish Read first: Oyakodon \u2014 Japanese Chicken and Egg Rice Bowl</p> <p>What you're learning: Oyakodon (\"parent and child bowl\") is chicken and egg simmered together in a dashi-based sauce and poured over rice. The eggs go in last and are taken off heat while still slightly runny \u2014 they finish cooking from residual heat. Restraint on the egg is the whole lesson.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Oyakodon \u00d7 4 - Miso soup - Pickled vegetables - Finish: matcha with a Japanese confection (mochi, yokan, whatever's available)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Oyakodon \u2014 Notice the moment he kills the heat and how far the eggs are from done \u2014 that's the whole trick.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#week-32-ramen-teriyaki-logic-and-japanese-fire-cooking","title":"Week 32 \u2014 Ramen, Teriyaki Logic, and Japanese Fire Cooking","text":""},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#monday-tonkotsu-style-ramen-quick-weeknight-approach","title":"Monday \u2014 Tonkotsu-Style Ramen (Quick Weeknight Approach)","text":"<p>Skill: Building ramen-adjacent richness without a 12-hour bone broth; tare (seasoning sauce) Read first: 15-Minute Miso Butter Ramen</p> <p>What you're learning: True tonkotsu ramen takes 12 hours. This session uses the SE technique for weeknight ramen that still teaches the essential components: rich base (miso + butter or pork fat), tare (concentrated seasoning added to bowl, not pot), toppings cooked separately, noodles cooked separately. Even shortcut ramen has architecture.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Miso butter ramen with soft-boiled eggs (marinated in soy + mirin) - Nori, corn, green onion, sesame on top</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Beginner Recipe for Rich Tonkotsu Ramen (Way of Ramen) \u2014 Tonkotsu broth is the opposite philosophy from your miso ramen \u2014 one is built on clarity, one on emulsified fat. Make the same toppings and taste the difference the broth alone makes.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#tuesday-teriyaki-sauce-from-scratch-chicken-thighs","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Teriyaki Sauce from Scratch + Chicken Thighs","text":"<p>Skill: Building teriyaki glaze (soy + mirin + sake + sugar); applying it to grilled or pan-seared protein Read first: Teriyaki Sauce \u2014 How to Make at Home</p> <p>What you're learning: Store-bought teriyaki is sweet, gloopy, and a poor substitute for the real thing \u2014 which is bright, salty-sweet, and translucent. Make the sauce from scratch, then use it on pan-seared chicken thighs with skin. The technique of glazing \u2014 reducing the sauce in the pan around the protein in the last 2 minutes \u2014 creates the restaurant sheen.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Teriyaki chicken thighs - Steamed rice, cucumber salad, pickled ginger</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#wednesday-yakitori-grilled-chicken-skewers","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Yakitori (Grilled Chicken Skewers)","text":"<p>Skill: Skewering technique; tare application during grilling; cooking different chicken parts Read first: Negima Yakitori (Chicken and Scallion Skewers)</p> <p>What you're learning: Yakitori is a study in whole-animal use and fire management. If you only use breast meat, you're missing the point \u2014 yakitori celebrates offal and underused cuts. Try at minimum: thigh, skin-wrapped tail (negima), and chicken skin skewers. Brush with tare every 30 seconds near the end.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Yakitori assortment (aim for 3\u20134 different cuts) - Beer, rice, Japanese mayo for dipping</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#thursday-rest-day","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":""},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#friday-shabu-shabu-or-sukiyaki-hot-pot","title":"Friday \u2014 Shabu-Shabu or Sukiyaki (Hot Pot)","text":"<p>Skill: Japanese hot pot; building a table cooking experience; broth control Read first: Shabu-shabu is a technique, not a recipe \u2014 no recipe needed. Buy paper-thin sliced ribeye from a Japanese grocery (or freeze a piece 2 hours and slice with a sharp knife). Stock: one large sheet of kombu in cold water, warmed slowly to 150\u00b0F \u2014 do not boil. Swirl 2\u20133 slices at a time for 10\u201315 seconds. Two dipping sauces: ponzu (citrus + soy) and sesame (tahini + rice vinegar + soy + sesame oil).</p> <p>What you're learning: Shabu-shabu means \"swish-swish\" \u2014 describing how briefly the beef meets the broth. The broth absorbs flavor from the beef as cooking progresses. This is a communal, slow-paced dinner that builds as the meal goes on, ending with udon or rice cooked in the enriched broth.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Shabu-shabu with thinly sliced beef ribeye, mushrooms, tofu, noodles, napa cabbage - Ponzu and sesame dipping sauces - Udon or rice to finish in the enriched broth</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#saturday-project-full-japanese-kaiseki-inspired-dinner","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Full Japanese Kaiseki-Inspired Dinner","text":"<p>Skill: Multi-component Japanese meal; balance of flavors and textures across courses Goal: Build a simplified kaiseki-inspired meal across 4 courses:</p> <ol> <li>Sakizuke: Small aperitif bite \u2014 tamagoyaki slice + cucumber sunomono</li> <li>Soup: Clear dashi soup with tofu, mitsuba, yuzu zest</li> <li>Main: Teriyaki salmon or yakitori selection</li> <li>Shokuji: Rice + miso soup + tsukemono (pickles)</li> </ol> <p>Full Meal: - Simplified 4-course Japanese dinner (formal but achievable) - Green tea and wagashi (Japanese sweets) to close</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: I Made Ramen From Scratch Using TRASH ft. Ramen Lord (Alex French Guy Cooking) \u2014 Alex and Ramen Lord turn kitchen scraps into serious broth. The mindset here \u2014 nothing is waste, everything extracts \u2014 is the kaiseki philosophy applied to ramen.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#dashi-the-foundation","title":"Dashi: The Foundation","text":"<p>Dashi is made in 10 minutes and is the reason Japanese soups, braises, and sauces taste the way they do. Once you understand that katsuobushi and kombu are the primary umami sources, you start seeing them everywhere.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Basic Japanese Dashi \u2014 The method and the reasoning, in Kenji's words. Also explains the difference between ichiban dashi (first extraction) and niban dashi (second extraction).</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#the-japanese-approach-to-simplicity","title":"The Japanese Approach to Simplicity","text":"<p>Japanese cooking is defined by restraint: fewer ingredients, better technique, more precise execution. It's the cuisine that rewards preparation and penalizes carelessness most directly.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Butter-Baste Steaks, Chops, and Fish \u2014 Not Japanese, but the technique connects to the close-attention cooking style you're practicing this week with tonkatsu.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Ramen master at work \u2014 Understanding the scale of commitment that goes into a proper ramen bowl puts your home version in context.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Knife sharpening in Japan \u2014 The knife skills block from Week 1 revisited through a Japanese lens.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Japanese Farm Food by Nancy Singleton Hachisu \u2014 Home-style Japanese cooking that isn't intimidating. Goes deep on dashi, fermentation, and the logic of the Japanese kitchen.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Weeks 31\u201332: Italian | Weeks 35\u201336: Chinese \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Weeks 33\u201334: Japanese","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/quick-ref.html#week-31-foundational-japanese-techniques","title":"Week 31 \u2014 Foundational Japanese Techniques","text":"Day Dish Technique Key Point Mon Dashi + Miso Soup Cold-soak kombu; bonito steep 140\u00b0F for kombu; never boil Tue Tonkatsu Flour \u2192 egg \u2192 panko; 350\u00b0F fry Panko must be fresh and airy Wed Tamagoyaki Thin layers rolled in stages Partially set before rolling Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Tempura (vegetable + shrimp) Ice-cold lumpy batter; 370\u00b0F Mix batter just before frying Sat PROJECT: Oyakodon + full Japanese dinner Simmer chicken in dashi; eggs barely set Off heat while yolks run"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/quick-ref.html#week-32-ramen-fire-cooking-and-hot-pot","title":"Week 32 \u2014 Ramen, Fire Cooking, and Hot Pot","text":"Day Dish Technique Key Point Mon Weeknight Miso Ramen Tare + rich base; components separate Noodles in bowl; broth poured over Tue Teriyaki Chicken (scratch sauce) Glaze reduction in pan at end Mirin + soy + sake + sugar; reduce by \u00bd Wed Yakitori Short skewers; repeated tare basting Multiple cuts; high direct fire Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Shabu-Shabu Brief swish in dashi; communal Paper-thin beef; don't overcook Sat PROJECT: Kaiseki-Inspired 4-Course Balance across courses; composed Make pickles and tamagoyaki ahead"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/quick-ref.html#japanese-pantry-reference","title":"Japanese Pantry Reference","text":"Ingredient Role Substitute Dashi Umami-rich stock base Kombu dashi (vegan) or dashi powder Mirin Sweet rice wine (cooking) Sake + pinch of sugar Sake Dry rice wine (cooking) Dry sherry or white wine Soy sauce Salinity + umami Tamari (gluten-free) Miso (white) Mild, sweet fermented paste Mixed or red miso (stronger flavor) Panko Light, airy Japanese breadcrumb Homemade coarse crumbs (not the same) Rice vinegar Mild acid for seasoning White wine vinegar (use less)"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/quick-ref.html#key-temperature-reference","title":"Key Temperature Reference","text":"Technique Temp Notes Kombu steep 140\u00b0F / 60\u00b0C Never boil \u2014 activates bitter compounds Tonkatsu fry 350\u00b0F / 176\u00b0C Test with a crumb; should sizzle Tempura fry 360\u2013375\u00b0F Higher than tonkatsu; batter is thinner Soft-boiled ramen egg 6.5 min boil, ice bath Jammy yolk; marinate overnight"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 33\u201334: Japanese","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Where to shop: Most Japanese pantry staples (kombu, katsuobushi, mirin, soba, ramen noodles, miso, panko) are found at Asian grocery stores or online. A good Japanese or Korean market is the right call here.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Tamagoyaki pan \u2014 rectangular Japanese omelette pan (~$15\u201325; get it)</li> <li>[ ] Wok or deep Dutch oven \u2014 for tempura and tonkatsu frying</li> <li>[ ] Thermometer \u2014 for oil temperature control</li> <li>[ ] Bamboo skewers \u2014 soaked in water (yakitori)</li> <li>[ ] Fine-mesh strainer \u2014 for dashi and other stocks</li> <li>[ ] Japanese rice cooker \u2014 helpful but optional</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-31","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 31","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Pork loin \u2014 4 thin cutlets, pounded flat (Tue tonkatsu)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (Wed tamagoyaki + Sat oyakodon)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken thighs, boneless \u2014 4 (Sat oyakodon)</li> <li>[ ] Shrimp \u2014 \u00bd lb, peeled (Fri tempura)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-32","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 32","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Chicken thighs \u2014 4\u20136 bone-in or boneless (Tue teriyaki + Wed yakitori)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken misc. parts for yakitori \u2014 skin, thigh chunks, optionally liver (Wed)</li> <li>[ ] Beef ribeye, very thinly sliced \u2014 1 lb (Fri shabu-shabu; ask butcher or use a semi-frozen block and slice yourself)</li> <li>[ ] Ramen toppings \u2014 soft-boiled eggs \u00d7 4, char siu pork (or use chashu from Week 19), nori</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Green onions \u2014 2 bunches (many dishes)</li> <li>[ ] Ginger \u2014 1 large piece</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Cucumber \u2014 4 (sunomono + teriyaki sides)</li> <li>[ ] Baby bok choy \u2014 4 (various)</li> <li>[ ] Corn \u2014 2 ears or 1 cup frozen (ramen topping)</li> <li>[ ] Napa cabbage \u2014 \u00bd head (shabu-shabu)</li> <li>[ ] Shiitake mushrooms \u2014 8 oz (tempura + shabu-shabu)</li> <li>[ ] Enoki mushrooms \u2014 1 pack (shabu-shabu)</li> <li>[ ] Firm tofu \u2014 1 block (shabu-shabu + miso soup)</li> <li>[ ] Green beans \u2014 1 lb (tempura)</li> <li>[ ] Lime + lemon \u2014 for ponzu (Fri shabu)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-japanese/shopping-list.html#japanese-pantry-buy-if-not-stocked","title":"\ud83e\udd6b Japanese Pantry (buy if not stocked)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Kombu (dried kelp) \u2014 1 oz</li> <li>[ ] Katsuobushi (bonito flakes) \u2014 1 oz</li> <li>[ ] White miso \u2014 1 lb tub</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Kikkoman or Japanese brand)</li> <li>[ ] Mirin \u2014 1 bottle</li> <li>[ ] Sake \u2014 cooking sake or drinking sake</li> <li>[ ] Rice vinegar \u2014 1 bottle</li> <li>[ ] Sesame oil \u2014 toasted</li> <li>[ ] Sesame seeds \u2014 white</li> <li>[ ] Panko breadcrumbs \u2014 1 large bag</li> <li>[ ] Japanese short-grain rice \u2014 5-lb bag</li> <li>[ ] Ramen noodles \u2014 fresh or dried, 4 servings</li> <li>[ ] Soba noodles \u2014 1 pack</li> <li>[ ] Udon noodles \u2014 1 pack (shabu-shabu finish)</li> <li>[ ] Nori (dried seaweed sheets) \u2014 1 pack</li> <li>[ ] Furikake \u2014 1 bottle (rice seasoning)</li> <li>[ ] Japanese mayo (Kewpie) \u2014 1 bottle</li> <li>[ ] Tonkatsu sauce \u2014 store-bought (Bull-Dog brand) or make your own (Worcestershire + ketchup + soy)</li> <li>[ ] Dashi powder \u2014 backup if you want to skip scratch dashi mid-week</li> <li>[ ] Togarashi (Japanese chili blend) \u2014 1 small bottle</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html","title":"\ud83e\udd62 Weeks 39\u201340: Chinese Cuisine","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 37\u201338: Japanese Cuisine | Weeks 41\u201342: Mexican Cuisine \u2192</p> <p>\"Chinese cooking is a philosophy of heat and time \u2014 of wok hei, the 'breath of the wok,' and of the patience to braise until the fat has melted into something transformed. Getting either right requires understanding the logic, not just following steps.\"</p> <p>Quick Reference: \u2192 Week 35\u201336 Recipe Quick Ref</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#before-you-start-week-35","title":"Before You Start Week 35","text":"<p>Chinese cuisine is the most codified and internally diverse cooking tradition in the world. The CIA teaches it because it contains techniques that have no Western analogue \u2014 wok hei (breath of the wok, achieved through intensely high heat), red-braising (hong shao rou, using soy and sugar to create a lacquer-like glaze), and the specific knife and cutting logic that underlies stir-fry.</p> <p>Two weeks is a narrow aperture. The goal is not representativeness \u2014 it is fluency in the techniques that are transferable to everything else you cook.</p> <p>What you're learning: - Wok technique and wok hei \u2014 what it is, why it requires a specific kind of heat, and how to approximate it at home - Chinese aromatic base \u2014 the \"flavor trinity\" of ginger, garlic, and scallion and how it differs from the French mirepoix or Italian soffritto - Red-braising (hong shao) \u2014 soy, sugar, Shaoxing wine, and time creating one of the world's great braised-meat techniques - Steaming as primary technique \u2014 the Cantonese philosophy of subtlety and freshness - Sichuan spice logic \u2014 m\u00e1l\u00e0 (numbing heat), the combination of Sichuan peppercorns and dried chilli, and why it works</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read first: Serious Eats \u2014 How to Build a Chinese Pantry \u2014 the pantry items in Chinese cooking are unlike a Western pantry. Stock these two weeks ahead of time.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#the-chinese-pantry","title":"The Chinese Pantry","text":"<p>Before Week 35 begins, verify you have:</p> Item What it does Soy sauce (light/regular + dark) Light for seasoning; dark for color and body Shaoxing rice wine The workhorse alcohol in Chinese cooking; not the same as sake or mirin Sesame oil (toasted) Finishing oil \u2014 not for cooking high heat Doubanjiang (Pixian brand if possible) Fermented chilli-bean paste; the base of many Sichuan dishes Oyster sauce Adds rounded savory depth to stir-fries and braises Black rice vinegar (Chinkiang/Zhenjiang) Sharp, slightly smoky fermented vinegar Sichuan peppercorns Numbing (not burning) heat; floral and citrusy Dried red chilli (tianjin or facing heaven) Heat + smokiness in Sichuan cooking Five-spice powder Star anise-led spice blend; a little goes a long way Fermented black beans Funky, salty, savory; central to Cantonese cooking Corn or potato starch Thickens sauces and velvetizes proteins"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#week-35-core-chinese-techniques","title":"Week 35 \u2014 Core Chinese Techniques","text":""},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#monday-the-wok-heat-motion-and-wok-hei","title":"Monday \u2014 The Wok: Heat, Motion, and Wok Hei","text":"<p>Skill: Wok cooking at home is a compromise because home stovetops produce roughly 7,000\u201315,000 BTUs, while restaurant wok ranges produce 150,000+ BTUs. Understanding this limits your expectations and teaches you to optimize within the constraint.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 The Wok vs. Skillet Debate (and How to Cook Properly on a Home Range)</p> <p>Seasoning your wok (if new): 1. Scrub all factory oil/coating off with steel wool under hot water 2. Heat wok over high flame until it smokes 3. Rub a thin layer of neutral oil all over interior with paper towel using tongs 4. Let cool; repeat 3\u20134 times</p> <p>The wok should be dark and slightly shiny after seasoning. After this, never wash with soap \u2014 rinse with hot water and dry on the stove over heat.</p> <p>Wok hei at home: - Heat the wok until it's smoking before adding oil - Cook in very small batches (1 portion at a time \u2014 proteins will steam if crowded) - Keep everything moving with a wok spatula (chan) - If you have a gas stove, allow some of the stir-fry flame to lick up the sides of the wok \u2014 this is the controlled wok \"toss\"</p> <p>The stir-fry formula: 1. Velvetize protein (see below) 2. Heat wok until smoking; add oil; let it shimmer 3. Add aromatics (ginger + garlic + scallion whites) for 15\u201330 seconds 4. Add protein; spread and sear; don't stir for 30 seconds 5. Add vegetables; toss 6. Add sauce; toss 30\u201360 seconds; remove from heat 7. Sesame oil + scallion greens off heat</p> <p>Velveting:</p> <p>Velveting is the technique that makes restaurant Chinese chicken silky instead of rubbery. Mix protein with egg white + cornstarch + Shaoxing wine; marinate 15 minutes. The coating creates a protective barrier during the high-heat cook.</p> <p>Full Meal: Chicken and Broccoli Stir-Fry (substitute chicken) with velveted chicken and hand-cut florets, served on white rice</p> Component Recipe Protein Chicken breast, sliced thin against grain, velveted Sauce Oyster sauce + light soy + Shaoxing wine + cornstarch slurry Aromatics Ginger + garlic + scallion Vegetable Broccoli florets, blanched 1 minute first <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The Secrets of Wok Hei (Chinese Cooking Demystified) \u2014 The most honest YouTube breakdown of what wok hei actually is and what's achievable at home.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#tuesday-red-braised-pork-belly-hong-shao-rou","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Red-Braised Pork Belly (Hong Shao Rou)","text":"<p>Skill: Red-braising (hong shao) is one of China's great braising traditions and one of the most beautiful things that happens to pork. The combination of soy sauce, Shaoxing wine, aromatics, and rock sugar creates a lacquer-dark, glossy sauce and transforms pork belly into something that nearly dissolves on the tongue. This is Chairman Mao's favorite dish. It is not subtle.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Hong Shao Rou (Red-Braised Pork Belly)</p> <p>The technique: 1. Blanch pork belly to remove blood and impurities \u2014 cold water to start, bring to boil, discard water 2. In a clean pot: caramelize rock sugar in a small amount of oil until amber 3. Add pork belly; coat in the caramelized sugar 4. Add Shaoxing wine + soy sauce (light and dark) + aromatics (ginger, scallion, star anise, cinnamon stick, dried chili) 5. Add water just to cover; bring to boil; reduce to very low simmer 6. Braise partially covered 60\u201390 minutes until a chopstick slides through the fat cap with no resistance 7. Remove pork; reduce braising liquid over high heat until thick and glossy 8. Return pork; coat in glaze</p> <p>Full Meal: Hong shao rou over steamed white rice + blanched baby bok choy with garlic</p> Component Recipe Pork 1.5 lbs skin-on pork belly, cut into 1.5-inch squares Rice Plain jasmine rice cooked in a rice cooker or pot Vegetable Baby bok choy, halved, wok-saut\u00e9ed with garlic and a splash of oyster sauce <p>The patience principle: You cannot rush hong shao rou. A properly braised piece of pork belly trembles when you move the plate. The collagen has fully converted to gelatin and the fat has rendered into the sauce. Any shortcut produces chewy, fatty pork instead of the silk it should be.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#wednesday-cantonese-steamed-fish","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Cantonese Steamed Fish","text":"<p>Skill: Steaming is the central Cantonese technique and the philosophy behind it is opposite to everything in French haute cuisine. Cantonese cooking prizes freshness and the natural flavor of the ingredient above all else. A Cantonese cook would look at a French braise and say it hides the ingredient. A steamed fish shows you everything \u2014 if the fish isn't fresh, you can't hide it.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Cantonese Steamed Fish</p> <p>The technique: 1. Select the freshest whole fish possible (sea bass, branzino, or tilapia); score diagonally on both sides 2. Season the inside cavity with ginger slices and scallion 3. Set fish on a plate or rack over boiling water; cover with a tight lid 4. Steam 8\u201312 minutes depending on size \u2014 the fish is done when a chopstick inserted at the thickest point meets no resistance 5. Drain accumulated liquid from the plate 6. Pour over: julienned ginger + scallion + soy + a pinch of sugar 7. Heat oil in a small pan until smoking; immediately pour over the garnish \u2014 the sizzle finishes the scallion and ginger</p> <p>Full Meal: Steamed whole fish + steamed rice + saut\u00e9ed morning glory or Chinese broccoli (gai lan) with oyster sauce</p> Component Recipe Fish Whole branzino or sea bass (1\u20131.5 lbs); or 2 large fillets Sauce Light soy + Shaoxing wine + sesame oil + pinch of sugar Garnish Julienned ginger, scallion chiffonade, hot oil flash <p>Why it matters: Steaming a whole fish correctly is a high-stakes test of precision \u2014 timing is unforgiving. Overcooked by 2 minutes it's dry; at the right moment it's silky and self-basting. This is exactly the kind of technique that separates experienced cooks from inexperienced ones.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#thursday-dan-dan-noodles","title":"Thursday \u2014 Dan Dan Noodles","text":"<p>Skill: Dan dan noodles are a Sichuan street food that demonstrates the entire Sichuan flavor vocabulary in one bowl: m\u00e1l\u00e0 (numbing + heat from Sichuan peppercorn + chilli), sour (black vinegar), sweet, rich (sesame paste), savory (soy), and the crunchy textural contrast of ya cai (preserved mustard greens).</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Dan Dan Noodles</p> <p>The sauce components \u2014 build this understanding:</p> Component Flavor role Sesame paste (or tahini) Richness, body, nutty depth Light soy sauce Salt, savory baseline Black vinegar (Chinkiang) Sourness, slight smoke Chilli oil Primary heat + red color Ground Sichuan peppercorns M\u00e1l\u00e0 numbing sensation Sugar Balance against the acid and heat Chicken stock or hot water Texture, loosens the sauce <p>This sauce formula \u2014 sesame + soy + vinegar + chilli + Sichuan pepper \u2014 is the Sichuan noodle sauce template. Understanding it unlocks a dozen dishes.</p> <p>Full Meal: Dan dan noodles (a full portion, made as a dinner for yourself or two people) \u2014 nothing else needed, they're substantial</p> Component Recipe Noodles Fresh wheat noodles or dried thin lo mein; al dente Topping Spiced pork mince with ya cai (preserved mustard greens) Sauce Full Sichuan dan dan sauce (above components) Garnish Chopped roasted peanuts, scallion greens, chilli oil drizzle <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Making Authentic Dan Dan Noodles at Home (Chinese Cooking Demystified) \u2014 covers the Sichuan peppercorn toasting and grinding process, which makes a meaningful difference.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#friday-mapo-tofu","title":"Friday \u2014 Mapo Tofu (\u9ebb\u5a46\u8c46\u8150)","text":"<p>Skill: Mapo tofu is one of the most technically interesting dishes in all of Chinese cooking. It requires managing: braising the tofu gently so it holds shape while absorbing flavors, building a complex base from doubanjiang + black bean + aromatics, achieving the proper \"flower\" texture of soft tofu, and finishing with Sichuan peppercorn oil and the \"pushing\" motion (tu\u012b d\u00f2ufu) that moves the tofu without breaking it.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 The Real Mapo Tofu</p> <p>The technique notes: - Use silken or soft tofu (not medium-firm or firm) \u2014 if it breaks a little, that's fine - Blanch tofu cubes in salted water before adding to the wok \u2014 this firms the surface slightly and seasons the interior - The doubanjiang brands matter: Pixian-style is aged and deeply savory; regular brands are brighter and saltier - The finishing step \u2014 Sichuan peppercorn oil poured over, then the tofu pushed with a circular spatula motion \u2014 is what gives the dish its characteristic wobble and distribution of heat</p> <p>Full Meal: Mapo tofu over steamed rice + simple soy-dressed cucumber salad (smashed cucumbers with black vinegar + garlic + sesame oil + chilli flake)</p> Component Recipe Tofu Soft or silken tofu, cubed, blanched Base Doubanjiang + fermented black beans + ground pork + aromatics Sauce Stock + soy + rice wine; thickened with cornstarch slurry Finish Sichuan peppercorn oil + scallion greens"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#saturday-project-sichuan-dinner","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Sichuan Dinner","text":"<p>Cook a complete Sichuan-focused dinner for two to four people. The goal is to compose a meal where the different heat/numbing levels of the dishes balance each other \u2014 Chinese meals are designed this way.</p> Dish Heat level Role on table Smashed cucumber salad Low (just chilli flake) Refreshing, palate-clearing starter Mapo tofu High m\u00e1l\u00e0 Center of the table Stir-fried green beans with garlic None Cooling, textural contrast Steamed white rice None Base and palate reset Dan dan noodles (half portion, dressed lighter) Medium A second carbohydrate"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#sunday-off","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>Read: The Sichuan Pepper Question on Serious Eats \u2014 the chemistry behind the m\u00e1l\u00e0 numbing sensation is genuinely fascinating.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#week-36-northern-cantonese-and-home-cooking","title":"Week 36 \u2014 Northern, Cantonese, and Home Cooking","text":""},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#monday-congee-rice-porridge","title":"Monday \u2014 Congee (Rice Porridge)","text":"<p>Skill: Congee is cooked rice broken down in a large quantity of water or stock until it becomes a thick, creamy porridge. The skill is in the ratio (1:10 or more) and the time (45 minutes minimum). It is the ultimate test of whether you can make something completely humble taste extraordinary \u2014 through good stock, proper consistency, and thoughtful toppings.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Congee (Chinese Rice Porridge)</p> <p>Full Meal: A congee bar \u2014 make a large pot of plain rice congee, and provide:</p> Topping How to prepare Century egg Nicked and sliced (an acquired taste; try it) Poached or sous vide chicken Shredded; seasoned with soy + sesame Crispy shallots Thin-sliced, fried until deep gold Pickled ginger Pre-made or store-bought White pepper Freshly ground; essential Sesame oil A few drops to finish Sliced scallions Raw, added at the last moment Fried dough (youtiao) Buy from an Asian bakery or skip"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#tuesday-dim-sum-at-home-har-gow-shrimp-dumplings","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Dim Sum at Home: Har Gow (Shrimp Dumplings)","text":"<p>Skill: Dim sum at home is ambitious and humbling. Har gow \u2014 translucent steamed shrimp dumplings \u2014 have a specific wheat starch wrapper that is unlike any pasta or dumpling wrapper in Western cooking. The folding technique is its own sub-skill that takes numerous attempts.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Har Gow (Cantonese Shrimp Dumplings)</p> <p>What the dough teaches: The har gow wrapper is made from wheat starch (not all-purpose flour) + cornstarch + boiling water. The hot water gelatinizes the starches, producing the translucent, slightly chewy wrapper characteristic of this dumpling. No other dough behaves this way.</p> <p>Full Meal: Har gow (make at least 16 \u2014 the first 4 will be ugly) + char siu bao (steamed BBQ pork buns) from store-bought char siu pork or pork belly</p> <p>Honesty note: This will take 2\u20133 hours and some of the dumplings will fall apart. That is exactly the right experience. Dim sum chefs spend months learning one fold. Your goal tonight is to understand the dough behavior and make a few that work.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#wednesday-chinese-egg-fried-rice","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Chinese Egg Fried Rice","text":"<p>Skill: Egg fried rice is the Chinese test of wok technique \u2014 the dish that tells you exactly where your heat management is. The keys are: cold day-old rice (never fresh; it's too wet), eggs added early so they set in the hot rice rather than scramble separately, and restraint with soy sauce (the dish should taste of rice and egg, not soy).</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 The Best Fried Rice</p> <p>Full Meal: Egg fried rice (a proper full-dinner portion) + Chinese cucumber salad + any leftover hong shao rou from earlier in the week if you made it ahead</p> <p>The egg fried rice method: 1. Wok, maximum heat, smoking before any oil 2. Oil; add cold cooked rice; stir-fry until individual grains separate and sizzle 3. Push rice to the sides; crack eggs into the center of the wok; scramble briefly 4. Incorporate rice into eggs before the eggs fully set \u2014 the rice finishes the eggs 5. Season with light soy sauce + white pepper; toss 30 seconds 6. Off heat: sesame oil + scallion greens</p> <p>Cold rice is non-negotiable. Fresh cooked rice has too much moisture and steams in the wok, producing gluey clumps. Cook rice the day before, spread on a tray to dry, and refrigerate uncovered overnight.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#thursday-kung-pao-chicken","title":"Thursday \u2014 Kung Pao Chicken (\u5bab\u4fdd\u9e21\u4e01)","text":"<p>Skill: Kung pao chicken is one of the most technically balanced dishes in Chinese cooking. It requires: velveted chicken, a fried-peanut garnish, the dual texture of the dried chillies (the shells add smokiness, the seeds add heat), and a sauce that is simultaneously sour, sweet, salty, and a little numbing.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Kung Pao Chicken</p> <p>The sauce formula:</p> Ingredient Amount Role Black vinegar 2 tsp Sour Soy sauce 2 tbsp Salt, savory Sugar 1 tsp Sweet Sichuan peppercorn oil 1 tsp Numbing Chilli oil 1 tsp Heat Cornstarch 1 tsp Thickener Chicken stock 3 tbsp Body <p>Full Meal: Kung pao chicken over steamed rice + sliced cucumber dressed with sesame oil and white vinegar</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#friday-hot-and-sour-soup","title":"Friday \u2014 Hot and Sour Soup (\u9178\u8fa3\u6c64)","text":"<p>Skill: Hot and sour soup is the Chinese umami bomb \u2014 built on a well-made pork stock (or chicken stock), with the interplay of acid (black vinegar), heat (white pepper + chilli), and texture (wood ear mushrooms, silken tofu, egg ribbons). The egg ribbon technique \u2014 pouring beaten egg in a thin stream into simmering soup while stirring \u2014 produces the characteristic feathery strands.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Hot and Sour Soup</p> <p>The thickening and egg ribbon technique: 1. Cornstarch slurry added to simmering stock thickens to a loose, viscous consistency 2. Egg: beat until uniform; hold over the pot; pour in a thin stream while stirring the soup in a circular motion with the other hand 3. The motion creates ribbons rather than clumps \u2014 the circular current spreads the egg before it sets</p> <p>Full Meal: Hot and sour soup as a complete dinner (it's substantial) + steamed white rice if needed + scallion pancakes (store-bought or make your own)</p> Component Recipe Stock Pork or chicken stock \u2014 good homemade makes this sing Mushrooms Reconstituted dried wood ear + shiitake Proteins Silken tofu cubes + thin pork strips Thickener Cornstarch slurry \u2014 add gradually until soup coats a spoon Acid + heat Black vinegar + white pepper \u2014 both added OFF heat to preserve sharpness"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#saturday-project-full-chinese-banquet-for-46","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Full Chinese Banquet (for 4\u20136)","text":"<p>The traditional Chinese dinner table presents everything at once \u2014 multiple dishes, a soup, rice. The guest serves themselves from shared platters. Cook a full banquet-style dinner:</p> Dish Why it's on the menu Celery root and cucumber appetizer Light opener; no cooking Hot and sour soup Starter; the egg ribbon technique on display Steamed whole fish Cantonese technique; freshness as the statement Hong shao rou Red-braised pork; make it Monday, reheat and it's even better Stir-fried bok choy with garlic Fast, green, balancing the rich dishes Steamed jasmine rice Cook double the amount <p>Total cook time if hong shao rou made ahead: approximately 90 minutes active.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#sunday-off_1","title":"Sunday \u2014 OFF","text":"<p>Begin Week 37 shopping. The Mexican block starts Monday.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#checkpoint-what-you-can-now-do","title":"Checkpoint: What You Can Now Do","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Season and maintain a wok</li> <li>[ ] Velvetize protein for silky stir-fry</li> <li>[ ] Braise pork belly in the hong shao red-braise method</li> <li>[ ] Steam a whole fish to exactly done</li> <li>[ ] Build and taste-balance a Sichuan sauce (sesame + soy + vinegar + m\u00e1l\u00e0 spice)</li> <li>[ ] Make egg fried rice with proper wok technique</li> <li>[ ] Cook congee to the right consistency</li> <li>[ ] Make egg ribbons in hot and sour soup</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 The Chinese Cooking Primer \u2014 a comprehensive technique reference</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Sichuan Peppercorn Reference \u2014 the science of m\u00e1l\u00e0</li> <li>\ud83c\udfa5 Chinese Cooking Demystified (YouTube) \u2014 the best English-language YouTube channel for authentic Chinese technique, bar none</li> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Wok by J. Kenji L\u00f3pez-Alt \u2014 the definitive English-language treatment of wok cooking; reads like an engineering manual and a recipe book simultaneously</li> <li>\ud83d\udcda Land of Fish and Rice by Fuchsia Dunlop \u2014 Dunlop is the best Western writer on Chinese food; this volume covers Jiangnan (Shanghai region) cuisine with deep historical context</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/quick-ref.html","title":"Weeks 39\u201340 Quick Reference \u2014 Chinese Cuisine","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Week 35\u201336 Guide</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/quick-ref.html#core-techniques-at-a-glance","title":"Core Techniques at a Glance","text":"Technique What it produces Key rule Stir-fry (wok) Crisp-tender vegetables, silky protein Smoking hot wok; small batches; keep moving Velveting Silky, tender chicken or beef Egg white + cornstarch + Shaoxing wine; 15-min marinade Red-braising (hong shao) Dark, lacquered, meltingly tender pork Blanch first; caramelize sugar; low low heat; long time Cantonese steaming Delicate, fresh-flavored fish Tight lid; boiling water beneath; sizzling oil finish Egg fried rice Separated, slightly smoky grains Cold day-old rice only; eggs before they fully set Egg ribbons Feathery egg strands in soup Thin stream + circular stirring motion Cornstarch thickening Glossy, coating sauce Mix cold water 1:1 with starch; add to simmering liquid gradually Congee Silky, broken-down rice porridge 1 cup rice : 10\u201312 cups liquid; low simmer 45+ minutes"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/quick-ref.html#velveting-protocol","title":"Velveting Protocol","text":"<ol> <li>Slice protein thin, against the grain (chicken breast, beef, pork)</li> <li>Toss with: 1 egg white + 1 tbsp cornstarch + 1 tsp Shaoxing wine + pinch of salt</li> <li>Let sit 15\u201330 minutes at room temperature (or refrigerate up to 2 hours)</li> <li>Add to wok when the wok is properly hot \u2014 the coating protects the protein</li> </ol>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/quick-ref.html#hong-shao-rou-red-braise-process-summary","title":"Hong Shao Rou (Red Braise) \u2014 Process Summary","text":"Step Detail 1. Blanch Cold water \u2192 boil; discard water; rinse pork 2. Caramelize sugar Rock sugar in neutral oil over medium; swirl to amber 3. Coat pork Add pork; toss in caramel until coated 4. Add liquids Shaoxing wine + light soy + dark soy + aromatics + water to cover 5. Braise Simmer VERY low, partially covered, 60\u201390 min 6. Reduce Remove pork; boil liquid until thick and glossy 7. Return + coat Pork back in; toss to glaze"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/quick-ref.html#sichuan-flavor-components","title":"Sichuan Flavor Components","text":"Component Flavor role Can't substitute Doubanjiang Fermented chilli-bean heat, umami depth Use Pixian brand ideally Sichuan peppercorns Numbing (m\u00e1l\u00e0) sensation; floral, citrus No substitute Chinkiang black vinegar Sharp, smoky sourness Balsamic is NOT a substitute Chilli oil Heat + color + aroma Make or buy; not plain vegetable oil Ya cai Fermented mustard greens; crunch Tianjin preserved vegetable or skip"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/quick-ref.html#the-stir-fry-order-of-operations","title":"The Stir-Fry Order of Operations","text":"<ol> <li>Mise en place first \u2014 stir-fry happens in 4\u20136 minutes; prep everything before the wok heats</li> <li>Heat wok until smoking</li> <li>Add oil; swirl to coat</li> <li>Aromatics (ginger + garlic + scallion whites) \u2014 15\u201330 sec</li> <li>Protein \u2014 spread; sear 30 sec; toss; cook until just done; remove</li> <li>Vegetables \u2014 highest volume first; toss 1\u20132 min</li> <li>Sauce \u2014 pour in around the edges; let it sizzle; toss to coat</li> <li>Return protein</li> <li>Off heat: sesame oil + scallion greens</li> </ol>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/quick-ref.html#congee-ratios","title":"Congee Ratios","text":"Rice Liquid Time Result 1 cup 10 cups 45 min Thick, creamy 1 cup 12 cups 60 min Very silky/thin <ul> <li>Use day-before rice or raw rice (raw = creamier; cook raw from the start)</li> <li>For depth: use chicken or pork stock instead of plain water</li> <li>Stir occasionally to prevent sticking; low simmer throughout</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/quick-ref.html#the-dan-dan-sauce-formula","title":"The Dan Dan Sauce Formula","text":"Ingredient Amount (for 2 servings) Sesame paste or tahini 3 tbsp Light soy sauce 2 tbsp Chinkiang black vinegar 1 tbsp Chilli oil 1\u20132 tbsp (to taste) Ground Sichuan peppercorns \u00bd tsp Sugar 1 tsp Toasted sesame oil 1 tsp Hot stock or water 4\u20136 tbsp (adjust to texture) <p>Mix thoroughly; taste; adjust heat/sour/sweet. Spoon over noodles.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/quick-ref.html#steamed-fish-timing-guide","title":"Steamed Fish \u2014 Timing Guide","text":"Fish Weight Steam time Whole branzino 1 lb 8\u20139 min Whole sea bass 1.5 lb 11\u201313 min Sea bass fillets (thick) 6 oz 6\u20137 min Whole red snapper 2 lb 14\u201316 min <p>Done when: Chopstick slides through thickest part with zero resistance. Eyes should be opaque and protruding.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/quick-ref.html#week-3536-dishes-summary","title":"Week 35\u201336 Dishes Summary","text":"Week Day Dish Technique 35 Mon Chicken and broccoli stir-fry Wok + velveting 35 Tue Hong shao rou (red-braised pork belly) Red braise 35 Wed Cantonese steamed whole fish Steaming 35 Thu Dan dan noodles Sichuan sauce building 35 Fri Mapo tofu Doubanjiang base + soft tofu 35 Sat Sichuan dinner party Multi-technique 36 Mon Congee (rice porridge) Long simmer 36 Tue Har gow + char siu bao Dim sum dough + steaming 36 Wed Egg fried rice Wok + egg integration 36 Thu Kung pao chicken Stir-fry + nut garnish 36 Fri Hot and sour soup Egg ribbon + thickening 36 Sat Full Chinese banquet Multi-dish timing"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/shopping-list.html","title":"Weeks 39\u201340 Shopping List \u2014 Chinese Cuisine","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Week 35\u201336 Guide</p> <p>Specialty shopping note: Chinese pantry staples (doubanjiang, Shaoxing wine, Chinkiang vinegar, wheat starch, ya cai, etc.) will not be found at a mainstream grocery store. Shop at your nearest Asian supermarket (99 Ranch, H Mart, Mitsuwa, or any Chinese/Pan-Asian grocery) at least one week ahead. Once purchased, most of these items last months.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/shopping-list.html#pantry-staples-to-stock-ahead","title":"\ud83e\uded9 Pantry Staples to Stock Ahead","text":"<p>These are permanent pantry additions \u2014 not single-use items. Buy once, use throughout the remaining weeks.</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Light soy sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Pearl River Bridge or Lee Kum Kee recommended)</li> <li>[ ] Dark soy sauce \u2014 1 bottle (smaller; used in small amounts for color)</li> <li>[ ] Shaoxing rice wine \u2014 1 bottle (not \"cooking wine\" with salt added; find the real thing)</li> <li>[ ] Chinkiang black vinegar (\u9547\u6c5f\u9999\u918b) \u2014 1 bottle</li> <li>[ ] Doubanjiang \u2014 1 jar (Pixian brand if possible; found in Asian grocery stores)</li> <li>[ ] Oyster sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Lee Kum Kee panda label or similar)</li> <li>[ ] Toasted sesame oil \u2014 1 small bottle (finishing only; not cooking)</li> <li>[ ] Fermented black beans (douchi) \u2014 1 small bag or jar</li> <li>[ ] Sichuan peppercorns \u2014 1 small bag (buy fresh; they lose numbness over time)</li> <li>[ ] Dried tianjin chillies or facing heaven chillies \u2014 1 bag</li> <li>[ ] Five-spice powder \u2014 1 small jar</li> <li>[ ] Rock sugar (\u51b0\u7cd6) \u2014 1 small package (for hong shao rou \u2014 can sub with brown sugar if needed)</li> <li>[ ] Cornstarch \u2014 1 box (if you don't have it already)</li> <li>[ ] Chilli oil \u2014 1 jar (Lao Gan Ma or your homemade from Week 1\u20132 chilli oil)</li> <li>[ ] Ya cai (Yibin preserved vegetables) \u2014 1 small packet (for dan dan; optional but authentic)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/shopping-list.html#proteins","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Skin-on pork belly \u2014 2 lbs (hong shao rou, Week 35 Tuesday; buy extra \u2014 it's better the next day)</li> <li>[ ] Ground pork \u2014 1 lb (dan dan noodles + mapo tofu + hot and sour soup)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken breast or thigh \u2014 2 lbs (stir-fry + kung pao; thigh preferred for flavor)</li> <li>[ ] Whole branzino or sea bass \u2014 1 fish, 1\u20131.5 lbs (steamed fish, Week 35 Wednesday; pick the freshest one)</li> <li>[ ] Shrimp \u2014 1 lb, peeled and deveined (har gow, Week 36 Tuesday)</li> <li>[ ] Pork loin, thin-sliced \u2014 \u00bd lb (hot and sour soup strips)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd6c Produce","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Broccoli \u2014 1 large head (stir-fry Week 35 Monday)</li> <li>[ ] Baby bok choy \u2014 2 bunches (steamed fish side + banquet satay)</li> <li>[ ] Soft or silken tofu \u2014 2 packages (mapo tofu + hot and sour soup)</li> <li>[ ] Ginger \u2014 1 large hand (used in everything; buy more than you think)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Scallions \u2014 3 bunches (used daily)</li> <li>[ ] Chinese broccoli (gai lan) \u2014 1 bunch (Week 35 Wednesday side or banquet)</li> <li>[ ] Celery \u2014 2 stalks (hot and sour soup)</li> <li>[ ] Long hot green peppers or Anaheim peppers \u2014 4 (kung pao)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumbers \u2014 3 (smashed cucumber salad; side dishes)</li> <li>[ ] Morning glory or Chinese water spinach \u2014 1 bunch (if available; use regular spinach if not)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/shopping-list.html#dried-goods-mushrooms","title":"\ud83c\udf44 Dried Goods / Mushrooms","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dried wood ear mushrooms \u2014 1 small bag (hot and sour soup)</li> <li>[ ] Dried shiitake mushrooms \u2014 1 bag (hot and sour soup + congee toppings)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh oyster or king oyster mushrooms \u2014 \u00bd lb (banquet side optional)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/shopping-list.html#noodles-rice","title":"\ud83c\udf5c Noodles &amp; Rice","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Jasmine rice \u2014 5 lbs (used every day; cook extra night before for fried rice)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh wheat noodles or lo mein \u2014 1 lb (dan dan noodles; dried thin noodles work too)</li> <li>[ ] Wheat starch (\u6f84\u7c89, NOT wheat flour) \u2014 200g (har gow wrappers; found at Asian grocery only)</li> <li>[ ] Scallion pancakes \u2014 1 package frozen (if making them from scratch, flour + water + scallions)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/shopping-list.html#dairy-eggs","title":"\ud83e\udd5a Dairy &amp; Eggs","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (egg fried rice + har gow + hot and sour soup egg ribbons; velveting)</li> <li>[ ] Note: no dairy in this block besides eggs</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/shopping-list.html#for-char-siu-bbq-pork-for-bao","title":"\ud83c\udf56 For Char Siu (BBQ Pork for Bao)","text":"<p>Two options: 1. Buy char siu ready-made from a Chinese BBQ shop (the simplest and most authentic option) 2. Make your own: Pork shoulder or pork butt (1 lb) + hoisin + soy + honey + five-spice \u2192 recipe on index.md</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Pre-made char siu OR 1 lb pork shoulder + hoisin + honey (store-bought bao shells are also acceptable)</li> <li>[ ] Bamboo steamer \u2014 essential for dim sum and Cantonese steaming</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/shopping-list.html#congee-toppings-week-36-monday","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Congee Toppings (Week 36 Monday)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Century eggs (\u76ae\u86cb) \u2014 2 (from Asian grocery; look for the dark preserved eggs; an experience)</li> <li>[ ] Shallots \u2014 3\u20134 (for crispy shallots)</li> <li>[ ] Pickled ginger \u2014 1 small jar (store-bought)</li> <li>[ ] White pepper (ground) \u2014 1 jar (essential for congee and hot and sour soup; different from black pepper)</li> <li>[ ] Peanuts (roasted, unsalted) \u2014 \u00bd cup (dan dan noodle garnish + kung pao)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-chinese/shopping-list.html#equipment-notes-for-this-block","title":"\ud83e\uddca Equipment Notes for This Block","text":"<ul> <li>Wok \u2014 carbon steel, 14-inch, flat-bottomed for home ranges (not round-bottomed without a wok ring)</li> <li>Wok spatula (chan) \u2014 the flat-edged wok ladle; essential for proper stir-fry motion</li> <li>Bamboo steamer \u2014 1 or 2 tiers; fits over a wok with boiling water below</li> <li>Rice cooker \u2014 strongly recommended; frees up attention for wok work</li> <li>Spider strainer or slotted spoon \u2014 for blanching and straining</li> <li>Heavy cleaver (optional) \u2014 for breaking down pork belly; a chef's knife works too</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html","title":"Weeks 37\u201338: Mexican","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 35\u201336: Chinese | Weeks 39\u201340: Indian \u2192</p> <p>\"Mexican cooking is not what you find at most restaurants north of the border. It's a cuisine of extraordinary depth \u2014 complex moles that take two days, fresh salsas that cook in ten minutes, braises that turn into sandwiches, soups that become street food. Understanding it properly changes how you think about heat, acid, and corn.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#week-33-pozole-tacos-al-pastor-and-carne-asada","title":"Week 33 \u2014 Pozole, Tacos al Pastor, and Carne Asada","text":"<p>Mexican cuisine covers centuries of indigenous technique layered with colonial influence and regional variation. This week focuses on the key dry-heat and braising techniques from Mexico's northern and central traditions. You've already done carnitas (Week 20) and al pastor-adjacent work \u2014 this week goes deeper.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#monday-carne-asada","title":"Monday \u2014 Carne Asada","text":"<p>Skill: Marinating thin beef for grill; char without overcooking; proper resting Read first: Carne Asada</p> <p>What you're learning: Carne asada is grilled marinated beef, usually flank or skirt steak, cut thin after resting and used in tacos. The marinade is citrus-heavy \u2014 lime + orange + garlic + cumin + chili \u2014 and the char is non-negotiable. Kenji's approach talks through why you want extreme heat and a thin piece of meat rather than a thick steak treated like carne.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Carne Asada tacos on warm corn tortillas - Pico de gallo, guacamole (prevent browning with the right technique), sliced radish, fresh lime</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#tuesday-pozole-rojo","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Pozole Rojo","text":"<p>Skill: Dried chile rehydration and integration; hominy preparation; pozole's garnish architecture Read first: Pozole \u2014 Mexican Red Chile Pork Soup</p> <p>What you're learning: Pozole is a pre-Columbian Mesoamerican soup built around hominy (nixtamalized corn) and slow-braised pork in a red chile broth. The dried chiles (guajillo, ancho, mulato) are toasted, rehydrated, and blended \u2014 this is the fundamental Mexican chile sauce technique you'll use throughout this block and beyond.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pozole Rojo with whatever garnishes you have: shredded cabbage, sliced radish, dried oregano, lime juice, tostadas</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Pozole Verde de Pollo \u2014 He makes the verde version; compare the green vs. red chile logic and notice how the hominy transforms the texture of the broth.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#wednesday-guacamole-salsa-verde-the-fundamentals","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Guacamole + Salsa Verde (The Fundamentals)","text":"<p>Skill: Avocado selection and browning prevention; charring tomatillos; raw vs. cooked salsa Read first: How to Prevent Guacamole from Browning</p> <p>What you're learning: Guacamole is technique (not just mashing avocados). Acid + salt applied at the right moment prevent browning. The onion is rinsed to remove harsh sulfur compounds before adding. This session: make a perfect guacamole AND a charred salsa verde (the tomatillo charring technique was covered in Week 20 \u2014 revisit and refine it).</p> <p>Full Meal: - Guacamole + charred salsa verde served as dinner accompaniments - Pair with braised pinto beans (from scratch or canned), warm tortillas, queso fresco</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Great Guacamole \u2014 Watch specifically how he handles the acid and salt timing \u2014 it's the thing most people get backwards.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#thursday-rest-day","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":"<p>Reflect: Compare the chile sauce you made for pozole with the chipotles-in-adobo you may have used in other recipes. How does rehydrating and blending dried chiles from scratch change the flavor? Note the complexity difference.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#friday-tacos-al-pastor","title":"Friday \u2014 Tacos al Pastor","text":"<p>Skill: Al pastor marinade (achiote paste base); achiote spice profile; stovetop vs. grill comal technique Read first: Tacos al Pastor</p> <p>What you're learning: Al pastor derives from Lebanese shawarma brought to Mexico in the 19th century and transformed with achiote paste, pineapple, and dried chiles. The SE version makes it achievable at home without a vertical spit. The pineapple chunk broiled at the end (or grilled separately) is mandatory.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Tacos al Pastor: pork, pineapple, white onion, cilantro, lime, corn tortillas - Refried beans alongside</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#saturday-project-enchiladas-red-chile-sauce-from-scratch","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Enchiladas + Red Chile Sauce from Scratch","text":"<p>Skill: Making a proper red chile sauce (not store-bought); enchilada rolling and baking What you're learning: Real enchiladas are dipped in a chile sauce, not smothered in sauce after. The corn tortilla is briefly fried or softened in the sauce itself, then rolled around the filling, laid in a pan, and baked until the sauce caramelizes. The sauce is the skill \u2014 make it from at least two dried chile varieties.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Enchiladas Rojas (beef or cheese and onion) - Mexican rice, refried beans or black beans - Crema, white onion, fresh cilantro, queso fresco</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Crispy-Edged Enchiladas \u2014 Notice the dipping-not-smothering technique; that's the structural difference between real enchiladas and the casserole version most people make.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#week-34-deeper-mexico-birria-mole-and-tamales","title":"Week 34 \u2014 Deeper Mexico: Birria, Mole, and Tamales","text":""},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#monday-birria-de-res-beef-birria","title":"Monday \u2014 Birria de Res (Beef Birria)","text":"<p>Skill: Long beef braise in a complex chile marinade; consomm\u00e9 for dipping Read first: Birria de Res (Beef Birria)</p> <p>What you're learning: Birria is Jalisco's slow-braised chile-rubbed beef (or goat in the original version). The braising liquid becomes the consomm\u00e9 \u2014 the broth in which you dip your quesabirria taco before eating it. This is a Saturday project that ended up on Monday because of its recent popularity; know the real version.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Birria tacos / quesabirria with consomm\u00e9 for dipping - Pickled onions, lime, cilantro, salsa</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Tacos de Birria \u2014 Watch how he builds the consomm\u00e9 and the importance of the chile marinade penetrating the meat before braising.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#tuesday-mole-negro-simplified-introduction","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Mole Negro (Simplified Introduction)","text":"<p>Skill: Multi-chile mole building; chocolate integration in savory sauce; depth layering Read first: Mole Negro (Oaxacan Black Mole Sauce)</p> <p>What you're learning: True mole negro is a week-long project. Today's simplified version should still require 2\u20133 hours and include: at minimum 3 dried chiles (toasted + rehydrated), tomatoes, tomatillos, dark chocolate, sesame, raisins, plantain, and spices. The result should be complex, savory, faintly bitter. Serve with chicken.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Simplified Mole Negro with chicken thighs - White rice and warm tortillas</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#wednesday-tamales-team-project","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Tamales (Team Project)","text":"<p>Skill: Masa dough preparation (masa harina + lard or fat); spreading on husks; steaming Read first: How to Make Tamales \u2014 Comprehensive Guide</p> <p>What you're learning: Tamales are one of the most community-oriented foods in Mexican culture \u2014 typically made in large quantities at family gatherings (\"tamaladas\"). Make a batch with a simple filling (braised pork in red chile, or cheese and rajas). The key skill is spreading the masa thinly and evenly enough that the husk folds without tearing.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Tamales (makes 12\u201316) \u2014 eat some tonight; freeze the rest - Black beans, salsa, crema</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#thursday-rest-day_1","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":""},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#friday-chiles-rellenos","title":"Friday \u2014 Chiles Rellenos","text":"<p>Skill: Roasting and peeling poblano peppers; battered egg-white fry technique Read first: Chiles Rellenos (Mexican-Style Cheese-Stuffed Chiles)</p> <p>What you're learning: Chiles rellenos are another study in egg-white batter frying (similar to tempura structurally \u2014 the white is beaten stiff, yolks folded in). The poblanos are charred under a broiler, steamed in a bag, peeled \u2014 this is the standard technique for all roasted peppers that applies across cuisines.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Chiles Rellenos (cheese or picadillo filled) - Tomato salsa, rice, beans</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Chiles Rellenos \u2014 Pay attention to his egg-white batter technique and what \"stiff peaks\" actually does for the fry structure.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#saturday-project-full-mexican-celebration-dinner","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Full Mexican Celebration Dinner","text":"<p>Skill: Multi-dish coordination; table presentation of Mexican feast Goal: Choose 4\u20135 dishes from the two weeks and serve them restaurant-style:</p> <ol> <li>Botanas: Guacamole, salsa verde, tortilla chips</li> <li>Sopa: Remainder of pozole (reheat) or a fresh black bean soup</li> <li>Main I: Whatever birria or enchiladas remain</li> <li>Main II: Carne asada or al pastor freshly prepared</li> <li>Dessert: Churros with chocolate sauce, or tres leches cake (store-bought acceptable tonight)</li> </ol> <p>Full Meal: - Multi-dish Mexican celebration spread - Margaritas or agua fresca as appropriate</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#the-chile-framework","title":"The Chile Framework","text":"<p>Mexican cooking is a chile curriculum. Guajillo, ancho, pasilla, chipotle \u2014 each dried chile has a distinct flavor profile, heat level, and application. Learning to distinguish them by taste is the single biggest skill jump in Mexican cooking.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Carne Asada: The Food Lab Recipe \u2014 The science behind the marinade and the high-heat grill approach, explained in detail.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Pozole Rojo \u2014 The full technique for the multi-chile broth. Understanding how the dried chiles are toasted, soaked, and blended is the core skill of Mexican sauce-making.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#mole-one-of-the-most-complex-sauces-in-the-world","title":"Mole: One of the Most Complex Sauces in the World","text":"<p>Mole negro is typically a multi-day project in its native context. Understanding why each ingredient \u2014 chocolate, dried chiles, charred onion, toasted sesame, plantain \u2014 is there turns an intimidating recipe into a logical sequence.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 A Comprehensive Guide to Mexican Chiles \u2014 The full vocabulary of dried chiles used in mole: ancho, mulato, pasilla, chipotle, guajillo, and more. Knowing the flavor profile of each one before you cook is how mole stops being frightening and starts being navigable.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Bayless on mole \u2014 The foremost authority on Mexican cuisine in the American culinary world. His mole breakdowns are the clearest explanations available in English.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Mexico: The Cookbook by Margarita Carrillo Bosco \u2014 The Phaidon comprehensive reference on Mexican regional cooking. If you want to understand the full diversity of what you started this week, this is the book.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Weeks 35\u201336: Chinese | Weeks 39\u201340: Indian \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Weeks 37\u201338: Mexican","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/quick-ref.html#week-33-techniques-of-central-and-northern-mexico","title":"Week 33 \u2014 Techniques of Central and Northern Mexico","text":"Day Dish Technique Key Point Mon Carne Asada Tacos Citrus marinade; extreme-heat grill or cast iron Thin cut; rest; slice against grain Tue Pozole Rojo Dried chile rehydration + blend; hominy braise Toast chiles; don't burn Wed Guacamole + Salsa Verde Acid + salt timing; charred tomatillos Rinse onion before adding to guac Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Tacos al Pastor Achiote marinade; comal/broiler finish Pineapple chunk is not optional Sat PROJECT: Enchiladas Rojas Dip tortilla in sauce; roll; bake Sauce first, not smothered after"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/quick-ref.html#week-34-deeper-mexico-birria-mole-tamales","title":"Week 34 \u2014 Deeper Mexico: Birria, Mole, Tamales","text":"Day Dish Technique Key Point Mon Birria de Res All-day braise in chile marinade; consomm\u00e9 Save broth for dipping Tue Simplified Mole Negro Multi-chile; chocolate; long simmer Balance bitter (chile) + sweet (chocolate, raisins) Wed Tamales Masa dough; corn husks; steam 1.5 hrs Spread masa thin; test one float test Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Chiles Rellenos Broil + peel; egg-white batter fry Beat whites stiff; stuff cold Sat PROJECT: Full Mexican Celebration Multi-dish service from both weeks Prep botanas first; keep mains warm"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/quick-ref.html#key-dried-chile-reference","title":"Key Dried Chile Reference","text":"Chile Heat Flavor Common Use Ancho Mild Chocolate, berry, prune Mole, enchilada sauce, pozole Guajillo Mild-medium Fruity, bright Pozole, birria marinade Mulato Mild Chocolate, smoky Mole negro Pasilla Mild-medium Earthy, raisin-like Mole, salsas Chipotle (dried) Hot Smoky Adobo, salsas; also available canned \u00c1rbol Hot Bright, clean heat Salsas, birria"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/quick-ref.html#tortilla-basics","title":"Tortilla Basics","text":"<ul> <li>Corn tortillas \u2014 masa harina + water; press with tortilla press; cook 60\u201390 sec/side on hot comal</li> <li>Flour tortillas \u2014 wheat flour + fat + water; softer; roll thin; cook 30\u201345 sec/side</li> <li>Warm for service: Wrap in damp paper towel and microwave, or keep in foil in 200\u00b0F oven</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 37\u201338: Mexican","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Where to shop: A Mexican grocery or Latin market is the right place for dried chiles, hominy, masa harina, fresh tortillas, tomatillos, Mexican oregano, achiote paste, and queso fresco. These are not optional upgrades \u2014 they're the correct ingredients.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Tortilla press \u2014 for making corn tortillas from scratch ($15\u201320, worth it)</li> <li>[ ] Comal or flat cast iron griddle \u2014 for tortillas and carne asada</li> <li>[ ] Blender \u2014 for chile sauces; must be high-powered to blend rehydrated chiles</li> <li>[ ] Steamer / tamale pot \u2014 for tamales (large pot with rack works)</li> <li>[ ] Dutch oven \u2014 pozole, birria, enchilada braise</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-33","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 33","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Flank or skirt steak \u2014 1.5 lbs (Mon carne asada)</li> <li>[ ] Pork shoulder \u2014 2 lbs (Tue pozole + Fri al pastor)</li> <li>[ ] Bone-in chicken thighs \u2014 4 (Sat enchiladas, or ground beef for picadillo filling)</li> <li>[ ] Ground beef or pork \u2014 1 lb (Sat enchilada filling \u2014 or use leftover braised pork)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-34","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 34","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Beef chuck \u2014 3 lbs (Mon birria)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken thighs \u2014 4\u20136 (Tue mole)</li> <li>[ ] Pork shoulder \u2014 1 lb if making pork tamale filling (Wed; or use birria leftovers)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (Fri chiles rellenos batter)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/shopping-list.html#dried-chiles-buy-at-mexican-market","title":"\ud83c\udf36\ufe0f Dried Chiles (buy at Mexican market)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Guajillo \u2014 6 pods</li> <li>[ ] Ancho \u2014 4 pods</li> <li>[ ] Mulato \u2014 3 pods (mole)</li> <li>[ ] Pasilla \u2014 2 pods (mole)</li> <li>[ ] \u00c1rbol \u2014 4 dry pods (birria + salsas)</li> <li>[ ] Chipotle in adobo \u2014 1 small can (al pastor marinade + backup)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Tomatillos \u2014 1 lb (Wed salsa verde + Fri chiles rellenos salsa)</li> <li>[ ] Poblano peppers \u2014 10 (Fri chiles rellenos \u00d7 4\u20136; spare for enchiladas)</li> <li>[ ] Avocados \u2014 6 (Wed guacamole + tacos throughout)</li> <li>[ ] Jalape\u00f1os \u2014 4 (various)</li> <li>[ ] Serrano chiles \u2014 2 (guac heat)</li> <li>[ ] Cilantro \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] White onion \u2014 3 (various; always rinsed before adding raw)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 3 heads</li> <li>[ ] Limes \u2014 8</li> <li>[ ] Oranges \u2014 3 (carne asada marinade + al pastor)</li> <li>[ ] Tomatoes \u2014 6 (pico de gallo, enchilada sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Radishes \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Pineapple \u2014 1 (al pastor Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Mexican dried oregano (different from Italian)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/shopping-list.html#masa-and-corn","title":"\ud83c\udf3d Masa and Corn","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Masa harina (Maseca) \u2014 2-lb bag (tamales + corn tortillas)</li> <li>[ ] Canned hominy \u2014 2 \u00d7 29-oz cans (Tue pozole, or cook dried hominy from scratch)</li> <li>[ ] Corn husks \u2014 1 bag (Wed tamales)</li> <li>[ ] Corn tortillas \u2014 2 packs (various tacos; good to have even if you make some)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-mexican/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Achiote paste \u2014 1 small block or tablespoon (al pastor marinade Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Cumin \u2014 ground, large jar</li> <li>[ ] Mexican cinnamon (Ceylon) \u2014 1 stick</li> <li>[ ] Dark chocolate (70%+) \u2014 2 oz (mole)</li> <li>[ ] Raisins \u2014 small bag (mole)</li> <li>[ ] Sesame seeds \u2014 (mole)</li> <li>[ ] Pumpkin seeds (pepitas) \u2014 (mole + garnish)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken or beef stock \u2014 2 quarts</li> <li>[ ] Lard or shortening \u2014 for tamale masa fat (lard is traditional; makes it better)</li> <li>[ ] Refried beans \u2014 canned as backup; or make from scratch with pinto beans</li> <li>[ ] Black beans \u2014 2 \u00d7 15-oz cans or 1 lb dried</li> </ul> <p>Fresh cheeses (buy at Mexican market): - [ ] Queso fresco \u2014 8 oz - [ ] Oaxacan cheese (quesillo) \u2014 4 oz (chiles rellenos or quesabirria) - [ ] Crema Mexicana \u2014 1 cup (not the same as sour cream; thinner and tangy)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html","title":"Weeks 39\u201340: Indian","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 37\u201338: Mexican | Weeks 41\u201342: Middle Eastern \u2192</p> <p>\"Indian cooking is chemistry in practice \u2014 the Maillard reaction in a tarka, the emulsion of yogurt in a marinade, the solubility of fat-soluble spice compounds in hot ghee. Learning to cook Indian food teaches you the molecular logic underneath every other cuisine, disguised as flavor.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#week-35-spice-mastery-butter-chicken-dal-and-naan","title":"Week 35 \u2014 Spice Mastery: Butter Chicken, Dal, and Naan","text":"<p>The first Indian week focuses on three foundational preparations: a tomato-cream curry (butter chicken), a lentil dish that teaches spice bloom and dal texture (moong dal), and flatbread from scratch (naan). Together they cover the core skills of Indian stovetop cooking.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#monday-butter-chicken-murgh-makhani","title":"Monday \u2014 Butter Chicken (Murgh Makhani)","text":"<p>Skill: Tandoor-style marination; tomato cream sauce construction; achieving the balance no restaurant can get wrong Read first: Stovetop Butter Chicken</p> <p>What you're learning: Butter chicken (murgh makhani) is North Indian restaurant cooking at a global scale \u2014 marinated chicken (yogurt + spices + char under a broiler), then simmered in a buttery tomato cream sauce. The SE version happens entirely on the stovetop. The lesson: blooming whole spices in butter or ghee before adding aromatics and sauce unlocks fat-soluble flavor compounds.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Butter Chicken - Basmati rice - Store-bought naan (garlic naan is fine; you'll make fresh on Thursday)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Lower-Calorie Butter Chicken (Ethan Chlebowski) \u2014 He approaches the same dish analytically \u2014 compare his sauce construction and fat tradeoffs to the SE version you made.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#tuesday-moong-dal-yellow-split-lentils","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Moong Dal (Yellow Split Lentils)","text":"<p>Skill: Tarka (spice bloomed in fat); dal texture from liquid ratio; tempering as finishing technique Read first: Moong Dal</p> <p>What you're learning: A tarka is hot ghee or oil with spices (cumin seed, mustard seed, dry chiles, asafoetida) fried until they pop and bloom, then poured over the finished dal. The sizzle and fragrance is the signal \u2014 overcooked tarka becomes bitter, undercooked misses the bloom entirely. This is one of the most-used techniques in Indian cooking.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Moong Dal with tarka finish - Rice + papad (store-bought poppadom) - Mango pickle on the side</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#wednesday-chicken-tikka-masala-grilled-version","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Chicken Tikka Masala (Grilled Version)","text":"<p>Skill: Tikka marinade; charring on high heat; integrating char flavor into sauce Read first: Chicken Tikka Masala for the Grill</p> <p>What you're learning: Tikka masala is arguably the most popular Indian-origin dish in the English-speaking world. The SE grill version gives the chicken the char you otherwise get from a tandoor. The masala sauce (tomato, cream, ginger, garam masala) is richer and more accessible than butter chicken's sauce but built the same way.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Chicken Tikka Masala (grilled tikka + masala sauce) - Basmati rice - Cucumber raita (yogurt + cucumber + cumin + salt) \u2014 cooling contrast, always needed</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#thursday-garlic-naan-from-scratch","title":"Thursday \u2014 Garlic Naan from Scratch","text":"<p>Skill: Leavened flatbread technique; cast-iron skillet substitute for tandoor; garlic + butter finish Read first: Garlic Naan</p> <p>What you're learning: Naan requires yeast or baking powder, yogurt (for color and tang), and extremely high heat. A fully preheated cast iron skillet at maximum heat is the home substitute for a 900\u00b0F tandoor. The result should have char spots, a slight chew, and elastic pull. Once you can make fresh naan, takeout naan will feel like a step backward.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Garlic Naan \u00d7 8\u201310 (it's flatbread night \u2014 pair with leftover dal from Tuesday or butter chicken)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Naan in a Pizza Oven \u2014 Watch how he manages extreme heat and why the char spots are a feature, not a mistake.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#friday-dal-makhani-all-day-slow-dal","title":"Friday \u2014 Dal Makhani (All-Day Slow Dal)","text":"<p>Skill: Long-cook black lentil + kidney bean dal; cream integration; patience Read first: Dal Makhani</p> <p>What you're learning: Dal makhani is the richest, most complex dal in the Punjabi repertoire \u2014 black urad lentils and kidney beans cooked for hours until they become creamy and almost stew-like, finished with cream and butter. The SE version adapts this to a pressure cooker for efficiency. The traditional version simmers overnight on a dying fire; the slow cooker is a valid home interpretation.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Dal Makhani - Basmati rice + naan (from Thursday's batch if any remain) - Chopped tomato, onion, cucumber salad alongside</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Dal Makhani (Ranveer Brar) \u2014 Restaurant-trained perspective on the long cook; pay attention to his point about why time \u2014 not more cream \u2014 is what makes dal makhani creamy.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#saturday-project-north-indian-feast","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: North Indian Feast","text":"<p>Skill: Coordinating multiple Indian dishes for simultaneous service Goal: Recreate a North Indian restaurant spread at home:</p> <ol> <li>Starters: Samosas (store-bought is fine, focus on chutney \u2014 make a tamarind chutney and mint chutney)</li> <li>Main dal: Dal makhani or moong dal</li> <li>Main curry: Butter chicken or tikka masala (from batch earlier in week)</li> <li>Bread: Fresh naan from Thursday</li> <li>Sides: Raita, papad, mango pickle</li> </ol> <p>Full Meal: - Full Indian banquet spread - Chai (Indian milk tea \u2014 steep strong black tea with ginger, cardamom, cinnamon, milk, sugar)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#week-36-south-india-vegetarian-mastery","title":"Week 36 \u2014 South India + Vegetarian Mastery","text":"<p>South Indian cooking is different from North Indian in almost every way: less cream, more coconut, more lentils, more rice, and hotter. Idli, dosa, sambar, rasam \u2014 a different grammar entirely.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#monday-chana-masala-chickpea-curry","title":"Monday \u2014 Chana Masala (Chickpea Curry)","text":"<p>Skill: Dried chickpea preparation; tomato + onion + spice masala from scratch; amchur (dry mango powder) as souring agent Read first: Chana Masala</p> <p>What you're learning: Chana masala is one of the great vegetarian dishes in the world. The chickpeas absorb spices during cooking and take on the sauce's character. Amchur (dried unripe mango powder) plus fresh lemon is what makes chana taste like chana rather than generic chickpea stew \u2014 it's the acidic finish that completes it.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Chana Masala - Puri (fried hollow puffy bread \u2014 or plain roti, or naan) - Sliced raw onion and lemon</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Quick Chole Masala (Ranveer Brar) \u2014 Watch his masala-building sequence and how long he cooks the tomato down; the amchur addition near the end is the technique note to compare against your version.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#tuesday-aloo-gobi-potato-and-cauliflower","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Aloo Gobi (Potato and Cauliflower)","text":"<p>Skill: Dry vegetable curry (no sauce); blooming spices in oil before vegetables; understanding dry vs. wet curry Read first: Aloo Gobi</p> <p>What you're learning: Aloo gobi is a dry curry \u2014 no sauce, no cream, just spiced vegetables cooked until tender and slightly crispy at the edges. The spice bloom is everything. The technique of cooking out raw spice smell in oil (bhunao) before adding vegetables is the central skill.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Aloo Gobi - Roti or naan - Toor dal alongside (quick version \u2014 see Thursday Week 35 moong dal approach, applied to toor)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#wednesday-lamb-biryani","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Lamb Biryani","text":"<p>Skill: Dum cooking (sealed pot, rice and meat layers); spiced rice; marinated lamb Read first: Lamb Biryani</p> <p>What you're learning: Biryani is one of the most complex Indian preparations \u2014 marinated meat, par-cooked rice, saffron milk, fried onions, and aromatics layered and then sealed (\"dum\") and steamed together for the final cook. The seal preserves steam, which finishes the rice and meat simultaneously. The result: each grain of rice is separate, fragrant, and distinct.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Lamb Biryani - Plain yogurt (raita) to cool against the spice - Simple green salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Chicken Dum Biryani (Ranveer Brar) \u2014 He uses chicken; you used lamb. Watch the dum sealing technique and par-cook timing \u2014 those are what transfer directly regardless of protein.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#thursday-rest-day","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":"<p>Reflect: Indian food uses 20 spices. French food uses 5 herbs. Japanese food uses 10 condiments. Which approach to flavoring feels most intuitive to you? What blends surprised you?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#friday-garam-masala-from-scratch-spice-inventory","title":"Friday \u2014 Garam Masala from Scratch + Spice Inventory","text":"<p>Skill: Dry-toasting and grinding whole spices; building a custom blend; understanding garam masala's role Read first: Garam Masala</p> <p>What you're learning: Garam masala is not curry powder and not a substitute for it. It's a warm spice blend (cardamom, cinnamon, cloves, black pepper, cumin, coriander) used at the end of cooking to reinforce aroma, not during early stages. Make a small batch from whole toasted spices. Taste it against store-bought \u2014 the difference is remarkable.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Make garam masala as the session - Cook a simple tarka dal using your fresh blend vs. one portion with store-bought - Taste compare + serve both as dinner with rice</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#saturday-project-south-indian-weekend","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: South Indian Weekend","text":"<p>Skill: Dosai batter fermentation; sambar construction; full South Indian thali Goal: Try a South Indian preparation:</p> <ul> <li>Masala dosa: fermented lentil and rice batter crepe filled with spiced potato (requires batter made Thursday or Friday night in advance \u2014 or use fast-sour version)</li> <li>Sambar: Toor dal-based vegetable soup / curry (tamarind-based, South Indian)</li> <li>Coconut chutney: Fresh coconut + green chiles + curry leaves</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: - Masala Dosa + Sambar + Coconut Chutney (South Indian thali) - Filter coffee if possible (South Indian coffee \u2192 chicory blend brewed through a metal filter)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#spice-blooming-why-the-order-matters","title":"Spice Blooming: Why the Order Matters","text":"<p>Indian cooking is largely about controlling heat's interaction with spice. Whole spices into hot oil before anything else \u2014 tempering \u2014 unlocks volatile flavor compounds that grinding and adding late cannot reproduce.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Stovetop Butter Chicken \u2014 The full technique for the dish you cooked, with the science behind the spice sequencing.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Moong Dal \u2014 Dal is the most honest expression of Indian pantry cooking. This recipe shows exactly how the tarka (tempered spice) finishes the dish.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#the-indian-pantry","title":"The Indian Pantry","text":"<p>Indian cooking draws on a pantry of 20\u201330 spices, but most dishes use the same core six: cumin, coriander, turmeric, chili, garam masala, and black mustard seed. Stocking these seven items puts 80% of the recipes within reach.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How Ghee Makes Everything Taste Better \u2014 Ghee is clarified butter with the milk solids removed \u2014 giving it a higher smoke point and a richer, nuttier flavor than butter. This explainer covers what it is, how to make it, and why Indian cooking depends on it.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Madhur Jaffrey's Indian Cooking \u2014 The woman who taught a generation of Western cooks to make Indian food at home. Every episode is a lesson in spice management.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda An Invitation to Indian Cooking by Madhur Jaffrey \u2014 The book that introduced Indian home cooking to the English-speaking world. Still the best starting point for building a usable Indian cooking repertoire.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Weeks 37\u201338: Mexican | Weeks 41\u201342: Middle Eastern \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Weeks 39\u201340: Indian","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/quick-ref.html#week-35-north-indian-fundamentals","title":"Week 35 \u2014 North Indian Fundamentals","text":"Day Dish Technique Key Point Mon Butter Chicken Spice bloom in ghee; tomato cream sauce Broil chicken first for char Tue Moong Dal + Tarka Tarka = spices bloomed in hot fat poured over Cumin seed should sizzle immediately Wed Chicken Tikka Masala Grill char on tikka; masala sauce Yogurt marinade minimum 2 hrs Thu Garlic Naan Yeast flatbread on screaming-hot cast iron Preheat pan minimum 5 min Fri Dal Makhani Long-cook black lentils; cream + butter finish Pressure cooker shortcut: 40 min Sat PROJECT: North Indian Feast Multi-dish banquet coordination Reheat curries; fresh naan last"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/quick-ref.html#week-36-south-india-vegetarian-mastery","title":"Week 36 \u2014 South India + Vegetarian Mastery","text":"Day Dish Technique Key Point Mon Chana Masala Dried chickpea soak + tomato masala Amchur or lemon at finish Tue Aloo Gobi Dry curry; bhunao spice technique No sauce \u2014 crispy edges matter Wed Lamb Biryani Dum (sealed steam cook); layered rice Par-cook rice before layering Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Garam Masala from Scratch Toast whole spices; grind fresh Use at end of cooking, not beginning Sat PROJECT: South Indian Thali Dosa + sambar + coconut chutney Ferment batter Thu/Fri night"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/quick-ref.html#key-indian-spice-reference","title":"Key Indian Spice Reference","text":"Spice Technique When to Add Example Use Cumin seeds Toast whole in fat Beginning (tarka) Dal, rice Mustard seeds Sizzle in fat until popping Beginning (tarka) South Indian, dal Turmeric Add to onion; cook out raw flavor Early All curries Garam masala Ground blend At end / finish Butter chicken, tikka Amchur (dry mango powder) Add near end Finish Chana masala Asafoetida (hing) Tiny pinch, never cook too long With tarka Dal (digestive role)"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/quick-ref.html#dal-water-to-lentil-ratios","title":"Dal Water-to-Lentil Ratios","text":"Lentil Cup Ratio (lentils:water) Cook Time Moong dal (split yellow) 1:3 20\u201325 min stovetop Toor dal (pigeon peas) 1:3 25\u201330 min stovetop Masoor dal (red lentils) 1:2.5 15\u201320 min stovetop Urad dal (black, whole) 1:4 45 min\u20131 hr (or pressure cooker) Chana dal (chickpea split) 1:3 30\u201340 min stovetop"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 39\u201340: Indian","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Where to shop: An Indian grocery store is mandatory for this block. You need fresh curry leaves, mustard seeds, asafoetida (hing), whole spices, moong dal, urad dal, idli/dosa rice, mango pickle, and ghee at proper prices and quality.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Heavy cast iron skillet \u2014 for naan and dosa</li> <li>[ ] Spice grinder or coffee grinder \u2014 for garam masala and fresh spice grinding</li> <li>[ ] Pressure cooker or Instant Pot \u2014 for dal makhani and biryani (quicker versions)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-35","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 35","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Chicken thighs, boneless \u2014 3 lbs (Mon butter chicken + Wed tikka masala)</li> <li>[ ] Lamb shoulder or cubes \u2014 1.5 lbs (Wed biryani Week 36; buy early)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-36","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 36","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (various; dosa batter)</li> <li>[ ] (Weeks 36 is largely vegetarian \u2014 no additional meat purchase required)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/shopping-list.html#lentils-and-beans","title":"\ud83e\uded8 Lentils and Beans","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Moong dal (yellow split mung) \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Whole urad dal (black lentils) \u2014 1 lb (dal makhani Fri Week 35)</li> <li>[ ] Toor dal (pigeon peas) \u2014 1 lb (sambar Week 36 Sat + weekday dal)</li> <li>[ ] Dried chickpeas \u2014 1 lb (Mon Week 36 chana masala; or 2 \u00d7 15-oz cans)</li> <li>[ ] Rajma (kidney beans) \u2014 \u00bd lb (dal makhani)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 4 heads</li> <li>[ ] Ginger \u2014 1 large piece (use throughout)</li> <li>[ ] White onions \u2014 4 large</li> <li>[ ] Tomatoes \u2014 10 (pureed for sauces + fresh sides)</li> <li>[ ] Cauliflower \u2014 1 head (Tue Week 36 aloo gobi)</li> <li>[ ] Yukon gold potatoes \u2014 2 lbs (Tue + biryani + various)</li> <li>[ ] Lemon \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Serrano or green chiles \u2014 10 (used daily in small amounts)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh cilantro \u2014 3 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Cucumber \u2014 4 (raita)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh curry leaves \u2014 1 sprig (Indian grocery; South Indian tarka)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/shopping-list.html#dairy","title":"\ud83e\udd5b Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Full-fat yogurt \u2014 2 lbs (marinade + raita + naan dough)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream or double cream \u2014 1 pint (butter chicken, dal makhani)</li> <li>[ ] Ghee \u2014 8 oz jar (use throughout; superior to butter for Indian cooking)</li> <li>[ ] Whole milk \u2014 1 quart (chai + various)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/shopping-list.html#whole-spices-buy-at-indian-market","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Whole Spices (buy at Indian market)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Cumin seeds \u2014 large bag</li> <li>[ ] Coriander seeds \u2014 large bag</li> <li>[ ] Mustard seeds (black/brown) \u2014 1 bag</li> <li>[ ] Cardamom pods (green) \u2014 1 small bag</li> <li>[ ] Black cardamom pods \u2014 4\u20135 (biryani)</li> <li>[ ] Cinnamon sticks \u2014 4</li> <li>[ ] Whole cloves \u2014 1 small bag</li> <li>[ ] Black peppercorns \u2014 1 bag</li> <li>[ ] Dried red chiles \u2014 1 bag</li> <li>[ ] Bay leaves \u2014 Indian variety (tegpatta)</li> <li>[ ] Mace \u2014 1 small bag (biryani)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/shopping-list.html#ground-spices-condiments","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Ground Spices + Condiments","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Turmeric \u2014 large jar</li> <li>[ ] Cumin (ground) \u2014 large jar</li> <li>[ ] Coriander (ground) \u2014 large jar</li> <li>[ ] Kashmiri red chili powder \u2014 1 jar (mild heat + color)</li> <li>[ ] Regular red chili powder or cayenne \u2014 1 jar (heat)</li> <li>[ ] Garam masala \u2014 store-bought (for comparison; also make fresh Fri Week 36)</li> <li>[ ] Amchur (dry mango powder) \u2014 1 bag (chana masala)</li> <li>[ ] Asafoetida (hing) \u2014 small jar (dal tarka; tiny amount goes very far)</li> <li>[ ] Coconut milk \u2014 2 cans (South Indian thali + sambar)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-indian/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83c\udf5a Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Basmati rice \u2014 5-lb bag</li> <li>[ ] All-purpose flour + bread flour (naan dough)</li> <li>[ ] Instant yeast \u2014 1 packet (naan)</li> <li>[ ] Saffron \u2014 small pinch (biryani)</li> <li>[ ] Tamarind paste \u2014 1 jar (sambar Week 36 Sat)</li> <li>[ ] Mango pickle (achar) \u2014 1 jar</li> <li>[ ] Papad (poppadum) \u2014 1 pack</li> <li>[ ] Samosas \u2014 store-bought fine for Saturday feast accompaniment</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html","title":"Weeks 41\u201342: Middle Eastern","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 39\u201340: Indian | Weeks 43\u201344: Southeast Asian \u2192</p> <p>\"Middle Eastern cooking is not a single cuisine \u2014 it's a family of cuisines spanning Persian, Lebanese, Israeli, Syrian, Turkish, Yemeni, Egyptian, and North African traditions, each distinct, many overlapping. What they share: olive oil, citrus, aromatics, legumes, and fire applied with extraordinary restraint. Start with hummus. Build from there.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#week-37-hummus-shakshuka-shawarma-and-the-mezze-framework","title":"Week 37 \u2014 Hummus, Shakshuka, Shawarma, and the Mezze Framework","text":"<p>The first week focuses on building the foundational components of a Middle Eastern meal: the mezze (small plates), the key dips, and one main protein (shawarma). By week's end you'll have the components for a complete mezze spread.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#monday-hummus-btahini-from-scratch","title":"Monday \u2014 Hummus b'Tahini (From Scratch)","text":"<p>Skill: Dried chickpea cooking to the right texture; tahini ratio; blending technique for silky result Read first: Hummus b'Tahini</p> <p>What you're learning: Hummus from canned chickpeas is acceptable. Hummus from dried chickpeas cooked with baking soda until almost crumbling, then blended warm into tahini \u2014 is a revelation. The warm chickpeas blend more efficiently. The baking soda softens the skins, which can be rubbed off for ultra-smooth result. This is the technique.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Hummus b'Tahini with olive oil, cumin, paprika, and warm pita - Sliced cucumbers and tomatoes alongside</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to LEVEL UP Hummus (Middle Eats) \u2014 He focuses on the specific tricks that separate home hummus from restaurant hummus; compare his chickpea cooking approach and blending technique to yours.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#tuesday-shakshuka","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Shakshuka","text":"<p>Skill: Tomato and pepper sauce construction; poaching eggs in sauce Read first: Shakshuka \u2014 North African Shirred Eggs</p> <p>What you're learning: Shakshuka is eggs poached in a spiced tomato and pepper sauce \u2014 one of the great one-pan meals of global cooking. The sauce (onion, peppers, tomato, cumin, paprika, often harissa) is made first, then wells are made in the sauce, eggs cracked in, and everything covered until the whites are set but the yolks still run. Timing is the only hard part.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Shakshuka with crusty bread or pita for scooping - Labneh (strained yogurt; buy or make) on the side</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#wednesday-baba-ganoush-muhammara","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Baba Ganoush + Muhammara","text":"<p>Skill: Char-roasting eggplant for smoky flavor; red pepper walnut dip technique Read first: The Best Baba Ganoush | Muhammara</p> <p>What you're learning: Baba ganoush requires eggplant charred directly over a gas flame or under a broiler until the skin is entirely black and the interior is soft. This char creates the smoke flavor that makes baba ganoush what it is \u2014 without it, it's just mashed eggplant. Muhammara (Syrian roasted red pepper and walnut dip) is the day's second preparation \u2014 make both and compare how they complement versus compete on a mezze board.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Mezze board: baba ganoush + muhammara + hummus (from Monday) + pita - Falafel from the freezer or store (you'll make fresh on Friday)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Creamiest Baba Ghanoush (Middle Eats) \u2014 Watch how long he lets the eggplant char; most home cooks stop too early and miss the smoke flavor that makes the dish what it is.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#thursday-rest-day","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":"<p>Reflect: All three starters from this week (hummus, baba ganoush, muhammara) require a pur\u00e9e from scratch. Compare the textural outcomes: what makes each one distinct? What tool used (blender vs. food processor vs. mortar and pestle) changed the result?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#friday-falafel","title":"Friday \u2014 Falafel","text":"<p>Skill: Dried chickpea-based falafel; herb incorporation; frying temperature management Read first: The Best Homemade Falafel</p> <p>What you're learning: Falafel uses dried (never canned) chickpeas soaked but not cooked \u2014 they're ground raw with herbs and spices and fried. Canned chickpeas produce wet, dense, falling-apart falafel. The raw soak approach gives the right texture: crispy outside, bright green inside. Fry at 350\u00b0F, 3 minutes.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Falafel in warm pita with tahini sauce, tomato, cucumber, pickled onions - Fattoush salad alongside (Fattoush) \u2014 fried pita + fresh vegetables + sumac dressing</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Falafel \u2014 He's emphatic about dried vs. canned chickpeas; watch the texture difference he describes and why canned ones fail.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#saturday-project-beef-shawarma","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Beef Shawarma","text":"<p>Skill: Thin beef marinade and cooking stack concept; shawarma wrap assembly Read first: Beef Shawarma</p> <p>What you're learning: Shawarma is a vertical rotisserie street food adapted at home as thin-sliced marinated beef (or chicken) cooked in a very hot pan or under a broiler to get the char-and-rendered-fat effect of a spit. The spice profile (cumin, coriander, cinnamon, cardamom, turmeric, garlic) is distinct from Indian spicing despite appearing similar. The wrap (pita + chicken or beef + pickled vegetables + tahini) is the delivery vehicle.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Beef Shawarma wraps with garlic sauce (toum) \u2014 mashed garlic + lemon + oil emulsion - Tabbouleh (Tabbouleh Salad) as a side \u2014 mostly fresh parsley, not mostly bulgur</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Legit Chicken Shawarma at Home (Middle Eats) \u2014 He uses chicken; you used beef \u2014 the marinade spice logic is the same. Compare his thin-sear technique and how both versions replicate the spit char at home.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#week-38-kebabs-adana-and-the-aromatic-rice-traditions","title":"Week 38 \u2014 Kebabs, Adana, and the Aromatic Rice Traditions","text":""},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#monday-adana-kebab-turkish-ground-lamb-skewer","title":"Monday \u2014 Adana Kebab (Turkish Ground Lamb Skewer)","text":"<p>Skill: Hand-mixing ground lamb fat; skewer technique; flat metal skewer cooking Read first: Adana Kebab \u2014 Turkish Ground Lamb</p> <p>What you're learning: Adana kebab is ground lamb mixed with tail fat (or cold fatty lamb shoulder, ground finely) and red chile \u2014 shaped onto wide flat metal skewers and grilled directly over fire. The binding technique relies on kneading the mixture until it becomes sticky; this is what holds the lamb to the skewer without falling off.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Adana Kebab with warm flatbread, grilled tomatoes and peppers - Yogurt and sumac, sliced raw onion with sumac</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#tuesday-fattoush-tabbouleh-deep-dive","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Fattoush + Tabbouleh Deep Dive","text":"<p>Skill: Fried pita crisp; sumac dressing; understanding bulgur vs. couscous vs. freekeh Read first: Fattoush | Tabbouleh</p> <p>What you're learning: Both are Lebanese-origin salads, both involve fresh herbs, both use an acid-forward dressing. The difference: fattoush uses fried pita + pomegranate molasses + sumac; tabbouleh is mostly fresh parsley (minimal bulgur, widely misunderstood in the West). Cook both today and taste them back-to-back.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Fattoush + Tabbouleh (a vegetarian evening) - Hummus, pita, labneh to round it out</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Fattoush Lebanese Chopped Salad \u2014 Notice how the fried pita and sumac define the dish; compare his ratios to tabbouleh's herb-forward logic and see how different they actually are.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#wednesday-persian-style-herb-frittata-kuku-sabzi-or-rice-chelow","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Persian-Style Herb Frittata (Kuku Sabzi) or Rice (Chelow)","text":"<p>Skill: Herb-heavy egg bake; or Persian steamed rice with tahdig crust Read first: For kuku sabzi \u2014 use a handful each of fresh dill, parsley, cilantro, and fenugreek leaves (dried works), with eggs, turmeric, and barberries; baked or pan-cooked. For chelow with tahdig: Chelow (Persian Steamed White Rice) | Tahdig (Persian Crunchy Rice)</p> <p>What you're learning: Either preparation represents a distinct Persian approach absent from the rest of the Middle Eastern block. Chelow with tahdig (the crispy bottom) is a study in rice control: high starch rice, soaked, parboiled, then steamed with a lid lined with a towel that absorbs steam. The bottom goldifies into a crust that is split among the table.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Kuku Sabzi with yogurt and bread, OR Chelow with tahdig as a side to grilled lamb - Simple cucumber and tomato salad</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#thursday-rest-day_1","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":""},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#friday-kabsa-saudi-spiced-chicken-and-rice","title":"Friday \u2014 Kabsa (Saudi Spiced Chicken and Rice)","text":"<p>Skill: One-pot rice and chicken; aromatic spiced stock; kabsa spice profile Read first: Kabsa \u2014 Spiced Chicken and Rice</p> <p>What you're learning: Kabsa is the national dish of Saudi Arabia \u2014 a one-pot preparation where chicken is braised in a spiced tomato broth, then rice is cooked in that same broth, absorbing all the flavor. The spice profile (cardamom, cloves, cinnamon, black lime, rosewater) is distinct from any other \"spiced rice and meat\" dish you've made.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Kabsa with charred tomato salsa (dakka) on the side - Yogurt, flatbread</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#saturday-project-full-mezze-table","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Full Mezze Table","text":"<p>Skill: Coordinating, plating, and timing a traditional mezze spread Goal: Assemble the most complete mezze table you can from the two weeks of Middle Eastern cooking:</p> <p>Cold mezze: Hummus, baba ganoush, muhammara, tabbouleh, fattoush, labneh, olives, pita Hot mezze / mains: Falafel (fried fresh), adana kebab skewers, shawarma meat (reserved or freshly made) Sauces: Tahini, toum (garlic sauce), harissa Bread: Warm pita throughout</p> <p>Full Meal: - Complete Middle Eastern mezze table - Arak, mint tea, or lemon juice to drink</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#the-mezze-philosophy","title":"The Mezze Philosophy","text":"<p>Middle Eastern cooking is organized around the table, not the plate. Mezze \u2014 the spread of small dishes \u2014 is an eating philosophy as much as a cooking style. Hummus, baba ganoush, and tabbouleh are designed to be eaten together with bread, not sequentially.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Best Baba Ganoush \u2014 The technique that separates good baba ganoush (charred, smoky eggplant) from bad (oven-roasted, bland eggplant).</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Hummus with Tahini \u2014 The recipe, plus the technique notes that explain why restaurant hummus is always smoother than yours (until now).</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#tahini-and-olive-oil","title":"Tahini and Olive Oil","text":"<p>Two pantry ingredients define the flavors of this week's food. The quality of your tahini and olive oil shows up directly in everything you made.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Tahini Sauce With Garlic and Lemon \u2014 Kenji's guide to tahini sauce covers the ratio, the thin-down technique with cold water, and why the sauce tightens before it loosens. All of this connects directly to your hummus and everything else you drizzled this week.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Jerusalem by Yotam Ottolenghi &amp; Sami Tamimi \u2014 The most influential Middle Eastern cookbook of the past two decades, blending Israeli and Palestinian food traditions. Every dish you cooked this week has a deeper version here.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Weeks 39\u201340: Indian | Weeks 43\u201344: Southeast Asian \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Weeks 41\u201342: Middle Eastern","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/quick-ref.html#week-37-hummus-shakshuka-shawarma","title":"Week 37 \u2014 Hummus, Shakshuka, Shawarma","text":"Day Dish Technique Key Point Mon Hummus b'Tahini Dried chickpeas + baking soda; blend warm Warm chickpeas \u2192 silkier blend Tue Shakshuka Tomato-pepper sauce; eggs poached in it Don't over-set the yolks Wed Baba Ganoush + Muhammara Direct flame char; roasted pepper walnut blend Black eggplant skin = the smoke flavor Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Falafel + Fattoush Raw soaked chickpeas (never canned); 350\u00b0F fry Must use dried chickpeas Sat PROJECT: Beef Shawarma + Tabbouleh Thin-cut marinated beef; broil or sear hot Tabbouleh = mostly parsley"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/quick-ref.html#week-38-kebabs-grains-aromatic-rice","title":"Week 38 \u2014 Kebabs, Grains, Aromatic Rice","text":"Day Dish Technique Key Point Mon Adana Kebab Kneaded ground lamb on flat skewers Knead until sticky; no egg needed Tue Fattoush + Tabbouleh deep dive Fried pita; sumac; herb-heavy Both are acid-forward; compare them Wed Kuku Sabzi or Chelow with Tahdig Herb frittata or Persian steamed rice Tahdig: crust forms at bottom; requires confidence Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Kabsa One-pot rice + spiced chicken stock Black lime is essential Sat PROJECT: Full Mezze Table Multi-component spread from both weeks Cold mezze first; hot served last"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/quick-ref.html#middle-eastern-pantry-essentials","title":"Middle Eastern Pantry Essentials","text":"Ingredient Role Source Tahini Sesame paste; base for hummus, sauces Soom or Seed + Mill brand Sumac Tart red spice; dressings, kebab finish Middle Eastern market Za'atar Thyme-based herb blend; used on bread and labneh Middle Eastern market Pomegranate molasses Tart-sweet syrup; fattoush + glazes Middle Eastern market Dried black lime (loomi) Intensely citrusy; used whole in stews Middle Eastern market Rose water Floral; desserts + kabsa Middle Eastern market Harissa North African chile paste Available widely Labneh Strained yogurt; smooth, tart Make by straining Greek yogurt overnight"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/quick-ref.html#key-ratios","title":"Key Ratios","text":"Preparation Ratio Hummus tahini 1 cup cooked chickpeas : \u00bc cup tahini : 2 tbsp lemon : 1 garlic clove Tabbouleh By volume: \u00be parsley : \u00bc everything else (not the reverse) Tahini sauce 1 part tahini : 1 part lemon juice : garlic + water to thin Falafel Soak dried chickpeas 12\u201324 hrs; do not cook; grind raw"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 41\u201342: Middle Eastern","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Where to shop: A Middle Eastern market (Lebanese, Persian, Turkish, or Arab grocery) is strongly recommended. You need: dried chickpeas, quality tahini, sumac, pomegranate molasses, dried black lime, za'atar, labneh, and pita from a bakery if possible.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Food processor \u2014 for hummus, baba ganoush, muhammara, falafel grinding</li> <li>[ ] Flat metal skewers \u2014 for adana kebab (at least 4\u20136)</li> <li>[ ] Fine-mesh strainer \u2014 for labneh straining (cheesecloth works)</li> <li>[ ] Blender \u2014 blender gives silkier hummus than food processor</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-37","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 37","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Beef \u2014 flank, skirt, or sirloin, 2 lbs (Sat shawarma \u2014 marinate Fri night)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (Tue shakshuka + Wed frittata Week 38)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-38","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 38","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Ground lamb \u2014 1.5 lbs (Mon adana kebab)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken thighs, bone-in \u2014 4 (Fri kabsa)</li> <li>[ ] Optional additional protein \u2014 chicken thighs or lamb for Sat mezze table</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#legumes","title":"\ud83e\uded8 Legumes","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dried chickpeas \u2014 2 lbs (hummus Mon + falafel Fri \u2014 must be dried, not canned)</li> <li>[ ] Canned chickpeas \u2014 1 can (backup for quick applications mid-week)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#produce-week-37","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 37","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Eggplant \u2014 3 medium (Wed baba ganoush; char all 3)</li> <li>[ ] Red bell peppers \u2014 4 (Wed muhammara; roast and peel)</li> <li>[ ] Walnuts \u2014 1 cup (Wed muhammara)</li> <li>[ ] Tomatoes \u2014 8 (Tue shakshuka + tabbouleh Sat + various)</li> <li>[ ] Red bell pepper \u2014 3 more (Tue shakshuka sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Italian frying peppers or cubanelle \u2014 4 (Tue shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Jalape\u00f1os \u2014 2 (shakshuka heat)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 4 bunches (tabbouleh is mostly parsley; use throughout)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh mint \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Green onions \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Cucumber \u2014 6 (mezze side, fattoush, tabbouleh)</li> <li>[ ] Romaine or Little Gem lettuce \u2014 1 head (fattoush base)</li> <li>[ ] Radishes \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 10 (used every day)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 4 heads</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#produce-week-38","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 38","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Pita bread \u2014 2 packs fresh (or buy from Middle Eastern bakery)</li> <li>[ ] Persian cucumbers \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 2 pints</li> <li>[ ] Pomegranate \u2014 1 (seeds for garnish Sat)</li> <li>[ ] Onion \u2014 4 medium (kabsa + various)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh herbs: parsley, mint, dill \u2014 additional bunches</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#pantry-middle-eastern-market","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry (Middle Eastern Market)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Tahini \u2014 1 large jar (Soom, Al Kanater, or Ziyad brand preferred)</li> <li>[ ] Sumac \u2014 1 small jar</li> <li>[ ] Za'atar \u2014 1 small jar</li> <li>[ ] Pomegranate molasses \u2014 1 bottle</li> <li>[ ] Dried black lime (loomi) \u2014 4\u20135 (kabsa Fri Week 38)</li> <li>[ ] Rose water \u2014 small bottle (kabsa)</li> <li>[ ] Harissa \u2014 1 jar or tube (shakshuka optional heat + mezze board)</li> <li>[ ] Labneh \u2014 1 tub (or make by straining Greek yogurt in cheesecloth overnight)</li> <li>[ ] Bulgur wheat \u2014 1 cup (tabbouleh \u2014 a tiny amount)</li> <li>[ ] Arak or pastis \u2014 optional for mezze drinks</li> <li>[ ] Pita chips \u2014 for mezze board (or fry stale pita for fattoush crisps)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#spices","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Spices","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Cumin \u2014 ground</li> <li>[ ] Coriander \u2014 ground</li> <li>[ ] Allspice \u2014 ground (shawarma)</li> <li>[ ] Cinnamon \u2014 ground</li> <li>[ ] Cardamom \u2014 ground (kabsa)</li> <li>[ ] Cloves \u2014 ground (kabsa)</li> <li>[ ] Turmeric \u2014 ground</li> <li>[ ] Smoked paprika</li> <li>[ ] Red pepper flakes + cayenne</li> <li>[ ] Black pepper</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#pantry-staples","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry Staples","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Olive oil \u2014 1 large bottle (extra-virgin; used for basically everything)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken stock \u2014 2 quarts (kabsa + shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Canned San Marzano tomatoes \u2014 2 cans (shakshuka + kabsa)</li> <li>[ ] Basmati rice \u2014 5 lbs (kabsa + multiple meals)</li> <li>[ ] Greek yogurt \u2014 32 oz (raita, labneh, shakshuka side)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html","title":"Weeks 43\u201344: Module 4 Capstone \u2014 Southeast Asian Cuisines","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 41\u201342: Middle Eastern | Weeks 45\u201346: Bread \u2192</p> <p>\"Southeast Asian cooking is the most flavor-dense cooking on earth per ingredient \u2014 the balance between salt (fish sauce), sour (lime), sweet (palm sugar), and heat (chili) is the entire lesson. Get that balance right in a pad Thai or a bowl of pho, and you understand the grammar of the whole region.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#week-39-the-big-four-thailand-vietnam-indonesia-malaysia","title":"Week 39 \u2014 The Big Four: Thailand, Vietnam, Indonesia, Malaysia","text":"<p>Southeast Asia is not one cuisine but a family of distinct traditions connected by rice, fish sauce, lemongrass, galangal, and the philosophy that every dish should balance all five flavors simultaneously. This week covers the central dishes of each major tradition.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#monday-pad-thai","title":"Monday \u2014 Pad Thai","text":"<p>Skill: Wok technique for noodles; tamarind-palm sugar sauce balance; egg incorporation Read first: Pad Thai</p> <p>What you're learning: Pad Thai isn't a dump-everything noodle \u2014 it's a study in wok heat management, timing, and the push-pull of the five flavors. The sauce (tamarind + fish sauce + palm sugar) must be pre-mixed and tasted before the noodles ever hit the pan. If the sauce is right, the dish is 80% there.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pad Thai with shrimp (or tofu) - Bean sprouts, peanuts, lime, green onion served at the table for individual seasoning</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: My BEST Authentic Pad Thai Recipe (Pailin's Kitchen) \u2014 Watch her handling of the noodle-to-heat ratio and the tamarind sourcing decision. Her explanation of what \"authentic\" actually means in a Thai context is worth the full video.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#tuesday-traditional-beef-pho","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Traditional Beef Pho","text":"<p>Skill: Long bone broth (or pressure cooker shortcut); pho spice toasting; assembly Read first: Traditional Beef Pho</p> <p>What you're learning: Pho broth is charred ginger and onion + toasted cinnamon, star anise, cloves, and cardamom simmered with marrow bones for hours. The SE traditional version requires time (start morning). The finished broth should be clear, deeply fragrant, and lightly beefy. Everything goes in the bowl at service \u2014 herbs, sprouts, sliced raw beef (cooked by broth), lime on the side.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Traditional Beef Pho with full herb plate: Thai basil, cilantro, bean sprouts, lime, jalape\u00f1o, hoisin, sriracha</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Southern-Style Vietnamese Chicken Pho \u2014 He makes the chicken version; compare the broth-building logic and see how the aromatic charring technique carries across both.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#wednesday-nasi-goreng-indonesian-fried-rice","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Nasi Goreng (Indonesian Fried Rice)","text":"<p>Skill: Day-old rice technique; shrimp paste (terasi) handling; kecap manis application Read first: Nasi Goreng</p> <p>What you're learning: Nasi goreng is Indonesia's national fried rice \u2014 darker, more caramelized, and more complex than Chinese fried rice. The key ingredients: kecap manis (sweet soy sauce) and terasi (shrimp paste, which must be toasted in the pan). Make the day before's leftover rice the base.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Nasi Goreng topped with a fried egg (mandatory) and prawn crackers (krupuk) - Pickled cucumber + sliced tomato on the side</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Egg Fried Rice Three Ways \u2014 He shows the same day-old rice technique across three styles; notice what changes and what the wok heat is really doing in each version.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#thursday-rest-day","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":"<p>Reflect: Three countries in three days. Thailand's pad Thai, Vietnam's pho, Indonesia's nasi goreng. What's the common thread? What's the dominant seasoning logic in each?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#friday-curry-laksa-malaysian","title":"Friday \u2014 Curry Laksa (Malaysian)","text":"<p>Skill: Coconut curry broth; building the spice paste (rempah) from scratch; laksa garnish assembly Read first: Curry Laksa</p> <p>What you're learning: Laksa is a rich coconut curry noodle soup from Malaysia and Singapore with a spice paste base that includes lemongrass, galangal, dried shrimp, and shallots \u2014 blended and fried until fragrant. The broth is finished with coconut milk. The result is silky, spiced, and uniquely complex. It's one of the great noodle soups of the world.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Curry Laksa with tofu puffs, shrimp, bean sprouts, hard-boiled egg, laksa leaf - Sambal on the side</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Thai Green Curry Recipe \u2014 The Right Way (Pailin's Kitchen) \u2014 Coconut-based Southeast Asian curry vs. the laksa you just made: same base logic, different spice architecture. Watch how she blooms the paste before the coconut milk.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#saturday-project-thai-chicken-satay-som-tam","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Thai Chicken Satay + Som Tam","text":"<p>Skill: Satay marinade (turmeric, lemongrass, coconut milk); peanut sauce from scratch; green papaya prep Read first: Thai Chicken Satay | Som Tam \u2014 Green Papaya Salad</p> <p>What you're learning: Satay is Southeast Asian street food at its most elegant: thin strips of marinated chicken threaded on bamboo skewers, grilled over direct fire, served with peanut sauce and fresh cucumber. Som tam is the great Thai salad made of shredded unripe green papaya, fish sauce, lime, palm sugar, chiles, and peanuts \u2014 pounded in a mortar, not dressed like a Western salad.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Thai Chicken Satay with peanut sauce - Som Tam (green papaya salad) - Sticky rice if available</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Thai Pork Satay &amp; Peanut Sauce (Pailin's Kitchen) \u2014 Pork vs. chicken, same skewer. Her peanut sauce proportions are worth writing down \u2014 compare them directly to what you made.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#week-40-pad-see-ew-pho-ga-rendang-banh-mi-and-the-third-quarter-review","title":"Week 40 \u2014 Pad See Ew, Pho G\u00e0, Rendang, Banh Mi, and the Third Quarter Review","text":""},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#monday-pad-see-ew","title":"Monday \u2014 Pad See Ew","text":"<p>Skill: Wide rice noodle technique; high-wok-heat char (\"wok hei\"); soy-based noodle sauce Read first: Pad See Ew</p> <p>What you're learning: Pad See Ew uses wide rice noodles (sen yai) that require different handling than the thin noodles in pad Thai \u2014 they tear easily, must be very fresh, and need the highest possible heat to develop the char edges that make the dish. This is a wok heat exercise. Use the hottest burner you have.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pad See Ew with beef or chicken - Simple cucumber salad with rice vinegar</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#tuesday-chicken-pho-pho-ga-30-minute-pressure-cooker","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Chicken Pho (Pho G\u00e0 \u2014 30-Minute Pressure Cooker)","text":"<p>Skill: Pressure cooker pho technique; understanding pho g\u00e0 vs. pho b\u00f2; quick broth extraction Read first: 30-Minute Pressure Cooker Pho G\u00e0</p> <p>What you're learning: Pho g\u00e0 is lighter and faster than beef pho. The pressure cooker approach extracts enough flavor in 20\u201325 minutes from a whole chicken broken down with aromatics. Compare it to the beef pho from Monday Week 39 \u2014 how does the lighter chicken broth change the eating experience?</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pho G\u00e0 with the same herb plate: basil, lime, bean sprouts, chili</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#wednesday-banh-mi","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Banh Mi","text":"<p>Skill: Picking/curing the daikon and carrot; Vietnamese p\u00e2t\u00e9 or headcheese; bread selection Read first: Breakfast Banh Mi</p> <p>What you're learning: Banh mi is the culinary child of French colonialism \u2014 a baguette (French bread) filled with Vietnamese proteins and condiments. The DO-AHEAD element: the pickled daikon and carrot must be made at minimum 1 hour ahead (overnight is better). The bread must be light and crackly \u2014 a French roll, specifically.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Banh Mi sandwiches (one of: pork belly, grilled pork, chicken liver p\u00e2t\u00e9 + fried egg, or breakfast style) - Fresh jalape\u00f1o slices, cucumber spears, extra cilantro</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#thursday-rest-day-third-quarter-review","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day + Third Quarter Review","text":"<p>The Nine-Month Mark. Reflect: - What are the three most lasting technique improvements from the last three months? - What global cuisine surprised you the most? - Which dish from weeks 27\u201339 do you want to add to your regular rotation?</p> <p>Write a brief cook's journal entry today. You're 9 months through a 12-month program.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#friday-beef-rendang-malaysianindonesian","title":"Friday \u2014 Beef Rendang (Malaysian/Indonesian)","text":"<p>Skill: Dry coconut braising technique; toasting desiccated coconut; rendang spice paste Read first: Beef Rendang</p> <p>What you're learning: Rendang is one of the few dishes that is wet (a braise) when it starts and completely dry when it's done \u2014 the coconut milk reduces entirely, and the beef almost fries in its own coconut fat at the end. This creates an intensely caramelized, complex exterior that stores for a week at room temperature. A technical masterpiece.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Beef Rendang - Steamed jasmine rice and coconut rice (variation) - Cucumber and tomato kachumber</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#saturday-project-southeast-asian-dinner-party-selection","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Southeast Asian Dinner Party (Selection)","text":"<p>Skill: Multi-nationality Southeast Asian menu; timing a large spread Goal: Build a Southeast Asian dinner from dishes spanning the block:</p> <p>Choose 3\u20134: - Som Tam (can make ahead or make fresh) - Satay skewers (make fresh on the grill) - Curry Laksa (make broth ahead; assemble to order) - Nasi Goreng (best made on the spot at high heat) - Beef Rendang (reheat from Friday beautifully) - Pho G\u00e0 broth from Tuesday as an opening \"tea\"</p> <p>Full Meal: - Southeast Asian Dinner Party - Tropical fruit for dessert: mango, pineapple, papaya - Thai iced tea or fresh coconut water</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#fish-sauce-and-fermented-flavors","title":"Fish Sauce and Fermented Flavors","text":"<p>Fish sauce is the backbone flavor of Thai, Vietnamese, and Indonesian cooking the way soy sauce is for Japanese and Chinese. Understanding how to use it \u2014 early for depth, late for brightness \u2014 is the central skill of SE Asian cooking.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Pad Thai \u2014 The full recipe and technique breakdown, including the proper sequence for tamarind, fish sauce, and sugar.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Pad Kee Mao (Drunken Noodles) \u2014 Another noodle dish from the Thai canon, using similar technique with different aromatics.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Pad See Ew \u2014 The third of the major Thai noodle preparations. These three together cover the core wok-noodle technique at different heat levels.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#wok-hei-the-impossible-home-kitchen-goal","title":"Wok Hei: The Impossible Home Kitchen Goal","text":"<p>Wok hei \u2014 the breath of the wok \u2014 is the smoky, slightly charred flavor you taste at Thai and Chinese restaurants. It's produced by extremely high heat (above what most home burners can generate) and professional woks. You probably can't fully replicate it at home, but you can get closer.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Traditional Beef Pho \u2014 The 8-hour stock approach, the spice-toasting technique, and the charred ginger and onion that give pho its signature depth.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Hot, Sour, Salty, Sweet by Jeffrey Alford &amp; Naomi Duguid \u2014 A sprawling, beautiful book on SE Asian cooking organized by the flavors of the region rather than by country. Essential reading if this week sparked serious interest.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Weeks 41\u201342: Middle Eastern | Weeks 45\u201346: Bread \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Weeks 43\u201344: Module 4 Capstone: Southeast Asian Cuisines","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/quick-ref.html#week-39-thailand-vietnam-indonesia-malaysia","title":"Week 39 \u2014 Thailand, Vietnam, Indonesia, Malaysia","text":"Day Dish Technique Key Point Mon Pad Thai Wok; tamarind-palm sugar sauce Pre-mix sauce and taste before cooking Tue Traditional Beef Pho Charred aromatics; long bone broth Start morning; clear broth required Wed Nasi Goreng Shrimp paste toast; kecap manis; day-old rice Terasi must be cooked in the pan Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Curry Laksa Rempah (spice paste) fried in oil; coconut broth Fry paste until oil separates (dry look) Sat PROJECT: Satay + Som Tam Grilled skewers; mortar-pounded papaya salad Pound, don't toss the som tam"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/quick-ref.html#week-40-pad-see-ew-pho-ga-banh-mi-rendang","title":"Week 40 \u2014 Pad See Ew, Pho G\u00e0, Banh Mi, Rendang","text":"Day Dish Technique Key Point Mon Pad See Ew Wide noodle wok; maximum heat for char Fresh wide noodles only Tue Pho G\u00e0 (Pressure Cooker) Quick broth extraction Compare to beef pho; lighter character Wed Banh Mi Pickled daikon + carrot; Vietnamese protein in French bread Pickle night before Thu Rest + Review Third-Quarter Journal 9 months in \u2014 write your review Fri Beef Rendang Wet \u2192 dry braise; all coconut milk evaporates Takes 3\u20134 hrs; don't rush dry Sat PROJECT: SE Asian Dinner Party Multi-dish selection; timing across cuisines Start broth before guests arrive"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/quick-ref.html#flavor-balance-reference-southeast-asian-five-element-seasoning","title":"Flavor Balance Reference \u2014 Southeast Asian Five-Element Seasoning","text":"Element Thai Vietnamese Indonesian Malaysian Salty Fish sauce (nam pla) Fish sauce (n\u01b0\u1edbc m\u1eafm) Kecap asin / fish sauce Fish sauce / soy Sour Lime juice Lime juice Tamarind Tamarind / lime Sweet Palm sugar Palm sugar Kecap manis Palm sugar Heat Bird's eye chili Fresh chili Sambal Sambal / bird's eye Umami Shrimp paste (kapi) Dried shrimp Terasi (shrimp paste) Shrimp paste"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/quick-ref.html#key-ingredient-notes","title":"Key Ingredient Notes","text":"<ul> <li>Day-old rice \u2014 mandatory for fried rice (Nasi Goreng); fresh rice is too wet</li> <li>Shrimp paste (terasi/kapi) \u2014 smells intense raw; frying or toasting transforms it</li> <li>Palm sugar \u2014 mellower than white sugar; substitute light brown sugar if unavailable</li> <li>Wide rice noodles (sen yai) \u2014 must be fresh or soaked just before cooking; never boil before stir-frying</li> <li>Green papaya \u2014 buy unripe, rock-hard; shred with mandoline or grater</li> <li>Fish sauce brands \u2014 Tiparos, Megachef, or Red Boat (higher quality); taste varies significantly</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 43\u201344: Southeast Asian","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Where to shop: A Southeast Asian grocery (or combined Asian supermarket) is ideal. You need: fresh wide rice noodles, lemongrass, galangal, kaffir lime leaves, dried shrimp, shrimp paste (terasi), kecap manis, palm sugar, fish sauce, tamarind paste, unripe green papaya, laksa paste or spice ingredients, and fresh herbs (Thai basil, Vietnamese mint, laksa leaf).</p>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Wok \u2014 essential for nasi goreng and pad see ew; cast iron acceptable but wok preferred</li> <li>[ ] Mortar and pestle \u2014 for som tam (clay mortar preferred for Thai salads)</li> <li>[ ] Pressure cooker or Instant Pot \u2014 for pho g\u00e0 (Tue Week 40) and pho b\u00f2 (Tue Week 39)</li> <li>[ ] Bamboo skewers \u2014 soaked 30 min before grilling (satay Sat Week 39)</li> <li>[ ] Fine-mesh strainer \u2014 for pho broth</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-39","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 39","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Shrimp \u2014 1 lb, peeled (Mon Pad Thai)</li> <li>[ ] Beef bones with marrow \u2014 2\u20133 lbs (Tue pho broth)</li> <li>[ ] Beef brisket or eye round \u2014 1 lb (Tue pho \u2014 cooked brisket slice + raw thin-sliced for bowl)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken thighs \u2014 1 lb (Sat satay)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-40","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 40","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Beef or chicken \u2014 1 lb, thinly sliced (Mon Pad See Ew)</li> <li>[ ] Whole chicken \u2014 3.5\u20134 lbs (Tue Pho G\u00e0 \u2014 break it down yourself)</li> <li>[ ] Pork belly \u2014 1 lb (Wed Banh Mi \u2014 marinate + roast or braise)</li> <li>[ ] Beef chuck \u2014 2 lbs (Fri Rendang \u2014 cut into 3-inch chunks)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (nasi goreng, banh mi egg, various)</li> <li>[ ] Extra firm tofu \u2014 1 block (laksa Fri Week 39; optional pad Thai Mon Week 39)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html#fresh-southeast-asian-aromatics-asian-market","title":"\ud83c\udf3f Fresh Southeast Asian Aromatics (Asian Market)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Lemongrass \u2014 4 stalks</li> <li>[ ] Galangal \u2014 1 small piece (or substitute ginger; not the same)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh ginger \u2014 1 large piece</li> <li>[ ] Kaffir lime leaves \u2014 1 pack (fresh or frozen)</li> <li>[ ] Thai bird's eye chiles \u2014 1 small bag (very hot; use with care)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh turmeric \u2014 1 small piece (or use 1 tsp ground)</li> <li>[ ] Lime \u2014 12 (used every day)</li> <li>[ ] Thai basil \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Vietnamese mint / perilla \u2014 1 bunch (pho + banh mi)</li> <li>[ ] Cilantro \u2014 3 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Green onions \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Unripe green papaya \u2014 1 (Sat Week 39 som tam; must be rock hard)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumber \u2014 6 (sides + banh mi + various)</li> <li>[ ] Bean sprouts \u2014 2 bags</li> <li>[ ] White onion + red onion \u2014 4 each</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html#southeast-asian-pantry-asian-market","title":"\ud83e\udd6b Southeast Asian Pantry (Asian Market)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Fish sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Tiparos, Red Boat, or Megachef)</li> <li>[ ] Kecap manis (sweet soy sauce) \u2014 1 bottle (nasi goreng Wed Week 39)</li> <li>[ ] Fermented shrimp paste / terasi \u2014 1 small block (nasi goreng; laksa rempah)</li> <li>[ ] Coconut milk \u2014 4 cans (satay marinade, laksa, rendang)</li> <li>[ ] Tamarind paste (or block) \u2014 1 jar/block</li> <li>[ ] Palm sugar \u2014 1 block (or substitute light brown sugar)</li> <li>[ ] Oyster sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Pad See Ew Mon Week 40)</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce (light) \u2014 1 bottle</li> <li>[ ] Hoisin sauce \u2014 small jar (pho tableside)</li> <li>[ ] Sriracha \u2014 1 bottle</li> <li>[ ] Sambal oelek \u2014 1 jar</li> <li>[ ] Dried shrimp \u2014 1 small bag (som tam, rempah)</li> <li>[ ] Peanuts \u2014 roasted, unsalted \u2014 2 cups (pad Thai + satay sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Sesame oil \u2014 toasted</li> <li>[ ] Prawn crackers (krupuk) \u2014 1 bag (nasi goreng garnish)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html#noodles-and-rice","title":"\ud83c\udf5d Noodles and Rice","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Flat rice noodles, thin (sen lek) \u2014 1 lb (Pad Thai Mon Week 39)</li> <li>[ ] Wide rice noodles, fresh (sen yai) \u2014 1 lb (Pad See Ew Mon Week 40) \u2014 buy day of if possible</li> <li>[ ] Pho rice noodles (medium width) \u2014 1 pack (pho Tue both weeks)</li> <li>[ ] Jasmine rice \u2014 5-lb bag</li> <li>[ ] Rice already cooked and cooled for nasi goreng \u2014 cook night before</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html#banh-mi-components-wed-week-40","title":"\ud83c\udf3f Banh Mi Components (Wed Week 40)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Daikon radish \u2014 1 small (pickle)</li> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 4 (pickle)</li> <li>[ ] White vinegar \u2014 for pickle</li> <li>[ ] French baguettes or hoagie rolls \u2014 light, crackly crust mandatory</li> <li>[ ] Pork liver p\u00e2t\u00e9 or store-bought liverwurst \u2014 for classic banh mi</li> <li>[ ] Vietnamese chili garlic sauce (Huy Fong) \u2014 for banh mi</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html#pho-aromatics","title":"\ud83c\udf39 Pho Aromatics","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Onion \u2014 2 (charred for pho)</li> <li>[ ] Ginger \u2014 charred for pho</li> <li>[ ] Star anise \u2014 4 pods</li> <li>[ ] Cinnamon stick \u2014 2</li> <li>[ ] Whole cloves \u2014 4</li> <li>[ ] Cardamom pods \u2014 2</li> <li>[ ] Rock sugar or regular sugar \u2014 small amount (pho broth finish)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/index.html","title":"Module 5: Mastery &amp; Pastry (Weeks 45\u201356)","text":"<p>The goal of this module: Finish strong. Bread and pastry demand precision that sharpens every other skill you've built. Then design your own signature dishes, learn to orchestrate a full dinner party, and cap the year with a self-administered final exam that proves \u2014 to yourself \u2014 that you can cook.</p> <p>By the end of Week 52, you will have completed a full professional-level culinary curriculum, delivered at home, over one year.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/index.html#weeks-in-this-module","title":"Weeks in This Module","text":"Weeks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 45\u201346 Bread \u2014 Fundamentals \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 47\u201348 Pastry \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 49\u201350 Desserts \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 51\u201352 Your Signature Dishes \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 53\u201354 Menus &amp; Timing \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 55\u201356 Module 5 Capstone: The Final Exam \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/index.html#core-skills-covered","title":"Core Skills Covered","text":"<ul> <li>Bread \u2014 levain maintenance; autolyse, bulk ferment, shaping, scoring; Pullman loaf for beginners; baking in Dutch oven</li> <li>Pastry \u2014 p\u00e2te bris\u00e9e, p\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e, rough puff; lamination logic; blind-baking; tart construction; choux</li> <li>Desserts \u2014 cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e; layer cake; Swiss and Italian meringue; ganache; bain-marie technique; tempering chocolate</li> <li>Signature dishes \u2014 developing, documenting, and refining 3 original dishes that reflect your palate and history</li> <li>Menus &amp; timing \u2014 backwards-planning a dinner party; mise en place at scale; timing charts; expediting</li> <li>Final exam \u2014 multi-course meal planned, shopped, and executed solo; written reflection on the year</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/index.html#equipment-youll-need","title":"Equipment You'll Need","text":"<p>See the Kitchen Equipment Guide. New items introduced in this module:</p> Item Introduced Kitchen scale (digital, 0.1g resolution) Week 45 Bench scraper Week 45 Banneton (proofing basket) Week 45 Pullman loaf pan with lid Week 45 Bread lame (scoring blade) Week 45 Stand mixer with dough hook Week 45 9-inch tart pan with removable bottom Week 47 9-inch pie dish Week 47 Pie weights (or dried beans) Week 47 Pastry bag + tips Week 47 Madeleine pan (optional) Week 47 Kitchen torch Week 49 Ramekins, 4\u20136 oz (set of 6) Week 49 9-inch round cake pans (\u00d73) Week 49 Pastry brush Week 49 Candy thermometer Week 49 Large roasting pan (for bain-marie) Week 49 Springform pan (optional) Week 49 Whetstone Week 51 Multiple-channel timer Week 53 <p>Previous module: Module 4 \u2014 The World's Kitchens (Weeks 29\u201344)</p> <p>Congratulations on completing the 56-Week Culinary Project. You cooked.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html","title":"Weeks 45\u201346: Bread","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 43\u201344: Southeast Asian | Weeks 47\u201348: Pastry \u2192</p> <p>\"Bread is the thing that most home cooks believe is beyond them and is not. It requires no special equipment, no professional skill, and no exotic ingredients. It requires: flour, water, salt, and time. The baker's greatest tool is patience, followed by touch. The recipe is the least important part.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#week-41-no-knead-focaccia-and-the-logic-of-bread","title":"Week 41 \u2014 No-Knead, Focaccia, and the Logic of Bread","text":"<p>This week establishes the principles of bread-making through the two most forgiving and impressive loaves a home baker can produce: no-knead bread (develops gluten passively through time) and focaccia (high-hydration dough with a generous olive oil soak). Both will reset your confidence about baking.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#monday-better-no-knead-bread","title":"Monday \u2014 Better No-Knead Bread","text":"<p>Skill: Autolyse; long cold fermentation; Dutch oven steam baking Read first: Better No-Knead Bread</p> <p>What you're learning: No-knead bread works because a long rest (12\u201318 hours) allows gluten strands to organize themselves without the mechanical action of kneading. The Dutch oven creates the steam that a commercial deck oven provides \u2014 essential for the brittle, shiny crust. Dough should be shaggy and wet; this is correct.</p> <p>Note: Mix the dough Sunday night for Monday baking.</p> <p>Full Meal: - No-Knead Bread, first loaf - Tear and eat warm with cultured butter and good olive oil. That's the meal.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: No-Knead Bread, Revisited \u2014 He updates the original technique with a few small tweaks; compare his rationale for the changes to what you experience with your own first loaf.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#tuesday-no-knead-bread-variation-folding-technique-upgrade","title":"Tuesday \u2014 No-Knead Bread Variation (Folding Technique Upgrade)","text":"<p>Skill: Stretch-and-fold technique during bulk fermentation; shaping surface tension Read first: Reference the better no-knead technique; try incorporating 3\u20134 rounds of stretch-and-fold during the first 2 hours</p> <p>What you're learning: The \"better\" part of Better No-Knead Bread is using the stretch-and-fold technique instead of just leaving the dough alone. This builds more structure and improves the crumb. Compare your Tuesday loaf to Monday's \u2014 the crumb should be more open and even.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Bread loaf #2 with different toppings or served alongside a simple soup</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#wednesday-no-knead-focaccia","title":"Wednesday \u2014 No-Knead Focaccia","text":"<p>Skill: High-hydration bread; olive oil bath; dimpling and topping technique Read first: Easy No-Knead Focaccia</p> <p>What you're learning: Focaccia is essentially no-knead bread taken through a different shaping process (poured into an oil-slicked pan, dimpled enthusiastically, topped generously). The high olive oil content creates a crispy-bottom, fluffy-interior bread. Toppings: fleur de sel, fresh rosemary mandatory; add olives, cherry tomatoes, or caramelized onions as taste dictates.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Focaccia with simple accompaniments - Serve with whatever soup or leftover protein you have \u2014 it elevates everything</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Extra-Flavorful Focaccia (Adam Ragusea) \u2014 Watch his oil quantity and the dimpling logic \u2014 he explains why the fat pools create the crust they do. Compare to your bake: where did the oil go, and how did the surface behave?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#thursday-rest-day","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":"<p>Reflect: You've now made three loaves of bread. How has each one been different? Notice how dough temperature, hydration, and fermentation time affect crust and crumb. Write down your observations.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#friday-pullman-loaf-sandwich-bread","title":"Friday \u2014 Pullman Loaf (Sandwich Bread)","text":"<p>Skill: Enriched bread dough technique; Pullman pan use; proper slice structure Read first: Pullman Loaf \u2014 Sandwich Bread</p> <p>What you're learning: Pullman bread is the American sandwich loaf at its best \u2014 tight, even crumb, soft crust, slightly enriched (some butter and milk) so it toasts beautifully. A Pullman pan (with a sliding lid) creates the rectangular profile. This is a different bread philosophy from artisan loaves \u2014 engineered for utility as well as flavor.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Sliced Pullman bread, the ideal vehicle for anything - Make sandwiches from the week's proteins/leftovers \u2014 use your best bread for your best filling</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: A Beginner's Guide to Making the Best Sandwich Bread (Ethan Chlebowski) \u2014 He documents the texture difference between enriched loaves at different hydrations. Slice yours next to a store loaf and notice what \"structure\" actually means.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#saturday-project-sourdough-starter-first-sourdough","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Sourdough Starter + First Sourdough","text":"<p>Skill: Starting a natural yeast culture; understanding sourdough fermentation timeline Read first: Sourdough Starter</p> <p>Note: You won't eat this bread today. Establishing a sourdough starter takes 5\u20137 days. Start it today; it will be ready for your first actual sourdough loaf in Week 42.</p> <p>What you're learning: Sourdough starter is a live culture of wild yeast and bacteria captured from the flour and air. It ferments flour as food. Feeding it (discarding and adding fresh flour + water on schedule) keeps the culture healthy. Consistency of temperature and timing is the key.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Focaccia (make a second batch if desired \u2014 your no-knead skill is solid by now) - Saturday dinner designed around the focaccia</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: A Non-Baker's Guide to Making Sourdough Bread (Alex French Guy Cooking) \u2014 His beginner lens matches yours right now. Watch when he knows the fermentation is right and how he reads the dough before shaping \u2014 that instinct is what you're building today.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#week-42-sourdough-croissants-and-brioche","title":"Week 42 \u2014 Sourdough, Croissants, and Brioche","text":""},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#monday-sourdough-first-real-loaf","title":"Monday \u2014 Sourdough: First Real Loaf","text":"<p>Skill: Levain build; bulk fermentation judgment; shaping; cold retard Read first: Reference the sourdough starter from Week 41; consult your flour brand's recommended ratios</p> <p>What you're learning: Your starter (if started Saturday Week 41) should now be active and bubbly. Build a levain (a measured feeding of your starter used as the leavener), mix into a dough, bulk ferment 4\u20136 hours with stretch-and-folds, shape, refrigerate overnight. Bake in a Dutch oven Tuesday morning.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Continue building the starter (no bread from this session yet) - Make dinner from something non-bread related tonight</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#tuesday-sourdough-bake-day","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Sourdough: Bake Day","text":"<p>Skill: Cold-retarded sourdough baking; scoring technique; reading the oven spring Read first: Continue sourdough journey \u2014 score with a lame or sharp razor; bake covered 20 min, uncovered 20\u201325 min</p> <p>What you're learning: The most important bake of the whole bread week. Oven spring (the final rise in a hot oven), scoring (the line you cut before baking that guides the bloom), and the crumb reveal after cooling (don't cut hot \u2014 wait 1 hour minimum) are all key moments.</p> <p>Full Meal: - First real sourdough loaf - Tear open warm with butter. You earned this.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#wednesday-brioche","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Brioche","text":"<p>Skill: Enriched dough with high butter content; emulsifying butter into dough; long cold overnight rest Read first: Brioche Loaf</p> <p>What you're learning: Brioche is bread enriched with so much butter (up to 50\u201360% of flour weight) and eggs that it blurs the line between bread and cake. The butter must be at room temperature and added gradually while the dough is already developed. If you add cold butter, the gluten breaks \u2014 the emulsification is fragile and temperature-sensitive.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Brioche loaf with jam and cultured butter - Use the remaining slices for French toast the next morning</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#thursday-rest-day_1","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":"<p>Reflect: This week's progression: no-knead \u2192 focaccia \u2192 sandwich loaf \u2192 sourdough \u2192 brioche covers the full spectrum of bread hydration, fermentation, and enrichment. What was the hardest step in each?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#friday-croissants","title":"Friday \u2014 Croissants","text":"<p>Skill: Laminated dough technique (d\u00e9trempe + beurrage); layering (tourage); the fold method Read first: Croissants</p> <p>What you're learning: Croissants are laminated \u2014 thin sheets of butter layered into a dough through a series of folds, creating hundreds of distinct layers that steam and puff in the oven. This requires cold butter (firm), cold dough, and patience between rest periods. Block out the full day. The result: the most honest test of your patience and precision so far.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Croissants (plain, butter, and chocolate-stuffed if you have pastry chocolate) - This is also dinner tonight</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Amazing French Baguettes at Home (Alex French Guy Cooking) \u2014 The lamination logic in croissants and the crust logic in baguettes come from the same place \u2014 steam and structure. Watch his scoring and look for the same \"ear\" on your croissants.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#saturday-project-bread-tasting-and-final-bake","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Bread Tasting and Final Bake","text":"<p>Skill: Assessing all your bakes; understanding the baker's vocabulary for evaluating bread Goal: Slice and taste all breads you baked this week alongside the best bread you can buy locally. Evaluate: crust texture, crumb structure, flavor complexity, fermentation character.</p> <p>Then: make one more loaf of whatever bread felt most satisfying. Practice it again while everything is fresh.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Bread tasting board with cultured butter, olive oil, jams - Build a cheese and charcuterie spread using breads as the carrier</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#gluten-the-thing-youre-actually-working-with","title":"Gluten: The Thing You're Actually Working With","text":"<p>Bread baking is flour + water + time. But the mechanism is gluten development \u2014 the protein network that traps CO\u2082 from yeast and gives bread its structure. Understanding what gluten is and how kneading, hydration, and fermentation affect it changes how you approach every recipe.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Better No-Knead Bread \u2014 The technique and the science, side by side. Why the long, cold ferment produces more complex flavor than a fast room-temperature rise.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Easy No-Knead Focaccia \u2014 High hydration, olive oil, and air holes explained. This is also the template for every Roman-style pan bread.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#sourdough-the-next-frontier","title":"Sourdough: The Next Frontier","text":"<p>No-knead and focaccia are gateway loaves. If you finished this week intrigued rather than intimidated, sourdough is the natural next project \u2014 wild yeast, longer fermentation, more complex crust.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Sourdough Starter \u2014 The complete guide to building a culture from scratch: hydration, feeding schedules, flour types, and how to know when your starter is actually ready to bake with. Don't attempt your first sourdough before reading this.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Chad Robertson shapes a loaf \u2014 The hand technique for shaping sourdough loaves is completely visual. Watch the pre-shape and the final shape before you attempt them.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Bread Science by Emily Buehler \u2014 The scientific explanation of everything that happens when you make bread \u2014 yeast activity, gluten networks, crust formation \u2014 written for home bakers who want to understand, not just follow instructions.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Weeks 43\u201344: Southeast Asian | Weeks 47\u201348: Pastry \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Weeks 45\u201346: Bread","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/quick-ref.html#week-41-the-forgiving-loaves","title":"Week 41 \u2014 The Forgiving Loaves","text":"Day Bread Hydration Method Timing Mon No-Knead Boule ~80% Mix Sun night; bake Mon 12\u201318 hr ferment + 45 min bake Tue No-Knead (stretch-and-fold upgrade) ~80% 3\u20134 folds in first 2 hrs Compare crumb to Monday's Wed No-Knead Focaccia ~80\u201385% Pan bake; oil-slicked Mix morning; dimple + bake same day Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 \u2014 Fri Pullman Sandwich Loaf ~65% Enriched; Pullman pan Standard 2-hour proof Sat Sourdough Starter (start) n/a Mix flour + water; 5\u20137 day culture Won't use until Week 42"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/quick-ref.html#week-42-sourdough-brioche-croissants","title":"Week 42 \u2014 Sourdough, Brioche, Croissants","text":"Day Bread Method Key Milestone Mon Sourdough \u2014 levain build + mix Levain 4\u20136 hrs; bulk ferment; refrigerate overnight Check starter is bubbly before mixing Tue Sourdough \u2014 Bake Dutch oven; 250\u00b0C; covered then uncovered Score before loading; wait 1 hr to cut Wed Brioche Enriched; butter added gradually; refrigerate overnight Butter must be room temp Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Croissants Laminated; 3+ book folds; refrigerate between Keep everything cold; block out full day Sat PROJECT: Bread Board + Rebake Taste + evaluate; rebake best loaf Compare all five breads side by side"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/quick-ref.html#bread-hydration-scale","title":"Bread Hydration Scale","text":"Bread Hydration Texture Shape Pullman / sandwich 60\u201365% Soft, tight crumb Loaf pan No-knead boule 75\u201380% Open, irregular crumb Free-form or Dutch oven Focaccia 80\u201385% Soft, airy, oily Sheet pan Sourdough 70\u201380% Open crumb, chewy Banneton \u2192 Dutch oven Brioche 65\u201370% (enriched) Tender, rich Loaf tin Croissant dough 55\u201360% Layered, laminated Rolled + shaped"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/quick-ref.html#bakers-troubleshooting","title":"Baker's Troubleshooting","text":"Problem Likely Cause Fix Dense, gummy crumb Underbaked; too much water Bake longer; check internal temp (210\u00b0F) No oven spring Weak yeast; didn't proof enough Use active starter/yeast; proper proof time Thick crust, no crunch Insufficient steam Use Dutch oven or steam pan Flat croissants Butter melted into dough during folds Keep dough cold; rest between folds Sourdough not rising Inactive starter Feed starter 2\u00d7 daily until bubbly before using"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 45\u201346: Bread","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Bread shopping is mostly flour. Get good flour \u2014 it matters here more than anywhere else in this program. King Arthur Bread Flour is reliable and widely available. For sourdough and higher-hydration loaves, bread flour (higher protein) performs better than all-purpose.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dutch oven \u2014 essential for no-knead and sourdough; 5\u20137 quart, cast iron</li> <li>[ ] Pullman pan with lid \u2014 for sandwich bread (Friday Week 41); ~$25\u201335</li> <li>[ ] Banneton (proofing basket) \u2014 for sourdough shaping (Week 42); optional but helpful</li> <li>[ ] Bench scraper \u2014 for dough handling</li> <li>[ ] Kitchen scale \u2014 bread is by grams, not cups; this is mandatory here</li> <li>[ ] Lame \u2014 a specialized razor blade for scoring sourdough; a very sharp knife works</li> <li>[ ] Stand mixer with dough hook \u2014 for brioche (the butter incorporation is nearly impossible by hand)</li> <li>[ ] Instant-read thermometer \u2014 internal bread temp: 200\u2013210\u00b0F when fully baked</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/shopping-list.html#flour-buy-more-than-you-think-you-need","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Flour (buy more than you think you need)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Bread flour \u2014 10 lbs (no-knead, pullman, sourdough, croissants)</li> <li>[ ] All-purpose flour \u2014 2 lbs (starter feeding, some focaccia applications)</li> <li>[ ] Whole wheat flour \u2014 1 lb (starter feeding; some add to sourdough for flavor)</li> <li>[ ] Rye flour \u2014 small bag (sourdough starter boost; optional)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Kosher salt \u2014 Diamond Crystal; other salts change hydration ratios</li> <li>[ ] Active dry yeast or instant yeast \u2014 1\u20132 packets (no-knead, pullman, brioche, croissants; sourdough uses starter)</li> <li>[ ] Olive oil \u2014 1 large bottle (focaccia uses a substantial quantity)</li> <li>[ ] Butter, European-style \u2014 2 lbs (brioche and croissants are butter-hungry; European-style has less water)</li> <li>[ ] Whole milk \u2014 1 quart (pullman enrichment, brioche)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 \u00bd pint (enriched doughs + egg wash for croissants)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (brioche dough + egg washes)</li> <li>[ ] Sugar / honey \u2014 small amounts (enriched doughs)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/shopping-list.html#toppings-and-finishing","title":"\ud83c\udf5e Toppings and Finishing","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Fleur de sel or Maldon \u2014 for focaccia topping</li> <li>[ ] Fresh rosemary \u2014 2 sprigs (focaccia)</li> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 for focaccia topping (Week 41 Wed)</li> <li>[ ] Olives \u2014 1 small jar (focaccia option)</li> <li>[ ] Cultured butter \u2014 Kerrygold or similar (for the bread tastings \u2014 this is the fun part)</li> <li>[ ] Good olive oil \u2014 for dipping alongside fresh bread</li> <li>[ ] Jam \u2014 2 varieties (for brioche)</li> <li>[ ] Pain au chocolat chocolate sticks or bittersweet chocolate \u2014 for chocolate croissants (Fri Week 42)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/45-46-bread/shopping-list.html#for-cheese-and-charcuterie-board-sat-week-42","title":"For Cheese and Charcuterie Board (Sat Week 42)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] 2\u20133 cheeses (firm and soft)</li> <li>[ ] Prosciutto or salami</li> <li>[ ] Cornichons, honey, whole-grain mustard</li> <li>[ ] Grapes or dried fruit</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html","title":"Weeks 47\u201348: Pastry","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 45\u201346: Bread | Weeks 49\u201350: Desserts \u2192</p> <p>\"Pastry is baking with stakes. A bread that's slightly underbaked can go back in the oven. A puff pastry that's overworked, or a tart shell that absorbed too much liquid \u2014 those failures are harder to fix. Pastry rewards obsessive mise en place, cold everything, and the willingness to start over when something goes wrong.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#week-43-pastry-doughs-pate-sucree-tarte-tatin-and-puff-pastry","title":"Week 43 \u2014 Pastry Doughs: P\u00e2te Sucr\u00e9e, Tarte Tatin, and Puff Pastry","text":"<p>French pastry week is the most technically demanding section of this program. The payoff is proportional to the investment. These are skills that make you the person in any dinner party circle who brings something people still talk about months later.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#monday-pate-sucree-sweet-tart-dough","title":"Monday \u2014 P\u00e2te Sucr\u00e9e (Sweet Tart Dough)","text":"<p>Skill: Creaming method for tart dough; blind baking; preventing shrinkage Read first: P\u00e2te Sucr\u00e9e \u2014 Sweet Tart Shell</p> <p>What you're learning: P\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e (sweet paste) is the French shortcrust tart dough \u2014 butter creamed with sugar, then flour added just until combined, then rested cold, then pressed or rolled into a tart ring and blind-baked. The creaming method (unlike rubbing cold butter into flour for pie crust) gives it a more cookie-like texture. No water \u2014 no gluten development.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Fill the baked tart shell with pastry cream and fresh fruit (strawberry, raspberry, kiwi) - Apricot glaze finish (brush with warm apricot jam)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#tuesday-pastry-cream-creme-patissiere","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Pastry Cream (Cr\u00e8me P\u00e2tissi\u00e8re)","text":"<p>Skill: Egg yolk + starch custard; tempering; the nappe; cooling without skin Read first: Vanilla Pastry Cream</p> <p>What you're learning: Pastry cream is the filling for every French pastry: eclairs, mille-feuille, fruit tarts, cream puffs. It's thickened with cornstarch and egg yolks. The key skills: tempering (pouring hot milk slowly into yolks to prevent scrambling), cooking while whisking constantly until it thickens (it will lump if you stop), and pressing plastic wrap directly on the surface to prevent a skin.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Eclairs or cream puffs using pastry cream (choux pastry \u2014 see Week 44 Friday for the full technique, or make a basic choux: butter + water + flour + eggs piped and baked at 400\u00b0F) - Chocolate glaze dipped</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How To Make A Fruit Tart (Claire Saffitz) \u2014 Pastry cream is the central skill in this video; watch her tempering step and the moment she declares it done \u2014 that's the texture you're aiming for.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#wednesday-tarte-tatin","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Tarte Tatin","text":"<p>Skill: Dry-heat caramelization in a pan; fruit arrangement; inverted bake Read first: Tarte Tatin</p> <p>What you're learning: Tarte Tatin is an upside-down apple tart \u2014 apples cooked in caramelized butter and sugar in a cast iron skillet, then tart dough pressed over the top and baked, then flipped. The caramel soaks into the apples and glazes the finished tart on top. Timing the inversion is the scary part \u2014 too soon and it's liquid chaos; too late and the caramel hardens.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Tarte Tatin with cr\u00e8me fra\u00eeche or vanilla ice cream - No other accompaniment needed \u2014 it's sufficient on its own</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Foolproof Tarte Tatin &amp; Rough Puff Pastry (Claire Saffitz) \u2014 Note how far she lets the caramel darken before adding the apples, and her confidence at the inversion step \u2014 that's the point most people flinch.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#thursday-rest-day","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":"<p>Reflect: Three days of pastry work. Each required cold butter, precise ratios, and timing. What's the common thread that keeps appearing? How does temperature control in pastry differ from temperature control in protein cooking?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#friday-quick-puff-pastry-rough-puff","title":"Friday \u2014 Quick Puff Pastry (Rough Puff)","text":"<p>Skill: Rough puff technique; fold method; maintaining butter layers without a lamination machine Read first: Rough puff (also called \u201cblitz puff\u201d or \u201cquick puff\u201d) has no dedicated SE recipe, but the technique is straightforward: grate frozen butter into flour, barely combine with ice water, fold 4\u00d7 with 20-minute rests between. The Mille-Feuille recipe explains the layer principle; the Croissant recipe demonstrates the lamination mechanics at full scale.</p> <p>What you're learning: True feuilletage (classic puff pastry) takes 6 rounds of folds over hours. Rough puff achieves 70\u201380% of the same result in a fraction of the time. Grate frozen butter into the flour, add water, barely combine, fold 3\u20134 times with 30-minute rests between. The result: flaky, buttery pastry dough for savory and sweet applications.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Savory pastry application: rough puff filled with caramelized onion and Gruy\u00e8re (galette or tart) - Green salad alongside</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#saturday-project-mille-feuille-napoleon","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Mille-Feuille (Napoleon)","text":"<p>Skill: Baked puff pastry sheets; layering and assembly; fondant or icing finish Goal: Bake puff pastry into flat sheets (store-bought puff pastry is acceptable here \u2014 your rough puff from Friday can also be used). Layer with pastry cream between three sheets of puff. Top with fondant (or powdered sugar glaze) and optional chocolate feathering.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Mille-Feuille: the test of pastry cream + puff pastry execution together - Espresso to accompany</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#week-44-croissant-application-quiche-and-the-art-of-the-pie-crust","title":"Week 44 \u2014 Croissant Application, Quiche, and the Art of the Pie Crust","text":""},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#monday-quiche-lorraine","title":"Monday \u2014 Quiche Lorraine","text":"<p>Skill: Savory custard in a tart shell; cream-to-egg ratio; setting without overcooking Read first: Quiche Lorraine</p> <p>What you're learning: Quiche custard sets at 160\u2013165\u00b0F. The oven texture should be: barely jiggly in the center when you pull it, firming as it cools. Overbaked quiche is grainy and rubbery. The technique applies to any savory tart or baked custard \u2014 ratio is 1 egg per 4 tablespoons (\u00bc cup) heavy cream.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Quiche Lorraine - Simple green salad with mustard vinaigrette</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#tuesday-flaky-pie-crust-apple-pie","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Flaky Pie Crust + Apple Pie","text":"<p>Skill: Rubbing cold fat into flour; water addition; laminated vs. mealy crust; rolling without tearing Read first: Best Fat for Pie Crust (explains the butter vs. lard vs. shortening science)</p> <p>What you're learning: Pie crust is the democratic pastry \u2014 it should be accessible, forgiving, and made with whatever fat you have. The SE analysis of which fat produces which result (butter for flavor, lard for flakiness, shortening for structure) gives you the science to make confident decisions. Make a double-crust apple pie with a butter-lard blend if possible.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Apple Pie with vanilla ice cream - This is a Tuesday, and that's fine</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make an Apple Pie \u2014 Sous Vide Method \u2014 He uses sous vide to pre-cook the filling so it's never soupy; compare his fat rationale for the crust to the approach you chose.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#wednesday-pate-brisee-savory-shortcrust-lemon-tart","title":"Wednesday \u2014 P\u00e2te Bris\u00e9e (Savory Shortcrust) + Lemon Tart","text":"<p>Skill: Savory shortcrust (unsweetened); lemon curd filling; balancing sweetness and acid Read first: Reference p\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e technique (Monday Week 43) \u2014 p\u00e2te bris\u00e9e is the same method without the sugar</p> <p>What you're learning: A lemon tart uses a baked p\u00e2te bris\u00e9e or p\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e shell, filled with lemon curd (eggs + sugar + lemon juice + butter, cooked to 170\u00b0F) that is poured in warm and sets as it cools. It should taste bright, sour, and sweet in equal measure.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Lemon Tart (serves 6\u20138; share) - No accompaniment needed \u2014 it's perfect alone</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#thursday-rest-day_1","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":""},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#friday-choux-pastry-eclairs-or-profiteroles","title":"Friday \u2014 Choux Pastry (\u00c9clairs or Profiteroles)","text":"<p>Skill: Choux dough technique (p\u00e2te \u00e0 choux); piping consistent shapes; filling and glazing Read first: Choux au Craquelin (for plain \u00e9clairs or profiteroles, skip the craquelin sugar disc on top \u2014 the choux base technique is identical)</p> <p>What you're learning: Choux is a cooked starch paste. The eggs are beaten in gradually \u2014 the correct dough consistency is \"ribbon-y\" when dropped from a spoon (falls in a thick, slow V). Underbaked choux will collapse. Properly baked choux has a hollow interior ready for filling.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Chocolate-glazed \u00e9clairs with pastry cream filling (pastry cream already mastered Tuesday Week 43) - Or profiteroles (small choux balls) with ice cream + chocolate sauce</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Chocolate \u00c9clairs / P\u00e2te \u00e0 Choux (Claire Saffitz) \u2014 Watch her dough consistency test \u2014 the ribbon drop off the spoon \u2014 that's the single diagnostic that tells you whether the choux will rise properly or collapse.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#saturday-project-pastry-afternoon-tea","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Pastry Afternoon Tea","text":"<p>Skill: Composed pastry spread; timing multiple preparations Goal: Assemble an afternoon tea spread using the two weeks of pastry work:</p> <ol> <li>Finger sandwiches (savory \u2014 cucumber, smoked salmon, egg salad on Pullman bread from Week 41)</li> <li>Petit fours or madeleine cookies (easy to add; baked in madeleine pan with browned butter batter)</li> <li>Lemon tart (from Wednesday) sliced</li> <li>Eclairs or mille-feuille from this week</li> <li>Scones with clotted cream and jam (or plain croissants from Week 42)</li> </ol> <p>Full Meal: - Full afternoon tea service - Earl Grey, chamomile, or English breakfast tea</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#pate-sucree-the-mother-of-tart-doughs","title":"P\u00e2te Sucr\u00e9e: The Mother of Tart Doughs","text":"<p>Sweet tart dough is the pastry equivalent of a mother sauce \u2014 once you can make it from memory, dozens of recipes open up. The gluten control (minimal mixing) and the fat distribution (workable but not warm) are the whole technique.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 P\u00e2te Sucr\u00e9e: Sweet Tart Shell \u2014 The full recipe with the technique notes that explain what blind baking is actually doing.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Vanilla Pastry Cream (Cr\u00e8me P\u00e2tissi\u00e8re) \u2014 Pastry cream is thickened with egg yolks and starch. Understanding the ratio between those two thickeners explains how you can adjust the texture.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#caramel-the-most-forgiving-hard-thing","title":"Caramel: The Most Forgiving Hard Thing","text":"<p>Tarte tatin requires caramelizing sugar in butter. It sounds terrifying. But caramel is just heated sucrose \u2014 and once you understand the temperature stages, you control it rather than fear it.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Tarte Tatin \u2014 The upside-down apple tart technique, including the caramel-base method, explained step by step.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda BraveTart by Stella Parks \u2014 The most scientifically rigorous American baking book ever written. Parks applies Food Lab-style testing to pastry. If you want to understand why your tart shell shrinks (and how to stop it), start here.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Weeks 45\u201346: Bread | Weeks 49\u201350: Desserts \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Weeks 47\u201348: Pastry","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/quick-ref.html#week-43-french-pastry-foundations","title":"Week 43 \u2014 French Pastry Foundations","text":"Day Preparation Key Technique Critical Point Mon P\u00e2te Sucr\u00e9e + Fruit Tart Creaming method; blind bake No water; press wrap to cool Tue Pastry Cream (Cr\u00e8me P\u00e2tissi\u00e8re) Temper eggs; constant whisking Plastic wrap directly on surface to prevent skin Wed Tarte Tatin Dry caramel in cast iron; inversion Time inversion: golden, not liquid, not rock-hard Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Rough Puff Pastry Grated frozen butter; fold 3\u20134\u00d7 Keep cold; rest between folds Sat PROJECT: Mille-Feuille Baked puff sheets + pastry cream layers Level the pastry sheets; press layers gently"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/quick-ref.html#week-44-applied-pastry-quiche-pie-lemon-tart-choux","title":"Week 44 \u2014 Applied Pastry: Quiche, Pie, Lemon Tart, Choux","text":"Day Preparation Key Technique Critical Point Mon Quiche Lorraine Savory custard in tart shell Pull at 160\u00b0F; jiggly center is correct Tue Apple Pie (double crust) Flaky pie crust; butter-lard blend Ice cold fat; add water 1 tbsp at a time Wed Lemon Tart Lemon curd to 170\u00b0F; pour warm into shell Balance acid-sweet; should taste clearly sour Thu Rest \u2014 \u2014 Fri Choux Pastry / \u00c9clairs Cooked paste; eggs added one at a time Ribbon test; fully bake (25\u201330 min) Sat PROJECT: Afternoon Tea Multi-pastry spread; composed service Most items make-ahead; assemble 1 hr before"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/quick-ref.html#pastry-fat-reference","title":"Pastry Fat Reference","text":"Dough Fat Amount (vs. flour) Result P\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e Unsalted butter ~50\u201360% Crisp, cookie-like, not flaky P\u00e2te bris\u00e9e Unsalted butter ~40% Flaky-tender American pie crust Butter + lard ~60% combined Flaky, rich Rough puff European butter ~75% Flaky, layered Brioche Unsalted butter 50\u201360% Rich, tender, not pastry-crisp Choux Unsalted butter 40% of water weight Hollow, crisped shell"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/quick-ref.html#custard-ratio-reference","title":"Custard Ratio Reference","text":"Preparation Eggs Liquid Temp Pastry cream 4 yolks per 500ml milk Milk + cornstarch Cook to 200\u00b0F (thick and glossy) Quiche custard 1 egg per \u00bc cup cream Heavy cream Pull at 160\u00b0F Lemon curd 4 yolks + 2 whole Lemon juice + butter Cook to 170\u00b0F Cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e 5\u20136 yolks per 500ml Heavy cream + vanilla Bake to 160\u00b0F"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Weeks 47\u201348: Pastry","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Cold butter is the recurring hero of this entire block. European-style butter (84%+ butterfat, lower water) is worth the premium here \u2014 Plugr\u00e0, Kerrygold, Isigny Sainte-M\u00e8re, or similar. Everything else builds on that.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] 9-inch tart pan with removable bottom \u2014 for p\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e and lemon tart</li> <li>[ ] 9-inch cast iron skillet \u2014 for tarte tatin</li> <li>[ ] Pie dish \u2014 for apple pie (9 inch)</li> <li>[ ] Pie weights or dried beans \u2014 for blind baking tart shells</li> <li>[ ] Stand mixer \u2014 for choux and pastry cream whisking</li> <li>[ ] Pastry bag + tips \u2014 for eclairs; a zip-top bag with corner cut works fine</li> <li>[ ] Madeleine pan \u2014 optional (Saturday's afternoon tea)</li> <li>[ ] Box grater \u2014 for grating frozen butter into rough puff dough</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/shopping-list.html#eggs-and-dairy","title":"\ud83e\udd5a Eggs and Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 2 dozen (pastry cream, quiche, tarte tatin caramel, choux, lemon curd, cake)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter, European-style \u2014 3 lbs (used every day this week; buy in bulk)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 1 quart (pastry cream, quiche, chantilly, \u00e9clairs)</li> <li>[ ] Whole milk \u2014 1 quart (pastry cream)</li> <li>[ ] Cr\u00e8me fra\u00eeche \u2014 1 cup (tarte tatin serving + quiche variation)</li> <li>[ ] Gruy\u00e8re \u2014 6 oz (quiche Mon Week 44)</li> <li>[ ] Bacon lardons \u2014 4 oz (quiche lorraine Mon Week 44)</li> <li>[ ] Mascarpone or cream cheese \u2014 optional (filling variations)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/shopping-list.html#produce-fruit-and-savory-fillings","title":"\ud83c\udf4e Produce \u2014 Fruit and Savory Fillings","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Apples \u2014 6 Granny Smith or Golden Delicious (tarte tatin Wed + pie Tue Week 44)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 10 (lemon curd Wed Week 44; various)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh berries \u2014 2 cups assorted (p\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e fruit tart Mon)</li> <li>[ ] Strawberries \u2014 1 pint (tart topping)</li> <li>[ ] Kiwi \u2014 3 (tart decoration)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumber \u2014 4 (finger sandwiches Sat Week 44)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/47-48-pastry/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] All-purpose flour \u2014 5 lbs (all doughs)</li> <li>[ ] Cake flour \u2014 1 lb (optional; lighter p\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e)</li> <li>[ ] Powdered sugar (confectioner's) \u2014 1 lb (p\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e, icing, d\u00e9cor)</li> <li>[ ] Granulated sugar \u2014 2 lbs (caramel, custard, pastry cream, pie)</li> <li>[ ] Cornstarch \u2014 1 box (pastry cream thickener)</li> <li>[ ] Kosher salt \u2014 Diamond Crystal</li> <li>[ ] Vanilla extract or vanilla bean paste \u2014 2 oz (pastry cream + various)</li> <li>[ ] Pure vanilla beans \u2014 2\u20133 (pastry cream; worth it)</li> <li>[ ] Almond extract \u2014 small bottle (optional tart variations)</li> <li>[ ] Apricot jam / preserves \u2014 1 jar (glaze for fruit tart + tarte tatin)</li> <li>[ ] Bittersweet chocolate (65\u201370%) \u2014 8 oz (\u00e9clair glaze + mille-feuille d\u00e9cor)</li> <li>[ ] Cocoa powder \u2014 (chocolate variations)</li> <li>[ ] Lard \u2014 4 oz (Tuesday Week 44 pie crust; optional but dramatically better)</li> <li>[ ] Puff pastry, store-bought \u2014 1\u20132 sheets as backup for mille-feuille (Sat Week 43)</li> <li>[ ] Ladyfingers \u2014 1 pack (optional; afternoon tea additions)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html","title":"Weeks 49\u201350: Desserts","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 47\u201348: Pastry | Weeks 51\u201352: Signature Dishes \u2192</p> <p>\"Dessert is the last thing someone tastes and the thing they remember longest. A great dessert after a good meal elevates the meal retroactively. The skills here \u2014 custard, chocolate, sugar work, meringue \u2014 combine with everything you've built over the year into the most complete expression of a cook.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#week-45-creme-brulee-panna-cotta-chocolate-mousse-and-pavlova","title":"Week 45 \u2014 Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e, Panna Cotta, Chocolate Mousse, and Pavlova","text":"<p>This week is about cold and room-temperature desserts \u2014 the ones that reward advance preparation and build confidence in gelatin, egg white foams, chocolate tempering, and custard control. These are dinner-party desserts you can make completely ahead while your guests are arriving.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#monday-creme-brulee","title":"Monday \u2014 Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e","text":"<p>Skill: Baked custard; water bath technique; caramelizing the top (br\u00fbl\u00e9e) Read first: Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e</p> <p>What you're learning: Cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e is a baked cream custard set with egg yolks only (no whites, no starch). The water bath (bain-marie) provides gentle, even heat that prevents curdling. The internal temperature is 160\u2013165\u00b0F \u2014 any more and the texture becomes grainy. The top sugar layer is caramelized with a kitchen torch immediately before serving (not before refrigerating \u2014 the crust will dissolve).</p> <p>Full Meal: - Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e \u00d7 4 (make ahead; refrigerate; br\u00fbl\u00e9e right before serving) - A savory dinner of your choice preceded it; this is dessert only</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e &amp; Cr\u00e8me Caramel (Claire Saffitz) \u2014 She makes both in one session; the cr\u00e8me caramel comparison shows how the same custard base behaves completely differently without the br\u00fbl\u00e9e crust.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#tuesday-panna-cotta","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Panna Cotta","text":"<p>Skill: Gelatin quantity and bloom; cream-to-milk ratio; demoulding Read first: Classic Panna Cotta</p> <p>What you're learning: Panna cotta (\"cooked cream\") is Italy's most elegant simple dessert: cream + sugar + vanilla + bloomed gelatin, set in a mold and flipped. The gelatin amount must be precise \u2014 too much and it bounces; too little and it collapses when unmolded. The right amount: barely holds its shape and quivers when touched.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Panna Cotta with raspberry or strawberry coulis, fresh fruit, or simply excellent olive oil and sea salt (the Sicilian approach)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#wednesday-chocolate-mousse","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Chocolate Mousse","text":"<p>Skill: Egg white foam; chocolate ganache base; folding without deflating Read first: Chocolate Mousse</p> <p>What you're learning: Classic French chocolate mousse is chocolate + butter, then beaten egg whites folded in. The chocolate must be cooled before the eggs go in (hot chocolate kills the foam). The folding technique \u2014 large, enveloping strokes that preserve the air \u2014 is the same technique as souffl\u00e9 and g\u00e9noise cake. It's a foundational movement in pastry.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Chocolate Mousse, chilled 2 hours minimum before serving - Whipped cream + bitter chocolate shavings on top</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#thursday-chocolate-tempering-confections","title":"Thursday \u2014 Chocolate Tempering &amp; Confections","text":"<p>Skill: Chocolate tempering \u2014 the technique that gives chocolate its gloss, snap, and professional finish. And truffles, which are the most accessible entry point into chocolate confectionery.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read first: How to Temper Chocolate</p> <p>What tempering actually is: Chocolate contains cocoa butter that crystallizes in six different forms depending on how it cools. Only Form V crystals (beta crystals) produce the glossy, snappy chocolate you recognize from a chocolate bar. Untempered chocolate (melted and cooled carelessly) produces Form IV or VI crystals \u2014 dull, streaky, soft. Tempering means bringing the chocolate to the right temperature sequence so only Form V crystals form.</p> <p>Two methods \u2014 both produce the same result:</p> Method Technique Best for Tabling Melt completely, pour 2/3 onto marble slab, work with spatula until cool, add back to remaining third Professional; fastest if you have marble Seeding Melt 2/3 of chocolate, add finely chopped unmelted chocolate (the \u201cseed\u201d) in stages, stir until smooth Home kitchen; easier to control <p>The seeding method \u2014 what you'll do tonight: 1. Chop 300g dark chocolate (70%+) finely. Reserve 100g. 2. Melt 200g over a double boiler to 115\u00b0F (46\u00b0C) \u2014 fully liquid, no lumps 3. Remove from heat. Add reserved 100g chopped chocolate in three additions, stirring until each melts 4. Check temperature: should reach 88\u201390\u00b0F (31\u201332\u00b0C). This is the working temperature 5. The snap test: Dip a teaspoon, let set 3\u20135 minutes at room temperature. It should be glossy with a sharp snap when you break it. Streaky or soft = not in temper; reheat gently to 88\u00b0F and try again</p> <p>Full Meal \u2014 Chocolate Truffles:</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Recipe: Dark Chocolate Truffles</p> <p>Truffles are the truest test of tempering: a ganache center (cream + chocolate emulsion) coated in a thin tempered chocolate shell. The shell requires tempered chocolate to set cleanly without fingerprints showing.</p> Component Notes Ganache (filling) 200g dark chocolate + 100ml heavy cream; heat cream, pour over chocolate, emulsify with a stir \u2014 not a whisk; cool until firm enough to scoop Shell Tempered chocolate; dip each truffle, tap off excess, set on parchment Finish Roll in cocoa powder, crushed nuts, or flaky salt \u2014 your call <p>The confection vocabulary \u2014 know these: - Ganache \u2014 chocolate + cream emulsion; ratio determines texture (thick for truffles, thin for glaze) - Tempered chocolate \u2014 Form V crystals; gloss + snap - Bonbon \u2014 tempered chocolate shell with flavored ganache inside; requires a mold - Bark \u2014 tempered chocolate poured flat, topped before it sets; no skill requirement beyond tempering</p> <p>The connection to the rest of the year: The emulsification in ganache is the same principle as hollandaise and mayonnaise \u2014 fat + water held stable by an emulsifier, in this case the lecithin in the cocoa solids. You've been building toward this all year.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#friday-pavlova","title":"Friday \u2014 Pavlova","text":"<p>Skill: Meringue construction; low-oven drying; stable topping Read first: Kiwi-Passion Fruit Pavlova</p> <p>What you're learning: Pavlova is a meringue case that is crispy on the outside and marshmallow-tender inside. The crispy outside requires a low, long oven (250\u00b0F / 2 hours); the marshmallow interior comes from cornstarch added to the meringue and from the moist residual air of the oven. Top with whipped cream and fresh fruit immediately before serving \u2014 the topping causes collapse if left too long.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pavlova with whipped cream, kiwi, passion fruit, strawberries - This is a Friday dinner: a big pavlova is a celebratory dessert</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Easy Pavlova (Claire Saffitz) \u2014 Watch how she handles the meringue stiffness and the oven door-crack finish; those two details are what create the marshmallowy interior.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#saturday-project-tiramisu-layer-dessert-review","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Tiramisu + Layer Dessert Review","text":"<p>Skill: Tiramisu without gelatin (structure from cold mascarpone cream); building a composed dessert narrative Read first: Best Tiramisu</p> <p>What you're learning: After cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e (baked custard), panna cotta (gelatin), mousse (egg white foam), and pavlova (meringue), tiramisu introduces a fifth dessert structure: mascarpone cream layered with coffee-soaked ladyfingers and set in the refrigerator until the layers merge. No gelatin, no baking, no tempering \u2014 just cold cream and time.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Tiramisu (make at least 4 hours ahead, ideally morning for evening service) - Espresso to accompany</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Classic Tiramisu (Claire Saffitz) \u2014 Compare her mascarpone cream technique to the SE version; the egg handling difference between the two approaches tells you exactly what structure you're building in each.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#week-46-caramel-sticky-toffee-chocolate-chip-cookies-and-the-layer-cake","title":"Week 46 \u2014 Caramel, Sticky Toffee, Chocolate Chip Cookies, and the Layer Cake","text":""},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#monday-caramel-wet-and-dry-methods","title":"Monday \u2014 Caramel: Wet and Dry Methods","text":"<p>Skill: Understanding dry vs. wet caramel; temperature stages of sugar; caramel sauce + butterscotch Read first: Caramel vs. Butterscotch vs. Toffee</p> <p>What you're learning: Sugar has distinct flavor stages as it heats. Dry caramel (no water) is faster and more consistent but harder to control. Wet caramel (water added first) is more forgiving. The difference between caramel (no butter until very end), butterscotch (butter added earlier), and toffee (fully crystallized) is explained clearly in the SE article. Today, make a caramel sauce from scratch.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Use caramel sauce over vanilla ice cream, on crepes, or as a component in your dessert drawer this week - Butterscotch version comparison</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Perfect Stovetop Chocolate Caramels (Claire Saffitz) \u2014 She's working at hard-crack stage rather than sauce stage; watch how she reads color as the primary signal and where she decides the thermometer is secondary.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#tuesday-sticky-toffee-pudding","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Sticky Toffee Pudding","text":"<p>Skill: English pudding structure (not cold dessert); date integration; toffee sauce coverage Read first: Sticky Toffee Pudding</p> <p>What you're learning: British sticky toffee pudding is a date-rich cake soaked in toffee sauce. The dates are pureed into boiling water and mixed into the batter (they disappear but contribute moisture and sweetness). The warm toffee sauce poured over immediately after baking is what creates the \"pudding\" character \u2014 dense, moist, caramel-soaked.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Sticky Toffee Pudding served warm with more toffee sauce and vanilla ice cream or clotted cream</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#wednesday-the-chocolate-chip-cookie-science","title":"Wednesday \u2014 The Chocolate Chip Cookie (Science)","text":"<p>Skill: Understanding fat, flour, and sugar ratios in cookie baking; brown butter; salt finishing Read first: The Best Chocolate Chip Cookies</p> <p>What you're learning: The \"perfect\" chocolate chip cookie encapsulates all of baking science: fat type (browned butter changes flavor significantly), sugar type (more brown sugar = chewier), flour protein level (bread flour = more chew), hydration (overnight chill dries the dough and concentrates flavor), and Maillard browning at the right temperature.</p> <p>Full Meal: - The chocolate chip cookie session \u2014 bake some today, refrigerate the rest for tomorrow - Eat warm with milk or coffee</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Chocolate Chip Cookies (Claire Saffitz) \u2014 Her flour and butter ratios differ from the SE brown-butter approach; bake both versions back-to-back and decide which texture you prefer.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#thursday-rest-day","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":""},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#friday-layer-cake-fundamentals","title":"Friday \u2014 Layer Cake Fundamentals","text":"<p>Skill: G\u00e9noise or butter cake layers; simple syrup moistening; level layers; crumb coat; frosting Read first: G\u00e9noise Sponge for the cake layers \u2014 the crumb coat (a thin layer of frosting sealing crumbs before the final layer) is the technique that separates clean from messy results</p> <p>What you're learning: A well-executed layer cake requires: even layers (weigh the batter), flat tops (cake strips or dome trim), proper cooling before frosting (warm cake will melt buttercream), a crumb coat, refrigerating the crumb coat before final frosting, and patience. Make a 3-layer cake: vanilla, chocolate, or lemon curd between layers.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Layer cake \u2014 completed tonight or Saturday depending on timing - Serve to anyone available; this is a milestone bake</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#saturday-project-grand-dessert-finale","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Grand Dessert Finale","text":"<p>Skill: Full dessert service for a dinner party Goal: Invite people over. Serve three desserts from this two-week block:</p> <ol> <li>Petit dessert first: Individual panna cotta already made, or chocolate mousse in small cups</li> <li>Main dessert: The layer cake from Friday, or the tiramisu from Saturday Week 45</li> <li>Mignardises: Chocolate truffles (ganache rolled in cocoa powder \u2014 simple to make), salted caramel bites</li> </ol> <p>Full Meal: - Full dessert dinner party - Champagne, dessert wines, or coffee throughout</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#custard-science","title":"Custard Science","text":"<p>Cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e and panna cotta are both custards, but they're set by different mechanisms: egg proteins vs. gelatin. Understanding the difference explains every texture variation in the entire custard family.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Classic Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e \u2014 The ratio, the water bath technique, and the blowtorch logistics all in one place.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Classic Panna Cotta \u2014 Gelatin sets at a specific concentration. This recipe explains how to dial the bloom and amount to land the texture you want.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#chocolate-a-module-of-its-own","title":"Chocolate: A Module of Its Own","text":"<p>Chocolate mousse is your introduction to working with chocolate structurally. Chopping, melting, tempering, and folding are four separate skills that the mousse exercise touches on.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Chocolate Mousse \u2014 The full recipe and technique, including the egg white folding method that creates the texture.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Physiology of Taste by Jean Anthelme Brillat-Savarin \u2014 The 19th-century French text that remains the most elegant meditation on the experience of eating and the philosophy of flavor. Not a cookbook \u2014 more like a sophisticated conversation with a great host.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Weeks 47\u201348: Pastry | Weeks 51\u201352: Signature Dishes \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/quick-ref.html","title":"Weeks 49\u201350: Desserts \u2014 Quick Reference","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 47\u201348: Pastry | Weeks 51\u201352: Signature Dishes \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/quick-ref.html#custard-set-dessert-reference","title":"Custard &amp; Set Dessert Reference","text":"Dessert Set By Eggs Liquid Temp Notes Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e Heat (egg yolk) 5 yolks 500ml cream 325\u00b0F, bake to 160\u00b0F Bain-marie; wobble test Panna Cotta Gelatin none 500ml cream + milk No bake 1 tsp gelatin per 2 cups; bloom first Pastry Cream Heat + starch (yolks) 4 yolks 500ml milk Boil then pull Plastic wrap on surface; refrigerate Cr\u00e8me Anglaise Heat (yolk) 4 yolks 500ml milk/cream 180\u00b0F, coat spoon Strain; do NOT boil Chocolate Mousse Air (whites) 3 whites \u2014 Cool chocolate first Fold in large strokes; chill 2h Tiramisu Cold (mascarpone) 4 yolks \u2014 No bake 4h minimum; overnight best"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/quick-ref.html#gelatin-reference","title":"Gelatin Reference","text":"Form Conversion Bloom Process Notes Powdered 1 packet = 2\u00bc tsp = 7g Sprinkle over cold water; wait 5 min Use 1 tsp per 2 cups for soft set Sheet (silver) 1 sheet \u2248 1 tsp powdered Submerge in cold water 5 min; squeeze dry More consistent; professional standard <p>Panna cotta gel strength: 1 tsp powdered = just-holds shape; 1\u00bd tsp = firmer; 2 tsp = bouncy (too much)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/quick-ref.html#sugar-stages-reference","title":"Sugar Stages Reference","text":"Stage Temperature Appearance Use Thread 230\u2013235\u00b0F Thin threads Simple syrups Soft ball 235\u2013240\u00b0F Soft pliable ball Fondant, fudge Firm ball 245\u2013250\u00b0F Holds shape Caramel candies Hard ball 250\u2013265\u00b0F Rigid ball Nougat Soft crack 270\u2013290\u00b0F Threads, brittle Butterscotch Hard crack 300\u2013310\u00b0F Glassy, shatters Toffee, brittles Caramel 320\u2013360\u00b0F Golden to dark amber Caramel sauce"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/quick-ref.html#pavlova-meringue-reference","title":"Pavlova / Meringue Reference","text":"Type Sugar Ratio Technique Use French Meringue 2:1 sugar:white Whip to stiff, fold granulated sugar Pavlova, macarons Swiss Meringue 2:1 over warm water Warm + whip; silky stable Buttercream, toasts Italian Meringue Hot syrup 240\u00b0F into whites Most stable Baked Alaska, pastries <p>Pavlova specifics: - Vinegar + cornstarch added \u2192 marshmallow interior guaranteed - Bake at 250\u00b0F for 90\u2013120 minutes; turn off oven and leave inside until cool - Top immediately before serving (whipped cream softens the crust after 30 min) - Humidity is the enemy of meringue; don't bake on rainy days</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/quick-ref.html#caramel-vs-butterscotch-vs-toffee","title":"Caramel vs. Butterscotch vs. Toffee","text":"Name Fat Stage Texture Caramel sauce Butter + cream added after amber 340\u2013360\u00b0F Pourable sauce Butterscotch sauce Brown sugar + butter cooked together Lower (soft ball) Butterier, richer Toffee Higher butter ratio, cooked to hard crack 300\u2013310\u00b0F Solid, brittle Sticky toffee sauce Butter + cream + brown sugar Boiled together Pourable, used warm"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/quick-ref.html#chocolate-chip-cookie-variables","title":"Chocolate Chip Cookie Variables","text":"Variable Effect on Result Bread flour vs. AP More chew, denser structure Brown butter Nuttier, more complex flavor More brown sugar Chewier, more moist More white sugar Crispier, spreads more Overnight chill Drier dough, concentrated flavor, better browning Sea salt on top Flavor contrast; brightens sweetness Higher bake temp Crispier exterior; less set interior"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/quick-ref.html#layer-cake-technique","title":"Layer Cake Technique","text":"<ol> <li>Weigh batter into even layers (don't eyeball)</li> <li>Bake with cake strips (wet strips around pan = even rise, no dome)</li> <li>Cool completely before any frosting contact</li> <li>Level tops with serrated knife</li> <li>Moistening syrup (simple syrup + flavoring) brushed on each layer</li> <li>Crumb coat \u2014 thin layer, refrigerate 15\u201320 minutes</li> <li>Final coat \u2014 smooth with bench scraper</li> <li>Refrigerate assembled cake; bring to temp 30 minutes before serving</li> </ol>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/quick-ref.html#week-4546-recipes-at-a-glance","title":"Week 45\u201346 Recipes at a Glance","text":"Day Dish Key Skill Source W45 Mon Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e Baked custard / bain-marie SE W45 Tue Panna Cotta Gelatin calibration SE W45 Wed Chocolate Mousse Air/fold/chocolate SE W45 Fri Pavlova Meringue / low-oven SE W45 Sat Tiramisu Mascarpone cream / layering SE W46 Mon Caramel Sauce Dry vs. wet caramel SE W46 Tue Sticky Toffee Pudding Date cake / toffee sauce SE W46 Wed Chocolate Chip Cookies Fat / flour / sugar science SE W46 Fri Layer Cake Crumb coat / frosting SE W46 Sat Grand Dessert Finale Full dessert dinner party \u2014"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/shopping-list.html","title":"Weeks 49\u201350: Desserts \u2014 Shopping List","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 47\u201348: Pastry | Weeks 51\u201352: Signature Dishes \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Kitchen torch (essential for cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e br\u00fbl\u00e9e step)</li> <li>[ ] 4\u20136 ramekins (cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e / panna cotta)</li> <li>[ ] Stand or hand mixer (pavlova meringue, buttercream frosting)</li> <li>[ ] 9-inch round cake pans \u00d7 3 (layer cake)</li> <li>[ ] Bench scraper (frosting the cake)</li> <li>[ ] Pastry brush (simple syrup on cake layers)</li> <li>[ ] Candy/instant-read thermometer (caramel, cookie dough, custard)</li> <li>[ ] Large roasting pan (bain-marie for cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e)</li> <li>[ ] Parchment paper</li> <li>[ ] Springform pan (optional \u2014 tiramisu, mousse presentation)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/shopping-list.html#dairy-eggs","title":"Dairy &amp; Eggs","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 2 quarts</li> <li>[ ] Whole milk \u2014 1 quart</li> <li>[ ] Mascarpone \u2014 8 oz (tiramisu)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 2 lbs (layer cake, caramel, cookies, sticky toffee)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 3 dozen (custards, mousse, meringue, cake, cookies)</li> <li>[ ] Cr\u00e8me fra\u00eeche or sour cream \u2014 1 cup (optional: fold into whipped cream for pavlova)</li> <li>[ ] Vanilla ice cream \u2014 1 pint (sticky toffee pudding accompaniment)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/shopping-list.html#chocolate","title":"Chocolate","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Bittersweet chocolate (70%) \u2014 12 oz (mousse + truffles)</li> <li>[ ] Semi-sweet or milk chocolate chips \u2014 12 oz (chocolate chip cookies)</li> <li>[ ] Dutch-process cocoa powder \u2014 \u00bc cup (truffle coating, cake option)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/shopping-list.html#pantry-baking","title":"Pantry &amp; Baking","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Granulated sugar \u2014 5 lbs</li> <li>[ ] Brown sugar (dark) \u2014 2 lbs (cookies, sticky toffee, butterscotch)</li> <li>[ ] Powdered/confectioners' sugar \u2014 1 lb (buttercream frosting)</li> <li>[ ] All-purpose flour \u2014 5 lbs</li> <li>[ ] Bread flour \u2014 2 lbs (chocolate chip cookies \u2014 more chew)</li> <li>[ ] Cake flour \u2014 2 lbs (layer cake \u2014 finer crumb)</li> <li>[ ] Baking powder \u2014 1 tin</li> <li>[ ] Baking soda \u2014 1 box</li> <li>[ ] Cornstarch \u2014 1 box (pavlova, pastry cream)</li> <li>[ ] Salt (Diamond Crystal kosher) \u2014 1 box</li> <li>[ ] Flaky sea salt (Maldon) \u2014 finishing for cookies</li> <li>[ ] Powdered gelatin \u2014 2 packets (panna cotta; possibly mousse)</li> <li>[ ] Vanilla extract \u2014 1 bottle (or vanilla bean paste)</li> <li>[ ] Vanilla beans \u2014 2 pods (cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e + panna cotta)</li> <li>[ ] Espresso or strong coffee \u2014 1 cup brewed (tiramisu)</li> <li>[ ] Coffee liqueur (Kahl\u00faa or Tia Maria) \u2014 optional for tiramisu</li> <li>[ ] Dates (Medjool) \u2014 8 oz (sticky toffee pudding)</li> <li>[ ] Ladyfingers (Savoiardi) \u2014 1 package (tiramisu)</li> <li>[ ] White vinegar or cream of tartar \u2014 (pavlova stability)</li> <li>[ ] Chocolate-covered espresso beans \u2014 optional garnish</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/shopping-list.html#fruit-produce","title":"Fruit &amp; Produce","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 4 (pavlova topping; cake option)</li> <li>[ ] Kiwi \u2014 4\u20136 (pavlova)</li> <li>[ ] Passion fruit \u2014 4 (pavlova topping; or top with strawberries)</li> <li>[ ] Strawberries \u2014 1 pint (pavlova and/or frosting between layers)</li> <li>[ ] Raspberries or raspberry jam \u2014 1 cup (panna cotta coulis + layer cake option)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/shopping-list.html#layer-cake-supplies","title":"Layer Cake Supplies","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Cake strips (wet fabric strips for pans) \u2014 or DIY with damp towel strips</li> <li>[ ] Cake board or large plate for assembly</li> <li>[ ] Offset spatula or large spoon for frosting</li> <li>[ ] Cocktail stick / cake tester (done test)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/49-50-desserts/shopping-list.html#planning-notes","title":"Planning Notes","text":"<p>Make-ahead order for Week 45: 1. Sat/Sun: Review recipes; buy all supplies 2. Mon: Cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e (make in morning, refrigerate all day; br\u00fbl\u00e9e before serving) 3. Tue: Panna cotta (make morning; unmold at night \u2014 6h minimum) 4. Wed: Chocolate mousse (make morning; chill 4h minimum) 5. Fri: Pavlova (bake morning; top immediately before serving) 6. Sat: Tiramisu (make morning \u00d7 4h; serve in evening)</p> <p>Make-ahead order for Week 46: 1. Mon: Caramel sauce (keeps refrigerated 2 weeks) 2. Tue: Sticky toffee pudding (bake; pour sauce over; reheat portions as needed) 3. Wed: Cookie dough (make; refrigerate overnight; bake Thu morning or Fri) 4. Fri: Layer cake (bake layers Thu if needed; assemble Friday; refrigerate overnight) 5. Sat: Dessert party \u2014 pull from fridge; arrange; serve</p> <p>Note: Cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e sugar must be br\u00fbl\u00e9ed immediately before serving \u2014 never ahead.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html","title":"Weeks 51\u201352: Signature Dishes","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 49\u201350: Desserts | Weeks 53\u201354: Menus &amp; Timing \u2192</p> <p>\"A signature dish is not the hardest dish you can make. It is the dish that is most you \u2014 the dish you make better than anyone else makes it, better every time, effortlessly, and that people ask for again and again. Signature dishes are earned through repetition, not invention.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#the-concept","title":"The Concept","text":"<p>By now you have cooked approximately 200 dishes across 46 weeks. You have made braises and stocks, fried and grilled, cured and fermented, made bread and croissants and mole. The question of this two-week block is not \"what can I make?\" but \"what do I make that is mine?\"</p> <p>A signature dish satisfies several criteria:</p> <ol> <li>Repeatability \u2014 you have made it enough times that you don't use a recipe</li> <li>Personal identity \u2014 it reflects your taste, your background, or a perfect moment</li> <li>Consistent improvement \u2014 each iteration is measurably better than the last</li> <li>Versatility \u2014 it can go on a weeknight dinner table or a dinner party table</li> </ol> <p>This block is structured differently. The first week is technical catch-up and deep refinement. The second week is your own creative project.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#week-47-mastery-sessions-wok-knife-chocolate-mise-en-place","title":"Week 47 \u2014 Mastery Sessions: Wok, Knife, Chocolate, Mise en Place","text":""},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#monday-advanced-wok-technique","title":"Monday \u2014 Advanced Wok Technique","text":"<p>Skill: High-heat wok work; \"wok hei\" production; toss technique; seasoning a wok Read first: How to Buy, Season, and Care for a Wok</p> <p>What you're learning: Wok hei (literally \"breath of the wok\") is the smoky, slightly charred, Maillard-browned quality you get only from extremely high heat applied briefly. It requires a seasoned wok, maximum burner heat, dry ingredients, and decisive action. Today: season your wok if you haven't; cook a simple stir-fry at maximum heat and study what happens. No recipe \u2014 technique only.</p> <p>Session: - Wok seasoning (if not done): high heat + oil + paper towel \u00d7 3 - Stir-fry: aromatics, vegetables, protein, sauce \u2014 separately, in rapid sequence - Take notes: was there smoke? A char smell? What happened to the garlic?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#tuesday-knife-skills-where-are-you-now","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Knife Skills: Where Are You Now?","text":"<p>Skill: Speed and accuracy assessment; brunoise; chiffonade; the \"claw\" grip Read first: How to Chop an Onion, compare your Week 1 time</p> <p>What you're learning: Return to the first skill you practiced in Week 1. Dice an onion and track time and uniformity. Chiffonade a stack of basil leaves. Cut a carrot into fine brunoise (2mm cubes). Speed is less important than consistency \u2014 uniform cuts cook evenly; uneven cuts produce uneven results. You have cooked for 47 weeks. How much faster and cleaner is your knife technique?</p> <p>Session: - Timed onion dice (compare Week 1 estimate) - Carrot brunoise (tedious; requires patience and a sharp knife) - Basil chiffonade (sharp knife only \u2014 a dull knife bruises and blackens basil)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#wednesday-the-best-chocolate-chip-cookie-refinement","title":"Wednesday \u2014 The Best Chocolate Chip Cookie (Refinement)","text":"<p>Skill: Cookie formula refinement; understanding your preferences; repeating with intention Read first: The Best Chocolate Chip Cookies</p> <p>What you're learning: The Serious Eats \"Food Lab\" chocolate chip cookie is a foundational study in technique: browned butter, bread flour, overnight rest, and the decision to use chips vs. chopped chocolate. After making them last week, today you make adjustments based on your notes. Do you want crunchier edges? More brown sugar. Chewier? More bread flour, less bake time. Crisper overall? Less brown sugar.</p> <p>Session: - Make cookie dough with intentional variation from last week - Document the variable changed and the result - Freeze half the dough as \"emergency cookies\" for future dinner parties</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Broiled Chocolate Chip Cookies (Adam Ragusea) \u2014 His technique is the opposite instinct from the Food Lab method \u2014 intense top heat vs. even oven heat. Watch how the variable changes the cookie structure and ask yourself which result you'd rather eat.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#thursday-mise-en-place-full-professional-setup","title":"Thursday \u2014 Mise en Place: Full Professional Setup","text":"<p>Skill: Station organization; timing a multi-dish dinner from scratch; cook-to-plate flow Read first: Mise en Place</p> <p>What you're learning: Professional kitchens work because everything is prepped before service begins. Your mise en place practice has evolved through the year \u2014 tonight, apply it formally to a 3-course dinner. Write out every prep step before you start cooking. Time the sequence. Identify what can be done ahead vs. what is last-minute. This is the cognitive skill that separates capable home cooks from experienced ones.</p> <p>Session: - Plan a 3-course dinner entirely from your existing repertoire - Write full mise en place list before cooking - Execute using proper station workflow - Debrief: what was left undone? What hit the table late?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#friday-the-caramel-sauce-perfection","title":"Friday \u2014 The Caramel Sauce (Perfection)","text":"<p>Skill: Repeating a technique until it is automated Focus: Caramel sauce from Week 46. Make it again. Faster and without hesitation.</p> <p>What you're learning: There is no new technique today. You are implementing the principle of \"repetition until the hands remember.\" The caramel sauce is chosen because sugar work is one of the skills that only becomes reliable through repetition. The first time you made it, you were watching the color carefully. Today you should begin to know by smell and sound.</p> <p>Session: - Caramel sauce (dry method \u2014 no water) - Butterscotch variation for comparison - Use over ice cream, cake, or sticky toffee pudding (if any remains)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#saturday-project-the-dish-you-havent-perfected-yet","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: The Dish You Haven't Perfected Yet","text":"<p>Skill: Choosing and attacking a weak point in your cooking Goal: Make one dish from any previous unit that you felt was the weakest or least successful.</p> <p>Look back at your notes across 47 weeks. Which dish didn't go as planned? Which one did you never feel settled with? Identify it and execute it again, this time with full attention: a better understanding of the technique, a cleaner mise en place, and the experience of 47 weeks behind you.</p> <p>Session: - Choose one dish from any prior week - Research any remaining questions about it - Execute it cleanly and completely - Document: what's different, what's the same</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Three Salting Methods You Should Know (Samin Nosrat) \u2014 Whatever dish you chose, salt is in it. Watch her explain the \u201cwhen\u201d and \u201chow much\u201d across different protein and cooking contexts \u2014 then apply it consciously to what you're making today.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#week-48-building-your-signature","title":"Week 48 \u2014 Building Your Signature","text":""},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#monday-define-it","title":"Monday \u2014 Define It","text":"<p>Exercise: Write three dishes you have made this year that you would feel confident serving to any person at any time. Not the most impressive \u2014 the most yours.</p> <p>There are no correct answers. These might be your braised short ribs, your pad thai, your sourdough, your tiramisu. They are yours because: - You made them multiple times - You know exactly where they might go wrong - You adjusted the recipe to your taste - You would make them without a recipe now</p> <p>Write these down. These are your current signatures.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#tuesday-wednesday-refine-signature-1-and-2","title":"Tuesday, Wednesday \u2014 Refine Signature #1 and #2","text":"<p>Skill: Intentional, focused repetition Goal: Execute Signature dishes #1 and #2 from your list, back-to-back on consecutive evenings. Make notes:</p> <ul> <li>What is your personal variation from the original recipe?</li> <li>What would you serve alongside it?</li> <li>At what point in a dinner party would you serve it?</li> <li>What is the one thing that could still go wrong?</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#thursday-rest-day-shopping-planning","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day / Shopping / Planning","text":"<p>Prepare for your final signature dinner on Saturday.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#friday-develop-a-new-recipe","title":"Friday \u2014 Develop a New Recipe","text":"<p>Skill: Synthesis \u2014 combining techniques across the 48 weeks into something original Challenge: Invent a dish or a meaningful variation on an existing dish. Use any technique from this year, applied to an ingredient or combination you have not cooked before.</p> <p>This is not a test. There is no grade. Failures here are valuable. The goal is to think like a cook \u2014 to ask \"what if\" and act.</p> <p>Session: - 30 minutes of planning (flavors, techniques, components) - Cook the experiment - Eat it, honestly assess it - Write one paragraph on what you would change next time</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#saturday-project-the-personal-tasting-menu","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: The Personal Tasting Menu","text":"<p>Goal: Cook and serve a 4-course meal entirely from your own repertoire, your own variations, for people who will give you honest feedback.</p> <p>Suggested structure: 1. Amuse-bouche: One bite \u2014 a compressed melon, a spoonful of something surprising, one perfect piece 2. Starter: A dish from your cured/vegetable/shellfish repertoire 3. Main: Your most comfortable, reliable, personal protein preparation 4. Dessert: The dessert you are most proud of from weeks 43\u201346</p> <p>House rules: - No recipe open during cooking - Music and candles acceptable - Write a menu card for the table (even if handwritten) - After dinner: ask each person for one honest criticism and one honest compliment</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#wok-mastery-building-the-foundation","title":"Wok Mastery: Building the Foundation","text":"<p>The wok is the most efficient cooking vessel ever designed. Seasoning it correctly, managing the heat zones, and developing the muscle memory for constant motion are the three skills required.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Buy, Season, and Care for a Wok \u2014 The complete guide to buying, seasoning, and maintaining a wok \u2014 from initial cure to ongoing care.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Butter-Baste Steaks, Chops, and Fish \u2014 Wok cooking and butter basting share the same principle: constant, deliberate application of fat over heat to build a crust and baste simultaneously.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#developing-a-signature-dish","title":"Developing a Signature Dish","text":"<p>The jump from following a recipe to owning a dish happens through iteration: make it 3 times, tweak one thing each time, then make it from memory. The dishes that feel like yours come from this process.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Dry-Brining Is the Best Way to Brine Meat, Poultry, and More \u2014 One of the highest-leverage techniques to apply to your signature dish if it involves any protein \u2014 the results are dramatic enough to impress guests immediately.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Martin Yan's wok technique \u2014 The master of wok showmanship, but the technique underneath is real and careful. His one-handed chopping and wok tossing are aspirational benchmarks.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Wok: Recipes and Techniques by J. Kenji L\u00f3pez-Alt \u2014 The most thorough wok cookbook ever written in English. Every heat level, every protein, every regional application. The natural follow-on from your Week 47\u201348 work.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Weeks 49\u201350: Desserts | Weeks 53\u201354: Menus &amp; Timing \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html","title":"Weeks 51\u201352: Signature Dishes \u2014 Quick Reference","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 49\u201350: Desserts | Weeks 53\u201354: Menus &amp; Timing \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html#wok-hei-what-it-is-and-how-to-get-it","title":"Wok Hei: What It Is and How to Get It","text":"Factor Requirement Common Failure Heat Maximum burner output \u2014 gas preferred Electric/induction: insufficient BTU Pan Seasoned wok; screaming hot before oil Cold wok = steaming, not searing Ingredients Dry surface; small batches Wet veg/protein releases steam Motion Constant toss; 30\u201360 seconds max Over-stirring = temperature drop Oil High smoke-point (peanut, grapeseed) Olive oil \u2192 burns bitter Sequence Aromatics \u2192 protein \u2192 veg \u2192 sauce Wrong order = mushy or raw"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html#wok-seasoning-method","title":"Wok Seasoning Method","text":"<ol> <li>Heat wok over high flame until water droplets vanish instantly</li> <li>Add 1 tbsp high-smoke-point oil; swirl to coat</li> <li>Rub with folded paper towel (tongs \u2014 do NOT burn yourself)</li> <li>Repeat 3\u00d7 until surface is uniformly darkened</li> <li>Store dry; never soap-scrub; re-season if rust appears</li> </ol>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html#knife-skill-self-assessment","title":"Knife Skill Self-Assessment","text":"Skill Week 1 Target Week 47 Target Benchmark Onion dice (medium) 3\u20134 minutes Under 90 seconds 1 min = professional Carrot brunoise (2mm) Rough approximation Uniform cubes Zero guesswork on size Basil chiffonade Bruised or thick Clean, thin, no black Sharp knife only Garlic minced Chunky Near-paste Flat-side press + rock Julienne carrot Skipped Consistent 2mm strips Patience + sharp blade"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html#mise-en-place-workflow","title":"Mise en Place Workflow","text":"<p>Before you cook: 1. Read the full recipe twice 2. Write a mise en place list (every ingredient prepped to what state) 3. Group by timing: what cooks longest goes first 4. Set up stations: cutting board, stove, plating area</p> <p>While cooking: - Keep mise en place bowls/plates in use order left to right - Clean as you go \u2014 wipe board between tasks - Taste as you build \u2014 every layer, not just the end</p> <p>For a 3-course dinner (timing template): | Stage | Window | Tasks | |---|---|---| | T-2 hours | Active prep | Stock, braises, doughs, marinades, dessert | | T-1 hour | Component prep | All veg cut, proteins seasoned, sauces made | | T-30 min | Final staging | Plates warmed, sauces reheated, garnish ready | | T-0 | Service | Cook-to-order only; assemble components |</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html#chocolate-chip-cookie-variables-decision-chart","title":"Chocolate Chip Cookie Variables (Decision Chart)","text":"Preference Adjustment Crispier edge More white sugar; higher temp (375\u00b0F); thinner dough ball Chewier center More brown sugar; bread flour; underbake slightly More complex flavor Brown butter; overnight rest (minimum); flaky salt on top Crunchy throughout Lower temp (325\u00b0F); longer bake; fully cool before eating Deeper chocolate Chopped dark chocolate instead of chips; chips melt different Bigger pools of chocolate Chopped wafers; reserve chunks for pressing on top before baking"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html#caramel-trouble-guide","title":"Caramel Trouble Guide","text":"Problem Cause Fix Crystallized / grainy Sugar crystals on pan sides got in Wet brush pan sides; start over Didn't get dark enough Under-cooked; light amber isn't enough Go to deep amber (350\u00b0F+) Bitter / burnt Over-cooked past 370\u00b0F Start over Seized when cream added Cream too cold; rapid temp drop Warm cream slightly first Too thick when cool Too little cream Add more warm cream and stir"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html#signature-dish-evaluation-criteria","title":"Signature Dish Evaluation Criteria","text":"<p>When deciding if a dish is \"yours,\" ask:</p> Question Yes / No Can I make this without a recipe? Have I made this 3+ times? Do I know what can go wrong and how to fix it? Have I adjusted it to my own taste? Would I serve this at a dinner party without anxiety? <p>3+ Yes answers: This is likely a signature dish for you.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html#week-4748-sessions-at-a-glance","title":"Week 47\u201348 Sessions at a Glance","text":"Day Session Key Skill W47 Mon Wok technique deep dive Wok hei, seasoning W47 Tue Knife skills assessment Self-audit; brunoise W47 Wed Chocolate chip cookies (refined) Variable adjustment W47 Thu Mise en place \u2014 formal setup 3-course timing W47 Fri Caramel sauce (repeated) Automation via repetition W47 Sat The difficult dish revisited Weak point attack W48 Mon Define your signatures Reflection + writing W48 Tue\u2013Wed Refine signatures #1 and #2 Intentional repetition W48 Fri Develop a new recipe Creative synthesis W48 Sat Personal Tasting Menu (4 courses) Full dinner party"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/shopping-list.html","title":"Weeks 51\u201352: Signature Dishes \u2014 Shopping List","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 49\u201350: Desserts | Weeks 53\u201354: Menus &amp; Timing \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Wok (carbon steel; 14-inch recommended)</li> <li>[ ] Wok spatula (chan dao / wok shovel)</li> <li>[ ] Sharpened chef's knife (hone before Week 47 knives session)</li> <li>[ ] Whetstone or knife sharpening service if needed</li> <li>[ ] Stand mixer with whisk and paddle (cookies, buttercream)</li> <li>[ ] Digital scale (cookies)</li> <li>[ ] Kitchen timer (mise en place drills)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/shopping-list.html#week-47-wok-session","title":"Week 47 \u2014 Wok Session","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] High smoke-point oil (peanut, grapeseed, or avocado) \u2014 16 oz</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 1 head</li> <li>[ ] Ginger \u2014 1 knob</li> <li>[ ] Scallions \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Protein of choice (chicken thigh, shrimp, or firm tofu) \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Mixed vegetables (bell pepper, broccoli, snap peas) \u2014 2\u20133 cups combined</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce, oyster sauce, sesame oil (use existing pantry stock)</li> <li>[ ] Cornstarch \u2014 (velveting protein if desired; existing stock)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/shopping-list.html#week-47-cookie-session","title":"Week 47 \u2014 Cookie Session","text":"<p>Note: purchase based on your planned variation from Week 46 batch</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Bread flour \u2014 2 lbs</li> <li>[ ] Granulated sugar \u2014 2 cups</li> <li>[ ] Dark brown sugar \u2014 2 cups</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 6 (room temperature)</li> <li>[ ] Baking soda \u2014 (existing stock)</li> <li>[ ] Flaky sea salt (Maldon) \u2014 (existing stock)</li> <li>[ ] High-quality dark chocolate \u2014 12 oz, chopped (better than chips if trying variation)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/shopping-list.html#week-47-mise-en-place-dinner-3-course","title":"Week 47 \u2014 Mise en Place Dinner (3-Course)","text":"<p>These items depend entirely on your menu choice; below is a suggested path:</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Protein for main course (from your signature list)</li> <li>[ ] Vegetables for starter</li> <li>[ ] Dessert components (pull from existing Week 45-46 stock if any remains)</li> <li>[ ] Wine or beverage for dinner party simulation</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/shopping-list.html#week-48-personal-tasting-menu","title":"Week 48 \u2014 Personal Tasting Menu","text":"<p>All 4 courses should be drawn from your existing repertoire. No new ingredients required that you don't already know.</p> <p>Suggested shopping by category: - [ ] Amuse-bouche protein or produce \u2014 1 small piece (enough for 1\u20132 bites per person) - [ ] Starter: pull from shellfish block (clams, mussels, oysters) or cured (gravlax, rillettes) - [ ] Main: your signature protein \u2014 buy the best quality version you can afford - [ ] Dessert: choose from Weeks 43\u201346 repertoire; buy any missing components</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/shopping-list.html#pantry-replenishment-whole-project","title":"Pantry Replenishment (whole project)","text":"<p>Now that you are in the final weeks, check and replenish:</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Extra virgin olive oil \u2014 fresh bottle</li> <li>[ ] Diamond Crystal kosher salt \u2014 full box</li> <li>[ ] Black peppercorns (whole) \u2014 grinder or mill refill</li> <li>[ ] Flaky sea salt (Maldon) \u2014 for finishing</li> <li>[ ] Vinegars \u2014 sherry, red wine, white wine (replace any empties)</li> <li>[ ] Dijon mustard \u2014 full jar</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce \u2014 full bottle</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce \u2014 check level</li> <li>[ ] Tahini \u2014 check level (if using)</li> <li>[ ] Capers \u2014 check level</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/51-52-signature-dishes/shopping-list.html#planning-notes","title":"Planning Notes","text":"<p>Week 47 is a technical week \u2014 all sessions except Saturday are repeat/refine. Minimal shopping required beyond the cookie ingredients and the wok session.</p> <p>Week 48 is about you \u2014 the shopping list for Week 48 is entirely based on your personal signature dishes. Look at your Week 48 menu, write your own shopping list customized to those dishes, and buy the highest-quality ingredients you have all year.</p> <p>Freezer note: Cookie dough from Week 47 Wednesday should be portioned and frozen; tag with date and bake time. These are your emergency dinner party cookies for weeks 49\u201352.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html","title":"Weeks 53\u201354: Menus and Timing","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 51\u201352: Signature Dishes | Weeks 55\u201356: Final Exam \u2192</p> <p>\"The difference between a cook and a chef is service. A cook makes one plate. A chef makes six plates \u2014 the same plate, at the same time, every night. The home cook equivalent: hosting a dinner party where every dish hits the table at the right temperature, in the right sequence, having been made by one person.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#the-challenge-of-this-block","title":"The Challenge of This Block","text":"<p>You have now cooked approximately 230 dishes across this program. The remaining barrier between you and true fluency is not technique \u2014 it is logistics. Cooking for yourself, cooking for two, and cooking for six are three completely different skills. This block teaches the last one.</p> <p>Over two weeks, you will plan and execute three increasingly ambitious dinners, learning the structure of a tasting menu, the dynamics of cooking multiple dishes simultaneously, and the emotional control required when something goes wrong during service.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#week-49-the-architecture-of-a-dinner-party","title":"Week 49 \u2014 The Architecture of a Dinner Party","text":""},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#monday-menu-design-theory","title":"Monday \u2014 Menu Design Theory","text":"<p>Skill: Menu composition; flavor arc; season-appropriate choices; dietary accommodation</p> <p>What you're learning: A menu is not a list of dishes \u2014 it is a narrative. It has a beginning (something light and inviting), a middle (the main event), and an end (resolution or surprise). Weight increases, then decreases. Flavors build and contrast. One rich dish does not follow another. One acid-forward dish cleans the palate between two heavy ones.</p> <p>Exercise: - Write three different 4-course menus using only dishes from this program - Identify the weight/flavor arc of each - Choose one to execute this Friday</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#tuesday-the-make-ahead-audit","title":"Tuesday \u2014 The Make-Ahead Audit","text":"<p>Skill: Identifying what in any menu can be prepared in advance vs. cooked \u00e0 la minute</p> <p>What you're learning: The professional kitchen trick for home cooks is the same as it is in restaurants: almost nothing at a dinner party should be cooked to order. The goal is to have 80% of the meal finished before guests arrive so you are present at the table, not absent in the kitchen. Today, take one of your three menus and do a component-by-component make-ahead audit.</p> <p>Exercise \u2014 Build a run-of-show for Friday's dinner:</p> Component How Far Ahead Notes Dessert Day before Tiramisu, panna cotta, mousse \u2014 all gel overnight Braise Day before Better the next day; reheat gently Bread Day before Slice just before service Starter Morning of Keep covered and refrigerated Sauce Hour before Hold warm in bain-marie Protein final cook 20\u201330 min before Only truly last-minute item Plating During service Pre-warm plates; garnish ready"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#wednesday-timing-under-pressure","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Timing Under Pressure","text":"<p>Skill: Executing a complete 3-course meal exactly on schedule Read first: How to Set Up a Prep Station Like a Pro Cook \u2014 the professional setup framework applies directly to dinner party timing</p> <p>What you're learning: Time pressure reveals the gaps in your prep. Today, cook a full 3-course dinner with a fixed start time (say, 7:00 PM). Work backward from that time to build a prep schedule. Stick to it. If something runs late, triage: what can be held? What cannot wait? What is the fallback?</p> <p>Session: - 3-course dinner, timed to your fixed service time - Debrief in writing: what was late? What was perfect? What would you prep differently?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#thursday-rest-day-planning-for-friday-dinner-party","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day / Planning for Friday Dinner Party","text":"<p>Plan your Friday dinner: - Confirm guest count (aim for 4\u20136 people) - Finalize menu (all 4 courses; confirmed dietary restrictions) - Write complete shopping list - Write your run-of-show timeline</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#friday-dinner-party-1-small-table","title":"Friday \u2014 Dinner Party #1: Small Table","text":"<p>Goal: Execute a 4-course dinner for 4\u20136 guests on schedule, without major stress</p> <p>Suggested menu structure (your choices): 1. Amuse / nibbles: Put these out as guests arrive \u2014 olives, charcuterie, something spreadable, bread 2. Starter: Cold or room-temperature (already plated before guests sit) 3. Main: Your most reliable protein preparation; components made-ahead; only final cooking during service 4. Dessert: Fully pre-made and refrigerated; plate during main course clearing</p> <p>Rules: - Kitchen timer on from the moment the first guest sits down - Estimate each course's timing and stick within 10 minutes - Clear one course completely before the next appears - Pour between courses; don't rush</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#saturday-post-dinner-debrief","title":"Saturday \u2014 POST-DINNER DEBRIEF","text":"<p>No cooking today. Write or record:</p> <ol> <li>What went exactly as planned?</li> <li>What went wrong and how did you recover?</li> <li>Which dish got the best reaction?</li> <li>What would you change about the menu composition?</li> <li>At what point did you feel most and least in control?</li> </ol>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#week-50-advanced-service-larger-table-multi-course-timing","title":"Week 50 \u2014 Advanced Service: Larger Table, Multi-Course Timing","text":""},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#monday-scaling-recipes","title":"Monday \u2014 Scaling Recipes","text":"<p>Skill: Scaling a recipe from 4 to 8 to 12 servings; understanding what doesn't scale linearly Read first: How to Scale a Recipe</p> <p>What you're learning: Most recipes scale linearly in ingredients \u2014 double the recipe, double the quantities. But timing does not scale linearly: a 2-inch-thick steak and a 4-pound roast don't take twice as long in proportion; they take 4\u00d7 longer. Braising liquid doesn't always need to double. Seasoning perception can shift when quantities are large. Baking, especially, does not always scale simply.</p> <p>Exercise: - Take your Friday dinner recipe and scale it from 4 to 8 servings - Identify every element that requires adjustment beyond simple multiplication - Practice scaling a sauce or braise quantity on your stovetop</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#tuesday-the-art-of-mise-en-place-for-groups","title":"Tuesday \u2014 The Art of Mise en Place for Groups","text":"<p>Skill: Station organization with multiple active pots and pans; delegating one component to a helper Read first: How to Set Up a Prep Station Like a Pro Cook</p> <p>What you're learning: Cooking for 8\u201310 people requires either a helper or a radically different structure \u2014 most of the meal cannot be \u00e0 la minute. Today: plan a dinner party with one additional element from Week 49's dinner, scaled to 8 people, and map out how you would execute it if you had one helper vs. none.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#wednesday-wine-and-beverage-pairing-basics","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Wine and Beverage Pairing Basics","text":"<p>Skill: Pairing beverages to a multi-course meal; non-alcoholic pairing options Read first: - The Basics of Pairing Drinks With Your Food - How to Organize Your Home Bar</p> <p>What you're learning: The classic rules of pairing (white with fish, red with meat) are guidelines, not laws. What matters more: weight of the dish matches weight of the wine; high-acid food pairs with high-acid wine; salt contracts tannin. A single well-chosen bottle per course is better than a confusing progression of many. For non-drinkers: shrubs, sparkling water with citrus, and soft herbal drinks should be prepared with the same care as wine.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#thursday-rest-day-full-planning-for-saturday","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day / Full Planning for Saturday","text":"<p>Plan the final dinner party: - Guest list (6\u201310 people) - Full 5-course menu (add an intermezzo or cheese course) - Complete timeline from the night before through dessert service - Shopping list finalized</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#friday-final-prep-day","title":"Friday \u2014 Final Prep Day","text":"<p>Full day of cooking in advance: - Morning: Start anything that requires 4+ hours (braise, stock, dessert, dough) - Afternoon: All vegetable prep; all sauces; all components plated/organized - Evening: Final walkthrough of your mise en place; set the table; rest</p> <p>Target: When guests arrive Saturday, you have less than 30 minutes of cooking left.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#saturday-project-dinner-party-2-the-full-table","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: Dinner Party #2 \u2014 The Full Table","text":"<p>Goal: A complete, multi-course dinner party for 6\u201310 guests executed with composure</p> <p>Five-course structure: 1. Canap\u00e9s / cocktail nibbles (served standing before sitting) 2. Cold starter (plated in advance) 3. Soup or palate cleanser (optional; ideal for refining timing) 4. Main course with sides (the centerpiece; 2+ components) 5. Dessert (pre-made; plated during main clearing)</p> <p>Metrics for success: - Every course served within 15 minutes of the target time - No course served cold that should be hot - You sat at the table for at least 60% of the meal - The dessert was placed without panic</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#menu-design-the-architecture-behind-the-meal","title":"Menu Design: The Architecture Behind the Meal","text":"<p>A great dinner party menu isn't a collection of dishes \u2014 it's a narrative. Something light and sharp at the start, something rich and satisfying in the middle, something refreshing or sweet at the end. Understanding the rhythm of courses means every meal you host has an internal logic, even if guests can't articulate it. Getting multiple dishes to the table simultaneously \u2014 all at the right temperature, nothing held too long \u2014 isn't talent. It's planning, a written timeline, and repetition.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Guide to Cooking With Wine \u2014 If you're building a menu, you're building wine pairings. This is the reference that covers the logic of pairing by texture, weight, and acidity.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Set Up a Station Like a Pro \u2014 Mise en place from Week 1, revisited at the dinner party scale. The principle of prep-before-service is the same whether you're cooking for 2 or 8.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Setting the Table by Danny Meyer \u2014 Meyer built some of New York's most beloved restaurants. This book is about the art of hospitality \u2014 how the experience of a meal is constructed beyond what's on the plate. Essential reading if you want to understand what separates a good dinner party from one people talk about afterward.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Weeks 51\u201352: Signature Dishes | Weeks 55\u201356: Final Exam \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html","title":"Weeks 53\u201354: Menus and Timing \u2014 Quick Reference","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 51\u201352: Signature Dishes | Weeks 55\u201356: Final Exam \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html#dinner-party-menu-composition-rules","title":"Dinner Party Menu Composition Rules","text":"Principle Application Weight before pleasure Light \u2192 medium \u2192 rich \u2192 light (dessert) Acid punctuation One acid-forward dish after each rich one Color contrast A plate of beige food needs green; a plate of all green needs contrast Temperature variety Not all hot; not all cold; one warm, one room temp Avoid repetition No protein appears twice; no sauce repeats Local and seasonal The best menus are limited by season, not ambition"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html#make-ahead-lead-times","title":"Make-Ahead Lead Times","text":"Component How Far Ahead Storage Braised meats 1\u20132 days Refrigerate in braising liquid; reheat gently Stocks / sauces 3\u20134 days Refrigerate; reduce and finish day-of Pasta dough (uncut) 1 day Wrapped airtight; refrigerate Pastry dough 2\u20133 days Refrigerate; blind-bake on party day Desserts (custard-based) 1 day Refrigerate; br\u00fbl\u00e9e / garnish day of Desserts (gelatin) 1\u20132 days Refrigerate unmolded; garnish last minute Tarts and pastry 1 day (baked) Room temp; fill day of Charcuterie / cured meats 1 week Refrigerate; slice day of Pickled vegetables 2 days+ Refrigerate; use as needed Bread (baked) Day before Room temp wrapped; reheat 5 min at 350\u00b0F"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html#recipe-scaling-guide","title":"Recipe Scaling Guide","text":"Element Scales Linearly Scales Non-Linearly Notes Dry ingredients \u2713 \u2014 Simple multiplication Wet ingredients (sauces) \u2713 \u2014 Double sauce = double quantity Salt and spices \u2014 \u2713 Start at 75%; taste and adjust Acid (lemon, vinegar) \u2014 \u2713 Less than linear; easy to over-acid Aromatics (garlic) \u2014 \u2713 1.5\u00d7 for 2\u00d7 recipe Baking time \u2014 \u2713 Same; watch internal temp not clock Braising / roasting time \u2014 \u2713 Size of piece, not number of pieces Pan size \u2014 \u2713 Bigger pan \u2192 less crowding \u2192 better browning"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html#dinner-party-timeline-template-4-course-7pm-service","title":"Dinner Party Timeline Template (4-Course, 7PM Service)","text":"Time Activity Day before Braise/dessert/stocks completed; refrigerate 10:00 AM Starter prep; check all mise en place 2:00 PM Protein prepped, marinated; bread made 4:00 PM Table set; garnishes prepped; plating elements ready 5:30 PM Final pre-heat oven; sauces warming; clean kitchen 6:00 PM Canap\u00e9s out; guest arrival 7:00 PM Guests sit; starter plated and served 7:30 PM Main course cooking begins (protein to oven or pan) 8:00 PM Mains served; sides complete 8:45 PM Dessert plated during table clearing 9:00 PM Dessert served"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html#wine-and-beverage-pairing-basics","title":"Wine and Beverage Pairing Basics","text":"Dish Character Wine Style Why Oysters / raw shellfish Crisp Muscadet or Chablis High acid mirrors brine Rich cream sauces White Burgundy or Viognier Weight matches weight Grilled white fish Sauvignon Blanc, Vermentino Acid cuts richness, herbal notes Braise / short rib Cabernet Sauvignon, Syrah Tannin + protein = balance Duck / duck confit Pinot Noir; light Grenache Less tannin for fat richness Lamb Rh\u00f4ne red; Ribera del Duero Iron in lamb \u2192 earthy reds Spicy food Off-dry Riesling; Gew\u00fcrztraminer Residual sugar cools heat Charcuterie / cured Chenin Blanc; light Beaujolais Acid cuts fat Rich dessert Sauternes; Banyuls; Tawny Port Wine sweeter than dish Chocolate Banyuls; Amontillado Sherry Bitter matches bitter <p>Non-alcoholic alternatives: - Acid-forward dishes \u2192 shrub (vinegar-based) with sparkling water - Rich main courses \u2192 strong sparkling water with lemon - Dessert \u2192 good espresso or brewed cold brew</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html#service-flow-checklist","title":"Service Flow Checklist","text":"<p>Before guests arrive: - [ ] Table set (plates, silverware, glasses, napkins, candles) - [ ] Canap\u00e9s plated and covered - [ ] Dessert in refrigerator, plated or ready to plate - [ ] All mise en place verified; nothing left unprepped - [ ] Oven preheated - [ ] Sauces in bain-marie or holding position</p> <p>During service: - [ ] Clear each course before next appears - [ ] Warm plates before serving hot courses - [ ] Pour before clearing (don't rush) - [ ] Final sauce/garnish added at last moment</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html#kitchen-triage-when-things-go-wrong","title":"Kitchen Triage: When Things Go Wrong","text":"Problem Immediate Fix Sauce broken (butter) Whisk ice cube in; or start from emulsified base Overcooked protein Thin-slice and serve with assertive sauce; never apologize at the table Underseasoned dish Salt at the table (offer Maldon); squeeze lemon on anything savory Sticking / burning stuck Deglaze with wine or stock; incorporate the fond into sauce Dessert didn't set Serve in glasses as \"deconstructed\"; add texture on top Completely failed component Fill with charcuterie, cheese, bread, olives \u2014 always keep these in reserve"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html#week-4950-at-a-glance","title":"Week 49\u201350 at a Glance","text":"Day Activity Guests W49 Mon Menu design theory No W49 Tue Make-ahead audit No W49 Wed 3-course timed dinner (practice) Optional W49 Thu Rest + planning No W49 Fri Dinner Party #1 (4 courses, 4\u20136 people) Yes (4\u20136) W49 Sat Debrief and reflection No W50 Mon Recipe scaling No W50 Tue Mise en place for groups No W50 Wed Wine and beverage pairing Optional W50 Thu Rest + planning No W50 Fri Full advance prep day No W50 Sat Dinner Party #2 (5 courses, 6\u201310 people) Yes (6\u201310)"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html","title":"Weeks 53\u201354: Menus and Timing \u2014 Shopping List","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 51\u201352: Signature Dishes | Weeks 55\u201356: Final Exam \u2192</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Large roasting pan (for bigger cuts or multiple servings)</li> <li>[ ] Extra half-sheet pans \u00d7 2 (for batch roasting)</li> <li>[ ] Bain-marie setup (hotel pan + hot water; for sauce holding)</li> <li>[ ] Serving platters (for family-style if applicable)</li> <li>[ ] Champagne flutes or white wine glasses for first course</li> <li>[ ] Extra large bowl for salad (scaled up)</li> <li>[ ] Timer with multiple channels (multi-dish tracking)</li> <li>[ ] Cocktail picks / small plates for canap\u00e9s (W49 Fri)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#week-49-dinner-party-1-46-guests","title":"Week 49 Dinner Party #1 (4\u20136 guests)","text":"<p>Shopping list is menu-dependent. The structure below assumes a French-influenced menu. Adjust items to match your chosen menu from the Week 49 Monday planning session.</p> <p>Assumed structure: 1. Canap\u00e9s: Gravlax on blini (or smoked salmon), olives, cornichons 2. Starter: Individual salads or tartare 3. Main: Braise (short ribs, lamb shoulder, or chicken) + roasted vegetables 4. Dessert: Tiramisu or panna cotta (pre-made)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#protein","title":"Protein","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Braising protein (choice): bone-in beef short ribs 4\u20136 lbs, OR lamb shoulder 3\u20134 lbs, OR whole chicken \u00d7 2</li> <li>[ ] Smoked salmon or gravlax \u2014 4\u20136 oz</li> <li>[ ] Charcuterie (prosciutto, salami) \u2014 4\u20136 oz mixed</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"Produce","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Shallots \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Celery \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Root vegetables for roasting (parsnip, turnip, or potato) \u2014 2 lbs</li> <li>[ ] Fresh herbs (thyme, rosemary, parsley) \u2014 1 bunch each</li> <li>[ ] Salad greens (if starter is salad) \u2014 2 heads</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Wine for braising \u2014 1 bottle (use restaurant-quality; it goes in the dish)</li> <li>[ ] Beef or chicken stock \u2014 1 quart (or use homemade from freezer)</li> <li>[ ] Crusty bread \u2014 2 loaves</li> <li>[ ] Olives \u2014 1 jar (canap\u00e9s)</li> <li>[ ] Cornichons \u2014 1 jar</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#dessert-if-tiramisu-or-panna-cotta","title":"Dessert (if tiramisu or panna cotta)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Mascarpone \u2014 8 oz (if tiramisu)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 1 pint</li> <li>[ ] Ladyfingers \u2014 1 package (if tiramisu)</li> <li>[ ] Espresso \u2014 brewed strong day prior</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#week-50-dinner-party-2-610-guests","title":"Week 50 Dinner Party #2 (6\u201310 guests)","text":"<p>Scale your Week 49 menu by 1.5\u20132\u00d7, or design a new 5-course menu. This is intentionally flexible.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#scale-considerations-from-quick-ref-guide","title":"Scale considerations (from quick-ref guide):","text":"<ul> <li>Braise: multiply protein weight 1.5\u20132\u00d7; liquid rises more slowly</li> <li>Sauce: multiply 1.75\u00d7 (less than recipe ratio for flavors)</li> <li>Bread: one extra loaf per 4 guests</li> <li>Butter for service: 1 stick per 6 guests</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#beverage-planning-610-people","title":"Beverage planning (6\u201310 people)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] White wine (aperitif / first course) \u2014 3 bottles</li> <li>[ ] Red wine (main course) \u2014 4 bottles</li> <li>[ ] Dessert wine or port \u2014 1 bottle (small pours)</li> <li>[ ] Sparkling water \u2014 3 liters</li> <li>[ ] Still water \u2014 3 liters</li> <li>[ ] Coffee / espresso for dessert \u2014 1 lb whole bean</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#canape-station-pre-dinner-nibbles-for-10","title":"Canap\u00e9 station (pre-dinner nibbles for 10)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Charcuterie \u2014 8\u201310 oz variety</li> <li>[ ] Cheese selection \u2014 2\u20133 types, 6\u20138 oz each</li> <li>[ ] Crackers or quality bread \u2014 2 packages</li> <li>[ ] Seasonal fruit (grapes, figs, or dried fruit)</li> <li>[ ] Nuts (Marcona almonds, walnuts)</li> <li>[ ] Olives \u2014 1 large jar</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#optional-wine-pairing-if-planning-pairings","title":"Optional Wine Pairing (if planning pairings)","text":"<p>See the wine pairing quick-ref. Bottle quantities for 8 guests: - Aperitif / sparkling: 2 bottles (standard 750ml; ~5 glasses/bottle, small pour) - White wine with starter: 2 bottles - Red wine with main: 3 bottles - Dessert wine: 1 bottle (2\u20133 oz pour per person)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#pantry-supply-top-up","title":"Pantry / Supply Top-Up","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Extra virgin olive oil \u2014 full bottle (you burn through it at this volume)</li> <li>[ ] Diamond Crystal kosher salt \u2014 full box</li> <li>[ ] Maldon sea salt \u2014 for finishing plates</li> <li>[ ] White balsamic or champagne vinegar \u2014 fresh</li> <li>[ ] Dijon mustard \u2014 full jar</li> <li>[ ] Fresh lemon \u2014 1 bag (8\u201310 lemons for finishing and garnish)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#planning-notes","title":"Planning Notes","text":"<p>Week 49 dinner (4\u20136 guests): Keep menu modest and high-quality. Two or three excellent dishes are better than five stressful ones. Choose your most reliable braise \u2014 one that can be made 100% the day before. Run a practice timing session on Wednesday to find gaps.</p> <p>Week 50 dinner (6\u201310 guests): The main stressor will be logistics, not technique. The cooking is familiar. Plan for twice the mise en place time. Have a reserve dish in the refrigerator (charcuterie board, cheese, bread) in case any component requires more time than expected. Guests do not know the menu \u2014 they only know what they taste.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html","title":"Weeks 55\u201356: Module 5 Capstone \u2014 The Final Exam","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 53\u201354: Menus and Timing</p> <p>\"There is no final exam with a pass or fail. There is only the cook you have become, compared to the cook you were. The real exam was every Monday morning when you had to decide to keep going. You kept going.\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#the-year-in-review","title":"The Year in Review","text":"<p>Fifty weeks of cooking. Approximately 250 to 300 dishes executed. Knife skills you didn't have. Stocks you now make on weekends without being asked. Techniques stored in your hands that require no recipes to activate.</p> <p>The final two weeks of this program are structured as a culmination and a retrospective \u2014 not a performance or an audition, but a homecoming. You will cook three meals that mean something: the most ambitious dinner you have ever planned, a quiet version of the first meal you ever cooked, and a dinner that answers the question \"who are you as a cook?\"</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#week-51-the-self-assessment","title":"Week 51 \u2014 The Self-Assessment","text":""},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#monday-skills-inventory","title":"Monday \u2014 Skills Inventory","text":"<p>Exercise: Pull out any notes, journals, or memories from Week 1. Answer the following questions honestly:</p> <ol> <li>What was the first dish you cooked in Week 1?</li> <li>Which week was the hardest? Why?</li> <li>What is a dish you thought you'd never make \u2014 and then made?</li> <li>What technique do you still find genuinely difficult?</li> <li>What do you now do without thinking that required real concentration in Week 1?</li> </ol> <p>Read first: The Serious Eats Knife Tutorial \u2014 your original knife skill reference. Time yourself on an onion dice. Compare.</p> <p>Session: Write at least one page (or record notes). This is the benchmark that gives meaning to everything else.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#tuesday-the-forgotten-dish","title":"Tuesday \u2014 The Forgotten Dish","text":"<p>Exercise: Cook one dish from the first 10 weeks that you have not returned to since. Not because it was bad \u2014 because life moved on and you never circled back.</p> <p>Dig into weeks 1\u201310. Find the dish you meant to repeat but didn't. Cook it today with all subsequent knowledge applied.</p> <p>Session: - Choose and cook the dish - Note how differently you approach it now - Serve it simply; eat and think</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#wednesday-cook-something-from-memory","title":"Wednesday \u2014 Cook Something From Memory","text":"<p>Skill: Executing a complete dish with no written recipe Challenge: Cook a complete 2-course meal entirely from memory. No recipe open. No quick checks. Only what your hands remember.</p> <p>This is the final practical test. It is not graded. But it reveals \u2014 more clearly than any other measure \u2014 what you have actually internalized vs. what you have only read.</p> <p>Debrief: Afterward, look up the recipe you cooked from memory. Where did you differ? Was your version better or worse? Why?</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#thursday-rest-day","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest Day","text":"<p>Eat somewhere you love. Put down the chef's hat. Eat as a guest.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#friday-the-final-mise-en-place-drill","title":"Friday \u2014 The Final Mise en Place Drill","text":"<p>Skill: Professional prep at home speed Goal: Prep a full 4-course dinner in under 2 hours of active kitchen time, starting from whole uncut ingredients</p> <ul> <li>Protein seasoned and resting</li> <li>All vegetables cut, portioned, organized</li> <li>All sauces made or prepped</li> <li>Dessert in refrigerator</li> <li>Table set</li> <li>You showered and at ease by 6 PM</li> </ul> <p>Whether or not guests are invited, execute the prep as if they are.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#saturday-project-the-anniversary-dinner","title":"Saturday \u2014 PROJECT: The Anniversary Dinner","text":"<p>Goal: Cook the dinner you would serve to mark the completion of this year</p> <p>Who do you invite? Your closest people. People who have eaten with you, who watched you improve, who benefited from your cooking experiments. A minimum of 4, a maximum of however many fit at your table.</p> <p>The menu: Let it be entirely yours. No prescribed structure. What do you want to cook? What represents the year? What represents you?</p> <p>Suggested constraints only: - At least 3 courses - At least one dish you learned in the first half of the year - At least one dish from the second half - One true new thing you've never served before</p> <p>Serve it. Sit at the table. Be present.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#week-52-the-final-exam","title":"Week 52 \u2014 The Final Exam","text":""},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#monday-define-the-exam-for-yourself","title":"Monday \u2014 Define the Exam for Yourself","text":"<p>Exercise: Write a brief personal culinary philosophy. 1\u20133 paragraphs. Answer these questions:</p> <ol> <li>What kind of cook do you want to be?</li> <li>What role does food play in your life now, compared to a year ago?</li> <li>What is your signature dish (from the Week 47\u201348 work)?</li> <li>What is the most valuable single thing you learned this year?</li> </ol> <p>There are no correct answers. There is only what is true for you.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#tuesday-cook-the-final-exam-dish","title":"Tuesday \u2014 Cook the Final Exam Dish","text":"<p>The exam: Cook one dish that represents everything.</p> <p>No constraints on cuisine, technique, or difficulty. But it must: - Require real skill (not just effort) - Be completely executed without assistance or recipe - Be something you would be proud to serve to anyone - Taste exactly the way you want it to taste</p> <p>Photograph it. Eat it. Write two sentences about it.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#wednesday-the-retrospective-meal","title":"Wednesday \u2014 The Retrospective Meal","text":"<p>Exercise: Cook a meal that traces the arc of the year:</p> <ul> <li>A bite or starter from weeks 1\u201310 (foundations)</li> <li>A smaller course from weeks 11\u201325 (proteins, cuisines)</li> <li>A main from weeks 25\u201340 (global techniques)</li> <li>A dessert from weeks 41\u201352 (pastry, desserts)</li> </ul> <p>This is a one-person retrospective tasting \u2014 a private tasting menu of the year. Eat slowly. Think about each one.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#thursday-rest","title":"Thursday \u2014 Rest","text":"<p>You have been cooking for 52 weeks. Today you do not cook.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#friday-the-open-kitchen","title":"Friday \u2014 The Open Kitchen","text":"<p>Goal: Cook for people. Whatever they want.</p> <p>Open your kitchen to family, friends, or anyone who wants to taste what you can do. Let them request dishes. Let them watch you cook. Show them the techniques. Cook without a net.</p> <p>This is not a class \u2014 you are not teaching. You are sharing.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#saturday-week-52-the-final-dinner","title":"Saturday \u2014 Week 52: The Final Dinner","text":"<p>No instructions. No structure. No format.</p> <p>You are a cook who has spent 52 weeks building this. Tonight, cook whatever you want, for whoever you love, in whatever way feels most like you.</p> <p>The year is complete.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#what-comes-next","title":"What Comes Next","text":"<p>The 52 weeks were a foundation \u2014 thorough, rigorous, intentional. But the cooking life doesn't end at week 52; it accelerates. Every additional meal is practice. Every new cuisine is a new unit. Every dish you repeat is a refinement.</p> <p>Resources to continue:</p> <ul> <li>Serious Eats \u2014 your primary source throughout; continue using it</li> <li>Kenji L\u00f3pez-Alt's work \u2014 the Food Lab framework; apply it to any new recipe you encounter</li> <li>The recipe you want to make next \u2014 start there</li> </ul> <p>The cook you are now:</p> Skill Week 1 Week 52 Sharp knife, proper grip Learning Automatic Stock from scraps Unknown Weekend habit Sauce from pan drippings Never Reflex Pasta from flour and eggs Unfamiliar Memory Sourdough from wild yeast Impossible-seeming Ongoing relationship A 3-course dinner for 8 Stressful Achievable Cook anything with what's available Unlikely The natural mode <p>You are a cook. You were always going to be.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#deepening-a-skill-you-already-have","title":"Deepening a Skill You Already Have","text":"<p>The best cooks pick one thing and develop mastery. Not breadth \u2014 depth. Pick the area that felt most alive during the year and go further.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How and When to Brine Vegetables \u2014 A small technique that applies to nearly every vegetable preparation. Classic \"go deeper\" territory.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Chef's Table \u2014 Documentary portraits of the world's most interesting chefs. The best cooking education that isn't actually about cooking \u2014 it's about why a life in the kitchen matters.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/index.html#books-for-the-years-ahead","title":"Books for the Years Ahead","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Food Lab by J. Kenji L\u00f3pez-Alt \u2014 If you haven't read it cover to cover yet, that's the next year of education right there.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcda On Food and Cooking by Harold McGee \u2014 The science behind everything you did this year. Read it once and you'll understand why at the level that makes you a better cook forever.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Weeks 53\u201354: Menus and Timing</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/quick-ref.html","title":"Weeks 55\u201356: Module 5 Capstone \u2014 The Final Exam: Quick Reference","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 53\u201354: Menus and Timing</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/quick-ref.html#year-end-skills-audit","title":"Year-End Skills Audit","text":"<p>Rate each skill honestly on a 1\u20135 scale: - 1 \u2014 Still can't do this reliably - 3 \u2014 Can do this correctly most of the time - 5 \u2014 Automatic; no recipe needed; would teach this</p> Skill Week 1 Rating Week 52 Rating Notes Knife skills \u2014 onion dice Sear protein without sticking Make stock from carcass/bones Pan sauce from drippings Season confidently without recipe Cook egg any style to order Emulsify a butter sauce Make fresh pasta by hand Grill protein to correct temp Braise a tough cut to tenderness Bake bread (any style) Make pastry dough (pie/tart) Make a gelatin-set dessert Cook 3-course dinner without stress Cook for 6+ people on schedule"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/quick-ref.html#52-week-cumulative-technique-reference","title":"52-Week Cumulative Technique Reference","text":"Technique Family Weeks Benchmark Dish Egg fundamentals 1\u20132 Perfect fried egg; French omelette Stocks and sauces 3\u20134 Brown chicken stock; pan sauce Knife and vegetable 5\u20136 Uniform brunoise; vegetable mise en place Braising and roasting 7\u20138 Braise to fork-tender; perfect roast Stewing and soups 9\u201310 Soup from stock; coq au vin variation Poultry all-in 11\u201312 Spatchcock roast; duck confit Beef fundamentals 13\u201316 Steak sear; short rib braise Beef advanced 17\u201318 Galbi; Bolognese from scratch Pork all cuts 19\u201320 Chashu; carnitas; porchetta Fish fundamentals 21\u201322 Crispy skin salmon; sole meuni\u00e8re Shellfish 23\u201324 Vongole; moules; lobster thermidor Curing and charcuterie 25\u201326 Gravlax; rillettes French cuisine 27\u201328 Cassoulet; b\u00e9arnaise; duck \u00e0 l'orange Italian cuisine 29\u201330 Osso buco; gnocchi; tiramisu Japanese cuisine 31\u201332 Dashi; tonkatsu; ramen tare Mexican cuisine 33\u201334 Pozole; mole; tamales Indian cuisine 35\u201336 Butter chicken; biryani; garam masala Middle Eastern 37\u201338 Hummus from dried; falafel; shawarma SE Asian 39\u201340 Pad thai; pho; rendang Bread 41\u201342 Sourdough loaf; croissants Pastry 43\u201344 P\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e; tarte tatin Desserts 45\u201346 Panna cotta; cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e; pavlova Signature / Mastery 47\u201348 Your defined dishes Menus / Timing 49\u201350 Dinner party for 8, on time"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/quick-ref.html#the-final-dish-self-assessment","title":"The Final Dish Self-Assessment","text":"<p>Answer before cooking your final exam dish:</p> Question Your Answer What dish have you chosen? Why this one? What technique does it require? Where could it go wrong? What is your contingency if it does? How will you know it's right?"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/quick-ref.html#recommended-ongoing-resources","title":"Recommended Ongoing Resources","text":"Resource What It's For Serious Eats Primary reference; continue using indefinitely The Food Lab articles (Kenji) Deep-dive technique science on any topic SE Recipe Index Find any specific dish SE Techniques Searchable by skill Local farmers market Seasonal ingredients teach more than recipes A notebook It always comes back to writing things down"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/quick-ref.html#what-you-have-made-52-week-summary","title":"What You Have Made (52-Week Summary)","text":"Category Approximate Dishes Egg and breakfast dishes 12+ Soups and stocks 20+ Vegetable preparations 40+ Fish and shellfish 30+ Poultry 20+ Beef 25+ Pork 15+ International complete meals 40+ Bread and pastry 20+ Desserts and custards 20+ Estimated total ~250\u2013280 dishes"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/quick-ref.html#week-5152-at-a-glance","title":"Week 51\u201352 at a Glance","text":"Day Activity W51 Mon Skills inventory + knife time trial W51 Tue Cook one dish from weeks 1\u201310 W51 Wed Cook complete 2-course meal from memory W51 Thu Rest W51 Fri Final mise en place drill W51 Sat Anniversary Dinner \u2014 your people, your menu W52 Mon Write culinary philosophy W52 Tue Final Exam Dish \u2014 no recipe W52 Wed Retrospective tasting menu (personal) W52 Thu Do not cook W52 Fri Open kitchen \u2014 cook for anyone W52 Sat The Final Dinner \u2014 no instructions"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/shopping-list.html","title":"Weeks 55\u201356: Module 5 Capstone \u2014 The Final Exam: Shopping List","text":"<p>\u2190 Weeks 53\u201354: Menus and Timing</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/shopping-list.html#equipment-check-full-year","title":"Equipment Check (Full Year)","text":"<p>This is a good moment to evaluate which equipment you've acquired over 52 weeks and what gaps remain.</p> <p>Essential \u2014 you should have these by now: - [ ] Chef's knife (8\u201310 inch), well-maintained and sharp - [ ] Carbon steel or cast iron skillet - [ ] Heavy-bottomed stainless saut\u00e9 pan - [ ] Dutch oven (5\u20137 qt) - [ ] Stock pot (8+ qt) - [ ] Instant-read thermometer - [ ] Digital scale - [ ] Mandoline (or very good knife skills) - [ ] Standing or hand mixer - [ ] Sheet pans \u00d7 2, with wire racks</p> <p>Nice to have if not yet acquired: - [ ] Wok (14-inch carbon steel) - [ ] Banneton and Dutch oven (sourdough) - [ ] Kitchen torch (cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e) - [ ] Spider strainer (frying) - [ ] Bench scraper (pastry + bread)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/shopping-list.html#week-51-shopping","title":"Week 51 Shopping","text":""},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/shopping-list.html#tuesday-the-forgotten-dish-from-weeks-110","title":"Tuesday \u2014 The Forgotten Dish (from weeks 1\u201310)","text":"<p>Items depend on which dish you choose. Common choices: - Coq au vin: whole chicken, mushrooms, pearl onions, lardons, wine - Roast chicken: whole bird, lemon, garlic, herbs, butter - Braised short ribs: bone-in short ribs, mirepoix vegetables, red wine - French omelette \u00d7 several: eggs, butter \u2014 no other ingredients needed</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/shopping-list.html#friday-final-mise-en-place-drill-4-course","title":"Friday \u2014 Final Mise en Place Drill (4-course)","text":"<p>Choose your menu; buy what that menu requires. Suggested: - Protein (your best cut): highest quality you can afford \u2014 this is the final practice - Vegetables \u00d7 3 types - Fresh herbs - Butter, cream, stock (from pantry or fresh) - Wine for braising or sauce</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/shopping-list.html#week-52-shopping","title":"Week 52 Shopping","text":""},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/shopping-list.html#tuesday-the-final-exam-dish","title":"Tuesday \u2014 The Final Exam Dish","text":"<p>This is your personal dish. Buy the ingredients for the dish you choose as your final exam.</p> Component Your Item Quantity <p>Recommendation: Buy the best version of every ingredient. This meal is worth it.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/shopping-list.html#wednesday-the-retrospective-tasting-menu","title":"Wednesday \u2014 The Retrospective Tasting Menu","text":"<p>This meal is built from previously mastered dishes. Pull from your freezer (stocks, braises, doughs) where possible. Buy only fresh components: - [ ] Fresh herbs for garnish - [ ] Fresh fish or shellfish if the retrospective includes one - [ ] Cream or mascarpone if needed for dessert layer - [ ] A small amount of good cheese (optional intermezzo)</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/shopping-list.html#friday-the-open-kitchen","title":"Friday \u2014 The Open Kitchen","text":"<p>Plan for however many people you expect; this is a free-form session. - [ ] Good bread \u00d7 2 loaves - [ ] Charcuterie and cheese board (always a backup) - [ ] Protein for on-request cooking (chicken thighs are forgiving; excellent pantry backup) - [ ] Eggs \u2014 2 dozen (the most versatile on-demand ingredient) - [ ] Pantry essentials fully restocked</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/shopping-list.html#saturday-the-final-dinner","title":"Saturday \u2014 The Final Dinner","text":"<p>No shopping list. You know what you're cooking. You know what you need.</p> <p>Buy the best you can find. Cook it the way you've learned. That's the whole thing.</p>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/shopping-list.html#pantry-final-inventory","title":"Pantry Final Inventory","text":"<p>Complete this before the final week, then replace anything low:</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Olive oil (replace with new bottle if more than 6 months old)</li> <li>[ ] Kosher salt (Diamond Crystal or Morton \u2014 check level)</li> <li>[ ] Maldon sea salt for finishing</li> <li>[ ] Whole peppercorns (grind fresh)</li> <li>[ ] Dried pasta \u00d7 4 shapes</li> <li>[ ] Canned whole tomatoes \u00d7 4 (San Marzano)</li> <li>[ ] Stock (homemade in freezer, or good quality purchased)</li> <li>[ ] Vinegars: sherry, red wine, white wine, champagne</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce, soy sauce, oyster sauce, mirin (check levels)</li> <li>[ ] Dijon mustard, whole grain mustard</li> <li>[ ] Tahini (if using in your signature repertoire)</li> <li>[ ] Capers, anchovies (small-batch flavor bombs)</li> <li>[ ] Dried chiles \u00d7 assortment (guajillo, ancho, \u00e1rbol)</li> <li>[ ] Good canned tuna or sardines (emergency pantry dinner)</li> <li>[ ] Chocolate: bittersweet 70% \u00d7 1 bar</li> </ul>"},{"location":"weeks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-final-exam/shopping-list.html#a-final-note","title":"A Final Note","text":"<p>After 52 weeks, you have a pantry that took a year to build. The stocks you're holding in the freezer, the dried chiles in the cabinet, the anchovy jar you learned to reach for \u2014 these are the materials of a cook's kitchen. </p> <p>The greatest investment of this year was not in equipment or ingredients. It was in the decision, repeated approximately 250 times, to cook rather than not cook.</p> <p>That practice is yours to keep.</p>"}]}